(100400104, 'Communication', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\n<h1>Communication</h1>\n\n<div id="rightcolumn">\n<img src="../images/communication.jpg" alt="" width="250" height="124" class="featurephoto" />\n\n<div id="resources">\n<h3>More information</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.net/patient/Coping/Relationships+and+Cancer" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Relationships and Cancer</a> (Cancer.Net)</li>\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.org/docroot/ESN/content/ESN_2_1x_Communicating_with_Friends_and_Relatives_About_Your_Cancer.asp" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Talking with Friends and Relatives About Your Cancer</a><br />(American Cancer Society)</li>\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.org/treatment/understandingyourdiagnosis/afterdiagnosis/after-diagnosis-talking-to-others-about-diagnosis" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">How Do I Talk to People About My Diagnosis?</a> (American Cancer Society)</li>\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/factsheet/Information/internet" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">How To Evaluate Health Information on the Internet: Questions and Answers</a><br />(National Cancer Institute)</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n</div>\n\n<div id="symptomtext">\n\n<p>One of the best tools to help cancer is communication. There are two parts to effective communication, talking and listening.  Openly telling your doctors and nurses how you feel helps them to take better care of you.   Listen to your doctors\' or nurses\' advice.  Follow up with your doctors and nurses by telling them what is helping and what is not helping you.</p>\n\n<p>Communication with family and friends is also important. Talk to your family and friends about how you feel, what you are thinking about, and how they can help you talk and listen to them, and how they can help you talk and listen to your doctors or nurses. </p>\n\n<p>Ask for help when you need it. Others may be able to help get the things that you need. Family, friends, co-workers, doctors and nurses can support you as you go through this experience.</p>\n\n<p>Click on a link below for tips that may help you talk to your doctor, family, and friends: </p>\n \n<ul>\n<li><a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_004_001_001">Communication with Healthcare Providers</a></li>\n<li><a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_004_001_002">Communication with Family and Friends</a></li>\n<li><a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_004_001_003">Asking for Help and Accepting Help</a></li>\n</ul>\n\n</div>\n\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->'),
(100400204, 'Finance', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\n<h1>Finances</h1>\n\n<div id="rightcolumn">\n<div id="resources">\n\n<h3>More information</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.net/patient/Diagnosis+and+Treatment/Finding+Quality+Care/Financial+Resources" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Financial Resources</a> (Cancer.Net)</li>\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.org/docroot/MIT/content/MIT_3_2X_Family_and_Medical_Leave_Act.asp?" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Family and Medical Leave Act</a><br />(American Cancer Society)</li>\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.org/treatment/findingandpayingfortreatment/managinginsuranceissues/healthinsuranceandfinancialassistanceforthecancerpatient/index" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Medical Insurance and Financial Assistance for the Cancer Patient</a><br />(American Cancer Society)</li>\n</ul>\n\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<div id="symptomtext">\n\n<p>Cancer can bring up many financial or money concerns for people with cancer and their families.  Besides the hospital bills and other charges related to treatment, there may be costs that are not covered by insurance, such as gas, bus fare or taxi fare, medicine, and child care.  At a time when people are concerned about losing their job or income, this burden may seem huge. Click the link to find out more about keeping your job or a family keeping their jobs during your cancer treatment. </p>\n\n<p>The good news is that there are programs to help with many costs.  You may need to do some homework to find ones that will fit your need and that will allow you to join.  There are programs for people who do not have insurance or need help with costs, such as medications, utility bills, and daily living.  If you have health insurance, learning about what your policy covers is a good place to start. Click one of the links to the right to find out more about aid during cancer treatment.</p>\n\n</div>\n\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\n');

