(100300100304, 'Anemia', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\n<h1>Anemia</h1>\n\n<div id="symptomtext">\n\n<ul><li><a href=#1>What is anemia?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#2>How do people describe anemia?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#3>What causes anemia?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#4>What can I do about anemia?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#5>How is anemia managed?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#6>What can family members and friends do to help me with my anemia?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#7>How can I talk to family and friends about my anemia?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#8>What should I report to my healthcare provider about my anemia?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#9>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about my anemia?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#10>Where can I get more information?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#11>References</a></li>\n<li><a href=#12>Supportive evidence-based practice</a></li>\n</ul><br />\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What is anemia?</h1><p>Anemia is caused when there are not enough red blood cells in the body. As many as half of all cancer patients experience anemia at one time or another. Red blood cells carry hemoglobin, a protein that carries oxygen the body needs for energy.<br /><br />Healthcare providers usually order a blood test, called a complete blood count (CBC), to diagnose anemia. The CBC has three key measures: red blood cell count, hematocrit, and hemoglobin.  A major loss in any of these measures will indicate anemia. Anemia is a primary cause of fatigue related to cancer and cancer treatment. </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>How do people describe anemia?</h1><p>Initially, anemia can be so mild it goes unnoticed.  As signs and symptoms increase, the condition becomes worse. Anemia is not often life threatening, but can play a major role in reducing the quality of life of a person with cancer. <br /><br />Many people report the following as signs of anemia: <ul> <li> Pale skin, fingernails, palms, and lining of eyelids. </li> <li> Dizziness. </li> <li> Tiredness. </li> <li> Light headed. </li> <li> Rapid pulse. </li> <li> Rapid heart beat. </li> <li> Fatigue. </li> <li> Chills. </li> <li> Inability to stay warm. </li> <li> Shortness of breath (especially when sitting or standing). </li> <li> Lack of energy. </li> <li> Weakness. </li> <li> Inability to concentrate. </li> <li> Chest pain. </li> <li> Feeling heart beating in chest. </li></ul></p><a name="3"></a><h1>What causes anemia?</h1><p>Anemia can be caused by any one or a combination of the following: <ul> <li> Cancer treatment, such as chemotherapy, surgery, or radiation. </li> <li> Lack of specific vitamins or minerals in the diet. </li> <li> Another chronic disease such as arthritis, kidney disease. </li> <li> Hereditary disorders, such as sickle cell disease. </li> <li> Infiltration of bone marrow with cancer. </li></ul></p><a name="4"></a><h1>What can I do about anemia?</h1><p>In general, it is not possible to prevent anemia during the course of cancer treatment. The severity of anemia depends on the kind of cancer being treated, the medications and doses used to treat it, and the general condition of the person receiving treatment. <br /><br />Here are some tips you might find helpful:<br /><br /><h2>ACTIVITY</h2><ul> <li> Get plenty of rest (8 hours of sleep with several rest periods during the day). </li> <li> Do some mild exercise daily.  Take at least a 15-minute walk each day. (Exercise can increase your energy level.) </li> <li> Schedule your day so that you have time to rest between major activities. </li> <li> Let others help you with housework, chores and meal preparation. </li> <li> Get help with daily activities. </li> <li> Try not to sleep for long periods during the day.  It may interfere with you getting a good night\'s sleep. </li> <li> Place things that you use often within easy reach. </li> <li> Rise slowly after sitting or lying down to prevent dizziness. </li> <li> Plan rest periods to conserve energy for important activities. </li> <li> Set priorities to do important or fun activities first. </li> <li> Change your work schedule.  Consider decreasing your work hours. </li> <li> Take time off from work during the weeks you have treatment. </li></ul><br /><h2>DIET</h2><ul> <li> Eat a diet rich in iron.  Foods rich in iron include red meats and green leafy vegetables. </li> <li> Eat a well balanced diet. </li> <li> Drink 8 (8oz.) glasses of water or other non-caffeinated drinks every day.  Avoid caffeine (e.g., colas, coffee) when possible.  Caffeine can cause dehydration. </li></ul><br /><h2>PSYCHOLOGICAL</h2><ul> <li> Use relaxation techniques, such as meditation, as a way to relax. </li> <li> Listen to music. </li> <li> Describe how you feel in a daily log, journal, or diary.  Each day record your fatigue on a scale from 0-10 (0= no fatigue and 10= worst fatigue possible). </li></ul></p><a name="5"></a><h1>How is anemia managed?</h1><p>There are two standard approaches to treating anemia in people with cancer. The treatment may vary depending on what type of cancer you have. <br /><br /><b>APPROACH #1</b><br />Cancer treatments can lower the level or erythropoietin (a hormone produced in the kidneys) in the blood.  Drugs, such as epoetin alfa (Epogen&#174;, Procrit&#174;) or darbepoetin alfa (Aranesp&#174;), are synthetic forms or erythropietin. Although injected into the body, they do not work instantly.  It may be several days to weeks before a patient notices a difference in their energy level.  Side effects are infrequent and mild. Some that are experienced include increased blood pressure, minor allergic response, edema, and diarrhea. (NOTE: These medications are not appropriate for use with all cancers.)<br /><br /><b>APPROACH #2</b><br />Blood transfusions are only appropriate for people who are very anemic, and whose cancer treatments can\'t be delayed while the anemia is being treated. Transfusions are the fastest way to improve red blood cell counts for people with severe anemia. </p><br /><a name="6"></a><h1>What can family members and friends do to help me with my anemia?</h1><p>Ask family members and friends to:<ul> <li> Help with housework, chores, yard work, and cooking. </li> <li> Take a walk with you and encourage you to walk every day. </li> <li> Offer you fluids throughout the day. </li> <li> Help you set daily priorities so you avoid overexertion. </li></ul></p><a name="7"></a><h1>How can I talk to family members and friends about my anemia?</h1><p>Here are some ideas that may help you talk to family members and friends:<ul> <li> Be open and honest about feelings with your family members. </li> <li> Ask your family members and friends how your fatigue is affecting them.  </li></ul></p><a name="8"></a><h1>What should I report to my healthcare provider about my anemia?</h1><p>If you experience any of the following signs or symptoms, report them to your healthcare provider:<ul> <li> Increased fatigue. </li> <li> Shortness of breath. </li> <li> Unable to do any of your usual daily activities. </li> <li> Unable to get out of bed for more than 24 hours. </li> <li> Rapid heart beat. </li> <li> Pale skin. </li> <li> Unable to think clearly. </li> <li> Chest pain. </li> <li> Difficulty focusing on things, such as TV, talking, or reading. </li> <li> Signs of bleeding. </li> <li> Difficulty staying warm. </li> <li> Dizziness. </li> <li> Headache. </li></ul></p><a name="9"></a><h1>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about my anemia?</h1><p>If you are experiencing anemia, you should discuss the following with your healthcare provider:<ul> <li> Should I use nutritional supplements to help my anemia? </li> <li> Will my anemia cause delays in my cancer treatment? </li> <li> What are the treatment options for my anemia? </li> <li> How long will it take for my anemia treatment to begin to work? </li> <li> If my health insurance does not pay for anemia treatment, what other options are available to me? </li> <li> Are there things that I can do to help my anemia? </li> <li> Ask your healthcare provider for your blood counts. </li></ul></p><a name="10"></a><h1>Where can I get more information?</h1><p>For more information, contact the people or organizations at the numbers or websites listed below:<ul> <li> American Cancer Society: 1-800-ACS-2345 or <a href=http://www.cancer.org target=_blank>http://www.cancer.org</a> Click on patients, family & friends, then coping with treatment. </li> <li> National Cancer Institute: 1-800-4-CANCER or <a href=http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo/ target=_blank>http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo/</a> Click on coping with cancer. </li> <li> The Family Care Research Program: <a href=http://www.cancercare.msu.edu target=_blank>http://www.cancercare.msu.edu</a> </li> <li> Anemia: <a href=http://www.anemia.com target=_blank>http://www.anemia.com</a> Click on chemotherapy-related anemia. </li></ul></p><a name="11"></a><h1>References</h1><p><ul> <li> Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality (n.d.).  Agency for Healthcare research and quality. Retrieved from: <a href=http://www.ahrq.gov target=_blank>http://www.ahrq.gov</a> </li> <li> American Society of Clinical Oncology (2008).  American Society of Clinical Oncology: Making a world of difference in cancer care.  Retrieved from: <a href=http://www.asco.org target=_blank>http://www.asco.org</a> </li> <li> American Society of Hematology (2008). American Society of Hematology: Helping hematologist conquer blood diseases. Retrieved from: <a href=http://www.hematology.org target=_blank>http://www.hematology.org</a> </li> <li> Cancer Care, Inc.(n.d.) CancerCare. Retrieved from: <a href=http://www.cancercare.org target=_blank>http://www.cancercare.org</a> </li> <li> National Cancer Institute (n.d.). National Cancer Institute. Retrieved from: <a href=http://www.cancer.gov target=_blank>http://www.cancer.gov</a> </li> <li> National Coalition for Cancer Survivorship (2008). National Coalition for cancer survivorship. Retrieved from: <a href=http://canceradvocacy.org/ target=_blank>http://canceradvocacy.org/</a> </li> <li> National Comprehensive Cancer Network (2007). Supportive evidenced-based practice.  Retrieved from: <a href=http://www.nccn.org target=_blank>http://www.nccn.org</a> </li></ul></p><a name="12"></a><h1>Supportive evidence-based practice</h1><p><ul> <li> Demetri, G., D. (2001). Anemia and its functional consequences in cancer patients: current challenges in management and prospects for improving therapy. British Journal Of Cancer, 84 (1), 31-37. </li> <li> Gillespie, T., W. (2003). Anemia in cancer. Cancer Nursing, 26(2), 119-128. </li> <li> Harper, P., & Littlewood, T. (2005). Anemia of cancer: impact on patient fatigue and long-term outcome. Oncology, 69 (2), 2-7. </li> <li> Mock, V., & Olsen, M. (2003). Current management of fatigue and anemia in patients with cancer. Seminars In Oncology Nursing, 19 (4), 36-41. </li> <li> Visovsky, C., & Schneider, S., (2003). Cancer-related fatigue. Online Journals Of Issues in Nursing, 8 (3), 1-23.  </li></ul></p>\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a>\n\n<div id="credit"><p>This information was developed in collaboration with Michigan State University and the Behavioral Cooperative Oncology Group.</p></div>\n\n</div>\n\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->'),
(100300100604, 'Lack of Appetite', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\n<h1>Lack of Appetite</h1>\n\n<div id="symptomtext">\n\n<ul><li><a href=#1>What is lack of appetite?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#2>How do people describe lack of appetite?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#3>What causes lack of appetite?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#4>What can I do about lack of appetite?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#5>What can family members and friends do to help me with my lack of appetite?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#6>How can I talk with my family members and friends about my lack of appetite?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#7>What should I report to my healthcare provider about my lack of appetite? </a></li>\n<li><a href=#8>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about my lack of appetite? </a></li>\n<li><a href=#9>Where can I get more information?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#10>References</a></li>\n<li><a href=#11>Supportive evidence-based practice</a></li>\n</ul><br />\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What is lack of appetite?</h1><p>A lack of or decreased appetite is when a person does not feeling hungry, even though they have not eaten enough to meet their basic caloric needs. If not treated and managed, it can lead to a more serious condition. Increasing your appetite, you can improve both your quality of life and ability to tolerate cancer treatments. </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>How do people describe lack of appetite?</h1><p>Lack of appetite can be described as not having the desire to eat.  Often, people with cancer or those undergoing cancer treatment report that they have no appetite, feel full quicker than usual, or both.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>What causes lack of appetite?</h1><p>Cancer itself can affect your appetite, food digestion, and energy level.  Many people report that their senses of taste and smell change because of their treatment. These changes can decrease appetite.  Some have experienced changes in appetite because of nausea, vomiting, or uncontrolled pain and fatigue.  Other factors that can contribute to appetite loss include medications, anxiety, depression or sadness, lack of sleep, difficulty swallowing, constipation, or diarrhea. </p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>What can I do about lack of appetite?</h1><p>Not eating well can keep you from getting the nutrients that you need.  Here are some tips you might find helpful:<br /><br /><h2>ACTIVITY</h2><ul> <li> Assess your nutritional status by keeping a log of the food that you eat.  Write down all of the food that you ate in a 24 hour period. </li> <li> Freeze food in meal size portions. </li> <li> Give food a chance.  Even though you have trouble eating now, you may find a time when eating is enjoyable. </li> <li> Weigh yourself at the same time every day. </li> <li> Stock up on favorite foods. </li> <li> Keep a supply of foods that can be eaten during times of illness, such as popsicles, broths, or lemon-lime soda. </li> <li> Do not eat your favorite foods on the day of your treatments or when you feel nauseated.  Your body may learn to associate these foods with nausea. </li> <li> Eat foods that are cold or room temperature if food odors bother you. </li> <li> Do not try to lose weight while being treated for cancer, unless directed by your healthcare provider to do so. </li> <li> Do light exercises for 30 minutes before mealtime may help you to feel hungrier.  Examples of light exercises are walking around the block or around the house. </li></ul><br /><h2>COMMUNICATION</h2><ul> <li> Ask your nurse, dietician, or doctor to help you assess your nutritional status before and during your treatment. </li></ul><br /><h2>DIET</h2><ul> <li> Try new foods.  Tastes can change.  Different foods may be a pleasant addition to your menu. </li> <li> Using sauces and gravies can make swallowing easier. </li> <li> Drink 8 (8oz.) glasses of water or other non-caffeinated drinks every day.  Avoid caffeine (i.e. colas, coffee) when possible.  Caffeine can cause dehydration. </li> <li> Eat calorie-rich foods such as malts, shakes, and omelets. </li> <li> Try eating 5-6 smaller meals or snacks throughout the day. </li> <li> Avoid carbonated beverages, they can make you feel full but do not add nutrition. </li> <li> Get approval from your oncologist to try Boost or Ensure. These high-calorie supplements can also be mixed with fruit or ice cream to make a shake.  Supplements can be filling, so try to eat your meal before taking them.  NOTE:  Supplements can stay on your tongue and mouth.  Many find it helpful to sip through a straw and drink them cold. </li> <li> Suck on hard candy if you have a metallic taste in your mouth. </li> <li> Eat meats, fruits and vegetables in small portions throughout the day.  Avoid milk if its upsets your stomach. </li> <li> Eat protein everyday (tuna fish, chicken, peanut butter, and cheese). </li><br /><ul> <li> Treat constipation and diarrhea.  Both of them can affect your appetite.</li> <li>Use seasonings on foods that you are finding unpleasant.  Basil, oregano and rosemary can make meat, fish or poultry more flavorful. </li></ul></ul><br /><h2>MEDICATION</h2><ul> <li> Take a daily vitamin supplement. </li> <li> Take your prescribed anti-nausea medications 30-60 minutes before eating. </li> <li> Ask your doctor if an appetite stimulant like Megace (a hormone that improves appetite and can help you increase your calorie intake) would be good for you. </li></ul><br /><h2>INFORMATION FOR CAREGIVERS</h2><ul> <li> Do not try to push your family member into eating or drinking. </li> <li> Provide encouragement and support without being overwhelming. </li> <li> Keep snacks and utensils within easy reach. </li> <li> Plan on small, frequent meals. </li> <li> Encourage fluids if your family member cannot eat. Many fluids are nutritious and contain calories. Your family member may not drink much at a time.  Even when sipped, juices and other fluids can be beneficial. </li> <li> Be prepared for changing tastes. They may changes day-to-day.  Favorite foods may not taste good some days. </li> <li> Have high-energy foods available. </li></ul></p><a name="5"></a><h1>What can family members and friends do to help me with my lack of appetite?</h1><p>Ask family members and friends to:<ul> <li> Keep foods around that require little or no preparation time.  Examples of easy to prepare foods include: cheese, eggs, pudding, peanut butter, or tuna fish. </li> <li> Help with grocery shopping and cooking. </li> <li> Make mealtime pleasant. This may include fresh flowers on the table or pleasant music while eating. </li></ul></p><a name="6"></a><h1>How can I talk with my family members and friends about my lack of appetite?</h1><p>Here are some ideas that may help you talk to family members and friends:<ul> <li> Tell your family members and friends how the lack of appetite is affecting your daily activities and emotions. </li> <li> Ask your family members and friends for suggestions that might help. </li> <li> Make suggestions about your food preferences. </li></ul></p><a name="7"></a><h1>What should I report to my healthcare provider about my lack of appetite?</h1><p>If you experience any of the following symptoms, report them to your healthcare provider:<ul> <li> Several days (3-5) of eating poorly. </li> <li> Decreased amount of urine. </li> <li> Dark colored urine. </li> <li> Fever greater than 100.4 degrees Farenheit (38.0 C) for over 24 hours. </li> <li> Dizziness. </li> <li> Mental confusion. </li> <li> Uncontrolled nausea or vomiting. </li> <li> Inability to tolerate fluids for over 24 hours. </li> <li> Loss of 5 pounds in a week or more than 2 pounds in 24 hours. </li> <li> Nothing to eat or drink for 24 hours. </li> <li> Constipation (no bowel movement for 2 days). </li> <li> Pain. </li> <li> Depression and/or anxiety. </li></ul></p><a name="8"></a><h1>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about my lack of appetite?</h1><p>If you are experiencing a lack of appetite, you should discuss the following with your healthcare provider at your next appointment:<ul> <li> Can you help me find ways to improve my diet, even though I lack an appetite? </li> <li> How many calories should I consume each day? </li> <li> How long will I continue to experience strange tastes in my mouth? What is causing this? </li> <li> I am losing weight steadily. How can we approach and reverse this problem? What are my options? </li></ul></p><a name="9"></a><h1>Where can I get more information?</h1><p>For more information, contact the people or organizations at the numbers or websites listed below:<ul> <li> Contact your healthcare provider. </li> <li> National Cancer Institute: 1-800-4-CANCER or <a href=http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo/ target=_blank>http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo/</a> Click on coping with cancer. Find and click on nutrition in cancer patients. </li> <li> American Cancer Society: 1-800-ACS-2345 or <a href=http://www.cancer.org target=_blank>http://www.cancer.org</a> Click patients, family & friends, then coping with treatment. </li> <li> Family Care Research Program: <a href=http://www.cancercare.msu.edu target=_blank>http://www.cancercare.msu.edu</a> </li> <li> National Coalition For Cancer Survivorship: <a href=http://canceradvocacy.org target=_blank>http://canceradvocacy.org</a> Click on Resource Guide then Side effects. </li> <li> Oncology Nursing Society: <a href=http://www.cancersymptoms.org target=_blank>http://www.cancersymptoms.org</a> </li></ul></p><a name="10"></a><h1>References</h1><p><ul> <li> Cunningham, R.S. (2003). The anorexia-cachexia syndrome. In C.H. Yarbro, M.H. Frogge, & M. Goodman (Eds.), Cancer Symptom Management, 3rd Ed. (pp. 137-167). Boston: Jones And Bartlett. </li> <li> National Cancer Institute (n.d.).  National Cancer Institute. Retrieved from  <a href=http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo/ target=_blank>http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo/</a> </li> <li> University Of Pennsylvania Oncolink (2008). OncoLink: The web\'s first cancer resource.  Retrieved from: <a href=http://www.oncolink.upenn.edu target=_blank>http://www.oncolink.upenn.edu</a> </li> <li> Wickham, R., Rewaldt, M., Kefer, C., Shott, S., Abbas, K., Glynn-Tucker, E., Et Al. (1999). Taste changes experienced by patients receiving chemotherapy. Oncology Nursing Forum, 26, 697-706. </li></ul></p><a name="11"></a><h1>Supportive evidence-based practice</h1><p><ul> <li> Laviano, A., Meguid, M.M., Inui, A., Muscaritoli, M., & Rossi-Fanelli, F. (2005). Therapy insight: cancer anorexia-cachexia syndrome-when all you can eat is yourself. Nature Clinical Practice Oncology, 2 (3), 158-165. </li> <li> Mcgrath, P. (2002). Reflections on nutritional issues associated with cancer therapy. Cancer Practice, 10 (2), 94-101. </li></ul></p>\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a>\n\n<div id="credit"><p>This information was developed in collaboration with Michigan State University and the Behavioral Cooperative Oncology Group.</p></div>\n\n</div>\n\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->'),
(100300100904, 'Constipation', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Constipation</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext">\r\n\r\n<ul><li><a href=#1>What is constipation?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>How do people describe constipation?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>What causes constipation?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>What can I do about constipation?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What can family and friends do to help me with my constipation?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>How can I talk with my family members and friends about my constipation?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#7>What should I report to my healthcare provider about my constipation? </a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#8>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about my constipation? </a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#9>Where can I get more information?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#10>References</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#11>Supportive evidence-based practice</a></li>\r\n</ul><br />\r\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What is constipation?</h1><p>Constipation is defined as a condition in which bowel (stool) movements are rare, incomplete, or there is difficulty in passing stool. No regular bowel movement for 3 days is described as constipation. Constipation is common for persons taking opioids (any medicine containing opium) and other medications for their pain. Constipation also occurs for those who have inadequate fluid or fiber intake, who have consistently low levels of physical activity, or as a result of the cancer process, chemotherapy or other drug therapies.</p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>How do people describe constipation?</h1><p>Many people have described constipation as feeling an enlargement or bloating in the abdomen, or a sense of fullness in the rectal area. Others describe small amounts of stool "leaking", small frequent "smears" of stool, or rectal pain with a bowel movement. Constantly feeling the need to have a bowel movement, but unable to pass stool, is another way to describe how constipation feels.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>What causes constipation?</h1><p>The cause of constipation varies. Pain medication and chemotherapy drugs can cause constipation. Constipation can be caused from the cancer itself.  Other causes include stress, fever, changes in diet, not drinking enough fluids, or low levels of physical activity. Constipation is common for those who spend a lot of time in bed, are not eating well, or are experiencing weakness.<br /><br />Don\'t think that constipation isn\'t important, will go away by its self, or is not worth treating. If constipation is not treated it is both very painful and dangerous to your health, and can lead to serious complications.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>What can I do about constipation?</h1><p>Here are some tips you may find helpful:<br /><br /><h2>ACTIVITY</h2><ul> <li> Exercise every day, at least a 15-minute walk.  Perform mild exercise, such as walking. </li> <li> Establish a daily bathroom routine that includes privacy.  Use the toilet after mealtime. </li> <li> Have a quiet comfortable environment when having a bowel movement. </li> <li> Avoid straining or pushing hard with bowel movements. </li></ul><br /><h2>DIET</h2><ul> <li> Drink 8 (8oz.) glasses of water or other non-caffeinated drinks every day.  Avoid caffeine (e.g., colas, coffee) when possible.  Caffeine can cause dehydration. </li> <li> Add unprocessed bran or wheat germ to your diet.  Start with two teaspoons per day and gradually increase to two tablespoons per day. </li> <li> Eat foods high in fibers, such as raw vegetables, popcorn, raisin bran, beans, whole grain cereal, raisins, and prunes. </li> <li> Drink warm liquids, such as lemon water, prune juice, or herbal tea after mealtime. </li></ul><br /><h2>MEDICATIONS</h2><ul> <li> Do not use suppositories or enemas without talking to your healthcare provider. </li> <li> Ask your healthcare providers for a stool softener and/or laxative. </li> <li> Ask your doctor for a laxative if you take a narcotic for pain. Pain medications with narcotics often cause constipation. </li></ul><br /><h2>COMMUNICATION</h2><ul> <li> Let your doctor or nurse know if you have hemorrhoids or tears in the skin around the rectum. </li></ul></p><a name="5"></a><h1>What can family and friends do to help me with my constipation?</h1><p>Ask family members and friends to:<ul> <li> Prepare foods high in fiber. </li> <li> Offer you fluids throughout the day. </li> <li> Exercise with you. </li> <li> Help keep a log or record of bowel movements, bloating, gas or abdominal pain. Record what you eat, drink, and any medication that you are taking. </li></ul></p><a name="6"></a><h1>How can I talk with my family members and friends about my constipation?</h1><p>Here are some ideas that may help you talk to family members and friends:<ul> <li> Describe how being constipated makes you feel. </li></ul></p><a name="7"></a><h1>What should I report to my healthcare provider about my constipation?</h1><p>If you experience any of the following symptoms, report them to your healthcare provider:<ul> <li> No bowel movement for 3-4 days. </li> <li> Vomiting or abdominal bloating accompanied by constipation that lasts over 24 hours. </li> <li> Inability to eat. </li> <li> Bloody, black, or tarry stools. </li> <li> Severe uncontrolled abdominal pain. </li> <li> Painful bowel function. </li> <li> Impaction-hardened stool that does not come out. </li> <li> Increased or decreased urge to urinate. </li> <li> Back pain. </li> <li> No bowel movement within 24 hours after starting a laxative. </li> <li> Have your log or record available with the following information: </li><br /><ul> <li> Your normal bowel pattern.</li> <li>Date and time of last bowel movement.</li> <li>How much food and fluids you have taken in the last 1-2 days.</li> <li>Medications you have taken in the last 2-3 days.</li> <li>Any over-the-counter products that you may have already tried.</li> <li>Any history of past bowel problems or surgeries.</ul></ul></p><a name="8"></a><h1>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about my constipation?</h1><p>If you are experiencing constipation, you should discuss the following with your healthcare provider at your next visit:<ul> <li> Does my chemotherapy or nausea medication cause constipation? </li> <li> Is it safe to use over-the-counter products? Do you have suggestions what I should use? </li> <li> What type of exercise would you recommend for me? </li> <li> Do you recommend that I use fiber supplements? </li></ul></p><a name="9"></a><h1>Where can I get more information?</h1><p>For more information, contact the people or organizations at the numbers or websites listed below:<ul>\r\n <li> Contact your healthcare provider. </li> <li> National Cancer Institute: 1-800-4-CANCER or <a href=http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo/ target=_blank>http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo/</a> Click on coping with cancer. Find and click on gastrointestinal complications. </li> <li> National Institutes for Health: <a href=http://www.nih.gov/ target=_blank>http://www.nih.gov/</a> Go to the health tab at the top of the screen, click on A-Z health topics and then, click on constipation. </li> <li> American Cancer Society: 1-800-ACS-2345 or <a href=http://www.cancer.org target=_blank>http://www.cancer.org</a> Type in constipation in the search box at the top of the screen. </li> <li> Family Care Research Program: <a href=http://www.cancercare.msu.edu target=_blank>http://www.cancercare.msu.edu</a> </li> <li> Familydoctor.org: <a href=http://familydoctor.org/ target=_blank>http://familydoctor.org/</a>  Click on the "C" at the top of the page and then click on constipation. </li></ul></p><a name="10"></a><h1>References</h1><p><ul> <li> Campbell, T., Draper, S., Reid, J. & Robinson, L. (2001). The management of constipation in people with advanced cancer. International Journal Of Palliative Nursing, 7(3), 110-9. </li> <li> Management of constipation in older adults. Best practice: evidence based practice information sheets for health professionals (1999). 3(1), 1-4. </li> <li> Massey, R., Haylock, P., & Curtiss, C. (2003). Constipation. In C.H. Yarbro, M.H. Frogge, & M. Goodman (Eds.), Cancer Symptom Management, 3rd Ed. (Pp. 512-527). Boston: Jones And Bartlett. </li></ul></p><a name="11"></a><h1>Supportive evidence based practice</h1><p><ul> <li> Bennett, M., & Cresswell, H. (2003). Factors influencing constipation in advanced cancer patients: A prospective study of opioid dose, Datron Dose And Physical Functioning. Palliative Medicine, 17, 418-422. </li> <li> Muller-Lissner, S., Kaatz, V., Brandt, W., Keller, J., & Layer, P. (2005). The perceived effect of various foods and beverages on stool consistency. European Journal Of Gastroenterology & Hepatology, 17 (1), 109-112. </li> <li> Sykes, N. (2006), The pathogenesis of constipation. The Journal Of Supportive Oncology, (4) 5, 213-218. </li> <li> Thomas, J. (2006). Strategies to manage constipation. The Journal Of Supportive Oncology, (4) 5, 220-223. </li> <li> Woolery, M., Bisanz, A., Lyons, H.F., Gaido, L., et. al. (2008). Putting evidence into practice: Evidence based interventions for the prevention and management of constipation in patients with cancer. Clinical Journal of Oncology Nursing, 12(2): 317-337. </li></ul></p>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a>\r\n\r\n<div id="credit"><p>This information was developed in collaboration with Michigan State University and the Behavioral Cooperative Oncology Group.</p></div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->'),
(100300101204, 'Cough', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\n<h1>Cough</h1>\n\n<div id="symptomtext">\n\n<ul><li><a href=#1>What is cough?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#2>How do people describe cough?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#3>What causes cough?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#4>What can I do about cough?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#5>What can my family members and friends do to help me with my cough?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#6>How can I talk with my family members and friends about my cough?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#7>What should I report to my healthcare provider?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#8>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#9>Where can I get more information?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#10>References</a></li>\n<li><a href=#11>Supportive evidence-based practice</a></li>\n</ul><br />\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What is cough?</h1><p>A cough is a reflex response to mechanical or chemical irritants, or inflammation of the trachea brachial tree.  It automatically helps to clear the airway of irritating materials or obstructions.</p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>How do people describe cough?</h1><p>People describe cough as either being dry and hacking or that it produces mucus. Usually a dry, hacking cough occurs with a sore throat and it may be a sign of infection.<br /><br />A constant cough can tire a person more easily, making it difficult to do his/her usual activities.  (Activity can aggravate the coughing.) Some report that coughing makes it hard to talk, eat meal or sleep at night.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>What causes cough?</h1><p>There are different kinds of cough. People with cancer may experience cough due to a number of different problems including viruses, chronic lung disorders, fatigue, pneumonia, pain, infection, or anxiety. Chemotherapy, radiation therapy, tumor or fluid in the lungs may also result in cough. Cough is often associated with flu like symptoms, such as chills, aches, and pains.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>What can I do about cough?</h1><p>Here are some tips you may find helpful:<br /><br /><h2>ACTIVITY</h2><ul> <li> Avoid smoking and being around smokers. </li> <li> Limit unnecessary activity. </li> <li> Pace your activities to provide rest periods. </li> <li> Place a cool washcloth on your cheeks. </li> <li> Avoid warm temperatures, unpleasant odors, and fumes. </li> <li> Avoid dryness in the home.  If you use humidifiers, be sure they are cleaned every few days. </li></ul><br /><h2>DIET</h2><ul> <li> Eat six small meals a day rather than 3 large ones. </li> <li> Drink 8 (8oz.) glasses of water or other non-caffeinated drinks every day.  Avoid caffeine (i.e. colas, coffee) when possible.  Caffeine can cause dehydration. </li> <li> Suck on hard candy. </li></ul><br /><h2>PSYCHOLOGICAL</h2><ul> <li> Remain calm, try to stay relaxed. </li> <li> Try relaxation exercises. </li></ul></p><a name="5"></a><h1>What can my family members and friends do to help me with my cough?</h1><p>Ask family member and friends to:<ul> <li> Assist with relaxation techniques and keeping the environment calm. </li> <li> Participate in activities to distract you from thinking about your cough, such as puzzles, visiting, and watching movies. </li> <li> Help you with cleaning, grocery shopping, and cooking. </li> <li> Refrain from smoking around you. </li> <li> Keep the air in your house moist by running a humidifier. </li></ul></p><a name="6"></a><h1>How can I talk with my family members and friends about my cough?</h1><p>Here are some ideas that may help you talk to family members and friends:<ul> <li> Describe how the cough affects your emotions and mood; you are the expert. </li> <li> Ask for suggestions that might help relieve the cough. </li> <li> Try to describe how coughing interferes with your usual activities and makes you tired. </li></ul></p><a name="7"></a><h1>What should I report to my healthcare provider?</h1><p>If you experience any of the following symptoms, report them to your healthcare provider:<ul> <li> Cough lasting more than 7 days. </li> <li> Chest pain with cough. </li> <li> Coughing up blood. </li> <li> Wheezing. </li> <li> Cold, clammy skin. </li> <li> High-pitched sound (stridor) when inhaling. </li> <li> Thick, yellow, green, or bloody phlegm (saliva mixed with mucus). </li> <li> Trouble breathing or shortness of breath. </li></ul></p><a name="8"></a><h1>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider?</h1><p>If you are experiencing a cough, you should discuss the following with your healthcare provider at your next appointment:<ul> <li> Will my cancer treatments make my cough worse? </li> <li> What is causing my cough? </li> <li> What can be done for my cough? </li> <li> Should I take medication to relieve my cough? </li></ul></p><a name="9"></a><h1>Where can I get more information?</h1><p>For more information, contact the people or organizations at the numbers or websites listed below:<ul> <li> Contact your healthcare provider. </li> <li> Care During Chemotherapy and Beyond: <a href=http://www.chemocare.com/managing/cough_and_chemotherapy.asp target=_blank>http://www.chemocare.com/managing/cough_and_chemotherapy.asp</a> </li> <li> American Cancer Society: 1-800-ACS-2345 or <a href=http://www.cancer.org target=_blank>http://www.cancer.org</a> Click on patients, family & friends, then coping with treatment, then coping with physical and emotional changes followed by side effects. </li> <li> The National Cancer Institute: 1-800-4-Cancer or <a href=http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo/ target=_blank>http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo/</a> Click on coping with cancer. </li> <li> The American Lung Association: <a href=http://www.lungusa.org target=_blank>http://www.lungusa.org</a> or 1-800-543-Lung (5864). </li> <li> The Family Care Research Program: <a href=http://www.cancercare.msu.edu target=_blank>http://www.cancercare.msu.edu</a> </li></ul></p><a name="10"></a><h1>References</h1><p><ul> <li> American Society Of Clinical Oncology (2008). Cancer. Net: Making a world of difference in cancer care. Retrieved from: <a href=http://www.plwc.org target=_blank>http://www.plwc.org</a> </li> <li> Hood, L. E & Harwood, K.V. (2003). Flu like symptoms. In C. H. Yarbro, M.H. Frogge, & M. Goodman (Eds.), Cancer Symptom Management, 3rd Ed. (Pp. 61-76). Boston: Jones And Bartlett. </li> <li> Cancer Care Inc. (n.d.) It\'s Time To Focus on Lung Cancer. Retrieved from: <a href=http://www.lungcancer.org target=_blank>http://www.lungcancer.org</a> </li> <li> Oncology Nursing Society(2006). Cancer Symptoms: Information for understanding cancer symptoms.  Retrieved from: <a href=http://www.cancersymptoms.org/ target=_blank>http://www.cancersymptoms.org/</a> </li> <li> The University Of Pennsylvania Cancer Center\'s -  Trustees of the University Of Pennsylvania (2008).  Oncolink. Retrieved from: <a href=http://www.oncolink.upenn.edu target=_blank>http://www.oncolink.upenn.edu</a> </li></ul></p><a name="11"></a><h1>Supportive evidence-based practice</h1><p><ul> <li> Ahmedzai, S. H. (2004). Cough in cancer patients. Pulmonary Pharmacology & Therapeutics, 17, 415-423. </li> <li> Dudgeon, D.J. (2002). Managing dyspnea and cough. Hematology Oncology Clinics Of North America, 16, 557-577. </li> <li> Estfan, B. & Legrand, S. (2004). Management of cough in advanced cancer. Journal Of Supportive Oncology, 2 (6), 523-527. </li></ul></p>\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a>\n\n<div id="credit"><p>This information was developed in collaboration with Michigan State University and the Behavioral Cooperative Oncology Group.</p></div>\n\n</div>\n\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->');
