(100300101504, 'Depression', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Depression</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext">\r\n\r\n<ul><li><a href=#1>What is depression?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>How do people describe depression?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>What causes depression?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>What can I do about depression?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What can family members and friends do to help me with my depression?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>How can I talk to my family members about my depression?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#7>What should I report to my healthcare provider about my depression?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#8>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about my depression?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#9>Where can I get more information?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#10>References</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#11>Supportive evidence-based practice</a></li>\r\n</ul><br />\r\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What is depression?</h1><p>Depression is sadness that is more than normal, lasts two weeks, and greatly impacts your daily life. It can happen in response to an event or is because of changes in your body chemistry.<br /><br />In fact, clinical depression occurs in about 25% of people with cancer.  It can cause great distress, impaired functioning, and decrease a person\'s ability to follow his/her treatment schedule. The good news is clinical depression is treatable.</p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>How do people describe depression?</h1><p>Depression can affect everything in a person\'s life.  People have described depression as the darkest time in their life.   It is common to not want to talk to friends and family.<br /><br />When depressed, people may have trouble experiencing pleasure.  Many report physical problems, such as crying spells, eating (too much or not enough), or sleeping (too much or too little).  Others have described feeling hopeless, helpless, or worthless.  Some even report feelings that they want to hurt themselves.  Contact your healthcare provider immediately if you begin to feel this way or call 911.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>What causes depression?</h1><p>Depression can occur in response to a specific event, such as a cancer diagnosis or a death to a loved one.  Depression can also be a result from medications, being tired, or from chemical changes in the brain. People can usually cope with short-term feelings of depression.  Persistent feelings of depression and sadness are treated with counseling and/or medication.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>What can I do about depression?</h1><p>Here are some tips you may find helpful: <br /><br /><h2>ACTIVITY</h2><ul> <li> Try to get enough sleep at night; avoid napping during the day. </li> <li> Go outdoors and walk in natural settings, such as a garden or park. </li> <li> Participate in regular, routine exercise (walking 20 minutes, 3-5 times per week).  Exercise has been shown to improve mood and well-being. </li></ul><br /><h2>COMMUNICATION</h2><ul> <li> Make an appointment with your healthcare provider, telling them exactly how you feel and ask for help. </li> <li> Make an appointment to talk to a counselor, clergy, spiritual advisor, or psychologist about your depression. </li></ul><br /><h2>DIET</h2><ul> <li> Avoid alcohol consumption; it can make you more depressed. </li> <li> Try to maintain good health by eating nutritious foods.  Ask a dietician for help if you are having problems eating. </li></ul><br /><h2>MEDICATIONS</h2><ul> <li> Make a list of all the medications you are taking and show it to your healthcare providers.  Some medications may have to be stopped or changed.  Only a healthcare provider should make changes to your medications.  Do not stop taking any of your medications without a healthcare provider\'s okay. </li> <li> Take medicines prescribed for your depression as directed. </li></ul><br /><h2>PSYCHOLOGICAL</h2><ul> <li> Try mediation, massage, controlled breathing and relaxation exercises; these can help release mood-enhancing substances from the brain. </li> <li> Try distraction, guided imagery, or music therapy to relax. </li> <li> Express your feeling through journal writing or creative expression (dance, cooking, exercise, painting, or music). </li> <li> Try to identify something that brings you pleasure every day. </li> <li> Be around other people in restful relaxing situation as much as possible. </li> <li> Join a support group. This can help relieve the isolation that is often felt by those who are depressed. </li></ul></p><a name="5"></a><h1>What can family members and friends do to help me with my depression?</h1><p>Ask family members and friends to: <ul> <li> Stay with you, especially during difficult times. Sometimes just having someone there with you is enough. </li> <li> Engage in enjoyable activities with you. </li> <li> Help you with your daily needs until you are able to care for these on your own. </li> <li> Help you with relaxation exercises, controlled breathing exercise, or visualizing pleasant scenes. </li> <li> Help you with situations or chores that you feel are stressful, such as going for doctor visits, paying bills, or doing household chores. </li> <li> Communicate with your healthcare providers if you feel you need that. </li></ul></p><a name="6"></a><h1>How can I talk to my family members about my depression?</h1><p>Here are some ideas that may help you talk to family members and friends:<ul> <li> Try to describe your depression and how it affects you. </li> <li> Ask your family members and friends for ideas to help you deal with your depression. </li> <li> Be open and honest about your feelings with your family members. </li></ul></p><a name="7"></a><h1>What should I report to my healthcare provider about my depression?</h1><p>Below is a list of symptoms for depression or sadness. If you have five or more symptoms on this list (must include item 1 or 2 on the list), then you should contact your healthcare provider for further information.<br /><br /><b>Summary Of The Symptoms Of Depression</b><br /><br /><b>If...</b> There is no physical illness of the brain or psychiatric illness;<br /><br /><b>Then...</b> depression consists of five of these symptoms present for two weeks (one of them must be item 1 or 2): <ol> <li> Depressed mood every day for most of the day. </li> <li> Very little interest or pleasure in most activities nearly every day for most of the day. </li> <li> Noticeable weight loss or weight gain - or a major change in appetite. </li> <li> Sleep disturbance: not being able to get to sleep or waking early or being very sleepy nearly every day. </li> <li> Feeling agitated, or feeling slowed-down nearly every day. </li> <li> Feeling excessively tired or lacking in energy nearly every day. </li> <li> Feeling worthless or guilty nearly every day. </li> <li> Feeling unable to concentrate or make decisions. </li> <li> Frequent thoughts of death or suicide. </li></ol></p><a name="8"></a><h1>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about my depression?</h1><p>If you are experiencing depression, you should discuss the following with your healthcare provider at your next appointment:<ul> <li> How can I recognize the symptoms of depression? </li> <li> How will you determine if I am depressed and need help? </li> <li> Could my cancer or treatment be causing or contributing to my feelings of depression? </li> <li> Will treating my depression interfere with my cancer treatment? </li> <li> Can you refer me to a social worker or other reliable sources of information about counseling and support groups? </li></ul></p><a name="9"></a><h1>Where can I get more information?</h1><p>For more information, contact the people or organizations at the numbers or websites listed below:<ul> <li> Contact your healthcare provider. </li> <li> American Cancer Society:  1-800-ACS-2345 or <a href=http://www.cancer.org target=_blank>http://www.cancer.org</a> Click on patients, family and friends, then click on coping with physical and emotional changes. </li> <li> Family Care Research Program: <a href=http://www.cancercare.msu.edu target=_blank>http://www.cancercare.msu.edu</a> </li> <li> National Coalition For Cancer Survivorship: <a href=http://canceradvocacy.org target=_blank>http://canceradvocacy.org</a> Click on learn /symptom management then issues of heart and mind. </li> <li> Oncology Nursing Society: 1-866-257-4ONS or <a href=http://www.cancersymptoms.org target=_blank>http://www.cancersymptoms.org</a> Click on reference for side effects. </li> <li> The National Cancer Institute: 1-800-4-CANCER or <a href=http://cancer.gov/cancerinfo target=_blank>http://cancer.gov/cancerinfo</a> Click on coping with cancer. </li> <li> Healthy Place: <a href=http://www.healthyplace.com/ target=_blank>http://www.healthyplace.com/</a> </li> <li> People living with cancer: <a href=http://www.plwc.org/depression target=_blank>http://www.plwc.org/depression</a> </li> <li> The National Institutes Of Mental Health: <a href=http://www.nimh.nih.gov target=_blank>http://www.nimh.nih.gov</a> </li></ul></p><a name="10"></a><h1>References</h1><p><ul> <li> Edwards, B. & Clarke, V. (2004). The psychological impact of a cancer diagnosis on families: the influence of family functioning and patients\' illness characteristics on depression and anxiety. Psycho-Oncology, 13, 562-576. </li> <li> National Cancer Institute(n.d.) Retrieved from: <a href=http://www.cancer.gov target=_blank>http://www.cancer.gov</a> </li> <li> National Coalition Of Cancer Survivorship (2008). Retrieved from <a href=http://canceradvocacy.org target=_blank>http://canceradvocacy.org</a> </li> <li> Van Fleet, S. (2006). Assessment and pharmacotherapy of depression. Clinical Journal Of Oncology Nursing, (10) 2, 158-161. </li></ul></p><a name="11"></a><h1>Supportive evidence-based practice</h1><p><ul> <li> Fulcher, C. (2006). Depression management during cancer treatment. Oncology Nursing Forum, (33) 1, 33-35. </li> <li> Fulcher, C.D., Badger, T., Gunter, A.K., Marrs, J.A. & Reese, J.M. (2008). Putting evidence into practice: Interventions for depression. Clinical journal of oncology nursing, 12 (1), 131-140. </li> <li> Reuter, K. & Harte, M. (2004). The concepts of fatigue and depression in cancer. European Journal Of Cancer, 38, 1447-1457. </li> <li> Sloman, R. (2002). Relaxation and imagery for anxiety and depression control in community patients with advanced cancer. Cancer Nursing, 25 (6), 432-435. </li></ul></p>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a>\r\n\r\n<div id="credit"><p>This information was developed in collaboration with Michigan State University and the Behavioral Cooperative Oncology Group.</p></div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->'),
(100300101804, 'Diarrhea', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\n<h1>Diarrhea</h1>\n\n<div id="symptomtext">\n\n<ul><li><a href=#1>What is diarrhea?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#2>How do people describe diarrhea?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#3>What causes diarrhea?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#4>What can I do about diarrhea?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#5>What can family members and friends do to help me with my diarrhea?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#6>How can I talk to my family members and friends about my diarrhea?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#7>What should I report to my healthcare provider about my diarrhea?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#8>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider? </a></li>\n<li><a href=#9>Where can I get more information?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#10>References</a></li>\n<li><a href=#11>Supportive evidence-based practice</a></li>\n</ul><br />\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What is diarrhea?</h1><p>Diarrhea is defined as three or more loose or watery stools (bowel movements) per day. Stool is what is left after your digestive system (stomach, small intestine, and colon) absorbs nutrients and fluid from what you eat and drink. When fluid is not absorbed or if your digestive system produces extra fluid, stools will be loose and watery. Loose stools are larger than usual, and people with diarrhea may pass more than a quart of watery stool a day. Severe or untreated diarrhea can lead to dehydration, which means the body does not have enough fluid to function properly.<br /><br />If left untreated diarrhea may cause dizziness, fainting, weight loss, dry skin, and weakness. Replacing fluids is the primary treatment for diarrhea.</p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>How do people describe diarrhea?</h1><p>People who have diarrhea may also have abdominal pain with cramping, bloating, and nausea. It is often described as having an urgent need to have a bowel movement and an inability to control it. People usually use the terms "loose" and "watery" stools, and report the number of times they have to use the bathroom within a period of time.<br /><br />Diarrhea can be mild (3 stools per day) to severe (12 or more stools per day). As a result, skin irritation and soreness around the rectum can occur.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>What causes diarrhea?</h1><p>Diarrhea can be caused by chemotherapy or radiation treatments to the abdomen, pelvis, or rectum. Treatments for cancer can interfere with normal bowel function, increase bowel activity, or by irritate the lining of the bowel. Loose or watery stools can start shortly after receiving treatment or up to two weeks later.  Other common causes of diarrhea include: antibiotics, infections, reactions to foods, or laxatives taken to prevent constipation.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>What can I do about diarrhea?</h1><p>Here are some tips you may find helpful:<br /><br /><h2>ACTIVITY</h2><ul> <li> Keep track of the number of stools you have within a 24 hour-period.  Also, record any cramping or gas pains in a diary. </li> <li> Diarrhea can cause pain and soreness to the skin around the rectum.  Clean the area often with unscented baby oil or baby wipes.  The aloe in baby wipes can be very soothing.  Use the wipes instead of toilet paper to gently wipe the rectal area.  Take warm baths or sitz baths 3-4 times a day.  Sit in the warm water for about 10 minutes.  Use Desitin&#174; or A&D&#174; ointment on the skin after each bowel movement. </li></ul><br /><h2>COMMUNICATION</h2><ul> <li> Contact your doctor or nurse to prescribe something for your diarrhea if over-the counter-medications do not work. </li></ul><br /><h2>DIET</h2><ul> <li> Try eating smaller, more frequent meals or snacks. </li> <li> Try eating foods such as: bananas, rice or oats, applesauce, smooth peanut butter, graham crackers, dry toast, crackers, plain pasta, eggs, poultry or baked potatoes. </li> <li> Avoid eating food that is high in fiber, fatty, or spicy.  Try not to eat rich desserts.  Examples of foods that can increase bowels movements or gas include: beans, raw vegetables, corn, cauliflower, broccoli, and hot peppers. </li> <li> Do not drink alcoholic beverages. </li> <li> Follow a low fiber/ low roughage diet.  Do not eat wheat and bran. </li> <li> Drink 8 (8oz.) glasses of water or other non-caffeinated drinks every day.  Avoid caffeine (e.g., colas, coffee) when possible.  Caffeine can cause dehydration. </li> <li> Replace lost fluids with nonfat broth, soup, orange juice, Pedialyte&#174; or sports drinks like Gatorade&#174;. </li> <li> When having diarrhea, drink less fluid with your meals.  Drink more fluid between meals and avoid hot liquids. </li> <li> Avoid nuts and dried fruits. </li> <li> Avoid milk products (including ice cream and cheese) until diarrhea subsides. </li></ul><br /><h2>MEDICATIONS</h2><ul> <li> Talk to your doctor or nurse about taking over-the-counter medications, such as Imodium&#174; AD, Kaopectate&#174;, Pepto-Bismol&#174; or Maalox&#174; antidiarrheal caplets (loperamide). </li> <li> Talk to your doctor or nurse before using any creams or ointments if you are receiving radiation treatments to the abdomen, pelvis, or rectal area. </li></ul></p><a name="5"></a><h1>What can family members and friends do to help me with my diarrhea?</h1><p>Ask family members and friends to:<ul> <li> Buy food that can help decrease diarrhea.  Food items are listed above. </li> <li> Remind you to take your over-the-counter medicines as directed by your healthcare provider. </li> <li> Prepare low fiber meals. </li> <li> Offer you fluids and broth throughout the day. </li> <li> Assist in locating restrooms when outside your normal environment. </li> <li> Help with keeping a log or record of your bowel movements and symptoms. This log or record will help your medical team better understand and treat your diarrhea. Try to log the number of stools, time of day, whether stools were formed or watery, any cramping you experienced, and your daily weight.  Also record if any medication was taken and fluid intake. </li></ul></p><a name="6"></a><h1>How can I talk to my family members and friends about my diarrhea?</h1><p>Here are some ideas that may help you talk to family members and friends:<ul> <li> Request privacy to discuss your concerns. </li> <li> Try to describe how the diarrhea makes you feel and express your concerns. </li> <li> Tell them if you are having any symptoms listed below. </li></ul></p><a name="7"></a><h1>What should I report to my healthcare provider about my diarrhea?</h1><p>If you experience any of the following symptoms, report them to your healthcare provider:<ul> <li> Skin around the rectum that is open, sore, or tender. </li> <li> Spike a fever of 100.4  (38.0 C) associated with diarrhea. </li> <li> Bloody or black tarry looking stools. </li> <li> Unable to eat or drink for more than 24 hours. </li> <li> Diarrhea that continues for more than 3 days. </li> <li> Being thirsty. </li> <li> Feeling tired or dizzy. </li> <li> Fainting. </li> <li> Weakness. </li> <li> Urinating less often than usual. </li> <li> Having dark yellow colored urine. </li> <li> Severe abdominal cramps or pain. </li> <li> Heart palpations (heart racing when you are at rest). </li> <li> Have your log or record available with the following information: </li><br /><ul> <li> Your normal bowel pattern.</li> <li>Color, consistency, and number of stools in the last 24 hours.</li> <li>How much food and fluid you have taken in the last 1-2 days.</li> <li>Medicines that you have taken in the last 2-3 days.</li> <li>Any history of past bowel problems.</li> <li>If you are being treated with radiation therapy to the pelvis, abdomen, or rectum.</li> <li>Weight loss.</ul></ul></p><a name="8"></a><h1>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider?</h1><p>If you are experiencing diarrhea, you should discuss the following with your healthcare provider at your next appointment:<ul> <li> Does my chemotherapy medication cause diarrhea? If so, how is it usually controlled? </li> <li> Will my radiation/chemotherapy cause me to have diarrhea? </li> <li> How long does the diarrhea usually last? </li> <li> Do I need to be on a low fiber diet? </li> <li> When do you want me to notify you if I develop diarrhea? </li></ul></p><a name="9"></a><h1>Where can I get more information?</h1><p>For more information, contact the people or organizations at the numbers or websites listed below:<ul> <li> The American Cancer Society: 1-800-ACS-2345 or <a href=http://www.cancer.org target=_blank>http://www.cancer.org</a> Type in the word, "diarrhea". </li> <li> The National Cancer Institute: 1-800-4-CANCER or  <a href=http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo/ target=_blank>http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo/</a>  Click on coping with cancer then side effects then click on gastrointestinal complications. </li> <li> The National Institutes for Health: <a href=http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus target=_blank>http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus</a> Click on diarrhea. </li> <li> CancerCare: <a href=http://www.cancercare.org target=_blank>http://www.cancercare.org</a> Click on "I am a person with cancer" Then click on "Education" then select "Connect booklets" and choose "Managing side effects."  </li> <li> The Family Care Research Program on the Internet at: <a href=http://www.cancercare.msu.edu target=_blank>http://www.cancercare.msu.edu</a> </li></ul></p><a name="10"></a><h1>References</h1><p><ul> <li> Engelking, C. (2003). Diarrhea. In C.H. Yarbro, M.H. Frogge, & M. Goodman (Eds.), Cancer Symptom Management, 3rd Ed. (Pp. 528-558). Boston: Jones And Bartlett. </li> <li> Korrnblau, S., Benson, A.B., Catalano, R., Champlin, R.E., Engelking, C. Field, M., et al. (2000). Management of cancer treatment related diarrhea: Issues and therapeutic strategies. Journal of pain and symptom management, 19(2), 118-129. </li> <li> Saltz, L.B. (2003). Understanding and managing chemotherapy-induced diarrhea.  Journal of Supportive Oncology, 1(1) 35-46. </li> <li> National Cancer Institute At: <a href=http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo/ target=_blank>http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo/</a> Click on coping with cancer then side effects then click on gastrointestinal complications. </li></ul></p><a name="11"></a><h1>Supportive evidence-based practice</h1><p><ul> <li> Anthony, L. (2003). New strategies for the prevention and reduction of cancer treatment induced diarrhea. Seminars In Oncology Nursing, 19(4), Suppl 3: 17-21. </li> <li> Gwede, G. K. (2003). Overview of radiation and chemoradiation-induced diarrhea. Seminars In Oncology Nursing, 19(4), Suppl 3: 6-10. </li> <li> Kornblau, S., Benson, A. B., Catalano, R., Et Al. (2000). Management of cancer treatment-related diarrhea: issues and therapeutic strategies. Journal Of Pain And Symptom Management, 19(2): 118-29. </li> <li> Stern, J. & Ippoliti C. (2003). Management of acute cancer treatment-induced diarrhea. Seminars In Oncology Nursing, 19(4), Suppl 3: 11-16. </li> <li> Viele C. S. (2003). Overview of chemotherapy-induced diarrhea. Seminars In Oncology Nursing, 19(4), Suppl 3: 2-5. </li></ul></p>\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a>\n\n<div id="credit"><p>This information was developed in collaboration with Michigan State University and the Behavioral Cooperative Oncology Group.</p></div>\n\n</div>\n\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->'),
(100300102104, 'Anxiety', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\n<h1>Anxiety</h1>\n\n<div id="symptomtext">\n\n<ul><li><a href=#1>What is anxiety (distress)?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#2>How do people describe anxiety?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#3>What causes anxiety?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#4>What can I do about anxiety?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#5>What can family members and friends do to help me with my anxiety?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#6>How can I talk to my family members about my anxiety?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#7>What should I report to my healthcare provider about my anxiety?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#8>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about my anxiety?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#9>Where can I get more information?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#10>References</a></li>\n<li><a href=#11>Supportive evidence-based practice</a></li>\n</ul><br />\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What is anxiety (distress)?</h1><p>Anxiety is a vague feeling of uneasiness, unpleasant feelings, or fear resulting from expecting some bad news or harm. Anxiety can happen to anyone. Persons with cancer who have had surgery, chemotherapy, or radiation may get anxious more easily than others. Anxiety and fear are common and normal feelings that patients have when coping with the diagnosis or treatment of cancer.</p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>How do people describe anxiety?</h1><p>People who have anxiety say they feel uneasy, tension, apprehensive, wary, and agitated. They have a feeling of restlessness, uncertainty, and are fearful or have a sense of dread or impending doom.<br /><br />People tremble, sweat, or have rapid breathing, rapid heart rate, or heart pounding in the chest. In addition, some people experience shakiness, or difficulty falling asleep. Sometimes people may become overly fearful and may no longer cope well with his or her day-to-day life.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>What causes anxiety?</h1><p>Many different things can cause people to feel anxious. Symptoms that are not under control, such as pain or nausea, can make a person feel anxious or "sick to his/her stomach". Loss of control from disease or treatment can also make a person feel anxious.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>What can I do about anxiety?</h1><p>No two people experience anxiety in the same way. Here are some tips people have found helpful: <br /><br /><h2>ACTIVITY</h2><ul> <li> Exercise can help bring calm as it reduces tension.  Try walking or yoga. </li></ul><br /><h2>COMMUNICATION</h2><ul> <li> Talk with your doctor or nurse about prescribing medicine to help reduce your anxiety. </li></ul><br /><h2>DIET</h2><ul> <li> Limit your caffeine intake by decreasing your intake of coffee, soda pop, tea, and chocolate. </li></ul><br /><h2>MEDICATIONS</h2><ul> <li> Medications may also be needed to help control anxiety. IF they are needed, they should be tailored to your situation, taking into account your treatment and other medical conditions. </li></ul><br /><h2>PSYCHOLOGICAL</h2><ul> <li> Try to identify what "triggers" your anxiety. </li> <li> List coping strategies that have helped in the past. </li> <li> Talk with others, such as in a support group, about your anxiety. </li> <li> Increase pleasurable, distracting activities such as listening to favorite music. </li> <li> Use relaxation techniques, such as controlled breathing or guided imagery (picture a pleasant scene in your mind). </li> <li> Be around others as much as possible, if this is relaxing. </li> <li> Use prayer or other types of spiritual support, such as meditation. </li> <li> Use relaxation tapes. </li> <li> Ask your doctor for a counseling referral if these tips are not helpful. </li> <li> Keeping a daily written record of your life and experiences with cancer can reduce anxiety for some people. </li></ul></p><a name="5"></a><h1>What can family members and friends do to help me with my anxiety?</h1><p>Ask family members and friends to: <ul> <li> Help you with relaxation exercises, such as deep breathing or visualizing pleasant scenery. </li> <li> Help you with situations or chores that you\'ve identified as stressful, such as accompanying you to doctors\' appointments. </li> <li> Bring home books that teach relaxation exercises or guided imagery from the library or bookstore. </li></ul></p><a name="6"></a><h1>How can I talk to my family members about my anxiety?</h1><p>Here are some ideas that may help you talk to family members and friends:<ul> <li> Be open and honest about your feelings and concerns with your family members. </li> <li> Try to describe your feelings when you\'re experiencing them (racing thoughts, lump in your throat, nausea, shortness of breath, dizzy or scared). </li> <li> Ask you family members and friends how your anxiety is affecting them. </li></ul></p><a name="7"></a><h1>What should I report to my healthcare provider about my anxiety?</h1><p>If you experience any of the following symptoms, report them to your healthcare provider:<ul> <li> Depression that last longer than 2 weeks. </li> <li> Trouble eating (a noticeable decrease in appetite, or no appetite, for a period of weeks). </li> <li> Persistent fearfulness. </li> <li> Shortness of breath that lasts for a period of time. </li> <li> Persistent problems sleeping or getting to sleep. </li> <li> Heart racing or beating hard in the chest. </li> <li> No relief after trying relaxation techniques. </li> <li> Excessive sweating.</ul></p><a name="8"></a><h1>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about my anxiety?</h1><p>If you are experiencing anxiety, you should discuss the following with your healthcare provider at your next appointment:<ul> <li> How can I recognize the symptoms of anxiety? </li> <li> Could my cancer or treatment be causing or contributing to my feelings of anxiety? </li> <li> Will treating my anxiety interfere with my cancer treatment? </li> <li> Can you refer me to a social worker or other reliable sources of information about counseling and support groups? </li> <li> Are the medications prescribed to me likely to cause anxiety? </li></ul></p><a name="9"></a><h1>Where can I get more information?</h1><p>For more information, contact the people or organizations at the numbers or websites listed below:<ul> <li> Contact your healthcare provider. </li> <li> American Cancer Society: 1-800-ACS-2345 or <a href=http://www.cancer.org target=_blank>http://www.cancer.org</a>  Click on patients, family, and friends, click on coping with physical and emotional changes. </li> <li> The Family Care Research Program: <a href=http://www.cancercare.msu.edu target=_blank>http://www.cancercare.msu.edu</a> </li> <li> The National Coalition for Cancer Survivorship: <a href=http://canceradvocacy.org target=_blank>http://canceradvocacy.org</a> Click on Learn /Symptom management then issues of heart and mind. </li> <li> Oncology Nursing Society: 1-866-257-4ONS or <a href=http://www.cancersymptoms.org target=_blank>http://www.cancersymptoms.org</a> </li> <li> The National Cancer Institute: 1-800-4-CANCER or <a href=http://cancer.gov/cancerinfo target=_blank>http://cancer.gov/cancerinfo</a> Click on coping with cancer. </li> <li> The National Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Patient Guidelines: <a href=http://www.nccn.org/patients/patient_gls.asp target=_blank>http://www.nccn.org/patients/patient_gls.asp</a> Go to supportive care and then distress. </li> <li> OncoLink&#174; (Abramson Cancer Center of the University Of Pennsylvania): <a href=http://www.oncolink.upenn.edu target=_blank>http://www.oncolink.upenn.edu</a> </li></ul></p><a name="10"></a><h1>References</h1><p><ul> <li> Edwards, B. & Clarke, V. (2004). The psychological impact of a cancer diagnosis on families: the influence of family functioning and patients\' illness characteristics on depression and anxiety. Psychooncology, 13, 562-576. </li> <li> Gobel, B.H. (2003). Anxiety. In C.H. Yarbro, M.H. Frogge, & M. Goodman (Eds.), Cancer Symptom Management, 3rd Ed. (Pp. 651-667). Boston: Jones And Bartlett. </li> <li> Madden, J. (2006). The problem of distress in patients with cancer: more effective assessment. Clinical Journal Of Oncology Nursing, 10, 615-619. </li> <li> National Cancer Institute at: <a href=http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo/ target=_blank>http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo/</a> </li> <li> National Coalition of Cancer Survivorship at: <a href=http://canceradvocacy.org target=_blank>http://canceradvocacy.org</a> </li> <li> Rawl, S.M., Given, B.A., Given, C.W., Champion, V., Kozachik, S.L., Barton, D., Emsley, C.L., & Williams, S.D. (2002). Intervention to improve psychological functioning for newly diagnosed patients with cancer. Oncology Nursing Forum, 29(6), 967-75. </li> <li> Sivesind, D., & Baile, W.F. (2001). The psychologic distress in patients with cancer. Nursing Clinics Of North America, 36(4), 809-25. </li> <li> Stark, D., Kiely, M., Smith, A., Velikova, G., House, A. & Selby, P. (2002). Anxiety disorders in cancer patients: their nature, associations, and relations to quality of life. Journal of Clinical Oncology, 20 (14), 3137-3148. </li></ul></p><a name="11"></a><h1>Supportive evidence-based practice</h1><p><ul> <li> Sloman, R. (2002). Relaxation and imagery for anxiety and depression control in community patients with advanced cancer. Cancer Nursing, 25 (6), 432-435. </li> <li> Smith, M.C., Kemp, J., Hemphill, L., & Vojir, C. P. (2002). Outcomes of the therapeutic massage for hospitalized cancer patients. Journal Of Nursing Scholarship, 34 (3), 257-262. </li></ul></p>\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a>\n\n<div id="credit"><p>This information was developed in collaboration with Michigan State University and the Behavioral Cooperative Oncology Group.</p></div>\n\n</div>\n\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->'),
(100300102404, 'Dry Mouth', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Dry Mouth</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext">\r\n\r\n<ul><li><a href=#1>What is dry mouth?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>How do people describe dry mouth?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>What causes dry mouth?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>What can I do about dry mouth?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>How is dry mouth managed?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What can family members and friends do to help me with my dry mouth?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#7>How can I talk to my family and friends about my dry mouth?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#8>What should I report to my healthcare provider about my dry mouth?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#9>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about my dry mouth?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#10>Where can I get more information?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#11>References</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#12>Supportive evidence-based practice</a></li>\r\n</ul><br />\r\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What is dry mouth?</h1><p>Dry mouth is an excessive or abnormal dryness of the mouth related to a decrease in the amount of saliva. Saliva lubricates and moistens the mouth.  It is essential for chewing, tasting, swallowing, and talking. The enzymes in saliva help the body to digest food and protect teeth from cavities.</p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>How do people describe dry mouth?</h1><p>Dry mouth is sometimes described as "cotton mouth".  Some people say that their tongue sticks to the inside of their cheek.  Burning and cracks in the tongue may occur.  Saliva may feel dry, thick and/or ropey.  A dry mouth can make it difficult to chew and swallow food.  Changes in taste may occur.  Speech may be altered.<br /><br />Dry mouth also increases your risk of infection and can cause dental cavities. Using tobacco products and drinking alcoholic beverages can make these symptoms worse.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>What causes dry mouth?</h1><p>Dry mouth can be troubling side effect that people being treated for cancer sometimes experience.  It can be cause by a number of factors such as:<ul> <li> Medications: chemotherapy, pain medications, diuretics (water-pills), medications for anxiety, depression and nausea. Over-the-counter allergy, cough, cold and flu medications can also cause a dry mouth. </li> <li> Radiation therapy can cause dry mouth after the salivary glands have been exposed to radiation. The salivary glands are responsible for producing saliva in the mouth.  After a period of time, the salivary glands may start to work again but they rarely return to normal function. Dry mouth caused by radiation to the salivary glands can be a life-long problem. If you are scheduled to undergo radiation of the head and neck should have a thorough mouth exam by your dentist prior radiation treatment. </li> <li> Conditions, such as dehydration or fungal infection of the mouth (candiasis), can cause dry mouth. </li> <li> Surgery to the salivary glands may cause dry mouth. </li></ul></p><a name="4"></a><h1>What can I do about dry mouth?</h1><p>Treatment for dry mouth varies depending on the underlying cause, such as dehydration, infection or medications. Dry mouth caused by damage to the salivary gland may be a life-long problem and require patience to treat. There are a lot of treatments to relieve dry mouth symptoms.<br /><br />Here are some tips you may find helpful: <br /><br /><h2>ACTIVITY</h2><ul> <li> Rinse mouth with water frequently.  Do this every two hours while awake.  Adding salt or baking soda (1/2 to 1 teaspoon in 8 ounces of water) can help. </li> <li> Inspect your mouth daily for signs of infection (such as redness, swelling, and white or red patches). Tell your healthcare provider if you notice any of these signs. </li> <li> Clean dentures and /or bridge after eating.  Do not put your dentures in if you are experiencing any discomfort caused by dry mouth. </li> <li> Use a soft bristled toothbrush to clean teeth after each meal and at bedtime. </li> <li> Use cool air, vaporized, or humidifiers. </li></ul><br /><h2>COMMUNICATION</h2><ul> <li> Talk to your dentist about daily fluoride treatments if you are receiving radiation therapy. Fluoride treatments may help reduce the risk of tooth decay. </li></ul><br /><h2>DIET</h2><ul> <li> Suck on non-irritating hard candy like lemon drops or jolly ranchers (sugar-free is best) chewing gum may also help. </li> <li> Drink 8 (8oz.) glasses of water or other non-caffeinated drinks every day.  Avoid caffeine (i.e. colas, coffee) when possible.  Caffeine can cause dehydration.  This also helps to loosen mucous. </li> <li> Carry a water bottle with you and sip frequently during the day to help keep the might moist. </li> <li> Limit coffee, tea, and alcohol.  These contribute to dry mouth. </li> <li> Avoid dry, sticky foods such as peanut butter. </li> <li> Do not eat or drink spicy or acidic products, such as salsa or citrus juices. </li> <li> Add liquids to solid foods to make them more tolerable (gravies, melted butter, yogurt, or mayonnaise). </li> <li> Milk is high in protein but may produce thick saliva.  If this is true for you, try soy or rice milk. </li></ul><br /><h2>MEDICATIONS</h2><ul> <li> Avoid mouth rinse products that have glycerin or alcohol as they can cause drying. </li> <li> Use saliva substitutes, which are available in the drug store without a prescription. (e.g., Biotene&#174;, Oral Balance&#174;, Moist Plus&#174;, and Salivant&#174;) </li><br /><ul> <li> Biotene&#174; products treat dry mouth. Examples of Biotene&#174; products include mouthwash, toothpaste, and chewing gum.</li> <li>Oral Balance&#174; is a type of moisturizing gel that can be applied to the mouth or tongue.</ul></ul></p><a name="5"></a><h1>How is dry mouth managed?</h1><p>If dry mouth is due to dehydration (not enough fluids) your healthcare provider may recommend intravenous (IV) fluids. For dry mouth caused by infection, or damage to the salivary glands your healthcare provider may prescribe: <ul> <li> Antifungals: Clortrimizole&#174;, Fluconozole&#174;, Nystatin&#174;, Diflucan&#174;. </li> <li> Antivirals: Acyclovir (Zovirax&#174;) or Famiciclovir (Famvir&#174;). </li> <li> Antibacterials: antiseptic mouthwash rinses. </li> <li> Pilocarpine tablets (Salagen&#174;): helps stimulate the salivary glands to produce saliva. </li></ul></p><a name="6"></a><h1>What can family members and friends do to help me with my dry mouth?</h1><p>Ask family members and friends to: <ul> <li> Encourage you to sip fluids throughout the day. </li> <li> Prepare foods that are soft and easy to swallow. </li> <li> Buy hard candy or sugarless gum for you. </li></ul></p><a name="7"></a><h1>How can I talk to my family and friends about my dry mouth?</h1><p>Here are some ideas that may help you talk to family members and friends:<ul> <li> Explain to them how the dry mouth is affecting your ability to eat and how you are feeling. </li> <li> Ask for suggestions on how to improve your dry mouth. </li></ul></p><a name="8"></a><h1>What should I report to my healthcare provider about my dry mouth?</h1><p>If you experience any of the following symptoms, report them to your healthcare provider:<ul> <li> Any new swelling, sores, white patches, redness, or bleeding in your mouth lasting more than 24 hours. </li> <li> Any new fever reading above 100.9 F (38.3 C), or a temperature higher than 100.4 F (38.0 C) that lasts for more than an hour. </li> <li> Inability to eat any food for 48 hours. </li> <li> Inability to swallow or talk. </li> <li> Difficulty breathing. </li> <li> Burning tongue. </li> <li> Difficulty chewing solid or soft foods due to dryness. </li> <li> Difficulty swallowing because it goes down the wrong way and causes choking. </li></ul></p><a name="9"></a><h1>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about my dry mouth?</h1><p>If you are experiencing dry mouth, you should discuss the following with your healthcare provider at your next appointment:<ul> <li> Am I at risk for having permanent damage to my salivary glands? </li> <li> Specifically, how do you recommend that I handle my dry mouth on a daily basis? </li> <li> How will I know if I have an infection? </li> <li> How will I know if I am dehydrated? </li> <li> Will my cancer treatment cause me to have a dry mouth? And how long will it last? </li></ul></p><a name="10"></a><h1>Where can I get more information?</h1><p>For more information, contact the people or organizations at the numbers or websites listed below:<ul> <li> Contact your healthcare provider. </li> <li> Contact your family dentist. </li> <li> American Cancer Society: 1-800-ACS-2345 or  <a href=http://www.cancer.org target=_blank>http://www.cancer.org</a> </li> <li> National Cancer Institute: 1-800-4-CANCER or <a href=http://cancer.gov/cancerinfo/ target=_blank>http://cancer.gov/cancerinfo/</a> Click on coping with cancer. Find and click on oral complications. </li> <li> The Family Care Research Program: <a href=http://www.cancercare.msu.edu target=_blank>http://www.cancercare.msu.edu</a> </li> <li> The National Coalition For Cancer Survivorship: <a href=http://canceradvocacy.org target=_blank>http://canceradvocacy.org</a> Click on learn then side effects. </li> <li> Chemocare: <a href=http://chemocare.com target=_blank>http://chemocare.com</a> Click on managing side effects. </li></ul></p><a name="11"></a><h1>References</h1><p><ul> <li> Berk, L., B. (2005). Pathophysiology and management of radiation-induced xerostomia. The Journal Of Supportive Oncology, (3) 3, 191-200. </li> <li> Davidson, D. (2006). Oral mucositis. Clinical Journal Of Oncology Nursing, 10 (2), 283-284. </li> <li> Iwamoto, R. (1999). In C. Yarbro, M. Frogge, & M. Goodman (Eds.) Cancer Symptom Management, (pp. 264-272). Sudbury, Massachusetts; Jones And Bartlett Publishers. </li> <li> Maher, K. (2003). Xerostomia. In C.H. Yarbro, M.H. Frogge, & M. Goodman (Eds.), Cancer Symptom Management, 3rd Ed. (Pp. 215-229). Boston: Jones And Bartlett. </li> <li> National Cancer Institute At: <a href=http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo/ target=_blank>http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo/</a> Click on coping with cancer. Find and click on oral complications (professional). </li> <li> Peterson, D., E. (2006). New strategies for management of oral mucositis in cancer patients. The Journal Of Supportive Oncology, (4) 2 Suppl. 1, 9-13. </li></ul></p><a name="12"></a><h1>Supportive evidence-based practice</h1><p><ul> <li> Cawley, M., M. & Benson, L., M. (2005). Current trends in managing oral mucositis. Clinical Journal Of Oncology Nursing, 9 (5), 584-592. </li> <li> Milligan, S., Mcgill, M., Sweeney, M.,P., & Malarkey, C. (2001). Oral care for people with advanced cancer: an evidence-based protocol. International Journal Of Palliative Nursing, 7(9), 418-26. </li></ul></p>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a>\r\n\r\n<div id="credit"><p>This information was developed in collaboration with Michigan State University and the Behavioral Cooperative Oncology Group.</p></div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->');
