(100300102704, 'Fatigue', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Fatigue</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext">\r\n\r\n<ul><li><a href=#1>What is fatigue?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>How do people describe fatigue?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>What causes fatigue?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>What can I do about fatigue?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What can family members and friends do to help me with my fatigue?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>How can I talk with family members and friends about my fatigue?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#7>What should I report to my healthcare provider? </a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#8>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#9>Where can I get more information?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#10>References</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#11>Supportive evidence-based practice</a></li>\r\n</ul><br />\r\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What is fatigue?</h1><p>Fatigue is an overwhelming sense of exhaustion. It is a decreased ability to do physical and mental work, regardless of enough sleep. People have less energy to do the things that they normally do. Fatigue is one of the most common side effects of cancer treatment, regardless of whether the treatment is radiation, or chemotherapy. It is more severe and distressing than everyday fatigue. Fatigue that is caused by cancer treatments can exist beyond the end of treatment. </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>How do people describe fatigue?</h1><p>Those who experience fatigue often report having no energy for usual daily activities. Some say that their arms and legs feel heavy.  Others describe fatigue as feeling tired, weak, exhausted, worn-out, slow, or unable to concentrate. Rest does not always relieve it. People sometimes have feelings of sadness, irritability, or frustration.  They may tire easily even after napping or getting a good night\'s sleep. </p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>What causes fatigue?</h1><p>Fatigue can result from cancer therapy, emotional stress, spending too much time in bed, or from not getting enough exercise.  It can be caused by anemia (low red blood cell count), infections, poor nutrition, and pain. <br /><br />It is very important that you discuss fatigue with your healthcare provider. Fatigue can affect your quality of life, mood, relationships, job performance, and can even interfere with your treatment. </p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>What can I do about fatigue?</h1><p>It may not be possible to prevent fatigue caused by cancer and its treatment. However, you can take steps to help manage this side effect. <br /><br />Here are some tips you might find helpful: <br /><br /><h2>ACTIVITY</h2><ul> <li> Take short naps (30-45 minutes) in the late morning or early afternoon. </li> <li> Avoid long periods of bed rest. </li> <li> Manage other side effects that can make fatigue worse such as pain, anemia, sleep problems, infections, and emotional stress. </li> <li> Exercise every day.  Talk to your healthcare provider about what exercises are right for you. </li> <li> Conserve your energy.  Plan your activities around times when you usually have the most energy. </li> <li> Set priorities for your activities. </li> <li> Delegate activities to other people that you do not need to do yourself. </li></ul><br /><h2>COMMUNICATION</h2><ul> <li> Ask your healthcare provider about: </li><br /><ul> <li> Massage and healing touch as a therapy for your fatigue.</li> <li>Getting a referral to a physical therapist for help developing an exercise plan.</li> <li>Seeing a nutritionist for recommendations on nutritional supplements.</li> <li>Educational information about fatigue.</ul></ul><br /><h2>DIET</h2><ul> <li> Eat a diet with fresh fruits and vegetables, and lean meat/fish/chicken, and milk products (as recommended by your healthcare provider).  You need to eat for energy and good nutrition. </li></ul><br /><h2>MEDICATION</h2><ul> <li> Ask your healthcare provider if psychostimulants or antidepressants are right for you. These medications are prescribed by doctors. They can improve your mood, energy levels, and outlook on life. </li></ul><br /><h2>PSYCHOLOGICAL</h2><ul> <li> Consider learning relaxation therapy, guided imagery and meditation. </li> <li> Join a support group. Support groups can provide suggestions and reassurance in a safe environment.  You can share similar concerns with other people experiencing fatigue. </li></ul></p><a name="5"></a><h1>What can family members and friends do to help me with my fatigue?</h1><p>Ask family members and friends to:<ul> <li> Help you with housework, chores, yard work or cooking. </li> <li> Take a walk with you and encourage you to walk every day. </li> <li> Offer you fluids throughout the day to increase your fluid intake. </li> <li> Help you set daily priorities. </li></ul></p><a name="6"></a><h1>How can I talk with family members and friends about my fatigue?</h1><p>Here are some ideas that may help you talk to family members and friends:<ul> <li> Be open and honest about your feelings.  Let them know how your fatigue is affecting your life. </li> <li> Ask them for ideas to manage or decrease your fatigue. </li> <li> Ask your family members and friends how your fatigue is affecting them. </li></ul></p><a name="7"></a><h1>What should I report to my healthcare provider?</h1><p>If you experience any of the following symptoms, report them to your healthcare provider:<ul> <li> A temperature above 100.9 F (38.3 C), or a temperature higher than 100.4 F (38.0 C) which lasts for more than an hour. Call your healthcare provider. </li> <li> Unable to get out of bed for 24 hours. </li> <li> Unable to think clearly or focus on things such as watching TV, talking, or reading. </li> <li> Unable to do any of your usual daily activities. </li> <li> Severe chills or sweats. </li> <li> Shortness of breath. </li> <li> Report the following information when contacting your healthcare provider: </li><br /><ul> <li> When your fatigue started.</li> <li>Describe how the fatigue has gotten worse since it began.</li> <li>What helps the fatigue or makes it worse.</li> <li>Describe how the fatigue affects your usual activities or activities you want to do. </ul></ul></p><a name="8"></a><h1>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider?</h1><p>If you are experiencing fatigue, you should discuss the following with your healthcare provider at your next appointment:<ul> <li> Is it likely that my cancer treatment will cause fatigue? </li> <li> What things can make the fatigue worse? </li> <li> What treatments are available to help manage my fatigue? </li> <li> How can we treat side effects I\'m experiencing to help reduce my fatigue? </li> <li> Will a dietician be available to help me develop an appropriate eating plan? </li> <li> If exercise is recommended for me, is a physical therapist available to help me develop a plan? </li> <li> What relaxation techniques do you recommend for me? </li> <li> After my treatment ends, how long will my fatigue last? </li></ul></p><a name="9"></a><h1>Where can I get more information?</h1><p>For more information, contact the people or organizations at the numbers or websites listed below:<ul> <li> Contact your healthcare provider. </li> <li> National Cancer Institute: 1-800-4-CANCER or <a href=http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo target=_blank>http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo</a> Click on coping with cancer. </li> <li> American Cancer Society: 1-800-ACS-2345 or <a href=http://cancer.org target=_blank>http://cancer.org</a> Click on patients, family & friends, then coping with treatment. </li> <li> Family Care Research Program: <a href=http://www.cancercare.msu.edu target=_blank>http://www.cancercare.msu.edu</a> </li> <li> Oncology Nursing Society: 1-866-257-4ONS or <a href=http://www.cancersymptoms.org/fatigue/managing.shtml target=_blank>http://www.cancersymptoms.org/fatigue/managing.shtml</a> </li> <li> National Comprehensive Cancer Network: <a href=http://www.nccn.org target=_blank>http://www.nccn.org</a> Click on patient version. </li> <li> OncoLink&#174; (Abramson Cancer Center of the University Of Pennsylvania):   <a href=http://www.oncolink.upenn.edu target=_blank>http://www.oncolink.upenn.edu</a> Click on coping with cancer. </li> <li> National Coalition for Cancer Survivorship: <a href=http://canceradvocacy.org target=_blank>http://canceradvocacy.org</a> Click on learn then side effects. </li> <li> CancerHelp&#174;: <a href=http://cancerhelp.org target=_blank>http://cancerhelp.org</a> </li></ul></p><a name="10"></a><h1>References</h1><p><ul> <li> American Society Of Clinical Oncology (2008).  Cancer. Net: Making a world of difference in cancer care. Retrieved from: <a href=http://www.plwc.org target=_blank>http://www.plwc.org</a> </li> <li> Beck, S., Dudley, W., & Barsevick, A. (2005). Pain, sleep disturbance, and fatigue in patients with cancer: using a mediation model to test a symptom cluster. Oncology Nursing Forum, 32(3), E48-E55. </li> <li> Mock, V., & Mikaela, O. (2003). Current management of fatigue and anemia in patients with cancer. Seminars In Oncology Nursing, 19(4), Suppl. 2, 36-41. </li> <li> Nail, L.M. (2003). Fatigue. In C.H. Yarbro, M.H. Frogge, & M. Goodman (Eds.), Cancer Symptom Management, 3rd Ed. (Pp. 47-60). Boston: Jones And Bartlett. </li> <li> National Coalition For Cancer Survivorship. Fatigue at: <a href=http://www.canceradvocacy.org/ target=_blank>http://www.canceradvocacy.org/</a> Click On Essential Care. </li> <li> Stone, P. (2002). The measurement, causes and effective management of cancer-related fatigue. International Journal Of Palliative Nursing. 8(3), 120-8. </li> <li> Whitmer, K. & Barsevick, A. (2001). Patient resources for cancer-related fatigue. Cancer Practice, 9(6), 311-13. </li></ul></p><a name="11"></a><h1>Supportive evidence-based practice</h1><p><ul> <li> Given, B., Given, C.W., Mccorkle, R., Kozachik, S., Cimprich, B. Rahbar, M. H., & Wojcik, C. (2002). Pain and fatigue management: results of a nursing randomized clinical trial. Oncology Nursing Forum, 29 (6), 949-956. </li> <li> Hammick, M., & Stone, P. (2003). Cancer fatigue and its impact on patients: knowledge within the cancer care team. Journal Of Interprofessional Care, 17 (2), 183-192. </li> <li> Mitchell, S.A., Beck, S.L., Hood, L.E., Moore, K. & Tanner, E.R. (2007). Putting evidence into practice: Evidence-based interventions for fatigue during and following cancer and its treatment. Clinical journal of oncology nursing, 11(1), 99-113. </li> <li> Nail, L.M. (2001). Long-term persistence of symptoms. Seminars In Oncology Nursing, 17 (4), 249-254. </li> <li> Stricker, C., Drake, D., Hoyer, K., & Mock, V. (2004). Evidence-based practice for fatigue management in adults with cancer: exercise as an intervention. Oncology Nursing Forum, 31(5), 963-976. </li> <li> Wilson, R.W., Jacobsen, P.B., & Fields, K.K. (2004). Pilot study of a home-based aerobic exercise program for sedentary cancer survivors treated with hematopoietic stem cell transplantation. Bone Marrow Transplantation, 35, 721-727. </li></ul></p>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a>\r\n\r\n<div id="credit"><p>This information was developed in collaboration with Michigan State University and the Behavioral Cooperative Oncology Group.</p></div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->'),
(100300103004, 'Fever', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Fever</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext">\r\n\r\n<ul><li><a href=#1>What is fever?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>How do people describe fever?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>What causes fever?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>What can I do about fever?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What can family members and friends do to help me with my fever?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>How can I talk with family members and friends about my fever?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#7>What should I report to my healthcare provider about my fever?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#8>What should I discuss with my healthcare provider about my fever? </a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#9>Where can I get more information?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#10>References</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#11>Supportive evidence-based practice</a></li>\r\n</ul><br />\r\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What is a fever?</h1><p>A fever is a body temperature that is higher than normal.  It is defined as a single temperature rise above 100.9 F (38.3 C) or a temperature higher than 100.4 F (38.0 C) that lasts for more than an hour (or as set by your doctor\'s office). Fever is a very important warning sign of infection in patients with cancer receiving chemotherapy. </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>How do people describe fever?</h1><p>Symptoms of fever in the cancer patient can include: increased skin temperature, feeling weak, muscle aches and pains, sweating and chills, feeling confused or dizzy. Depending on how long you have a fever and where you are, it can become an emergency. Most people have a body temperature range of 98.0 F to 98.6 F by mouth.  Normal body temperatures can range from 97.0 to 99.6 F (and will be one degree higher if taken rectally).</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>What causes fever?</h1><p>Bacteria and other organisms can enter the blood stream through many places in the body, such as the skin or mucous membranes lining the mouth and gastrointestinal tract. The immune system attacks bacteria in the blood and releases substances causing the brain to raise the body temperature. It is estimated that 30% of people with cancer are at risk of developing neutropenia (low white blood count) and will develop a fever sometime during the course of cancer treatment. The main causes of fever in the cancer patient are infection and tumor. Other causes include drugs, cancer treatment, blood transfusion reactions and autoimmune problems. Common locations for infection include the lungs, vagina, urinary system, and skin.<br /><br />Most biotherapy drugs, such as Interlukin-1 and Interferon, are associated with acute flu-like syndrome.   Symptoms associated with the syndrome include fever, chills, fatigue, headache and body aches. The administration of colony-stimulating factors (CSFs), also known as blood growth factors, is associated with fever. The most common CSFs are Filgrastim (Neupogen&#174;), Pegfilgrastim, (or Neulasta&#174;) and Sargramostim (Leukine&#174;). CSFs can be given along with chemotherapy to keep the white blood cell count (WBC) from going down to dangerous levels.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>What can I do about fever?</h1><p>Here are some tips you might find helpful: <br /><br /><h2>ACTIVITY</h2><ul> <li> Have an easy-to-read thermometer on hand. </li> <li> Check your temperature at least 4 times a day if you are not feeling well.  Do not take your temperature within 10-15 minutes of drinking hot beverages.  Keep a record of your temperature readings. </li> <li> Relieve the discomfort of fever and chills by taking a luck-warm sponge bath or shower. </li> <li> Wash your hands with antibacterial soap often and with extra care, especially after using the bathroom, blowing your nose, or handling raw meat, fruits or vegetables. </li> <li> Ask your healthcare provider how often you should take your temperature if you have a fever. </li> <li> Ask your healthcare provider when you should call the office or go to the emergency room. </li> <li> Avoid contact with crowds or large groups of people. </li> <li> Avoid people who you know are sick. </li> <li> Use air conditioning or a fan to make you feel more comfortable. </li> <li> Try an ice pack wrapped in a towel or washcloth to the body, such as the forehead or under the arms. </li> <li> Get enough rest. </li> <li> Cover yourself with a blanket if you are chilly or a single sheet if you are hot. </li></ul><br /><h2>COMMUNICATION</h2><ul> <li> Ask your doctor or nurse how often you should be taking your temperature if you have a fever. </li> <li> Ask your doctor or nurse when you should call the office or go to the emergency room. </li></ul><br /><h2>DIET</h2><ul> <li> Eat and drink products that are high in protein and calories, such as peanut butter, Vitamin D milk products, and Carnation&#174; Instant Breakfast&#174. (Fever increases your metabolism.  Products high in protein and calories will help you feel better. </li> <li> Drink 8 (8oz.) glasses of fluid.  Water, lemonade, lemon-lime soda, popsicles, broth, and other soups can help keep you hydrated. </li> <li> Avoid caffeine products, such as coffee, dark cola drinks, and Mountain Dew&#174;. Caffeine can make you more dehydrated. </li></ul><br /><h2>MEDICATION</h2><ul> <li> Avoid taking any Tylenol&#174; or aspirin products before talking with your doctor or nurse. </li></ul></p><a name="5"></a><h1>What can family members and friends do to help me with my fever?</h1><p>Ask family members and friends to: <ul> <li> Prepare high protein and calorie foods. </li> <li> Encourage you to drink fluids throughout the day. </li> <li> Call your doctor\'s office when warranted. (see below) </li> <li> Draw a luke-warm shower or bath. </li> <li> Help you stay free from an infection by washing their hands.  They can also help by asking visitors to do the same. </li></ul></p><a name="6"></a><h1>How can I talk with family members and friends about my fever?</h1><p>Here are some ideas that may help you talk to family members and friends:<ul> <li> Tell your family members and friends how the fever makes you feel and how it is affecting you. </li> <li> Ask your family members and friends for suggestions to bring your fever down. </li></ul></p><a name="7"></a><h1>What should I report to my healthcare provider about my fever?</h1><p>If you experience any of the following symptoms, report them to your healthcare provider:<ul> <li> Any new fever reading above 100.9 (38.3 C), or a temperature higher than 100.4 F (38.0 C) that lasts for more than an hour. Do not drink any hot drinks 10-15 minutes before taking your temperature. </li> <li> Any fever that is accompanied by: </li><br /><ul> <li> Chills with the shakes.</li> <li>Nausea and vomiting.</li> <li>Diarrhea or loss stools for 24 hours.</li> <li>Pain on urination and increased frequency.</li> <li>Shortness of breath.</li> <li>Cough with yellow or green phlegm.</li> <li> Draining sore or wound.</li> <li>Severe fatigue.</li> <li>Unable to get out of bed.</li> <li>Mouth sores.</li> <li>Sore throat.</li> <li>Sinus tenderness or stuffy nose.</li> <li>Rectal discomfort with bowel movements.</li> <li>Skin rashes.</li> <li>Redness, swelling, or warm at the site of an injury, surgical wound, or IV site.</li> <li>Confusion or dizziness.</ul></ul></p><a name="8"></a><h1>What should I discuss with my healthcare provider about my fever?</h1><p>If you are experiencing a fever, you should discuss the following with your healthcare provider:<ul> <li> How often should I check my temperature if my white blood cells are low? </li> <li> Can I take Tylenol&#174; or Motrin&#174; for my fever? </li> <li> Will I still get chemotherapy if I have a fever? </li> <li> Do I go to the hospital if I have a fever? </li></ul></p><a name="9"></a><h1>Where can I get more information?</h1><p>For more information, contact the people or organizations at the numbers or websites listed below:<ul> <li> Call your healthcare provider. </li> <li> American Cancer Society: 1-800-ACS-2345 or  <a href=http://www.cancer.org target=_blank>http://www.cancer.org</a> Click on patients, Family & friends, then coping with treatment. </li> <li> National Cancer Institute: 1-800-4-CANCER or <a href=http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo/ target=_blank>http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo/</a>  Click on coping with cancer. </li> <li> Oncology Nursing Society: 1-866-257-4ONS or <a href=http://www.ons.org target=_blank>http://www.ons.org</a>  Click on patient information. </li> <li> OncoLink&#174; (Abramson Cancer Center of the University Of Pennsylvania):   <a href=http://www.oncolink.upenn.edu target=_blank>http://www.oncolink.upenn.edu</a> Click on coping with cancer. </li> <li> Family Care Research Program: <a href=http://www.cancercare.msu.edu target=_blank>http://www.cancercare.msu.edu</a> </li> <li> National Comprehensive Cancer Network (2006). Fever and neutropenia guidelines for patients with cancer, retrieved from <a href=http://www.nccn.org/patients/patient_gls/_english/_fever_and_neutropenia/1_introduction.asp#understanding_fever target=_blank>http://www.nccn.org/patients/patient_gls/_english/_fever_and_neutropenia/1_introduction.asp#understanding_fever</a> </li></ul></p><a name="10"></a><h1>References</h1><p><ul> <li> Arnold, S.M., Patchell, R., Lowly, A.M., & Foon, K.A. (2001). Paraneoplastic Syndromes, Cpt 47 In Vt Devita, S Hellma, Sa Rosenberg (Eds) Cancer principles and practice of oncology, 6th Ed Philadelphia, Pa: Lippincott, Williams And Wilkins. </li> <li> Dalal, S. & Zhukovsky, D., S. (2006). Pathophysiology and management of fever. The Journal Of Supportive Oncology, (4)1, 9-16. </li> <li> Ezzone, S.A. (2000). Fever. In D Camp-Sorrell And Ra Hawkins (Eds.), Clinical Manual For The Oncology Advanced Practice Nurse, Chapter 140. Pittsburgh, Pa: Oncology Nursing Press, Inc. </li> <li> Shelton, B. (2003). Flulike Syndrome. In C.H. Yarbro, M.H. Frogge, & M. Goodman (Eds.), Cancer Symptom Management, 3rd Ed. (Pp. 61-76). Boston: Jones And Bartlett. </li> <li> National Comprehensive Cancer Network (2006). Fever and neutropenia guidelines for patients with cancer, Retrieved From <a href=http://www.nccn.org/patients/patient_gls/_english/_fever_and_neutropenia/1_introduction.asp#understanding_fever target=_blank>http://www.nccn.org/patients/patient_gls/_english/_fever_and_neutropenia/1_introduction.asp#understanding_fever</a> </li></ul></p><a name="11"></a><h1>Supportive evidence-based practice</h1><p><ul> <li> Viscoli, C., & Castagnola, E. (2002). Treatment of febrile neutropenia: what is new? Current Opinion In Infectious Diseases, 15, 377-382. </li></ul></p>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a>\r\n\r\n<div id="credit"><p>This information was developed in collaboration with Michigan State University and the Behavioral Cooperative Oncology Group.</p></div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->'),
(100300103304, 'Hair Loss', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Hair Loss</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext">\r\n\r\n<ul><li><a href=#1>What is hair loss (alopecia)?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>How do people describe hair loss?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>What causes hair loss? </a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>What can I do about hair loss? </a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>How can family members and friends help me with my hair loss (alopecia)? </a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>How can I talk to family members and friends about my hair loss?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#7>What should I report to my healthcare provider about my hair loss? </a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#8>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about my hair loss? </a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#9>Where can I get more information?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#10>References</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#11>Supportive evidence-based practice</a></li>\r\n</ul><br />\r\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What is hair loss (alopecia)?</h1><p>Alopecia is a temporary or permanent loss of hair that accompanies some types of chemotherapy. During chemotherapy hair follicles are damaged.  The follicles produce weak and brittle hair that breaks off at the scalp. This is a common side effect of cancer treatments.</p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>How do people describe hair loss?</h1><p>Each person experiences hair loss differently.  Many people describe a tingling or aching sensation at their scalp just before hair begins to fall out.  Others repot that their hair started to thin before it fell out.  Hair loss typically occurs while being washed or brushed and can fall off on your pillow.  It can come out in clumps, or a few strands at a time. If complete hair loss is expected, it is usually complete within 3-7 days after the hair started to fall out. </p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>What causes hair loss?</h1><p>Chemotherapy attacks rapidly growing cells in the body such as cancer cells. It can also affect normal cells that grow rapidly, like our hair follicles. Many chemotherapy treatments have no affect on your hair. Others can cause mild hair thinning to complete hair loss. Your healthcare provider should tell you if hair loss is expected with your treatment and when to expect it. Scalp hair is most commonly affected. However, it is possible to lose other kinds of body hair, such as eyelashes, eyebrows, facial, and pubic hair.<br /><br />Most people begin to experience hair loss around 2 weeks after their first treatment. However, some people may not lose their hair until after the second treatment. Right now, there is no effective strategy to prevent or minimize hair loss. Hair loss is generally temporary and should begin to regrow when treatment is finished. Some people experience a small regrowth during treatment. Most experience a significant regrowth 3 months after treatment is completed. It is common for the regrowth to come in as different color and texture.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>What can I do about hair loss?</h1><p>Here are some tips you might find helpful: <br /><br /><h2>ACTIVITY</h2><ul> <li> Use a soft bristled hairbrush and a gentle, pH-balanced shampoo. </li> <li> Choose a wig before you lose your hair.  Try it on and see how it suits you.  Your local American Cancer Society can direct you to specialty wig stores.  Most phone books list these in yellow pages as well. </li> <li> Consider wearing a scarf, turban, or hat to conceal hair loss.  These may be cooler and more comfortable than wigs. </li> <li> Use sunscreen on your scalp and wear a wide-brimmed hat to protect from sunburn.  Your scalp will be very sensitive to the sunburn. </li> <li> Sleep on a satin pillowcase to decrease friction. </li> <li> Avoid excessive brushing, combing, and washing your hair. </li> <li> Cut your hair to a manageable length before treatment begins.  (Shorter styles may help.) </li> <li> Avoid bleaching or coloring your hair. </li> <li> Have your stylist save several strands of hair from a haircut.  This will help you to match a wig to your normal hair color. </li> <li> Do not get a perm or color treatments, such as all-over color, highlights, or lowlights. </li> <li> Avoid extreme temperatures that may bother your scalp. </li> <li> Air-dry your hair.  If possible, do not use a hair dryer. </li> <li> Avoid using curling irons, curlers, or flat irons. </li></ul><br /><h2>COMMUNICATION</h2><ul> <li> Contact your insurance company to see if they will cover all or part of a wig (hair prosthesis).  Many insurance companies do cover (some or all of) the cost if it is prescribed by a physician as part of cancer treatment.  Medicare will not pay for wigs.  If you must pay for your own wig, save the receipt.  For tax purposes, it can be used as a medical deduction. </li> <li> Contact the Look Good...Feel Better program through the American Cancer Society.  It is an excellent way to learn how to put on scarves, turbans, and other head coverings in a way that suits you. </li></ul><br /><h2>MEDICATION</h2><ul> <li> Lubricate your scalp with baby oil, A&D ointment, or mineral oil.  This may help minimize drying and flaking after hair loss is complete. </li></ul></p><a name="5"></a><h1>How can family members and friends help me with my hair loss (alopecia)?</h1><p>Ask a family member or friend to: <ul> <li> Go with you to a wig shop or hair appointment for support. </li> <li> Listen to you and be there for you. Losing your hair can be devastating and a constant reminder of your cancer when you look in the mirror. </li> <li> Remind you to contact the insurance company to see if they will pay for the wig as a hair prosthesis. </li></ul></p><a name="6"></a><h1>How can I talk to family members and friends about my hair loss?</h1><p>Here are some ideas that may help you talk to family members and friends:<ul> <li> Talk with your family members and friends about your feelings. </li> <li> Tell family and friends how your hair loss is affecting you.  It is normal to be upset and may affect how you feel about yourself. It is a stressful event for most patients. </li></ul></p><a name="7"></a><h1>What should I report to my healthcare provider about my hair loss?</h1><p>If you experience any of the following symptoms, report them to your healthcare provider:<ul> <li> Lesions or sores on the scalp. </li> <li> Any of the following feelings after losing your hair: </li><br /><ul> <li> Unable to enjoy normal social or leisure activities.</li> <li>Social isolation.</li> <li>Withdrawal from family and friends.</li> <li>Loss of libido (sex drive).</li> <li>Feeling of being unattractive.</li> <li>Depression or sadness lasting more than 2 weeks.</ul></ul></p><a name="8"></a><h1>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about my hair loss?</h1><p>If you are experiencing hair loss, you should discuss the following with your healthcare provider at your next appointment:<ul> <li> Will my chemotherapy or radiation cause me to lose some or all of my hair? </li> <li> When is my hair likely to start to fall out? </li> <li> If my hair doesn\'t fall out from my treatment does that mean the chemotherapy is not working? </li> <li> Can you provide me with information on managing the hair loss process and arranging for head coverings? Where can I go for help? </li> <li> Please provide me with a prescription for "hair prosthesis" (wig), for my insurance company.  Insurance companies are more likely to cover a wig if it is written as a "hair prosthesis." </li> <li> If financial circumstances make it difficult for me to purchase a wig, where can I get help paying for one? </li> <li> How long after chemotherapy ends will it be before my hair grows back? </li></ul></p><a name="9"></a><h1>Where can I get more information?</h1><p>For more information, contact the people or organizations at the numbers or websites listed below:<ul> <li> Contact your healthcare providers. Share your feelings with them. They can direct you to support groups and educational programs in your area. </li> <li>  American Cancer Society: 1-800-ACS-2345 or <a href=http://www.cancer.org/ target=_blank>http://www.cancer.org/</a>  Click on managing your cancer experience and then coping with cancer. </li> <li> OncoLink&#174; (Abramson Cancer Center of the University Of Pennsylvania):   <a href=http://www.oncolink.upenn.edu target=_blank>http://www.oncolink.upenn.edu</a> Click on coping with cancer and then side effects. </li> <li> Look Good... Feel Better&#174;: 1-800-395-5665 or <a href=http://www.lookgoodfeelbetter.org target=_blank>http://www.lookgoodfeelbetter.org</a> for information on wigs and personal care. </li> <li> Family Care Research Program: <a href=http://www.cancercare.msu.edu target=_blank>http://www.cancercare.msu.edu</a> </li> <li> National Coalition for Cancer Survivorship: <a href=http://canceradvocacy.org target=_blank>http://canceradvocacy.org</a> Click on learn /symptom management then issues of heart and mind. </li> <li> Oncology Nursing Society: 1-866-257-4ONS or <a href=http://www.cancersymptoms.org target=_blank>http://www.cancersymptoms.org</a> </li></ul></p><a name="10"></a><h1>References</h1><p><ul> <li> Trustees of the University of Pennsylvania (2008).  OncoLink: The Web\'s first cancer resource. Retrieved from: <a href=http://www.oncolink.upenn.edu target=_blank>http://www.oncolink.upenn.edu</a> </li> <li> American Cancer Society (2008). American Cancer Society. Retrieved from: <a href=http://www.cancer.org target=_blank>http://www.cancer.org</a> </li> <li> Batchelor, D. (2001). Hair and cancer chemotherapy: consequences and nursing care- a literature study. European Journal Of Cancer Care, 10, 147-163. </li> <li> Macduff, C., Mackenzie, T., Hutcheon, A., Melville, L., & Archibald, H. (2003). The effectiveness of scalp cooling in preventing alopecia for patients receiving Epirubicin and Docetaxel. European Journal Of Cancer Care, 12, 154-161. </li> <li> Reeves, D.M. (2003). Alopecia. In C.H. Yarbro, M.H. Frogge, & M. Goodman (Eds.), Cancer Symptom Management, 3rd Ed. (Pp. 561-570). Boston: Jones And Bartlett. </li></ul></p><a name="11"></a><h1>Supportive evidence-based practice</h1><p><ul> <li> Hesketh, P.J., Batchelor, D., Golant, M., Lyman, G.H., Rhodes, N., & Yardley, D. Chemotherapy-induced alopecia: psychosocial impact and therapeutic approaches. Support Care Cancer, 12, 543-549. </li> <li> Rosman, S. (2004). Cancer and stigma: experience of patients with chemotherapy-induced alopecia. Patient Education And Counseling, 52, 333-339. </li></ul></p>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a>\r\n\r\n<div id="credit"><p>This information was developed in collaboration with Michigan State University and the Behavioral Cooperative Oncology Group.</p></div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->'),
(100300103604, 'Hand-Foot', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Hand-Foot Syndrome</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext">\r\n\r\n<ul><li><a href=#1>What is hand-foot syndrome?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>How do people describe hand-foot syndrome?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>What causes hand-foot syndrome?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>What can I do about hand-foot syndrome?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>How is hand-foot syndrome managed?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What can family members and friends do to help me with my hand-foot syndrome?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#7>How can I talk to my family members and friends about my hand-foot syndrome?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#8>What should I report to my healthcare provider? </a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#9>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider? </a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#10>Where can I get more information?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#11>References</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#12>Supportive evidence-based practice</a></li>\r\n</ul><br />\r\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What is hand-foot syndrome?</h1><p>Hand-foot syndrome is a condition caused by some types of chemotherapy where the palms of the hands and soles of the feet burn or tingle and then become red and sore. Sometimes the hands and feet become so painful that it may be difficult to hold objects in your hands, wear shoes, and even walk without discomfort. It is very important that all of these symptoms are reported to your doctor or nurse immediately. Early reporting of hand-foot syndrome is the best way to decrease the severity and prevent further complications.</p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>How do people describe hand-foot syndrome?</h1><p>Most of the time, the earliest symptoms of hand-foot syndrome are tingling and numbness with slight redness. Tingling and redness in the hands and/or feet can occur at any time while on chemotherapy. It can be expected with some drugs, too.  Do not stop taking medication unless you receive other instructions from your doctor.  Tell your healthcare provider know that you are experiencing these symptoms. If the redness continues, the hands and/or feet become red and swollen, or you have any discomfort contact your healthcare provider immediately.<br /><br />Other more severe symptoms described are dryness, cracking, flaking, and small blisters or sores on the palms of the hands and/or soles of the feet. Hand-foot syndrome can be uncomfortable and interfere with your ability to do normal daily activities.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>What causes hand-foot syndrome?</h1><p>The exact cause of hand/foot syndrome is unknown. One theory is that the chemotherapy builds up in the sweat glands in the hands and feet. Heat or friction on the palms and soles increase the amount of the chemotherapy drug in the capillaries, which can leak out into the tissue. This leakage of drug results in the redness, tenderness, peeling, and discomfort in the hands and/or feet. The chemotherapy drugs most commonly reported to cause hand-foot syndrome include: <ul> <li> Capecitabine (Xeloda&#174;) </li> <li> Fluorouracil (5-FU) continuous infusion </li> <li> Liposomal doxorubicin (Doxil&#174;) </li> <li> Idarubicin (Idamycin&#174;) </li> <li> Floxuridine (fudr&#174;) </li> <li> Continuous infusion of doxorubicin </li> <li> Sunitinib (Sutent&#174;) </li> <li> Sorafenib (Nexavar&#174;) </li></ul></p><a name="4"></a><h1>What can I do about hand-foot syndrome?</h1><p>Prevention is very important in trying to reduce the development of hand-foot syndrome. Management involves modifying some of your normal activities to reduce friction and heat exposure to your hands and feet for a period of time following treatment.  This period is about one week after receiving the IV medication and as long as possible while you are taking oral (by mouth) medications, such as Capcitabine or continuous infusion of 5-FU.<br /><br />Here are some tips you might find helpful:<br /><br /><h2>ACTIVITY</h2><ul> <li> Avoid long exposure of hands and feet to hot water.  Examples of hot water exposures include washing dishes, long showers, or tub baths. </li> <li> Take short, cool water showers to reduce the drug exposure to the soles of your feet. </li> <li> Do not wear rubber gloves to wash dishes or clean.  The rubber will hold heat against your palms. </li> <li> Avoid activities that cause unnecessary force or friction on the feet, such as jogging, aerobics, and long walks or standing for long periods of time. </li> <li> Avoid contact with harsh chemicals used in laundry detergents or household cleaning products. </li> <li> Avoid using garden tools, household tools (such as screwdrivers), and other tasks that require squeezing your hand on a hard surface. </li> <li> Do not use knives to chop food. It may cause excessive pressure and friction on your palms. </li> <li> Cool your hands and feet with ice packs or cool compresses for 15-20 minutes at a time.  Do not apply ice directly to the skin. </li> <li> Elevate your hands and feet to avoid swelling when sitting or lying down. </li> <li> Pat skin carefully to dry.  Try not to rub your skin with a towel. </li> <li> Apply mild skin care lotion to keep your hands and feet moist.  Do not rub or massage lotion into your hands or feet.  Rubbing or massaging can create friction. </li> <li> Avoid sunny windows, or sitting in the sun and wear sunscreen on all exposed skin when you go outside. </li> <li> Wear loose, well-ventilated shoes and clothes. </li> <li> Try gel inserts in your shoes. </li> <li> Wear cotton socks. </li> <li> Immerse hands and feet in cool water 3-4 times a day. </li> <li> Avoid wearing rings. </li> <li> Check your skin for signs of infections. Look for any drainage, odor, or increased redness. If you have an infection, you may also have a fever.  If you notice any of these signs contact your healthcare provider. </li></ul><br /><h2>COMMUNICATION</h2><ul> <li> Report any change in your daily activities to your healthcare provider. </li></ul><br /><h2>DIET</h2><ul> <li> Drink 8 (8oz.) glasses of water or other non-caffeinated drinks every day.  Avoid caffeine (i.e. colas, coffee) when possible.  Caffeine can cause dehydration. </li></ul><br /><h2>MEDICATION</h2><ul> <li> Over-the-counter drugs, such as Tylenol&#174; or ibuprofen&#174;, may be helpful to relieve discomfort associated with hand-food syndrome. Check with your doctor before taking any pain medication. </li> <li> Corticosteroids may be ordered from your doctor to help reduce swelling and redness. </li> <li> Taking Vitamin B6 (pyridoxine) may be beneficial in preventing and treating hand-foot syndrome and should be discussed with your doctor. </li> <li> Emollients such as Aveeno&#174;, Lubriderm&#174;, Udder Cream&#174;, Bag Balm&#174;, and Aquaphor&#174; provide excellent moisturizing to our hands and feet. </li> <li> Avoid topical anesthetics or diphenhydramine-containing creams.  These can make the toxicity of the skin worse. </li></ul></p><a name="5"></a><h1>How is hand-foot syndrome managed?</h1><p>Severe cases of hand-foot syndrome are first treated by reducing or temporarily stopping the chemotherapy drug that is causing it. Other approaches that your healthcare provider may suggest include: <ul> <li> Over-the-counter Tylenol&#174; or ibuprofen&#174; may help to relieve the discomfort associated with hand-foot syndrome. Check with your healthcare provider before taking any pain medication. </li> <li> Corticosteriods may be ordered by your healthcare provider to help reduce swelling and redness. </li> <li> Vitamin B6 (Pyridoxine) may be beneficial in preventing and treating hand-foot syndrome. Discuss this option with your healthcare provider before taking it. </li></ul></p><a name="6"></a><h1>What can family members and friends do to help me with my hand-foot syndrome?</h1><p>Ask family members and friends to:<ul> <li> Prepare meals for you. </li> <li> Help with daily household chores such as gardening or dishwashing. </li> <li> Test water temperatures before bathing or washing dishes.  Inexpensive thermometers are sold in stores that can check water temperatures.  This may be an option for you and your family. </li> <li> Help gently apply lotions to hands and feet. </li> <li> Help with your daily activities, such as bathing, and driving. </li></ul></p><a name="7"></a><h1>How can I talk to my family members and friends about my hand-foot syndrome?</h1><p>Here are some ideas that may help you talk to family members and friends:<ul> <li> Ask family members and friends how the hand-foot syndrome is affecting them. </li> <li> Talk to family and friends how the hand-foot syndrome is affecting your emotions and mood. </li> <li> Talk to family and friends how the hand-foot syndrome is interfering with your life and ability to function. </li> <li> Ask family members for suggestions to help you function as close to normal as possible. </li></ul></p><a name="8"></a><h1>What should I report to my healthcare provider?</h1><p>If you experience any of the following symptoms, report them to your healthcare provider:<ul> <li> Redness, swelling, tingling, or pain in the hands and/or feet. Discuss any symptoms with your healthcare provider immediately.  Do not stop your medication until you have talked to your healthcare provider. </li> <li> Any temperature rise above 100.9 F (38.3 C), or a temperature higher than 100.4 F (38.0 C) that lasts for more than an hour, or as set by your doctor\'s office. </li> <li> An increase of 4 stools over normal bowel pattern in a 24 hour period or diarrhea during the night. </li> <li> Tenderness, redness, or sores in the mouth. </li> <li> Vomiting. </li> <li> Unable to keep down any fluids for 24 hours. </li></ul></p><a name="9"></a><h1>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider?</h1><p>If you are experiencing hand and foot syndrome, you should discuss the following with your healthcare provider at your next appointment:<ul> <li> Will my chemotherapy put me at risk for developing hand-foot syndrome? </li> <li> Are there things you can give me if my hands and/or feet become painful? </li> <li> Will I be able to continue to work? </li> <li> If I do all of the things suggested could hand-foot syndrome be prevented? </li> <li> What symptoms do you want me to call you for? </li></ul></p><a name="10"></a><h1>Where can I get more information?</h1><p>For more information, contact the people or organizations at the numbers or websites listed below:<ul> <li> Contact your healthcare provider. </li> <li> Caring 4 Cancer: <a href=http://cancer.caring4health.com/default.aspx target=_blank>http://cancer.caring4health.com/default.aspx</a> Click on managing side effects (in the center of the page), then click on less common side effects (In the right hand column), and finally on hand-foot syndrome (located in the right hand column). </li> <li> Chemocare: <a href=http://chemocare.com target=_blank>http://chemocare.com</a> Click on managing side effects and then hand-foot syndrome. </li> <li>  American Cancer Society: 1-800-ACS-2345 or <a href=http://www.cancer.org target=_blank>http://www.cancer.org</a> </li> <li> Family Care Research Program: <a href=http://cancercare.msu.edu/ target=_blank>http://cancercare.msu.edu/</a> </li> <li> National Cancer Institute: 1-800-4-CANCER or <a href=http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo target=_blank>http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo</a> Click on coping with cancer. </li></ul></p><a name="11"></a><h1>References</h1><p><ul> <li> Backes, W. ( 2001). Prodrugs. Clinical Journal Of Oncology Nursing, 5(1), 35-37. </li> <li> Oestreicher, P. (2007). Manage Skin Toxicities Associated with Targeted Therapies. ONS connect, 22(11),20-21. </li> <li> R4 Healthcare LLC. (2008). Caring4  Cancer: Your complete source for knowledge & support.  Retrieved from <a href=http://cancer.caring4health.com/default.aspx target=_blank>http://cancer.caring4health.com/default.aspx</a> </li> <li> The Cleveland Clinic Foundation (2005). Chemocare.com. Retrieved from <a href=http://chemocare.com target=_blank>http://chemocare.com</a> </li> <li> Wood, L., S. (2006). Managing the side effects of Sorafenib and Sunitinib. Journal Of Community Oncology, (3)9, 558-562. </li></ul></p><a name="12"></a><h1>Supportive evidence-based practice</h1><p><ul> <li> Coyle, C., & Wenhold, V. (2001). Painful blistered hands and feet. Clinical Journal Of Oncology Nursing, 5(5), 230-232. </li> <li> Gressett, S. Stanford, B., & Hardwicke, F. (2006). Management of hand-foot syndrome induced by Capecitabine. Journal Of Oncology Pharmacy Practice, 12(3), 131-141. </li> <li> Pike, K. (2001). Hand-Foot Syndrome. The Oncology Nursing Forum, 28 (10), 1519-1520. </li> <li> Wilkes, G., & Doyle, D. (2005). Palmar-Planter Erythrodysesthesia. Clinical Journal Of Oncology Nursing, 9(1), 103-106. </li></ul></p>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a>\r\n\r\n<div id="credit"><p>This information was developed in collaboration with Michigan State University and the Behavioral Cooperative Oncology Group.</p></div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->');
