(100300103904, 'Mouth Sores', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Mouth Sores</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext">\r\n\r\n<ul><li><a href=#1>What are Mouth Sores?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>How do people describe mouth sores?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>What causes mouth sores?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>What can I do about mouth sores?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What can family members and friends do to help me with my mouth sores?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>How can I talk to my family and friends about my mouth sores?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#7>What should I report to my healthcare provider about my mouth sores?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#8>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about my mouth sores?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#9>Where can I get more information?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#10>References</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#11>Supportive evidence-based practice</a></li>\r\n</ul><br />\r\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What are mouth sores?</h1><p>Mucositis is when the mucus lining of the mouth and tongue and throat become reddened, swollen and painful. Open sores called ulcers can develop. About half of cancer patients on chemotherapy and almost all who have radiation to the head or neck will experience mouth discomfort as a side effect of treatment.<br /><br />The discomfort can range from mild to severe. Mild discomfort is a change in the way the mouth feels. It is easily treated and quick to heal. Moderate discomfort is considered to be redness and open sores in the mouth. Severe mucositis involves many sores in the mouth, bleeding, and severe pain. None of these discomfort levels are pleasant. Each can cause other problems including difficulty swallowing, talking, eating, and infection. There are preventive steps and treatment that you can do to minimize this uncomfortable side effect. <br /><br />It is very important that any discomfort in your mouth is reported to your doctor or nurse immediately. Early reporting is the best way to decrease the severity and prevent further complications. Mucositis can delay your cancer treatment or limit the dose of your therapy.</p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>How do people describe mouth sores?</h1><p>After about three to five days of chemotherapy and/or radiation therapy, the lining of the mouth may feel a little warm. There may be some tingling or minor soreness. Within one to two weeks of starting your treatment, sores may begin to appear. A week or two after your treatment is finished the sores begin to heal.  Usually after the third week out of treatment, the ulcers and pain will have disappeared. <br /><br />There are a number of warning signs that commonly describe mucositis, including:<ul> <li> Burning or tingling feeling inside the mouth. </li> <li> Inside of the mouth looks red, shiny, and swollen. </li> <li> Red, inflamed patches. These may include white spots. </li> <li> Raw feeling in the throat. </li> <li> Unusual mouth dryness. </li> <li> Open sores or ulcers in the mouth or under the tongue. </li> <li> Thick secretions or saliva. </li> <li> Blood in the mouth or saliva. </li> <li> Pain in the mouth. </li></ul></p><a name="3"></a><h1>What causes mouth sores?</h1><p>Chemotherapy and radiation therapy work on rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  They also attack other cells in the body, including those forming the lining of the mouth and throat. As mouth cells die from the treatment, open sores can develop.  Gradually, normal cells in the mouth start to grow again and the sores heal. <br /><br />Individual risk factors for developing mouth sores include: <ul> <li> Advanced age. </li> <li> Poor nutritional status. </li> <li> Poor oral hygiene. </li> <li> Poor fitting dentures. </li> <li> Tobacco use (cigarettes, cigars, or pipes). </li> <li> Drink alcohol beverages (beer, wine, or liquor). </li></ul><p>Treatment related risk factors include:<ul> <li> Drug dosage. </li> <li> Treatment schedule. </li> <li> Receiving radiation therapy. </li></ul><p>A large number of chemotherapy drugs can cause mouth sores. It is most commonly reported with:<ul> <li> 5- fluoroucil (5-FU) </li> <li> Cisplatin&#174; </li> <li> Etoposide&#174; </li> <li> Methotrexate&#174; </li> <li> Cytarabine&#174; </li> <li> Bleomycin&#174; </li> <li> Cyclophosphamide&#174; </li> <li> Dactinomycin&#174; </li> <li> Paclitaxel&#174; </li> <li> High doses of chemotherapy </li></ul></p><a name="4"></a><h1>What can I do about mouth sores?</h1><p>Proper mouth care on a frequent, daily basis plays an important role in oral health during cancer therapy. You may not be able to prevent all problems, but it will decrease the severity of the problems, especially with certain chemotherapy treatments and/or radiation therapy.<br /><br /><h2>ACTIVITY</h2><ul> <li> Schedule a complete dental examination before you begin your chemotherapy and/or radiation treatment.  Inform your dentist that you will be undergoing cancer treatment. </li> <li> Take care of your mouth and keep it clean.  That means careful brushing and flossing based on discussion with your doctor and/or dentist. </li> <li> Use the softest bristle brush available or an oral sponge.  (Rinsing the bristles in hot water can even make them softer). </li> <li> Brush your teeth after every meal and at bedtime using nonabrasive toothpaste with no strong whiteners, which may cause irritation. Brush all tooth surfaces for at least 90 seconds. </li> <li> Brush your tongue as well as teeth and gums to help reduce the risk of fungal infections. </li> <li> Change your toothbrush frequently --every week or so. </li> <li> Do not use special appliances, such as water piks and electric toothbrushes. They may further irritate sensitive mouth tissue and gums. </li> <li> Floss gently everyday with unwaxed dental floss.  Stop flossing if you experience any bleeding or low blood counts. </li> <li> Clean dentures after every meal.  If possible, avoid wearing dentures overnight while asleep. </li> <li> Make sure your dentures fit properly. Repair or replace them if they do not fit well.  Poor fitting dentures can rub and cause additional pain in a tender mouth. </li> <li> Avoid using mouth rinse products that have glycerin or alcohol as they can cause dying in your mouth. </li> <li> Rinse mouth frequently (every 2 hours while awake & when awake during the night).  Mouth solution: </li><br /><ul> <li> 1/2 teaspoon salt</li> <li>2 teaspoons baking soda</li> <li>4 cups (1 quart) of plain water</li> <li>Shake or stir the solution.  Keep it with you for regular use.  If you make more than a one-day supply, keep the remainder in the refrigerator.</ul></ul><br /><h2>COMMUNICATION</h2><ul> <li> Check with your healthcare provider to make sure it is safe to wear your dentures if you are receiving radiation treatments to the head and neck area. </li> <li> Talk to your healthcare provider if you need additional suggestions or continue to lose weight during your treatment.  Many practices have dieticians available for advice. </li> <li> Ask your doctor if you can take Tylenol&#174; or ibuprofen&#174; for pain relief. </li> <li> Ask your healthcare provider if there is a specific medication that can help fight infections.  Chemotherapy and radiation can weaken the immune system.  Bacteria that live in the mouth can cause infections in mouth sores. </li></ul><br /><h2>DIET</h2><ul> <li> Drink at least 8-10 glasses of non-carbonated liquids each day. </li> <li> Suck on non-irritating hard candy (sugar-free is best). Chewing gum may help. </li> <li> Eat popsicles or suck ice cubes for moisture. </li> <li> Avoid very hot food.  If your mouth is tender, try eating most of your food warm or at room temperature. </li> <li> Avoid highly seasoned food, which can aggravate mouth soreness. </li> <li> Avoid alcohol and tobacco.  Both irritate an already-sore mouth and throat. </li> <li> Restrict the amount of citrus fruit, tomatoes, and salty food in your diet. They can be uncomfortable for some people with mouth sores. </li> <li> Grind up or puree food in a blender. Foods with shape edges, such as chips and cracker, may be irritating. </li> <li> Use sauces or gravies to make foods easier for you to swallow and chew. </li> <li> Small, frequent meals may also be easier for you to eat. </li> <li> Drink liquid supplements to maintain your calorie intake. Examples of supplements are  Carnation&#174; Instant Breakfast&#174;, Ensure&#174;, and Boost&#174;. </li> <li> Choose to eat soft and soothing foods. Examples include: ice cream, milkshakes, baby foods, mashed potatoes, scrambled eggs, cottage cheese, custards, puddings, and gelatin. </li></ul><br /><h2>MEDICATION</h2><ul> <li> Try artificial saliva, such as Oral Balance&#174;, Moist Plus&#174;, and Salivant&#174;. This can be purchased at a drugstore without a prescription. </li> <li> Keep your lips moist with lip balm, Chapstick&#174;, or petroleum jelly. </li> <li> Use a water-based mouth moisturizer to help keep the mouth moist. An example of a moisturizer is Biotene&#174; Oral Lubricant.) </li> <li> Do not use liquid medications containing alcohol, such as cough medications. They may irritate the mouth. </li> <li> Take stronger drugs for severe pain. Pain causes stress, depression, and fatigue. Opiates are a class of strong drugs, one of which is morphine, that provide effective pain relief. It is very important to talk to your doctor or nurse if your pain is not being controlled. Many opiates are also available in liquids and patches if you are not able to swallow pills. </li> <li> Treat discomfort/pain: </li><br /><ul> <li> Use topical or local agents such as Orajel&#174;, Anbesol&#174;, Zilactin-b&#174;, or Orabase&#174;, which are available in the drugstore.</li> <li>A combination mouthwash with a local anesthetic can be prescribed from your healthcare provider. Take 2 teaspoons every 2-4 hours or prior to meals to alleviate mild discomfort.</li> <li>Gelclair&#174; is a prescription medication available to sooth the oral pain from sores.</li> <li>Ask your doctor if you can take Tylenol&#174; or ibuprofen&#174; for pain relief.<br /><br/></ul> <li> Severe pain: </li><br /><ul> <li> Do not resist taking stronger drugs for severe pain. Pain causes stress, depression, and fatigue. Opiates&#174;, a class of drug that includes morphine, are used for pain relief. It is very important to talk to your healthcare provider if your pain is not being controlled. Many opiates are also available in liquids and patches if you are not able to swallow pills.<br/><br/></ul> <li> Fight infections: </li><ul> <li> Chemotherapy and radiation can weaken the immune system.  Bacteria that live in the mouth can cause infections in mouth sores. Your healthcare provider may order specific medications to help fight infections.</ul></ul></p><a name="5"></a><h1>What can family members and friends do to help me with my mouth sores?</h1><p>Ask family members and friends to: <ul> <li> Prepare meals high in protein to promote healing. </li> <li> Remind you to perform mouth care after meals and at bedtime. </li> <li> Prepare bland, soft foods that will be more tolerable. </li> <li> Help buy or prepare mouth care solutions, toothpaste and lip balm. </li></ul></p><a name="6"></a><h1>How can I talk to my family and friends about my mouth sores?</h1><p>Here are some ideas that may help you talk to family members and friends:<ul> <li> Be open with your family members about how you feel having mouth sores. </li> <li> Ask them for ideas on how to deal with your mouth sores. </li> <li> Tell your family members how your mouth sores are affecting your emotions. </li> <li> Ask your family members how your mouth sores are affecting them. </li></ul></p><a name="7"></a><h1>What should I report to my healthcare provider about my mouth sores?</h1><p>If you experience any of the following symptoms, report them to your healthcare provider:<ul> <li> New red or white patches your mouth or tongue. </li> <li> New sores in your mouth or tongue. </li> <li> Weight loss of more than 5 pounds in one week. </li> <li> Inability to eat any food for 24 hours. </li> <li> Pain that is not relieved. </li> <li> Bleeding from gums or mouth sores. </li> <li> Pain with swallowing or sore throat that interferes with eating, drinking, or sleeping. </li> <li> Fever. </li> <li> Pain or signs of infection (tongue heavily coated). </li></ul></p><a name="8"></a><h1>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about my mouth sores?</h1><p>If you are experiencing mouth sores, you should discuss the following with your healthcare provider at your next appointment:<ul> <li> Is it likely that my cancer treatment will cause mouth sores? </li> <li> Specifically, how should I manage my mouth care on a daily basis? </li> <li> Is there a dietician available to help guide me in choosing appropriate foods? </li> <li> Will the mouth sores interfere with the schedule of my cancer treatment? </li> <li> What medications can I use for pain and how often should I use them? </li> <li> What are the warning signs of infection, and what should I do if my mouth becomes infected? </li></ul></p><a name="9"></a><h1>Where can I get more information?</h1><p>For more information, contact the people or organizations at the numbers or websites listed below:<ul> <li> Contact your family dentist. </li> <li> Contact your healthcare provider. </li> <li> National Cancer Institute: 1-800-4-CANCER or <a href=http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo target=_blank>http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo</a> Click on coping with cancer. </li> <li> American Cancer Society: 1-800-ACS-2345 or <a href=http://cancer.org target=_blank>http://cancer.org</a> </li> <li> Family Care Research Program: <a href=http://www.cancercare.msu.edu target=_blank>http://www.cancercare.msu.edu</a> </li> <li> National Coalition For Cancer Survivorship: <a href=http://canceradvocacy.org target=_blank>http://canceradvocacy.org</a> Click on learn then side effects. </li> <li> Chemocare: <a href=http://chemocare.com target=_blank>http://chemocare.com</a> Click on managing side effects. </li> <li> Oncology Nursing Society: 1-866-257-4ONS or <a href=http://www.cancersymptoms.org target=_blank>http://www.cancersymptoms.org</a> </li></ul></p><a name="10"></a><h1>References</h1><p><ul> <li> Cawley, M., M. & Benson, L., M. (2005). Current trends In managing oral mucositis. Clinical Journal Of Oncology Nursing, 9 (5), Pp. 584-592. </li> <li> Davidson, D. (2006). Oral mucositis. Clinical Journal Of Oncology Nursing, 10 (2), pp. 283-284. </li> <li> Multiple association of supportive care in oncology. Summary of evidenced-based guidelines for care of patients with oral and gastrointestinal mucositis. Retreived From The Internet From <a href=http://www.masc.org target=_blank>http://www.masc.org</a> On December 18, 2006. </li> <li> Peterson, D., E. (2006). New strategies for management of oral mucositis in cancer patients. The Journal Of Supportive Oncology, (4) 2 Suppl. 1, Pp. 9-13. </li> <li> Posner, M.R. & Haddad, R.I. (2007). Novel agents for the treatment of mucositis. A Supplement to: The Journal of Supportive Oncology, 5(9), 33-39. </li> <li> Rajesh, V., L., & Peterson, D., E. (2006). Treatment of mucositis, including new medications. The Cancer Journal, 12 (5), Pp. 348-354. </li> <li> Shish, A., Miaskowski, D., Dodd, M., J., Stotts, N., A., & Mcphail, L., (2002). A research review of the current treatments for radiation-induced oral mucositis in patients with head and neck cancer. Oncology Nursing Forum, 29 (7), Pp. 1063-80. </li> <li> Sonis, S., T., Elting, L., S., Keefe, D., Peterson, D., E., Schubert, M., & Hauer-Jensen, M., Et Al. (2004). Perspectives on cancer therapy-induced mucosal injury. Cancer, 100 (9) Suppl. Pp.1995-2011. </li> <li> Zitella, L., J., Friese, C., R., Hauser, J., Gobel, B., Woolery, M., & O\'leary, C. (2006). Putting evidence into practice: prevention of infection. Clinical Journal Of Oncology Nursing, 10 (6), Pp. 739-745. </li></ul></p><a name="11"></a><h1>Supportive evidence-based practice</h1><p><ul> <li> Harris, D.J., Eilers, J., Harriman, A., Cashavelly, B.J., Maxwell, C. (2008). Putting evidence into practice: Evidence-based interventions for the management of oral mucositis. Clinical Journal of Oncology Nursing, 12(1), 141-152. </li> <li> Rubenstien, E. B., Peterson, D. D., Schubert, M., Keefe, D., Mcguire, D., Et Al. (2004). Clinical practice guidelines for the prevention and treatment of cancer therapy-induced oral gastrointestinal mucositis. Cancer, 100 (9), 2026-2046. </li></ul></p>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a>\r\n\r\n<div id="credit"><p>This information was developed in collaboration with Michigan State University and the Behavioral Cooperative Oncology Group.</p></div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->'),
(100300104204, 'Nausea', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Nausea</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext">\r\n\r\n<ul><li><a href=#1>What is nausea?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>How do people describe nausea?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>What causes nausea?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>What can I do about nausea?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What can family members and friends do to help with my nausea?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>How can I talk to my family and friends about nausea?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#7>What should I report to my healthcare provider about my nausea?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#8>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about my nausea? </a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#9>Where can I get more information?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#10>References</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#11>Supportive evidence-based practice</a></li>\r\n</ul><br />\r\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What is nausea?</h1><p>Nausea is an unpleasant feeling in the back of the throat and stomach that could result in vomiting. Feeling nauseous can be worse than vomiting. Nausea and vomiting that does not go away can cause dehydration (loss of fluids), loss of appetite, imbalance of vitamin and minerals, weakness, difficulty concentrating and poor quality of life. <br /><br />Two of the side effects that people find most concerning while undergoing cancer treatment are nausea and vomiting. Controlling these side effects is a very important part of your treatment. There are many medications and therapies that can effectively control nausea and vomiting.  Report your symptoms to your healthcare provider so that the right treatment can be found for you.</p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>How do people describe nausea?</h1><p>People describe nausea as an unpleasant feeling related to food, smells or situations, such as cancer treatment. With this feeling, there may be a biter (or acidic) taste in the mouth or abdominal fullness while eating.  Some people who feel nauseous describe it as, "sick to my stomach", "queasy", or "butterflies". Nausea may cause increased saliva, lightheadedness, dizziness, difficulty swallowing, skin temperature changes, fast heart rate and lack of appetite. </p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>What causes nausea?</h1><p>Nausea is caused when certain parts of the intestinal tract or specific areas of the brain become stimulated.  Chemotherapy and radiation treatments can cause a person with cancer to have nausea and vomiting.</p><h4>Chemotherapy</h4><p>All chemotherapies are different. Some can cause more nausea and vomiting than others. There are different types of chemotherapy related nausea and vomiting: <ul> <li> Acute- occurs a few minutes to hours after chemotherapy is given and goes away within the first 24 hours. </li> <li> Delayed- develops more than 24 hours after the chemotherapy is given and can last 6-7 days. </li> <li> Anticipatory- learned from previous experiences with vomiting. It occurs as a result of an unpleasant experience with chemotherapy. </li> <li> Breakthrough- occurs despite treatment to prevent it. </li> <li> Refractory- occurs after a few chemotherapy treatments even though the person is being treated for nausea. </li></ul><h4>Radiation</h4><p>The chance of nausea and vomiting is greater when the area being radiated is the brain or the abdomen, specifically the small intestine (or small bowel). The symptoms can occur 1-2 hours after treatment and can last for several hours. <br /><br />Other causes of nausea are:<ul> <li> The cancer itself can cause nausea and vomiting, especially with gastrointestinal tumors and brain cancer. </li> <li> Use of pain medications (narcotics) and antidepressants. </li> <li> Constipation and bowel obstruction. </li> <li> Anxiety. </li> <li> Taste changes and smells. </li></ul></p><a name="4"></a><h1>What can I do about nausea?</h1><p>Nausea is different for every person who experiences this symptom. The key is to prevent nausea from occurring. A variety of medications and behavioral therapies can be used to manage nausea. <br /><br />Here are some tips you might find helpful:<br /><br /><h2>ACTIVITY</h2><ul> <li> Get plenty of rest. </li> <li> Decrease unnecessary motion. </li> <li> Wear loose fitting clothes, be comfortable. </li> <li> Have fresh air with a fan or window open. </li> <li> Brush your teeth after meals. </li> <li> Use mouthwashes that do not contain alcohol to improve the taste in your mouth. </li></ul><br /><h2>DIET</h2><ul> <li> Avoid large meals. Try to eat several, small frequent meals to help maintain calories without overfilling the stomach. </li> <li> Eat slowly. </li> <li> Sip fluids slowly, such as ginger ale or ginger tea no sooner than 2 hours after the last vomiting episode. </li> <li> Try cool or cold foods, if hot food is unappealing.  Some suggestions include Jell-O, cottage or ricotta cheese, yogurt, pudding, sherbet, cold sandwiches, pasta or potato salads, and popsicles. </li> <li> Try eating dry foods, such as crackers, bagels, and toast. </li> <li> Bland foods work well from many people: try toast, cereals, yogurt, ices, cookies, pretzels and skinless cooked chicken. </li> <li> Avoid sweet, fried, or fatty foods. </li> <li> Avoid gas-producing vegetables, like broccoli, cauliflower, cucumbers, green peppers, brussel sprouts, and sauerkraut. </li> <li> Avoid acidic foods such as salsa, tomatoes, citrus fruits and citrus fruit juices, or vinegar. </li> <li> Chew gum or suck on hard candy. </li> <li> Try eating most foods during the time of when you are able to eat better.  Many people find that breakfast time is best. </li> <li> Avoid alcoholic beverages. </li> <li> Avoid your favorite foods if you are nauseated.  You may start to associate your favorite foods with feeling sick if you eat them while nauseated. </li> <li> Do not force yourself to eat. </li> <li> Avoid food aromas and other strong odors. </li></ul><br /><h2>MEDICATION</h2><ul> <li> Treat heartburn and gas with antacids. </li> <li> Learn your schedule for taking your anti-nausea medications and stay on it.  Do not decide to stop the medicine if you are feeling well.  Nausea can come back. </li></ul><br /><h2>PSYCHOLOGICAL</h2><ul> <li> Try using television or music as a distraction. </li> <li> Try behavioral therapies and techniques that can be helpful in treating nausea and vomiting include: </li><br /><ul> <li> Acupuncture.</li> <li>Acupressure.</li> <li>Guided imagery.</li> <li>Music therapy.</li> <li>Muscle relaxation.</li> <li>Counseling, support, and structured educational interventions.</ul></ul></p><a name="5"></a><h1>What can family members and friends do to help with my nausea?</h1><p>Ask family members and friends to: <ul> <li> Not smoke or wear heavy perfume around you. Either of these smells can make the nausea worse. </li> <li> Assist with relaxation therapies such as, music, guided imagery or relaxation. </li> <li> Give you a backrub or foot massage to help you relax. </li> <li> Go with you to your chemotherapy treatments to help distract you. </li> <li> Prepare foods ahead of time that you can warm up in the microwave after the nausea has passed. </li> <li> Prepare bland foods. </li> <li> Remind you to take your anti-nausea medicines. </li></ul></p><a name="6"></a><h1>How can I talk to my family and friends about nausea?</h1><p>Here are some ideas that may help you talk to family members and friends:<ul> <li> Be open with your family members and friends about how the nausea makes you feel. </li> <li> Remind them of things that help relieve nausea. </li> <li> Ask for ideas to help deal with your nausea. </li> <li> Ask your family members and friends how your nausea is affecting them. </li></ul></p><a name="7"></a><h1>What should I report to my healthcare provider about my nausea?</h1><p>If you experience any of the following symptoms, report them to your healthcare provider:<ul> <li> Vomit that looks like coffee grounds. </li> <li> 3 or more vomiting episodes an hour form more than 6 hours. </li> <li> Vomiting episodes several times a day form 2 days. </li> <li> Projectile vomiting. </li> <li> Blood-tinged or bright red blood in vomit. </li> <li> Weight loss of more than 2 pounds in a day. </li> <li> Faint and weakness. </li> <li> Vomit several times a day for 2 days. </li> <li> Unable to eat solid foods for 24 hours. </li> <li> Shortness of breath. </li> <li> Unable to keep fluids down for more than 12 hours (with or without the use of anti-nausea medicines). </li> <li> Severe stomach pain with nausea. </li> <li> Persistent weakness or dizziness, or if you are confused (mixed up). </li> <li> Dark yellow urine or if you are not going to the bathroom as much as you normally do.  These can be signs of dehydration. </li> <li> Abdominal bloating with nausea and vomiting. </li></ul></p><a name="8"></a><h1>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about my nausea?</h1><p>If you are experiencing nausea, you should discuss the following with your healthcare provider at your next appointment:<ul> <li> What chemotherapy medications am going to be taking that can cause nausea and vomiting? </li> <li> What medications will I be taking to prevent nausea or vomiting prior to treatment? </li> <li> What will be my anti-nausea medication schedule be after treatment? </li> <li> What do you recommend that I eat before and after treatment? Should I brink snacks to eat during my treatment? </li> <li> If my medications fail to control nausea, whom should I contact for additional help? </li> <li> What relaxation techniques do you recommend for me? </li></ul></p><a name="9"></a><h1>Where can I get more information?</h1><p>For more information, contact the people or organizations at the numbers or websites listed below:<ul> <li> Contact your healthcare provider. </li> <li> National Cancer Institute: 1-800-4-CANCER or <a href=http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping target=_blank>http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping</a> Click on coping with cancer. Find and click on nausea and vomiting. </li> <li> American Cancer Society: 1-800-ACS-2345 or <a href=http://www.cancer.org target=_blank>http://www.cancer.org</a> </li> <li> National Institutes for Health: <a href=http://www.nih.gov target=_blank>http://www.nih.gov</a> </li> <li> National Comprehensive Cancer Network: <a href=http://www.nccn.org target=_blank>http://www.nccn.org</a> Click on guidelines for patients. Find and click on nausea and vomiting. </li> <li> Family Care Research Program: <a href=http://www.cancercare.msu.edu target=_blank>http://www.cancercare.msu.edu</a> </li> <li> National Coalition For Cancer Survivorship: <a href=http://www.canceradvocacy.org target=_blank>http://www.canceradvocacy.org</a> Click on essential care. </li></ul></p><a name="10"></a><h1>References</h1><p><ul> <li> Booth, C.M., Clemons, M., Dranitsaris, B.P., Joy, A. Young, S., Callaghan, W. et al. (2007). Chemotherapy-Induced Nausea and Vomiting in Breast Cancer Patients: A prospective observational study. The Journal of Supportive Oncology, 5, 374-380. </li> <li> National Cancer Institute At: <a href=http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo/ target=_blank>http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo/</a> Click on coping with cancer. Find and click on nausea and vomiting (Professionals). </li> <li> National Comprehensive Cancer Network on the Internet at: <a href=http://www.nccn.org target=_blank>http://www.nccn.org</a>  Click on treatment guidelines for patients. Find and click on nausea and vomiting. </li> <li> Van Fleet, S. (2000). Relaxation and imagery for symptom management: improving patient assessment and individualizing treatment. Oncology Nursing Forum, 27(3), 501-10. </li> <li> Wickham, R. (2003). Nausea and vomiting. In C.H. Yarbro, M.H. Frogge, & M. Goodman (Eds.), Cancer Symptom Management, 3rd Ed. (Pp. 77-96). Boston: Jones And Bartlett. </li></ul></p><a name="11"></a><h1>Supportive evidence-based practice</h1><p><ul> <li> Baker, P., D., Morzarati, S., L., & Ellitt, M., L., (2005) the pathophysiology of chemotherapy-induced nausea and vomiting. Gastroenterology Nursing (28) 6, Pp.468-480. </li> <li> Sahler, L.J.Z., Hunter, B.C., & Liesveld, J.L. (2003). The effect of using music therapy with relaxation imagery in the management of patients undergoing bone marrow transplantation: a pilot study. Alternative Therapies, 9 (6), 70-74. </li> <li> Tipton, J.M., McDaniel, R.W., Barbour, L., Johnston, M.P., Kayne, M., LeRoy, P. & Ripple, M.L. (2007). Putting evidence into practice: Evidence-based interventions to prevent, manage, and treat chemotherapy-induced nausea and vomiting. Clinical Journal of Oncology Nursing, 11(1), 69-78. </li></ul></p>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a>\r\n\r\n<div id="credit"><p>This information was developed in collaboration with Michigan State University and the Behavioral Cooperative Oncology Group.</p></div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->'),
(100300104504, 'Neutropinia', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Neutropenia</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext">\r\n\r\n<ul><li><a href=#1>What is neutropenia?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>How do people describe neutropenia?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>What causes neutropenia?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>What happens to people when they have neutropenia?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What can I do about neutropenia?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>How is neutropenia managed?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#7>What can family members and friends do to help me with my neutropenia?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#8>How can I talk to family members and friends about my neutropenia?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#9>What should I report to my healthcare provider? </a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#10>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about neutropenia? </a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#11>Where can I get more information?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#12>References</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#13>Supportive evidence-based practice</a></li>\r\n</ul><br />\r\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What is neutropenia?</h1><p>Neutropenia is a low level of white blood cells (WBC), which are called neutrophils.  WBC defends the body against infection.  Neutrophils make up a large part of the total WBC count, and protect against most types of bacterial infections.  People who have neutropenia are at risk of infection.  Their bodies do not have the normal number of white blood cells needed to fight off infection.</p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>How do people describe neutropenia?</h1><p>Neutropenia will not necessarily cause you to become sick. You may not have any symptoms. Watch for signs of infection.<br /><br />There are several types of WBC.  Each plays an important role in the body\'s defense system.  Ask your healthcare provider when you are most likely to have low blood counts so that you can take extra precautions.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>What causes neutropenia?</h1><p>People undergoing cancer treatments, such as chemotherapy or radiation therapy, are at greater risk for infection. Chemotherapy is the most common cause of a weakened immune system. Radiation therapy can damage the skin and lining layers, making them unable to keep infection out of your body.<br /><br />Cancer treatments, such as radiation and chemotherapy, destroy the most rapidly dividing cells in the body, which includes cancer cells as well as healthy cells, such as red blood cells and white blood cells.<br /><br />The time when your WBC will be at its lowest depends on the type and dose of chemotherapy that you are receiving.  People receiving chemotherapy every 21 days, they tend to experience low blood counts 10 to 14 days after a treatment. It is important to take precautions against infection during this time. Ask your healthcare provider when you will most likely have low counts.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>What happens to people when they have neutropenia?</h1><p>An infection occurs when bacteria or viruses grow, causing illness. The body has a normal defense system against infection that includes: skin, gastrointestinal tract (GI tract) lining, blood cells, and the immune system. When the WBC is low some people with neutropenia may have a fever, chills or sweating.  These symptoms can indicate your body is trying to fight off an infection. It becomes much more difficult for the body to help fight infection without as many neutrophils. The longer a person is neutropenic, the greater the risk for infection. </p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What can I do about neutropenia?</h1><p>While you are having treatment, you are more likely to get an infection because your body has of fewer neutrophils to fight of germs. People need to watch carefully for early signs of infection. Call your healthcare provider immediately if you have any signs or symptoms of infection. <br /><br />Here are some tips you might find helpful:<br /><br /><h2>ACTIVITY</h2><ul> <li> Take your temperature daily at about the same time or as recommended by your healthcare provider.  This might be up to 4 times per day or every 4 hours if you temperature is up. </li> <li> Keep a record of you temperature on a sheet of paper. </li> <li> Wash your hands often with antibacterial soap when handling raw meat, fruits, or vegetables.  Proper hand washing is especially important after using the bathroom or blowing your nose. </li> <li> Moisturize hands after washing.  This will help skin from cracking. </li> <li> Use electric shavers. </li> <li> Wash all fresh fruits and vegetables carefully with tap water before preparing them.  Try a fruit and vegetable wash such as Fit. </li> <li> Get enough rest and try not to get overly tired. </li> <li> Cover yourself with a blanket if you are chilled or a single sheet if you are hot. </li> <li> Avoid constipation or straining with bowel movements. Use a stool softener daily if needed. </li> <li> Clean your rectal area gently but thoroughly after each bowel movement -- wipe front to back. </li> <li> Wear shoes to prevent cuts on feet. </li> <li> Wear protective gloves when you are gardening or cleaning up after pets. </li> <li> Use deodorant rather than antiperspirant. </li> <li> Bath daily. </li> <li> Do not brush teeth vigorously.  This may injure gums.  Use a soft toothbrush and mild toothpaste. </li> <li> Avoid contact with fresh flowers and plants.  The soil and plants may have bacteria that your body is unable to fight. </li> <li> Avoid contact with animal feces, saliva, or urine. </li> <li> Wash hands after any contact with animals. </li> <li> Do not clean birdcages, cat litter boxes, or dog kennels. </li> <li> Avoid contact with crowds or large groups of people. </li> <li> Avoid people that are sick. </li> <li> Do not attend large or crowded social events when your WBC is low. </li> <li> Do not get manicures, pedicures or pick at your cuticles.  Open sores or nicks around your nails can easily become infected. </li></ul><br /><h2>COMMUNICATION</h2><ul> <li> Report loose stools or diarrhea lasting more than 24 hours to your healthcare provider. </li> <li> Call your healthcare provider if you have a temperature above 100.9 F (38.3 C) or higher than 100.4 F (38.0 C) that lasts for more than an hour.  Do not take any Tylenol&#174; or ibuprofen&#174; products without asking your healthcare provider. </li></ul><br /><h2>DIET</h2><ul> <li> Drink plenty of fluids, including water, popsicles, and fruit juices (at least 8 (8oz.) glasses per day). </li> <li> Avoid eating raw meat or eggs and any fish or shellfish during treatment. </li> <li> Peel and cook fruits and vegetables. </li> <li> Avoid salad bars in restaurants.  (Bacterial growth is encouraged when many people touch the food.) </li></ul><br /><h2>MEDICATION</h2><ul> <li> Do not use enemas or suppositories. </li></ul></p><a name="6"></a><h1>How is neutropenia managed?</h1><p>Your doctor may order a medication called colony stimulating factors (CSFSs) to help your bone marrow produce more white blood cells after your cancer treatment. The most common medications are neupogen and neulasta. These medications can help reduce your risk of infection and also prevent delays in your chemotherapy schedule or lowering of your chemotherapy dose. <br /><br />These medications are given by injection under the skin over a number of days. Your healthcare provider will determine how many days of shots you will need. Many patients and family members learn how to administer the shots at home. </p><br /><a name="7"></a><h1>What can family members and friends do to help me with my neutropenia?</h1><p>Ask family members and friends to: <ul> <li> Keep track of temperature. </li> <li> Wash their hands frequently. </li> <li> Remind you to drink more fluids. </li> <li> Care for your pets. </li> <li> Help wash and prepare fruits and vegetables. </li></ul></p><a name="8"></a><h1>How can I talk to family members and friends about my neutropenia?</h1><p>Here are some ideas that may help you talk to family members and friends:<ul> <li> Tell them how the low white blood count might affect your daily activities. </li> <li> Explain why you need to stay away from crowds of people and people who are sick. </li></ul></p><a name="9"></a><h1>What should I report to my healthcare provider?</h1><p>If you experience any of the following symptoms, report them to your healthcare provider:<ul> <li> Any signs of infection or an overall feeling of being real sick or exhausted. If you have a very low neutrophil count the normal signs of infection, such as pus from a wound, and inflammation (pain, swelling, and redness) may be absent. It is important to know that a fever may be the only sign of an infection. </li> <li> A temperature spike above 100.9 F (38.3 C), or a temperature higher than 100.4 F (38.0 C) that lasts for more than an hour, or as set by your doctor\'s office. </li> <li> Increased skin temp. </li> <li> Body aches. </li> <li> Shaking, chills, or swats. </li> <li> Burning with urination. </li> <li> Headache. </li> <li> Vaginal discharge or itching. </li> <li> Sore throat. </li> <li> Mouth sores. </li> <li> Cough, excess mucous. </li> <li> Feeling confused, dizzy or weak. </li> <li> Redness, swelling or warmth at an intravenous (IV) site, or wound. </li> <li> Pus or drainage from a wound or incision. </li> <li> Diarrhea or loose stools for 24 hours. </li> <li> Productive cough with yellow or green sputum (spit). </li> <li> Difficulty swallowing. </li> <li> Sinus tenderness or nasal congestion. </li> <li> Shortness of breath or painful breathing. </li> <li> Frequent urge to urinate. </li> <li> Pain, burning, redness, swelling or drainage anywhere. </li> <li> Pain with bowel movements. </li> <li> Stomach pain or cramps. </li></ul></p><a name="10"></a><h1>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about neutropenia?</h1><p>If you are experiencing neutropenia, you should discuss the following with your healthcare provider at your next appointment:<ul> <li> Is it ok for me to get my flu and/or pneumococcal vaccine? </li> <li> Can I travel with low blood counts? </li> <li> Is it ok for me to be intimate with my spouse or partner? </li> <li> Can I have dental work done? </li> <li> What are my risks of developing neutropenia with the chemotherapy I am taking? </li></ul></p><a name="11"></a><h1>Where can I get more information?</h1><p>For more information, contact the people or organizations at the numbers or websites listed below:<ul> <li> Contact your doctor or nurse. </li> <li> National Cancer Institute: 1-800-4-CANCER or <a href=http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo/ target=_blank>http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo/</a> Click on coping with cancer. Find and click on fever, sweats. </li> <li> American Cancer Society: 1-800-ACS-2345 or <a href=http://www.cancer.org target=_blank>http://www.cancer.org</a> </li> <li> Cancer Symptoms: <a href=http://www.cancersymptoms.org target=_blank>http://www.cancersymptoms.org</a> Click on cancer symptoms. Find and click on neutropenia. </li> <li> Family Care Research Program: <a href=http://www.cancercare.msu.edu target=_blank>http://www.cancercare.msu.edu</a> </li> <li> National Comprehensive Cancer Network. Fever and neutropenia guidelines for patients with cancer, retrieved from <a href=http://www.nccn.org/patients/patient_gls/_english/_fever_and_neutropenia/1_introduction.asp#understanding_fever target=_blank>http://www.nccn.org/patients/patient_gls/_english/_fever_and_neutropenia/1_introduction.asp#understanding_fever</a> </li></ul></p><a name="12"></a><h1>References</h1><p><ul> <li> Barber, F.D. (2001) Management of fever in neutropenic patients with cancer. Nursing Clinics Of North America, 36(4): 631-644. </li> <li> Cancersymptoms.org at: <a href=http://www.cancersymptoms.org/neutropenia/ target=_blank>http://www.cancersymptoms.org/neutropenia/</a> </li> <li> Marrs, J.(2006). Care of patients with neutropenia. Clinical Journal of Oncology Nursing, 10(2), 164-166. </li> <li> National Cancer Institute (n.d.) National Cancer Institute. Retrieved from <a href=http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo/ target=_blank>http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo/</a> </li> <li> National Coalition For Cancer Survivorship (2008). National Coalition for Cancer Survivorship. Retrieved from: <a href=http://www.canceradvocacy.org target=_blank>http://www.canceradvocacy.org</a> </li> <li> National Comprehensive Cancer Network (2007).Nationa lComprehensive Cancer Network. Retrieved from <a href=http://www.nccn.org target=_blank>http://www.nccn.org</a> </li> <li> Wilson, B.J. (2002). Dietary recommendations for neutropenic patients. Seminars In Oncology Nursing, 18(1), 44-9. </li> <li> Wujcik, D. (2003). Infection. In C.H. Yarbro, M.H. Frogge, & M. Goodman (Eds.), Cancer Symptom Management, 3rd Ed. (Pp. 252-275). Boston: Jones And Bartlett. </li> <li> Zitella, L., Friese, C., Hauser, J., Gobel, B., Woolery, M., & O\'leary, C. (2006). Putting evidence into practice: Prevention of infection. Clinical Journal Of Oncology Nursing, 10 (6), 739-750. </li></ul></p><a name="13"></a><h1>Supportive evidence-based practice</h1><p><ul> <li> Hartkopf-Smith, L., & Galford-Besser, S. (2000). Dietary restrictions for patients with neutropenia: A survey of instiutional practices. Oncology Nursing Forum, 27 (3), 515-520. </li> <li> Nirenber, A., Bush, A., Davis, A., Friese, C., Gillespie, T., & Rice, R. (2006). Neutropenia: State of the knowledge part 1 & 11. Oncology Nursing Forum, 33(6), 1193-1208. </li></ul></p>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a>\r\n\r\n<div id="credit"><p>This information was developed in collaboration with Michigan State University and the Behavioral Cooperative Oncology Group.</p></div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->');
