(100300105704, 'Physical Functioning', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Physical Functioning</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext">\r\n\r\n<ul><li><a href=#1>What is physical functioning?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>How do people describe physical functioning?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>What can I do about changes in physical functioning?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>What can family members and friends do to help me with changes in my physical functioning?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>How can I talk to my family members and friends about my physical functioning?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I report to my healthcare provider about my physical functioning? </a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#7>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about my physical functioning? </a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#8>Where can I get more information?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#9>References</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#10>Supportive evidence-based practice</a></li>\r\n</ul><br />\r\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What is physical functioning?</h1><p>Physical functioning is the ability to keep up physically with the demands of everyday life. It is getting around and the ability to do your daily activities.</p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>How do people describe physical functioning?</h1><p>People describe physical functioning as the activities of daily living: bathing, grooming, cooking, cleaning, eating, getting work, driving, and shopping. Physical functioning can be affected by feeling weak, tired, low red blood count, infection, pain, fatigue, or a decreased vitality.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>What can I do about changes in physical functioning?</h1><p>Here are some tips you might find helpful:<br /><br /><h2>ACTIVITY</h2><ul> <li> Set priorities for activities you must complete during the day. </li> <li> Delegate activities to others that you are unable to complete or feel comfortable delegating. </li> <li> Use a cane or walker to prevent falls. </li> <li> Let others help you with housework, chores or meal preparation. </li> <li> Select important things to do first. </li> <li> Change your work schedule. </li> <li> Consider reducing your work hours or taking time off during the weeks you have cancer treatment. </li> <li> Do range of motion exercises using your arms and legs for 5-10 minutes daily. </li> <li> Exercise daily. </li> <li> Keep active and walk each day. </li> <li> Arrange your home to promote safety.  Remove obstacles, throw rugs, and clutter. </li></ul><br /><h2>COMMUNICATION</h2><ul> <li> Check with your healthcare provider about how much exercise and activity you should do each day. Make exercise part of your daily routine. </li></ul></p><a name="4"></a><h1>What can family members and friends do to help me with changes in my physical functioning?</h1><p>Ask family members and friends to:<ul> <li> Do the grocery and other shopping for you. </li> <li> Prepare meals for you. </li> <li> Help with transportation. </li> <li> Assist with household chores. </li> <li> Help you prioritize your to-do list. </li> <li> Walk with you. </li></ul></p><a name="5"></a><h1>How can I talk to my family members and friends about my physical functioning?</h1><p>Here are some ideas that may help you talk to family members and friends:<ul> <li> Ask family members and friends for suggestions on how to prioritize work at home and in the workplace. </li> <li> Tell family members and friends how changes in your physical functioning are affecting your mood and emotions. </li> <li> Ask how these changes are affecting your family and friends. </li></ul></p><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I report to my healthcare provider about my physical functioning?</h1><p>If you experience any of the following symptoms, report them to your healthcare provider:<ul> <li> Severe numbness. </li> <li> Changes in physical functioning that interfere with your ability to carry out your basic activities of caring for yourself. </li> <li> Changes that keep you limited to a bed or chair for more than 24 hours. </li> <li> Uncontrollable pain. </li> <li> Unable to walk. </li></ul></p><a name="7"></a><h1>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about my physical functioning?</h1><p>If you are experiencing a decrease in your physical functioning, you should discuss the following with your healthcare provider at your next appointment:<ul> <li> What exercises do you recommend for me? </li> <li> Are there exercises that I should avoid? </li> <li> Can you refer me to an exercise trainer or physical therapist to help me get started? </li></ul></p><a name="8"></a><h1>Where can I get more information?</h1><p>For more information, contact the people or organizations at the numbers or websites listed below:<ul> <li> American Cancer Society: 1-800-ACS-2345 or <a href=http://www.cancer.org target=_blank>http://www.cancer.org</a> Click on patients, family & friends, then on coping with treatment, followed by coping with physical and emotional chances. Click on taking care of someone at home under side effects followed by difficulty in moving. </li> <li> Family Care Research Program: <a href=http://www.cancercare.msu.edu target=_blank>http://www.cancercare.msu.edu</a> </li> <li> National Cancer Institute: 1-800-4-CANCER or <a href=http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo target=_blank>http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo</a> Click on coping with cancer. </li> <li> National Coalition for Cancer Survivorship: <a href=http://canceradvocacy.org target=_blank>http://canceradvocacy.org</a> Click on Resource Guide. </li> <li> CancerHelp&#174;: <a href=http://cancerhelp.org target=_blank>http://cancerhelp.org</a> </li></ul></p><a name="9"></a><h1>References</h1><p><ul> <li> Armstrong, T.S. (2003). Symptoms experience: A concept analysis. Oncology Nursing Forum, 30(4), 601-606. </li> <li> Dodd, M., Miakowski, C., & Paul, S.M. (2001). Symptom clusters and their effects on the functional status of patients with cancer. Oncology Nursing Forum, 28, 465-470. </li> <li> Gift, A., G., Jablonski, A., Stommel, M., & Given, C. (2004). Symptom clusters in elderly patients with lung cancer. Oncology Nursing Forum, 31(2) P. 203-210. </li> <li> Given, B., Given, C.W., Mccorkle, R., Kozachik, S., Cimprich, B., Rahbar, M.H., & Wojcik, C. (2002). Pain and fatigue management: results of a nursing randomized clinical trial. Oncology Nursing Forum, 29(6), 1-14. </li> <li> Given, B., Given, C., Azzouz, F., & Stommel, M. (2001). Physical functioning of elderly cancer patients prior to diagnosis and following initial treatment. Nursing Research, 50, 222-232. </li> <li> Holley, S. (2002). A look at the problem of falls among people with cancer. Clinical Journal Of Oncology Nursing, 6(4), 193-197. </li> <li> Mock, V., Dow, K.H., Meares, C., Grimm, P., Dienemann, J., Haisfield-Wolfe, M.E., Et Al. (1997). Effects of exercise on fatigue, physical functioning, and emotional distress during radiation therapy for breast cancer. Oncology Nursing Forum, 24, 991-1000. </li></ul></p><a name="10"></a><h1>Supportive evidence-based practice</h1><p><ul> <li> Adamsen, L., Midtgarrd, J., Rorth, M., Borregaard, N., Andersen, C., Quist, M., & Et Al. (2003). Feasibility, physical capacity, and health benefits of a multidimensional exercise program for cancer patients undergoing chemotherapy. Supportive Care Cancer, 11, 707-716. </li> <li> Armstrong, T.S. (2003). Symptoms experience: A concept analysis. Oncology Nursing Forum, 30(4), 601-606. </li> <li> Mctiernan, A. (2004). Physical activity after cancer: Physiologic outcomes. Cancer Investigation, 22 (1), 68-81. </li> <li> Mock, V., Picket, M., Ropka, M., Lin, E., Stewart, K., Rhodes, V., Et Al. (2001). Fatigue, physical functioning, emotional distress, and quality of life outcomes of a walking intervention during breast cancer treatment. Cancer Practice, 9, 119-127. </li> <li> Zacho, M. (2003). Feasibility, physical capacity, and health benefits of a multidimensional exercise program for cancer patients undergoing chemotherapy. Supportive Care Cancer, 11, 707-716. </li></ul></p>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a>\r\n\r\n<div id="credit"><p>This information was developed in collaboration with Michigan State University and the Behavioral Cooperative Oncology Group.</p></div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->'),
(100300106004, 'Rash', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\n<h1>Rash</h1>\n\n<div id="symptomtext">\n\n<ul><li><a href=#1>What is rash?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#2>How do people describe rash?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#3>What causes a rash?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#4>What can I do about rash?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#5>What can family and friends do to help with my rash?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#6>How can I talk with my family members and friends about my rash?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#7>Drugs that may be prescribed by your healthcare provider</a></li>\n<li><a href=#8>What should I report to my healthcare provider about my rash?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#9>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about my rash?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#10>Where can I get more information?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#11>References</a></li>\n<li><a href=#12>Supportive evidence-based practice</a></li>\n</ul><br />\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What is a rash?</h1><p>A rash is any change in the skin that alters its appearance or texture. It may affect all of the skin or be localized to one part of the body. Rashes can irritate the skin by causing it to itch, change colors, become warm, bumpy, dry, crack or blister. Swelling and pain can also occur. If you are receiving chemotherapy it is important to let your healthcare provider know when you develop a rash. It will be important for you to describe the appearance of the rash, where it is located, when it first appeared, and any symptoms you are experiencing.</p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>How do people describe rash?</h1><p>Rash is a general term for a skin reaction. There are many terms used to describe what the rash looks like such as:<ul> <li> Erythematous - Redness. </li> <li> Macular - Small, distinct, flat areas. </li> <li> Papular - Small raised lesions. </li> <li> Macular-Papular - Usually bright red in color. The skin may feel hot, burning, or itchy. </li> <li> Hives (uticaria) - Round, raised, itchy, or red blotches, which may be pale in the center and red around the outside. </li> <li> Follicular eruptions - Tiny sacs on the skin surface from which hair grows.  These eruptions look very similar to acne. Some doctors call it an acne-like rash. Follicular eruptions are raised and can be filled with pus have a yellow drainage. </li> <li> Itching (or pruitis) - A peculiar tingling or uneasy irritation of the skin that causes a desire to scratch the affected area. Itching may be over the whole body (generalized), or only in a particular location (localized). </li> <li> Flushing - A temporary redness of the face and neck caused by swelling of the blood vessels. </li> <li> Blistering - Round raised areas of fluid under the upper layer of the skin, which can weep or drain clear fluid. </li> <li> Honey yellow crusting - Yellowish-brown crust over the red eruptions with oozing of fluid from lesions may indicate a bacterial infection. </li></ul></p><a name="3"></a><h1>What causes a rash?</h1><p>It is very important that you understand the side effects of your chemotherapy treatment. Many chemotherapy drugs can cause rashes and skin changes. Some of the skin reactions can develop immediately during treatment or within the first 36 hours after receiving your treatment. This is an acute allergic or hypersensitivity reaction causing hives, flushing and itching. It is very important that you let your healthcare provider know immediately if you experience this type of rash. This is your body\'s protective immune response to a foreign substance that has entered the body, such as chemotherapy. This is not a common reaction, but is more common with certain chemotherapy drugs, such as, Paclitaxel, Bleomycin, L-Asparaginase, Docetaxel, Cisplatin, Carbotaxol and Monoclonal Antibodies. <b>Ask your healthcare provider if your chemotherapy might cause a reaction</b>.<br /><br /><b>Allergic drug rashes can also be delayed developing within days or weeks after your treatment.</b> This type of skin rash usually develops on the back of the body. The arms and legs are often involved however, the face is not usually affected. This rash is usually bright red in color, and the skin will feel hot and burning. It is very important to let your healthcare provider know all the medications that you are currently taking and whether you have any medication allergies or history of allergic reactions.<br /><br />There are many new chemotherapy drugs that are associated with rashes. Scientists have developed numerous new drugs that appear to be effective treatments for many different kinds of cancer. Known as <b>targeted treatments</b>, these drugs are designed to prevent cancer cells from getting nourished, growing, dividing, and possibly spreading.  Targeted treatments are different than chemotherapy.  Unlike chemotherapy, which can harm healthy cells as it kills cancer cells, targeted treatments focus on blocking cancer cell growth and killing cancer cells.  Treatments may be given in combination with chemotherapy or alone as a single treatment.<br /><br />In particular, one type of targeted treatment blocks the epidermal growth factor receptors (EGFRs), which can cause rashes and dry skin.  These rashes are not an allergic response.  They are a side effect from the drug itself.  EGFR - blocking drugs that commonly cause a rash include Cetuximab (Erbitux&#174;), Erlotinib (Tarceva&#174;), Gefitinib (Iressa&#174;) and Panitumumab (Vectibix&#174;). <br /><br />Another type of targeted treatment blocks the development of blood vessels that feed tumors.  It is called vascular endothelial growth factors receptors (VEGFRs).  VEGF - blocking drugs include Sorafenib (Nexavar&#174;) and Sunitinib (Sutent&#174;).<br /><br />These rashes usually appear within 1-3 weeks of treatment. The rash is characterized by an acne-like rash with pustules.  Generally, they first appear on the face, particularly around the nose or on the cheeks.  However, the rash may also appear on the back, arms and legs. The severity of the rash may come and go during your treatment. Typically the rash clears up within 1-2 months after your treatment is completed. The rash normally does not require you to stop your treatment. Some studies have suggested that the rash may actually be a positive sign that your body is responding to the drug. <b>It is very important that you notify your healthcare provider if this rash develops.  This rash is NOT acne.  Do not treat it with acne medication</b>.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>What can I do about rash?</h1><p>Here are some tips you might find helpful:<br /><br /><h2>ACTIVITY</h2><ul> <li> Wear loose soft cotton clothing. </li> <li> Use a mild moisturizing soap without perfumes when bathing.  Examples of mild moisturizing soaps are Dove&#174;, Ivory&#174; Skin Cleansing Liquid Gel, Cetaphil&#174;, Neutrogena&#174; and Aveeno&#174;. </li> <li> Pat skin gently after washing the area with a clean soft towel or washcloth. </li> <li> Avoid exposing your skin to temperature extremes.  Try not to use hot lamps, ice packs, heating pads and electric blankets. </li> <li> Treat dry skin with emollient lotions, such as: Eucerin&#174; Cream, Cetaphil&#174; Cream, Bag&#174; Balm, Udder&#174; Cream, Zim\'s&#174; Crack Cream, Aquaphor&#174; ointment, Vanicream&#174;, Neutrogena&#174;, or Vaseline&#174; Intensive Care (dye free & alcohol free). </li> <li> Treat itchy skin with the emollient lotions listed above and Aveeno&#174; Baths, Sarna&#174; Ultra Cream, Regenecare&#174; Gel, Gold Bond&#174; Powder and Sweet cream. </li> <li> Strong gloves will help avoid skin contact with friction and harsh chemicals, which can further damage your skin.  Wear light cotton gloves when gardening or doing outdoor work.  Put on rubber or latex gloves before washing dishes. </li> <li> Use Band-Aid&#174; brand Liquid Bandage, Bag&#174; Balm, and Zim\'s&#174; Crack Cream for cracks and fissures. </li> <li> For inflammation around your fingernails try soaking your fingertips in a solution of white vinegar diluted 1:10 in tap water for 5 minutes a day. </li> <li> Wash your clothes and other fabrics that come in direct contact with your skin in mild hypoallergenic detergents.  Deft and Tide make a hypoallergenic laundry soap.  Read the label to be sure that buy the correct type. </li> <li> Avoid tanning beds. </li> <li> Wear sunscreen everyday, even on cloudy days.  Your sensitivity to the sun has increased.  Wearing long sleeves and long pants can help but you still need to wear sunscreen.  A new ingredient called Helioplex keeps a sunscreen from breaking down.  Helioplex is gentle on sensitive skin and can be found in several Neutrogena sunscreens, including Neutrogena Ultra Sheer Dry Tough Sunblock SPF 55. </li> <li> Wear a hat. </li> <li> DO NOT treat the rash with acne medication such as Clearasil&#174;, Oxy&#174;, Benzoyl&#174; Peroxide&#174;, or Stridex&#174;. </li> <li> Makeup is safe to use, but avoid makeup products that contain many ingredients. </li> <li> Avoid lotions, creams and soaps that contain alcohol, perfumes, or dyes.  These ingredients may increase dryness and can cause further skin irritation. </li></ul><br /><h2>COMMUNICATION</h2><ul> <li> Call your healthcare provider immediately if a new rash appears before your next appointment. </li></ul><br /><h2>DIET</h2><ul> <li> Drink 8 (8oz.) glasses of water or other non-caffeinated drinks every day.  Avoid caffeine (i.e. colas, coffee) when possible.  Caffeine can cause dehydration. </li></ul><br /><h2>MEDICATION</h2><ul> <li> Ask your healthcare provider if a topical or oral medication is right for you. They may be able to prescribe one. </li></ul></p><a name="5"></a><h1>What can family and friends do to help with my rash?</h1><p>Ask family and friends to:<ul> <li> Help select proper lotions for dryness and itching. </li> <li> Help remind you to wear sunscreen when outside. </li> <li> Help apply medications and lotions to skin if necessary. </li> <li> Assist you with chores around the house. </li> <li> Help bathing to keep skin clean. </li> <li> Help by letting your healthcare provider know if rashes or itching occur. </li></ul></p><a name="6"></a><h1>How can I talk with my family members and friends about my rash?</h1><p>Here are some ideas that may help you talk to family members and friends:<ul> <li> Describe how having a rash makes you feel. </li> <li> Ask your family member how your rash is affecting them. </li> <li> Ask family members for support or suggestion to help cope with the rash. </li> <li> Tell family members what feels good and helps with the rash. </li> <li> Try describing how the itching or rash may interfere with your usual activities. </li></ul></p><a name="7"></a><h1>Drugs that may be prescribed by your healthcare provider</h1><p><ul> <li> Topical steroid creams are currently not recommended. </li> <li> Topical antibiotics creams may include: </li><br /><ul> <li> Clindamycin</li> <li>Erythromycin<br/><br/></ul> <li> Antibiotics taken by mouth in pill form may include: </li><br /><ul> <li> Tetracyline</li> <li>Minocylcline</li> <li>Doxycycline<br/><br/></ul> <li> Mild, localized itching may benefit from a topical antihistamine cream like Benadryl&#174;. Oral antihistamine drugs, such as, Benadryl&#174;, Claritin&#174;, or Allegra&#174; are all available over the counter and can be helpful for severe itching.  If the rash hurts, pain medications may be prescribed. </li></ul></p><a name="8"></a><h1>What should I report to my healthcare provider about my rash?</h1><p>If you experience any of the following symptoms, report them to your healthcare provider:<ul> <li> Report all rashes even if they are not causing you discomfort. Not all rashes require treatment. </li> <li> Any new fever reading above 100.9 (38.3), or a temperature higher than 100.4 F (38.0 C) that lasts for more than an hour. Make sure that when you take your temperature you have not had any hot drinks within the last 10-15 minutes. </li> <li> Increase warmth or redness to the skin area. </li> <li> Any drainage or pus from the rash. </li> <li> A rash that will not go away or becomes infected. </li> <li> Any blisters that formed. </li> <li> Cracking or peeling fingernails. </li> <li> Dry nagging cough. </li> <li> Severe or unmanageable itching. </li> <li> Hives, flushing and difficulty breathing. Seek help immediately and notify your healthcare provider. </li> <li> If your rash worsens or if the medications prescribed by your healthcare provider are not working. </li></ul></p><a name="9"></a><h1>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about my rash?</h1><p>If you are experiencing a rash, you should discuss the following with your healthcare provider at your next appointment:<ul> <li> Am I at risk for developing an allergic reaction or rash with my treatment? </li> <li> Do I need to take any medications prior to my treatment to reduce my risk of reaction? </li> <li> Do I stop taking my chemotherapy if I develop at rash? </li> <li> Can I wear make-up if I develop a rash? </li></ul></p><a name="10"></a><h1>Where can I get more information?</h1><p>For more information, contact the people or organizations at the numbers or websites listed below:<ul> <li> Call your healthcare provider. </li> <li> American Cancer Society: 1-800-ACS-2345 or <a href=http://www.cancer.org target=_blank>http://www.cancer.org</a> Click on patients, family & friends, then coping with treatment. </li> <li> National Cancer Institute: 1-800-4-CANCER or <a href=http://www.cancer.gov target=_blank>http://www.cancer.gov</a> Click on coping with cancer. </li> <li> Family Care Research Program: <a href=http://cancercare.msu.edu target=_blank>http://cancercare.msu.edu</a> </li> <li> Chemo Care: <a href=http://www.chemocare.com target=_blank>http://www.chemocare.com</a>   Click on managing side effects. </li> <li> Cancer<i>Care</i>: <a href=http://CancerCare.org target=_blank>http://CancerCare.org</a> or 1-800-813-HOPE (4673). </li></ul></p><a name="11"></a><h1>References</h1><p><ul> <li> Esper, P., Gale, D. & Muehlbauer, P. (2007).  What kind of rash is it? Deciphering the dermatologic toxicities or biologic and targeted therapies. Clinical Journal of Oncology Nursing, 11(5) 659-666. </li> <li> Lacouture, M.E. (2007) Tips to help with EGFR Targeted therapy. The Oncologist. AlphaMed Press. </li> <li> Lynch, T.J., Kim, E.S., Garey, J., West, D.P., Lacouture, M.E. (2007). Epidermal growth factor receptor inhibitor- Associated cutaneous toxicities: An evolving paradigm in clinical management. The Oncologist,12, 610-621. </li> <li> Oestreicher, P. (2007). Mangage Skin Toxicities Associated with Targeted Therapies. ONS connect, 22(11):20-21. </li> <li> Oishi, K. (2008). Clinical approaches to minimize rash associated with EGFR inhibitors. Oncology Nursing Forum, 35(1): 103-111. </li> <li> Sipples, R. (2006). Common side effects of Anti-EGF therapy: Acneform Rash. Seminars in Oncology Nursing, 22(1), 28-34. </li> <li> Viele, C., S. (2005). Keys to unlock cancer: Targeted therapy. Oncology Nursing Forum, 23(5), 935-940. </li> <li> Perez-Soler, R., Delord, J., Halpern, A., Kelly, K., Krueger, J. & Sureda, B. et al. (2005). HER1/EGFR Inhibitor-associated rash: Future directions for management and investigation outcomes from the HER/EGFR inhibitor rash management forum. The Oncologist, 10, 345-356. </li> <li> Family Care Research Program, Michigan State University. Retrieved September 21, 2006 from <a href=http://www.cancercare.msu.edu target=_blank>http://www.cancercare.msu.edu</a> </li> <li> National Cancer Institute. Retrieved September 21, 2006 from <a href=http://www.cancer.gov target=_blank>http://www.cancer.gov</a> </li> <li> Hamilton, S. Care during chemotherapy and beyond: Skin reactions & Allergic reaction and chemotherapy. Retrieved September 21, 2006 from Http://chemocare.com/managing/skin_reactions.asp, Http://www.chemocare.com/managing/allergic_reactions_and_chemotherapy.asp. </li> <li> Herberst, R., Fox, L., Viele, C., & Messner, C. Managing rash and other skin reactions to targeted treatments. Retrieved October 26, 2006 from <a href=http://cancercare.org target=_blank>http://cancercare.org</a> </li> <li> Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia. Retrieved September 21, 2006 from <a href=http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rash target=_blank>http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rash</a> </li> <li> Fox, L. (2006). Pathology and management of dermatologic toxicities associated with anti-EGFR Therapy. Oncology, 20(5) suppl. 26-33. </li></ul></p><a name="12"></a><h1>Supportive evidence-based practice</h1><p><ul> <li> Lenz, H. (2006). Anti-EGFR mechanism of action: Antitumor effect and underlying cause of adverse events. Oncology, 20(5) suppl. 5-13. </li> <li> Write, L. (2006). Maculopapular skin rashes associated with high-dose chemotherapy: Prevalence and risk factors. Oncology Nursing Forum, 33(6), 1095-1103. </li></ul></p>\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a>\n\n<div id="credit"><p>This information was developed in collaboration with Michigan State University and the Behavioral Cooperative Oncology Group.</p></div>\n\n</div>\n\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->'),
(100300106304, 'Remembering', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Remembering Things</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext">\r\n\r\n<ul><li><a href=#1>What is trouble with remembering things (Cognitive Dysfunction)? </a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>How do people describe difficulty remembering things? </a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>What causes difficulty remembering things? </a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>What can I do about difficulty remembering things? </a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>How is difficulty remembering things managed? </a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What can family members and friends do to help with my difficulty remembering things? </a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#7>How can I talk to my family members about my difficulty remembering things? </a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#8>What should I report to my healthcare provider about my difficulty remembering things? </a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#9>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about my difficulty remembering things? </a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#10>Where can I get more information?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#11>References</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#12>Supportive evidence-based practice</a></li>\r\n</ul><br />\r\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What is trouble with remembering things (Cognitive Dysfunction)?</h1><p>Cancer patients may experience a decline in mental functioning, ranging from mild impairment (lack of concentration) to extreme impairment (delirium). People with delirium may feel confused, excited, or disoriented. </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>How do people describe difficulty remembering things?</h1><p>People may describe cognitive impairment as mental fatigue, "chemo brain", or "brain fog". This includes problems with distraction, feeling exhausted by tasks that require mental energy, or problems with handling complex information. In more extreme cases people may have difficulty with their sleep/wake cycle, mood changes, disorganized thinking and speech, inability to concentrate, or short-term memory loss.<br /><br />People often notice these problems during their chemotherapy treatment. Within one year of treatment, people find that these symptoms are greatly improved or no longer exist. However for some people, "chemo brain" can continue for years following the completion of treatment.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>What causes difficulty remembering things?</h1><p>The primary causes of cognitive problems are the cancer itself and the treatments involved in working to cure it. Other things that can contribute to cognitive problems are: <ul> <li> The central nervous system, including the brain, is particularly sensitive to many cancer treatments. Cancer treatments such as chemotherapy and immunotherapy are not precise. They affect more parts of your body than just where the cancer tumor is located. </li> <li> Poor nutrition. Low levels of iron, Vitamin B and folic acid can decrease a person\'s memory and abilities to pay attention or speak. </li> <li> Medicine. Some of the medications used to manage side effects, such as pain and nausea can make people sleepy and less alert. Others like antibiotics to fight infection and steroids can also impair mental function. </li> <li> Rapid changes in hormone levels, such as the kind women experience from menopause-inducing chemotherapies or hormone-producing cancer can alter brain function and cause forgetfulness. </li> <li> Stress, spread of the cancer to the brain and low red blood cells (anemia). </li> <li> Anxiety and depression. </li> <li> Discomfort from other side effects, such as constipation and diarrhea. </li></ul></p><a name="4"></a><h1>What can I do about difficulty remembering things?</h1><p>Keeping your memory sharp is very important. Here are some tips that you might find helpful: <br /><br /><h2>ACTIVITY</h2><ul> <li> Work a crossword or other kind of puzzle. </li> <li> Play a musical instrument. </li> <li> Take up a hobby such as needlework, crocheting or knitting. </li> <li> Paint a picture. </li> <li> Try woodworking or gardening. </li> <li> Go to a lecture or an educational program that interests you. </li> <li> Try walking every day for 15-30 minutes, preferably outside. </li> <li> Take the stairs instead of the elevator. </li> <li> Take up gardening. </li> <li> Hiking, cycling and driving. </li> <li> Observe wildlife: birds and animals.  Look out your window and watch the birds or other animals. </li> <li> Cancer support groups can offer a wonderful opportunity to speak with others likely experiencing side effects like yours. </li> <li> Combat fatigue -- learn some management strategies. </li> <li> Keep pocket organizers. </li> <li> Concentrate on what matters and divide activities up into manageable parts.  You will feel a greater sense of accomplishment. </li> <li> Make a list to help you remember.  Carry a pad of paper with you to write things down.  Make a list for the day and post it on your refrigerator door. </li> <li> Use a calendar to track appointments and important things to do.  Write down birthdays and doctor appointments. </li> <li> Get enough sleep. </li> <li> Avoid distractions.  Work, read and do your thinking in an uncluttered, peaceful environment. </li> <li> Organize your environment so that things remain in familiar places. </li></ul><br /><h2>DIET</h2><ul> <li> Reduce stimulants, such as caffeine from your diet. </li> <li> Maintain good nutrition and drink plenty of fluids. </li></ul><br /><h2>PSYCHOLOGICAL</h2><ul> <li> Try meditation or guided imagery exercises. </li></ul></p><a name="5"></a><h1>How is difficulty remembering things managed?</h1><p>Some approaches that your healthcare team may use to treat your cognitive problems include:<ul> <li> Counseling. </li> <li> Stimulants and anti-depression medications. </li> <li> Nutrition evaluation and treatment. </li> <li> Physical therapy. </li> <li> Sleep medications. </li></ul></p><a name="6"></a><h1>What can family members and friends do to help with my difficulty remembering things?</h1><p>Ask family members and friends to: <ul> <li> Help remind you of important events. </li> <li> Walk with you. </li> <li> Take up a new hobby with you (See above suggestions). </li> <li> Help you get information on your cancer.  Information can be found on the Internet, through the American Cancer Society or the National Cancer Institute. </li> <li> Buy crossword puzzles for you. </li> <li> Help you cope with your memory loss. </li></ul></p><a name="7"></a><h1>How can I talk to my family members about my difficulty remembering things?</h1><p>Here are some ideas that may help you talk to family members and friends:<ul> <li> Ask for ideas to help improve your mental functioning. </li> <li> Tell family members and friends how this problem is affecting your emotions. </li> <li> Ask your family members and friends for suggestions to improve your memory and concentration. </li> <li> Ask your family member how this problem is affecting them. </li></ul></p><a name="8"></a><h1>What should I report to my healthcare provider about my difficulty remembering things?</h1><p>If you experience any of the following symptoms, report them to your healthcare provider:<ul> <li> Changes in speech pattern, such as slurred speech. </li> <li> Changes in alertness, such as not being alert, or unable to recognize loved ones. </li> <li> Changes in personality. </li> <li> Dramatic mood changes that last more than a few days. </li> <li> Disorganized thinking or feeling "scatter brained". </li></ul></p><a name="9"></a><h1>What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about my difficulty remembering things?</h1><p>If you are experiencing difficulty remembering things, you should discuss the following with your healthcare provider at your next appointment:<ul> <li> Will my cancer treatment cause me to have trouble remembering things? </li> <li> How long do you think my problems will continue? What has been your experience with other patients taking similar treatments? </li> <li> Are there treatments that can help? </li> <li> Will my problems get worse as treatment continues? </li> <li> Do I have any other conditions that I may have that are contributing to this problem? </li></ul></p><a name="10"></a><h1>Where can I get more information?</h1><p>For more information, contact the people or organizations at the numbers or websites listed below:<ul> <li> Contact your healthcare provider. </li> <li> National Cancer Institute: 1-800-4-CANCER or <a href=http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo target=_blank>http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo</a>  Click on coping with cancer. </li> <li> American Cancer Society: 1-800-ACS-2345 or <a href=http://www.cancer.org target=_blank>http://www.cancer.org</a> </li> <li> Family Care Research Program: <a href=http://www.cancercare.msu.edu target=_blank>http://www.cancercare.msu.edu</a> </li> <li> Chemo Care: <a href=http://chemocare.com target=_blank>http://chemocare.com</a>  Click on managing side effects. </li> <li> Oncology Nursing Society: <a href=http://www.cancersymptoms.org target=_blank>http://www.cancersymptoms.org</a> Click on cognitive dysfunction. </li></ul></p><a name="11"></a><h1>References</h1><p><ul> <li> Cohen, M.Z. & Armstrong, T.S. (2003). Cognitive dysfunction. In C.H. Yarbro, M.H. Frogge, & M. Goodman (Eds.), Cancer Symptom Management, 3rd Ed. (Pp. 635-650). Boston: Jones And Bartlett. </li> <li> Jansen, C., Miaskowski, C., Dodd, M., & Dowling, G. (2005). Chemotherapy-induced cognitive impairment in women with breast cancer: a critique of the literature. Oncology Nursing Forum, (32) 2, 329-342. </li> <li> Jansen, C., Miaskowski, C., Dodd, M., Dowling, G. & Kramer, J. (2005). Potential mechanisms for chemotherapy-induced impairments in cognitive function. Oncology Nursing Forum, (32) 6, 1151-1161. </li> <li> National Coalition For Cancer Survivorship: Cognitive Issues From: <a href=http://www.canceradvocacy.org target=_blank>http://www.canceradvocacy.org</a> </li></ul></p><a name="12"></a><h1>Supportive evidence-based practice</h1><p><ul> <li> Booth-Jones, M., Jacobsen, P.B., Ransom, S., & Soety, E. (2005). Characteristics and correlates of cognitive functioning following bone marrow transplantation. Bone Marrow Transplant, 26, 695-702. </li> <li> Staat, K., & Segatore, M. (2005). The phenomenon of chemo brain. The Journal Of Oncology Nursing, (9) 6, 713-721. </li></ul></p>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a>\r\n\r\n<div id="credit"><p>This information was developed in collaboration with Michigan State University and the Behavioral Cooperative Oncology Group.</p></div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->'),
(100300106604, 'Sexual Dysfunction', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Sexual Dysfunction</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext">\r\n\r\n<ul><li><a href=#1>What is sexual dysfunction?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>How do people describe sexual dysfunction?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>What causes sexual dysfunction?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>What can I do about sexual dysfunction?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What can my partners do about my sexual dysfunction?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>How can I talk to my partner about sexual dysfunction?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#7>What should I report to my healthcare provider about sexual dysfunction?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#8>What should I discuss with my healthcare provider about sexual dysfunction?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#9>Where can I get more information?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#10>References</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#11>Supportive evidence-based practice</a></li>\r\n</ul><br />\r\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What is sexual dysfunction?</h1><p>Sexual dysfunction is difficulty or inability to engage in sexual activities. It is also described as decreased libido (interest in sex), the inability to achieve or maintain sexual arousal, or the delay or absence of orgasm.</p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>How do people describe sexual dysfunction?</h1><p>Sexual dysfunction can be a loss (or decrease) of interest in sex, changes in sexual desire, difficulty enjoying sexual activities, or pain in genital area during intercourse. It may appear as vaginal dryness in women, erectile dysfunction or problems with ejaculation in men. </p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>What causes sexual dysfunction?</h1><p>Sexual dysfunction after cancer treatment can be caused by hormonal changes, excessive fatigue, pain, discomfort, or changes in self-image. Sometimes the physical toll of the treatments and the resulting side effects, such as nausea and fatigue, may reduce the desire for sexual activity. Concerns over ability to perform and attractiveness after cancer treatment may also cause a person to lose their desire or arousal. </p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>What can I do about sexual dysfunction?</h1><p>Here are some tips you might find helpful:<br /><br /><h2>ACTIVITY</h2><ul> <li> Take a nap before sex to reduce fatigue. </li> <li> Avoid temperature extremes in the room.  Temperature extremes can cause your body to use extra energy to adjust. </li> <li> Explore various ways of sharing pleasure and intimacy with your partner , such as touching, cuddling, caressing, holding hands, hugging and kissing.  Sexual intercourse is not the only way to be intimate. Be creative. </li> <li> Take time for intimacy with your partner. </li> <li> Assume a comfortable position for intercourse.  For instance lying on your side can use less energy. </li> <li> Let your partner know if any types of touching cause pain.  Show your partner what feels good to you or positions that are not painful. </li></ul><br /><h2>COMMUNICATION</h2><ul> <li> Talk to your healthcare provider if a sexual problem has not resolved after you have tried some of these suggestions.  Your healthcare provider may refer you to a specialist or sex therapist. </li></ul><br /><h2>MEDICATION</h2><ul> <li> Use water-soluble lubricants such as K-Y&#174; Jelly or Astroglide&#174; if you have vaginal dryness.  These lubricants can reduce friction and irritation to the penis and vagina during intercourse. </li> <li> Take medication about 30 minutes to 1 hour before intercourse if you feel nauseated or are having pain. </li></ul></p><a name="5"></a><h1>What can my partners do about my sexual dysfunction?</h1><p>Ask your partner to: <ul> <li> Share their feelings and desires, as well as concerns and worries. </li> <li> Use some tools (such as erotic pictures, lubrication or a vibrator) to stimulate or increase arousal or to decrease your discomfort. </li></ul></p><a name="6"></a><h1>How can I talk to my partner about sexual dysfunction?</h1><p>Many patients and their partners are fearful or anxious about their first sexual experience after treatment. Here are some ideas that may help you talk to your partner:<ul> <li> Share your feelings of concern about resuming an active sexual life. </li> <li> Communicate honestly about your feelings, concerns, and preferences. </li></ul></p><a name="7"></a><h1>What should I report to my healthcare provider about sexual dysfunction?</h1><p>If you experience any of the following symptoms, report them to your healthcare provider:<ul> <li> Genital pain. </li> <li> Bleeding during and after intercourse. </li> <li> Itching or rashes in the genital area. </li> <li> Foul-smelling or discolored discharge from penis or vagina. </li></ul></p><a name="8"></a><h1>What should I discuss with my healthcare provider about sexual dysfunction?</h1><p>If you are experiencing sexual dysfunction, you should discuss the following with your healthcare provider at your next appointment:<ul> <li> Is it safe for me to have sexual activity? </li> <li> What precautions do I need to take while I am receiving chemotherapy and/or radiation therapy? </li> <li> What if my platelets or white blood cells are low? </li></ul></p><a name="9"></a><h1>Where can I get more information?</h1><p>For more information, contact the people or organizations at the numbers or websites listed below:<ul> <li> Contact your healthcare providers. </li> <li> American Cancer Society: 1-800-ACS-2345 or <a href=http://www.cancer.org/docroot/mbc/content/mbc_2_2x_how_about_my_sexuality.asp?sitearea=mbc target=_blank>http://www.cancer.org/docroot/mbc/content/mbc_2_2x_how_about_my_sexuality.asp?sitearea=mbc</a> </li> <li> National Cancer Institute: 1-800-4-CANCER or <a href=http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/sexuality/patient target=_blank>http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/sexuality/patient</a> </li> <li> Lance Armstrong Foundation: <a href=http://www.livestrong.org/site/c.jvkzlbmrisg/b.704929/k.b663/physical_topics.htm target=_blank>http://www.livestrong.org/site/c.jvkzlbmrisg/b.704929/k.b663/physical_topics.htm</a> </li></ul></p><a name="10"></a><h1>References</h1><p><ul> <li> The Health Information Center at The Cleveland Clinic (2008).  Cleveland Clinic: health information. Retrieved from: <a href=http://www.clevelandclinic.org/health target=_blank>http://www.clevelandclinic.org/health</a> </li> <li> Stronach, K. (2006) The National Bone Marrow Transplant. Retrieved from: <a href=http://www.nbmtlink.org/sg.asp target=_blank>http://www.nbmtlink.org/sg.asp</a> </li> <li> National Cancer Institute (n.d.)  Sexuality And Reproductive Issues PDQ.  Retrieved from: <a href=http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/sexuality/patient/ target=_blank>http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/sexuality/patient/</a> </li></ul></p><a name="11"></a><h1>Supportive evidence-based practice</h1><p><ul> <li> Ananth, H., Jones, L., King, M., And Tookman, A., (2003). The impact of cancer on sexual function: a controlled study. Palliative Medicine, 17, 202-205. </li> <li> Monga, U. (2002). Sexual functioning in cancer patients. Sexuality And Disability, 20(4), 277-295. </li> <li> Shell, Ja. (2002) Evidence-based practice for symptom management in adults with cancer: sexual dysfunction. Oncology Nursing Forum, 29(1), 53-69. </li> <li> Tan, G., Waldman, K., And Bostick, R., (2002) Psychological issues, sexuality, and cancer. Sexuality And Disability, 20(4), 297-318. </li> <li> Wilmoth, Mc.(1998) Patient resources: Sexuality resources for cancer professionals and their patients. Cancer Practice, 6(6), 346. </li></ul></p>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a>\r\n\r\n<div id="credit"><p>This information was developed in collaboration with Michigan State University and the Behavioral Cooperative Oncology Group.</div>\r\n</p>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->');
