(100400100304, 'asking for help', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\n<h1>Asking for Help and Accepting Help</h1>\n\n<div id="symptomtext">\n\n<ul><li><a href=#1>What does it mean to ask for help and accept it? </a></li>\n<li><a href=#2>Why is it important to ask for or accept help? </a></li>\n<li><a href=#3>How can I ask for help? </a></li>\n<li><a href=#4>How can my family members and friends help me? </a></li>\n<li><a href=#5>When should I ask for help? </a></li>\n<li><a href=#6>How to handle well-wishers? </a></li>\n<li><a href=#7>Helpful tips </a></li>\n<li><a href=#8>Where can I get more information? </a></li>\n<li><a href=#9>References</a></li>\n</ul><br />\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What does it mean to ask for help and accept it?</h1><p>Asking for help means telling someone that you need assistance with something. Accepting help means letting someone assist you to get what you need. </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>Why is it important to ask for or accept help?</h1><p>Asking people for help lets them know what you need. It allows them to help you in a specific way.  When you have symptoms and are tired and weak, accepting help may allow you to rest while getting your need met.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How can I ask for help?</h1><p>As a cancer patient you are not alone. Call your friends, family, and anyone else who supports you. Everyone needs support. Even if you are coping well and able to function, the additional stress of the disease and its treatment can put a strain on your body, relationships, and quality of life.<br /><br />There are no disadvantages to having support in place in case you need it. Asking for help is a sign of strength and taking control. If asking for help is difficult for you, practice saying the words in front of the mirror. This is technique may make you feel more comfortable asking for what you want or need.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How can my family members and friends help me?</h1><p>Here are some suggestions of things that you could ask your family, friends, and co-workers to do: <ul> <li> Get items on your shopping list. </li> <li> Help your family by inviting them out and taking them places. (You may be sick, but they are also suffering.) </li> <li> Water your flowers. </li> <li> Talk to you about the future. Hope is important. </li> <li> Call when they have a minute to just talk. </li> <li> Send you a card to let you know they care. </li> <li> Help you with household chores, such as dirty dishes, folding laundry, and cleaning up around the house. </li> <li> Have a positive attitude, it\'s catching. </li> <li> Take you or your children somewhere. </li> <li> Drive you to your treatments or doctor\'s office. </li> <li> Walk or feed your pet. </li> <li> Listen to you/spend time with you. </li></ul><p>It may be helpful to make a list of people and things that they are doing for you.  One of your friends or family can organize everyone else.</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>When should I ask for help?</h1><p>It\'s never too early to ask for help.  If you can, ask in advance of needing the help.  This gives your family and friends time to plan, too.</p><br /><a name="6"></a><h1>How do I handle well-wishers?</h1><p>Although friends, family, and well-wishers usually speak from their hearts and are often sincere, some comments can be difficult to take.  People may not know how to talk with you about your cancer or cancer treatment.  The first time that this happens, you may be surprised or shocked.  You can use this experience to learn how to handle these kinds of situations in the future. Constructive ways to deal with inappropriate questions or comments are to:<ul> <li> Ignore it, particularly when it is painful. </li> <li> Answer questions in an evasive or general way. </li> <li> Tell them that the question or comment hurt your feelings.  As is often the case, you may hear similar questions or comments time and time again.  Feeling hurt and angry by these questions or comments is okay. </li></ul><h4>Here are some tips that may be helpful:</h4><ul> <li> Be straightforward and honest at whatever level feels comfortable to you. You can share as much or as little as you want. </li> <li> Save the personal information for people who are close to you. </li> <li> Decide in advance who gets what level of information about you, your cancer, and treatment. </li> <li> When people touch you and say, "How are you really feeling?", you may want to respond by saying how you truly feel (if they are someone close to you). </li> <li> Say you feel "fine" or "okay" (if they are someone who is a casual acquaintance). Be honest if you want help. </li> <li> Be prepared to encounter people that are uncomfortable being around you.  They may try to avoid you or talking to you. Realize that you can\'t count on them. </li> <li> Do not overlook someone you may not know well who is ready to be genuinely helpful. </li></ul></p><a name="7"></a><h1>Where can I get more information?</h1><p>For more information, contact the people or organizations at the numbers or websites listed below:<ul> <li> Contact your healthcare provider. </li> <li> American Cancer Society: 1-800-ACS-2345 or <a href=http://www.cancer.org target=_blank>http://www.cancer.org</a> Click on patients, family & friends. Look for emotional support. </li> <li> Family Care Research Program: <a href=http://www.cancercare.msu.edu target=_blank>http://www.cancercare.msu.edu</a> </li> <li> The National Cancer Institute: 1-800-4-CANCER <a href=http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo/ target=_blank>http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo/</a> Click on coping with cancer. </li> <li> National Coalition for Cancer Survivorship: <a href=http://canceradvocacy.org target=_blank>http://canceradvocacy.org</a> </li></ul></p><a name="8"></a><h1>References</h1><p><ul> <li> Osse, B.H.P., Wernooij-Dassen, M., Schade, E., de-Vree, B., van-den-Muijsenbergh, M., & Grol, R. (2002). Problems to discuss with cancer patients in palliative care: A comprehensive approach. Patient Education and Counseling, 47(3), 195-204. </li> <li> Roe, B., Maxine, W., Young, H., & Dimond, M. (2001). Elder\'s perceptions of formal and informal care: Aspects of getting and receiving help for their activities of daily living. Journal of Clinical Nursing, 10, p.398-405. </li></ul></p>\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a>\n\n\n</div>\n\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\n'),
