(100200500101004, 'Aldesleukin', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Aldesleukin</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=39756" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Aldesleukin</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a692009.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Aldesleukin</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext">\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br>\r\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Aldesleukin (al-des-LOO-kin)<br />\r\nTrade name: Proleukin&#174;<br />\r\nOther names: IL-2, Interleukin-2, r- serHuIL </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Aldesleukin is used to treat kidney cancer (renal cell cancer), melanoma, and skin cancer.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a type of cancer treatment known as "immunotherapy". In immunotherapy, the drug is given to make the body\'s immune system work better to fight cancer. Interluekin-2 may be given in your IV, or you may receive it as an injection under the skin. You or a family member may learn to give the injections, or they may be given in the doctor\'s office.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Aldesleukin may be given by injection under the skin (subcutaneous, SubQ) or intravenously (IV).</p><p>If you are given this drug by injection, you may notice some hard bumps under your skin. Do not get the injection at the same site. Rotate the injection sites often. It may be helpful to put an ice pack on the injection site. Do this before and after the shot. </p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> \r\n\r\n<li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> \r\n<li> Vomiting </li> \r\n<li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a> </li> \r\n<li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">Fatigue</a> </li> \r\n<li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">Fever</a>, chill </li> \r\n<li> Skin change (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a>) </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> \r\n<li> Chest pain, heart beats fast </li> \r\n<li> Low blood pressure </li> \r\n<li> Lung congestion </li> \r\n<li> Swelling (feet, ankles, or other places) </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> \r\n<li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> \r\n<li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a> (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> \r\n<li> Severe <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a> </li> \r\n<li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> or sleepiness </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a> and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> \r\n<li> Dizziness, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">weakness</a>, headache, or confusion </li> \r\n<li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> \r\n<li> Have any allergies. </li> \r\n<li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> \r\n<li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a>\r\n\r\n</div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->'),
(100200500102004, 'Aminoglutethimide', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Aminoglutethimide</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext">\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a><br>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br>\r\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic:  Aminoglutethimide (ah-mee-no-gloo-TEH-tha-mide)<br />Trade:  Cytadren&#174;, Elipten<br />Other names:  None </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Aminoglutethimide may be used to treat breast cancer and metastatic prostate cancer. </p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug.  It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body.  Aminoglutethimide is in the "adrenal steroid inhibitor" group. </p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Aminoglutethimide is taken by mouth as a pill. </p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> \r\n<li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> \r\n<li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> \r\n<li> Vomiting </li> \r\n<li> Loss of appetite </li> \r\n<li> Swelling (especially of the lower extremities) </li> \r\n<li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">Weakness</a>  </li> \r\n<li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a>  </li> \r\n<li> Blurred vision </li> \r\n<li> Skin change (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a>) </li> \r\n<li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_033">Hair loss</a>  </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> \r\n<li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Mouth sores</a>  </li> \r\n<li> Dizziness, confusion </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> \r\n<li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> \r\n<li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a>  (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a>  and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> \r\n<li> Headache or confusion </li> \r\n<li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> or sleepiness </li> \r\n<li> Blurred vision </li> \r\n<li> Loss of balance </li> \r\n<li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> \r\n<li> Black stools or stools that look like tar </li> \r\n<li> Severe <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a> </li> \r\n<li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> \r\n<li> Have any allergies. </li> \r\n<li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> \r\n<li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a>\r\n\r\n</div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->'),
(100200500103004, 'Bevacizumab', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Bevacizumab</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=43234" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Bevacizumab</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a607001.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Bevacizumab Injection</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext">\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br>\r\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Bevacizumab (be-va-SIZ-yoo-mab)<br />Trade name: Avastin&#174;<br />Other names: None </p><br />\r\n\r\n<a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Bevacizumab is not a chemotherapy drug. It may be used to treat colon or rectal cancer, breast cancer, and non-small cell lung cancer.</p><br />\r\n\r\n<a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This is a monoclonal antibody directed specifically against vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF). The drug blocks the tumor\'s ability to create new blood vessels from which to get nourishment to live. This causes cell death due to lack of oxygen and nutrients.</p><br />\r\n\r\n<a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Bevacizumab is given intravenously (IV). It takes about 90 minutes to give the first infusion. If your body handles the infusion well, the second infusion will be given to you in about 60 minutes. If your body handles that infusion well, the remaining infusion will be given to you in about 30 minutes. </p><br />\r\n\r\n<a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br />\r\n\r\n<h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> \r\n<li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> \r\n<li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> \r\n<li> Vomiting </li> \r\n<li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">Fatigue</a>, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">weakness</a> </li> \r\n<li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a> </li> \r\n<li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_033">Hair loss</a> </li> \r\n<li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">Rash</a> or peeling skin </li> \r\n<li> Headache, dizziness </li> \r\n<li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">Pain</a></li>\r\n<li> Nose bleeds </li> \r\n<li> High blood pressure </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> \r\n<li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Mouth sores</a> </li> \r\n<li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">Fever</a>, chills, muscle aches </li> \r\n<li> Watery eyes, stuffy nose </li> \r\n<li> Heart rate changes (slow or fast) </li> \r\n<li> Skin irritation at IV site </li> \r\n<li> Liver or kidney damage </li> \r\n<li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_009">Constipation</a> </li> \r\n<li> Blood in urine </li> \r\n<li> Bleeding, blot clots </li> \r\n<li> Test change:  protein in the urine </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> \r\n<li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> \r\n<li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a> </li> \r\n<li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> or sleepiness </li> \r\n<li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a> and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> \r\n<li> Dizziness, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">weakness</a>, headache, or confusion </li> \r\n<li> Strange or unusual bruising or bleeding </li> \r\n<li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a>\r\n\r\n</div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->'),
(100200500104004, 'Bleomycin', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Bleomycin</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=39139" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Bleomycin</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a682125.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Bleomycin</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext">\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br>\r\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Bleomycin (blee-oh-MYE-sin)<br />Trade name: Blenoxane&#174;<br />Other names: Bleomycin Sulfate</p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Bleomycin may be used to treat Hodgkin\'s and non-Hodgkin\'s lymphoma, squamous cell cancers, melanoma, sarcoma, and testicular cancer. It may also be used to treat pleural effusion.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug. It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells. There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs. Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body. Bleomycin is in the "anti-tumor antibiotics" group. </p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Bleomycin is given intravenously (IV). It is often used with other drugs because it does not decrease bone marrow functioning. This drug can be prepared in a syringe, bag, or bottle. It takes only a few minutes to give. Tell your nurse if you are having trouble breathing, short of breath, dizziness, confusion, chest tightness, numbness, or itching.</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">Fever</a>, chills (Some patients experience <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> and chills 6-8 hours after treatment. Tylenol taken before treatment may minimize or prevents this effect. <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">Fever</a> experienced on the day of treatment does not require the attention of a doctor.) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Swelling of fingers or hands </li> <li> Skin changes (darkening, redness, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a> over hands and elbows) </li> <li> Nails thicken </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_033">Hair loss</a> </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Mouth sores</a> </li> <li> Lung toxicity (This is related to age, dose, and radiation therapy. The dose you receive is watched closely. Chest x-rays and a physical exam can be used to check your lungs.) </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a> (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> Black stools or stools that look like tar </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Mouth sores</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a> and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a>\r\n\r\n</div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->'),
(100200500105004, 'Busulfan', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\n<h1>Busulfan</h1>\n\n<div id="rightcolumn">\n<div id="resources">\n\n<h3>More information</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=41947" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Busulfan</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a682248.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Busulfan</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\n</ul>\n\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<div id="symptomtext">\n<ul>\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\n</ul><br>\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name:  Busulfan  (byoo-SUL-fan)<br />Trade name:  Busulfex&#174;, Myleran&#174;<br />Other names:  None</p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Busulfan may be used to treat some kinds of leukemias and blood disorders. It can also be used in bone marrow transplantation. </p><br />\n<a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug.  It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body.  Busulfan is in the "alkylating agent" (L-ka-Late-ing Agent) group.  Alkylating agents damage the DNA of a cell and cancer cells are more sensitive to this type of DNA damage. </p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Busulfan may be taken by mouth as a pill or given intravenously (IV). </p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_006">Lack of appetite</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Sore mouth</a>  or throat </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Discoloration of the skin (especially in hands and nails) </li> <li> Skin changes (itching or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a>) </li> <li> Itching </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a>  (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a>  and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Yellow eyes </li> <li> Extra fluid in belly (ascites), which may cause you belly to feel very full or distended </li> <li> Sudden weight loss </li> <li> Dizziness, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">weakness</a>, headache, or confusion </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> or sleepiness </li> <li> Loss of balance </li> <li> Seizures </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> Black stools or stools that look like tar </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a>\n\n</div><br>\n\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->'),
(100200500106004, 'Camptothecin-11', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Camptothecin-11</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext">\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br>\r\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name:  Camptothecin-11 (kamp-toe-THE-kin),CPT-11<br />Trade name:  Camptosar&#174;,Irinotecan&#174;<br />Other names:  None </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Camptothecin-11 may be used to treat colon and rectal cancer.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug. It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells. There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs. Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body. Camptothecin-11 is in the "alkylating agent" (L-ka-Late-ing Agent) group. Alkylating agents damage the DNA of a cell and cancer cells are more sensitive to this type of DNA damage. </p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>CPT-11 is given intravenously (IV). Treatments are usually about 90 minutes long. NOTE:  Do not take prochlorperazine (Compazine&#174;) within 24 hours of getting Camptothecin-11. </p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_033">Hair loss</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_006">Lack of appetite</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">Fever</a>  </li> <li> Test change:  increase of blood sugar  (Check frequently if you have diabetes.) </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Allergic Reactions (Possible signs:  sweating or flushing of face during treatment. Tell your nurse if you are having these side effects.) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_009">Constipation</a>  </li> <li> Chills </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Mouth sores</a>  </li> <li> Skin change (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a>) </li> <li> Headache </li> <li> Unable to sleep </li> <li> Swelling of feet and ankles </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Allergic Reactions (Possible signs:  <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">diarrhea</a> or belly cramping. Tell your nurse if you are having these side effects. Do not take any laxatives or stool softeners without talking to your doctor or nurse.) </li> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a>  and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Dizziness, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">weakness</a>, headache, or confusion </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> Dark colored urine (may be a sign of dehydration) </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a>\r\n\r\n</div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->'),
(100200500107004, 'Capecitabine', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Capecitabine</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=42852" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Capecitabine</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a699003.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Capecitabine</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.xeloda.com" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Xeloda&#174;</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext">\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br>\r\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name:  Capecitabine (Cap-Site-o-Bean)<br />Trade name: Xeloda&#174; (ZA-low-duh)<br />Other: None</p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Capecitabine may be used to treat colon, rectal, and breast cancer.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug. It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body.  Capecitabine is in the "anti-metabolite" (ANT-I-met-TAB-o-light) group.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Capecitabine is taken by mouth as a pill.  Take this drug exactly as your doctor tells you to take it.  Usually, this drug is taken in twice a day, in the morning and in the evening.  Take the drug after food (within 30 minutes of a meal) and with water.  If you miss a dose, do not double the next dose.  Continue your regular dosing schedule and check with your doctor.</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all of the side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away.<br /><br />Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.<br /><br />COMMON SIDE EFFECTS<ul> <li> Low red blood cell count (increased risk for <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">Fatigue</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a>  or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_009">constipation</a> </li> <li> Hand-foot syndrome (Skin on hands and feet may turn red, peel, or be painful.) </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_039_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_006">Lack of appetite</a>  </li> <li> Test change:  increased bilirubin </li></ul>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS<ul> <li> Low white blood cell count (increased risk of infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_039_045">neutropenia</a>) </li> <li> Low platelet count (increased risk of bleeding) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_039_030">Sore mouth</a>  or throat </li> <li> Skin changes (dry or itching) </li> <li> Fingernail color may become darker </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_039_051">Pain</a> (stomach, chest, back, joint, or muscles) </li> <li> Hair thinning </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_072">Disturbed sleep</a>  </li></ul>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS<ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a>  (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> Black stools or stools that look like tar </li> <li> Painful <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_039_030">mouth sores</a> </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul></p><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1>\r\n<p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a>\r\n\r\n</div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->'),
(100200500108004, 'Carboplatin', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Carboplatin</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=39176" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Carboplatin</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a695017.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Carboplatin</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext">\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br>\r\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name:  Carboplatin   (car-BO-plat-tin)<br />Trade name:  Paraplatin&#174;<br />Other names:  None</p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Carboplatin is used to treat many cancers.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug.  It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body.  Carboplatin is in the "alkylating agent" (L-ka-Late-ing Agent) group.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Carboplatin may be given intravenously (IV) or into the belly (abdomen) by special injection.</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away.<br /><br />Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.<br /><br />COMMON SIDE EFFECTS<ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk for infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_039_045">neutropenia</a>, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_039_003">anemia</a>, or bleeding) </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_039_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> Taste change in the mouth </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_039_033">Hair loss</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_039_075">Weakness</a>  </li> <li> Taste change in the mouth </li> <li> Test change: magnesium </li></ul>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS<ul> <li> Burning feeling at the injection site </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_039_051">Pain</a> (belly) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_039_018">Diarrhea</a>  or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_039_009">constipation</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_039_039">Sore mouth</a>  or throat </li> <li> Numbness or tingling in finger tips </li> <li> Difficulty walking </li> <li> Test changes:  sodium, potassium, calcium, and liver function tests </li></ul>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS<ul> <li> Dizziness, loss of balance, or confusion </li> <li> Excessive sleepiness </li> <li> Seizures </li> <li> Hearing loss </li> <li> Muscle cramps or twitches </li> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_039_018">Diarrhea</a>  (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> Painful <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_039_039">mouth sores</a> </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> Black stools or stools that look like tar </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_039_012">Cough</a>  and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_039_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_039_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul></p><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1>\r\n<p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies.  </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<br/>\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->');
