(100200500109004, 'Carmustine', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Carmustine</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=43027" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Carmustine</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a682060.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Carmustine</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext">\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br>\r\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Carmustine (kar-MUS-teen)<br />Trade names:  BiCNU&#174;, Becenum&#174;, Carmubris&#174;<br />Other names: BCNU </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Carmustine may be used to treat brain tumors, multiple myeloma, Hodgkin\'s disease, non-Hodgkin\'s lymphomas, melanoma, lung cancer, and colon cancer.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug.  It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body.  Carmustine is in the "alkylating agent" (L-ka-Late-ing Agent) group.  Alkylating agents damage the DNA of a cell and cancer cells are more sensitive to this type of DNA damage. </p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Carmustine is given intravenously (IV).  It takes about 30 minutes to 1 hour to infuse.  This drug could be very irritating to the skin if any leaked out from the vein.  If you feel any burning or notice a change in sensation along your arm while the drug is infusing, immediately notify a nurse.</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_039_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_039_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_039_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> Loss of appetite </li> <li> Headache </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_039_069">Shortness of breath</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_039_075">Weakness</a>  </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Lung toxicity (The dose you receive is watched closely.  Chest x-rays and a physical exam can be used to check your lungs.) </li> <li> Blurred vision, redness </li> <li> Dizziness, loss of balance </li> <li> Test change:  liver function tests </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_039_012">Cough</a>  and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_039_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Dizziness, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_039_075">weakness</a>, headache, or confusion </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_039_027">fatigue</a> or sleepiness </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> Blurred vision </li> <li> Yellow skin or eyes </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_039_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<br/>\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->'),
(100200500110004, 'Cetuximab', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Cetuximab</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=42384" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Cetuximab</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a607041.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Cetuximab Injection</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br>\r\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Cetuximab (se-TUX-i-mab)<br />Trade name: Erbitux&#174;<br />Other names: C225 </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Cetuximab may be used to treat colorectal cancer and squamous cell carcinoma of the head and neck.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>Cetuximab is a recombinant monoclonal antibody that binds specifically to the epidermal growth factor receptor (EGFR) on both normal and tumor cells. Binding of Cetuximab to the EGFR results in decreased cell growth and causes cell death.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Before getting the infusion, you will be given Benadryl to help decrease the chance of a reaction to Cetuximab.</p><p>Cetuximab is given intravenously (IV). It is a clear solution. It takes about 2 hours for the first infusion. The remaining infusions will take about 1 hour to complete. Immediately tell a nurse if you feel any <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">pain</a>or a burning sensation along the vein or at the IV site. Also, tell your nurse if you are having trouble breathing, short of breath, dizziness, confusion, chest tightness, numbness, or itching.</p><p>To make sure that you do not have any side effects from Eribtix, your nurse will monitor you for about 1 hour after the infusion. </p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Skin change (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a>; looks like acne, appears mainly on face, upper chest, and back) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">Fatigue</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a>  </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_009">Constipation</a>  </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Lung injury (Less than half of 1% of people have experienced this effect. You will be watched closely throughout your treatment.) </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a>  and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->'),
(100200500111004, 'Cisplatin', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Cisplatin</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=39515" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Cisplatin</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a684036.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Cisplatin</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br>\r\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name:  Cisplatin (SIS-pla-tin)<br />\r\nTrade name:  Platinol&#174;<br />\r\nOther names:  CDDP</p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Cisplatin is used to treat many cancers.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug.  It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body.  Cisplatin is in the "alkylating agent" (L-ka-Late-ing Agent) group.  </p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Cisplatin is given intravenously (IV).</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by this drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away.<br /><br />Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.<br /><br />COMMON SIDE EFFECTS<ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk for infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>, or bleeding) </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> Taste change in mouth (For example, some people say it tastes like metal.) </li> <li> Test changes:  can lower magnesium, calcium, and potassium </li></ul>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS<ul> <li> Numbness or tingling in finger tips </li> <li> Difficulty walking </li> <li> Hearing loss </li> <li> Test change: liver function tests </li></ul>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS<ul> <li> Dizziness, loss of balance, or confusion </li> <li> Seizures </li> <li> Excessive sleepiness </li> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> Black stools or stools that look like tar </li> <li> Blood in urine or no urine passed in 12 hours </li> <li> Yellow skin or eyes </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul></p><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->'),
(100200500112004, 'Cladribine', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Cladribine</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=41184" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Cladribine</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a693015.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Cladribine</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br>\r\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Cladribine (KLA-drih-bean)<br />Trade name: Leustatin&#174;<br />Other names: 2-CdA, 2-Chlorodeoxyadenosine </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Cladribine is may be used to treat hairy cell leukemia (leukemic reticuloendotheliosis), chronic lymphocytic leukemia (CLL), and non-Hodgkin\'s lymphomas.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug.  It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body.  Cladribine is in the "anti-metabolite" (ANT-I-met-TAB-o-light) group.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Cladribine is given intravenously (IV). It is a clear solution. </p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_006">Lack of appetite</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_009">Constipation</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">Fatigue</a>, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">weakness</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">Pain</a> (belly, trunk) </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Headache </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_006">Lack of appetite</a> </li> <li> Skin change (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a>) </li> <li> Redness or itching at IV site </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a> and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Dizziness, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">weakness</a>, headache, or confusion </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> or sleepiness </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n'),
(100200500113004, 'Cyclophosphamide', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Cyclophosphamide</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=39748" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Cyclophosphamide</a><br />(NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a682080.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Cyclophosphamide</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br>\r\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name:  Cyclophosphamide   (SI-clow-FOS-fa-mide)<br />Trade name:  Cytoxan&#174;<br />Other names:  Neosar&#174;</p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Cyclophosphamide is used to treat many cancers.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug.  It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body.  Cyclophosphamide is in the "alkylating agent" (L-ka-Late-ing Agent) group.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Cyclophosphamide may be taken by mouth as a pill or given intravenously (IV).</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all of the side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away.<br /><br />Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.<br /><br />COMMON SIDE EFFECTS<ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (may happen 7-14 days receiving this drug) </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_033">Hair loss</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_006">Lack of appetite</a>  </li> <li> Fingernail color may become darker </li> <li> Loss of fertility (This drug may affect ability get pregnant or father a child.) </li></ul>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS<ul> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Sore mouth</a>  or throat </li> <li> Bladder irritation  </li></ul>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS<ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a>  (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> Black stools or stools that look like tar </li> <li> Painful <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">mouth sores</a> </li> <li> Painful or burning urination </li> <li> Blood in urine </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul></p><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n'),
(100200500114004, 'Cytarabine', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Cytarabine</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=39015" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Cytarabine</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a682222.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Cytarabine</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br>\r\n<a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name:  Cytarabine (SI-tear-Ah-bean)<br />Trade name:  Cytosar-U&#174;<br />Other names:  Ara-C</p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Cytarabine may be used to treat leukemia and lymphoma. </p><br /> <a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug.  It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body.  Cytarabine is in the "anti-metabolite" (ANT-I-met-TAB-o-light) group </p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Cytarabine may be given intravenously (IV), as an injection, or into the fluid that surrounds the brain by a special injection.</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by this drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  Side effects almost always go away after treatment.<br /><br />Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.<br /><br />COMMON SIDE EFFECTS<ul> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_006">Lack of appetite</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Sore mouth</a>  or throat </li> <li> Test changes: uric acid and liver function tests </li></ul>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS<ul> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a>  </li> <li> Skin changes (redness, itching, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a>) </li> <li> Flu-like symptoms (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a>, chills, generalized aches and pains) </li> <li> Watery eyes, bright light may bother eyes (photophobia or light sensitivity) </li> <li> Hair thinning </li> <li> Hand-foot syndrome (Skin on hands and feet may turn red, peel, or be painful.) </li></ul>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS<ul> <li> Dizziness, headache, loss of balance, or confusion </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> or sleepiness </li> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a>  (more than 4 episodes in 24 hours) </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> Black stools or stools that look like tar </li> <li> Painful <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">mouth sores</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a>  and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Yellow skin or eyes </li> <li> Stomach <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">pain</a></li> <li> No urine passed in 12 hours </li> <li> Chest pain, heart beats fast </li></ul></p><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->'),
(100200500115004, 'Dacarbazine', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Dacarbazine</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=39768" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Dacarbazine</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a682750.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Dacarbazine</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Dacarbazine (da-KAR-ba-zeen)<br />Trade name: DTIC-Dome&#174;<br />Other names: DTIC, DIC, Imidazole Carboxamide </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Dacarbazine may be used to treat melanoma, Hodgkin\'s disease, and soft tissue sarcomas.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug.  It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body.  Dacarbazine is in the "alkylating agent" (L-ka-Late-ing Agent) group.  Alkylating agents damage the DNA of a cell and cancer cells are more sensitive to this type of DNA damage. </p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Dacarbazine is given intravenously (IV).  It takes about one hour to infuse.  This drug could be very irritating to the skin if any leaked out from the vein.  If you feel any burning or notice a change in sensation along your arm while the drug is infusing, immediately notify a nurse.</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> Loss of appetite </li> <li> Flu-like symptoms (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a>, chills, muscle aches) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">Weakness</a>, dizziness </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Phlebitis (irritation of the vein </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a> (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a> and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Headache or confusion </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> or sleepiness </li> <li> Loss of balance </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> Black stools or stools that look like tar </li> <li> Severe <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a> </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n'),
(100200500116004, 'Daunorubicin', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Daunorubicin</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=39779" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Daunorubicin</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a682289.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Daunorubicin</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Daunorubicin (daw-noe-ROO-bi-sin)<br />Trade names: Cerubidine&#174;, DaunoXome&#174;<br />Other names: Daunorubicin Hydrochloride, Daunomycin, Rubidomycin Hydrochloride</p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Daunorubicin may be used to treat different kinds of leukemias.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug. It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells. There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs. Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body. Daunorubicin is in the "antitumor antibiotics" group.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Daunorubicin is given intravenously (IV) through either a vein or central line. It is red. Immediately tell a nurse if you feel a burning sensation along the vein or at the IV site. Also, tell your nurse if you are having trouble breathing, short of breath, dizziness, confusion, chest tightness, numbness, or itching.</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">Fatigue</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_033">Hair loss</a> </li> <li> Urine may appear red, pink, or orange from the color of the drug (This generally goes away within 24 hours after treatment.) </li> <li> Numbness or tingling in hands or feet </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">Pain</a> (jaw) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">Weakness</a> </li> <li> Cramping </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_009">Constipation</a> </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Mouth sores</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a>, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">Pain</a> (belly) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_006">Lack of appetite</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">Fever</a>, chills, or aches </li> <li> Numbness or tingling in hands or feet </li> <li> Heart toxicity (Long-term use of this drug can weaken heart muscles. The total dose you receive is watched closely.) </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2>\r\n<ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a> (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Mouth sores</a> </li> <li> Heart beats fast </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> or sleepiness </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a> and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Dizziness, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">weakness</a>, headache, or confusion </li> <li> Strange or unusual bruising or bleeding </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->'),
(100200500117004, 'Docetaxel', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Docetaxel</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=41657" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Docetaxel</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a696031.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Docetaxel</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Docetaxel (doe-se-TAKS-sel)<br />Trade name: Taxotere&#174;<br />Other names: None </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Docetaxel may be used to treat breast cancer, non-small cell lung cancer, metastatic prostate cancer, stomach cancer, and head and neck cancer.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug. It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells. There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs. Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body. Docetaxel is in the "plant alkaloid" (Plant L-ka-Loid) group. It is a topoisomerase type I inhibitors. Drugs in this group work by interfering with cancer cell enzymes, which damage and kill it.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Docetaxel may be given intravenously (IV) through either a vein or a central line. It takes about 60 minutes to infuse. Immediately notify a nurse if you feel a warm sensation, tightness in the chest, or itching during the infusion. Any of these signs could mean there is a possible allergic reaction to the drug.</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">Fatigue</a>  </li> <li> Swelling (feet, ankles, or hands) </li> <li> Sudden weight gain </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_033">Hair loss</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">Pain</a> (You may experience muscle, joint, or bone <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">pain</a> for a few days following each infusion. If you do, tell your doctor or nurse. They will suggest ways to make you more comfortable.) </li> <li> Nail changes (Finger and toenails may color or become soft and tender. </li> <li> Numbness or tingling in hands or feet </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> Test change:  liver function test </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Allergic reactions (Reactions are rare. Tell the nurse immediately if you feel a warm sensation, tightness in the chest, or itching during treatment.) </li> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a>  (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Mouth sores</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a>  </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> Black stools or stools that look like tar </li> <li> Swelling </li> <li> Sudden weight gain </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> or sleepiness </li> <li> Dizziness, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">weakness</a>, headache, or confusion </li> <li> Loss of balance </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n'),
(100200500118004, 'Doxorubicin', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Doxorubicin</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a682221.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Doxorubicin</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Doxorubicin (dox-oh-ROO-bi-sin)<br />Trade names:  Doxil&#174;, Adriamycin&#174;, Adriamycin PFS&#174;, Adriamycin RDF&#174;, Rubex&#174;<br />Other names: Hydroxydaunomycin, Hydroxydoxorubicin, Liposomal doxorubicin</p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Doxorubicin may be used to treat many different types of cancers including:  breast, ovarian, prostate, testis, bladder, and head and neck.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug. It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells. There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs. Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body. Doxorubicin is in the "antitumor antibiotics" group.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Doxorubicin is given intravenously (IV). It is red. Immediately tell a nurse if you feel any <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">pain</a>or a burning sensation along the vein or at the IV site. Also, tell your nurse if you are having trouble breathing, short of breath, dizziness, confusion, chest tightness, numbness, or itching.</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by this drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">Fatigue</a>  </li>\r\n <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_033">Hair loss</a>  </li> <li> Urine may appear red from the color of the drug (This generally goes away within 12-24 hours after treatment.) </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Mouth sores</a>  </li> <li> Heart toxicity (Long-term use of this drug can weaken heart muscles. The total dose you receive is watched closely.) </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a>  </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> or sleepiness </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a>  and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Dizziness, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">weakness</a>, headache, or confusion </li> <li> Strange or unusual bruising or bleeding </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->');
