(100200500119004, 'Doxorubicin Liposomal', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Doxorubicin Liposomal</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Doxorubicin Liposomal (doks-oh-ROO-bi-sin lye-poe-SOE-mal)<br />Trade names:  Doxil&#174;, Dox-SL&#174;, Evacet&#174;, LipoDo&#174;<br />\r\nOther names: None </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Doxorubicin Liposomal may be used to treat AIDS-related Kaposi\'s sarcoma, breast cancer, ovarian cancer, and other solid tumors.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug. It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells. There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs. Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body. Doxorubicin Liposomal is in the "anti-tumor antibiotic" group.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Doxorubicin Liposomal is given intravenously (IV) through either a vein or a central line. It takes 1-2 hours to infuse. Immediately tell a nurse if you feel any lower back <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">pain</a>, chest tightness, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a>. Any of these symptoms could be a sign of a possible allergic reaction to the drug.</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">Fatigue</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_033">Hair loss</a>  </li> <li> Hand-foot syndrome (Skin on hands and feet may turn red, peel, or be <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">pain</a>ful.) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Mouth sores</a>  </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Urine may appear red, pink, or orange from the color of the drug </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a>  (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> Heart beats fast </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> Black stools or stools that look like tar </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a>  </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> or sleepiness </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a>  and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Dizziness, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">weakness</a>, headache, or confusion </li> <li> Strange or unusual bruising or bleeding </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n'),
(100200500120004, 'Edrecolomab', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Edrecolomab</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=39352" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Edrecolomab</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic Name:  Monoclonal antibody 17-1A<br />Trade Name: Panorex<br />Other names:  MOAB 17-1A </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Edrecolomab may be used to treat colon cancer and breast cancer.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a monoclonal antibody (protein). It is capable of binding to an antigen (a specific part of a cell). Edrecolomab adheres to antigens on the surface of tumor cells, which helps the body recognize the tumor cells as foreign and destroy them. </p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Edrecolomab is given intravenously (IV).</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">Fever</a>, chills </li> <li> Abdominal (belly) <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">pain</a> </li> <li> Loss of appetite </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a> (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n'),
(100200500121004, 'Epirubicin', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Epirubicin</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=39232" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Epirubicin</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a603003.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Epirubicin</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Epirubicin (eh-pih-ROO-bih-cin)<br />Trade names: Ellence&#174;, Pharmorubicin&#174;<br />Other names: None </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Epirubicin may be used to treat breast cancer.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug.  It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body.  Epirubicin is in the "antitumor antibiotics" group. </p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Epirubicin is given intravenously (IV).  It is red in color.  This drug could be very irritating to the skin if any leaked out from the vein.  If you feel any burning or notice a change in sensation along your arm while the drug is infusing, immediately notify a nurse.</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> Loss of appetite </li> <li> Swelling (especially of the lower extremities) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">Weakness</a>, dizziness </li> <li> Urine may appear red, pink, or orange from the color of the drug (This may happen 1-2 days after you receive the drug.) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_033">Hair loss</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Mouth sores</a> </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Heart toxicity </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a> (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a> and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Headache or confusion </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> or sleepiness </li> <li> Loss of balance </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> Black stools or stools that look like tar </li> <li> Severe <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a> </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->'),
(100200500122004, 'Estramustine', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Estramustine</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=39235" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Estramustine</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a608046.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Estramustine</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Estramustine (es-tra-MUS-teen)<br />Trade name: Emcyt&#174;<br />Other names: Estramustine Phosphate Sodium </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Estramustine may be used to treat progressive prostate cancer.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body.  Estramustine is in the "antimicrotubule agent" group.  The way that Estramustine works is not completely understood.  It seems to interfere with the growth of cancer cells, which are eventually destroyed. </p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Estramustine is taken by mouth as a capsule.  Do not take Estramustine within one hour before or two hours after meals.  Milk, milk products, calcium rich foods, and drugs must not be taken with Estramustine.</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_006">Loss of appetite</a> </li> <li> Swelling (especially of the lower extremities) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">Weakness</a>, dizziness </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_066">Sexual dysfunction</a> (unable to have or maintain an erection) </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Phlebitis (irritation of the vein) </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a> (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a> and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Headache or confusion </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> or sleepiness </li> <li> Loss of balance </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> Black stools or stools that look like tar </li> <li> Severe <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a> </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->'),
(100200500123004, 'Etoposide', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Etoposide</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=39207" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Etoposide</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a684055.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Etoposide</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Etoposide (e-TOE-poe-side)<br />Trade names: Toposar&#174;, VePesid&#174;, Etopophos&#174;<br />Other names: VP-16, Etoposide phosphate </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Etoposide may be used to treat testicular cancer, lung cancer, bladder cancer, prostate cancer, stomach cancer, uterine cancer, Hodgkin\'s and non-Hodgkin\'s lymphoma, Wilm\'s tumor, Kaposi\'s sarcoma, and Ewing\'s sarcoma.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug. It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells. There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs. Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body. Etoposide is in the "plant alkaloid" (Plant L-ka-Loid) group. It is a topoisomerase type I inhibitors. Drugs in this group work by interfering with cancer cell enzymes, which damage and kill it. </p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Etoposide may be taken as a pill or given intravenously (IV). Immediately tell a nurse if you feel any pain, burning sensation, chest tightness, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a>, dizziness, confusion, or itching. Any of these symptoms could be a sign of a possible allergic reaction to the drug.</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">Fatigue</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_033">Hair loss</a>  </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Mouth sores</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_006">Lack of appetite</a>  </li> <li> Numbness or tingling in fingers or toes </li> <li> Taste change in mouth (For example, some people say it tastes like metal.) </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a>  (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> Black stools or stools that look like tar </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Mouth sores</a>  </li> <li> Numbness or tingling in fingers or toes </li> <li> Severe <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a> or itching </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a>  </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> or sleepiness </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a>  and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Dizziness, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">weakness</a>, headache, or confusion </li> <li> Strange or unusual bruising or bleeding </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n'),
(100200500124004, 'Filgrastim', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Filgrastim</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=41057" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Filgrastim</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a692033.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Filgrastim</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name:  Filgrastim (fil-GRA-stim)<br />Trade name:  Neupogen&#174;<br />Other:  Granulocyte Colony Stimulating Factor (G-CSF)</p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Filgrastim is not used to treat cancer. It is used to decreases the risk of infection.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is speeds up the recovery of the white blood cells (WBC) after chemotherapy.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Filgrastim may be given intravenously (IV) or injection under the skin (subcutaneous, SubQ). It is given several days after chemotherapy. Blood tests are done to check your body\'s response to this drug.</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by this drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. Side effects almost always go away after treatment.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">Pain</a> (bone; typically in the back or legs) </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">Fever</a>  </li> <li> Headache, generalized aches and pains </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a>  </li> <li> Fast or irregular heartbeats </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">Rash</a>  </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n'),
(100200500125004, 'Fludarabine', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Fludarabine</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=39244" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Fludarabine phosphate</a><br />(NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a692003.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Fludarabine phosphate</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Fludarabine (floo-DARE-a-been)<br />Trade name: Fludara&#174;<br />Other names: None </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Fludarabine may be used to treat chronic lymphocytic leukemia (CLL).  It is also used for therapy for acute leukemia and non-Hodgkin\'s lymphoma.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug.  It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body.  Fludara is in the "anti-metabolite" (ANT-I-met-TAB-o-light) group.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Fludarabine is given intravenously (IV). It is a clear solution.</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">Fever</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_006">Lack of appetite</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">Weakness</a>  or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a>  </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a>  </li> <li> Flu-like symptoms (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a>, chills, aches and pains) </li> <li> Numbness or tingling of hands or feet </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a>  </li> <li> Skin change (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a>) </li> <li> Sweating </li> <li> Swelling </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Mouth sores</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_033">Hair loss</a>  </li> <li> Taste change in mouth (For example, some people say it tastes like metal.) </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a>  (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a>  and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Chest pain, heart beats fast </li> <li> Dizziness, headache, loss of balance, or confusion </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> or sleepiness </li> <li> Seizures </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> Black stools or stools that look like tar </li> <li> Test change:  uric acid, potassium, and phosphorus (Tumor Lysis Syndrome) </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n'),
(100200500126004, '5-Fluorouracil', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>5-Fluorouracil</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=43130" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Fluorouracil</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a682708.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Fluorouracil</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name:  Fluorouracil (FLURE-oh-YOU\'RE-a-sill)<br />Trade name:  Adrucil&#174;,\r\nAdrucil&#174;, Carac&#174;, Efudex&#174;, Fluoroplex&#174;<br />Other names:  5-FU</p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>5-Fluorouracil may be used to treat colon, rectal, head and neck, breast, and ovarian cancer.  It can also be used to treat basal cell cancer of the skin. </p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug.  It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body.  5-Fluorouracil is in the "anti-metabolite" (ANT-I-met-TAB-o-light) group.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>5-Fluorouracil may be taken by mouth as a pill, applied to the skin as a cream, or given intravenously (IV).</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by this drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  Side effects almost always go away after treatment.<br /><br />Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.<br /><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> \r\n<li> Low blood counts (increased risk for infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>, or bleeding) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a>  </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Sore mouth</a>  or throat </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_006">Lack of appetite</a>  </li> <li> Watery eyes, bright light bothers the eyes (photophobia or light sensitivity) </li> <li> Taste change in mouth (For example, some people say it tastes like metal. </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Skin change (dry) </li> <li> Hair thinning </li> <li> Finger nail color may become darker </li> <li> Hand-foot syndrome (Skin on hands and feet may turn red, peel, or be painful.) </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a>  (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> Black stools or stools that look like tar </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> </li> <li> Painful <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">mouth sores</a> </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul></p><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->'),
(100200500127004, 'Flutamide', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Flutamide</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=39811" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Flutamide</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Flutamide (FLOO-ta-mide)<br />Trade name: Eulexin&#174;<br />Other names: None </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Flutamide may be used to treat prostate cancer.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug.  It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body.  Flutamide is in the "anti-androgen" group.</p><p>The adrenal glands produce a small amount of male hormones (androgens).  Flutamide blocks the androgens from feeding the cancerous prostate cells.  It is usually given in combination with Lupron.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Flutamide is taken by mouth as a pill.</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a> </li> <li> Impotence </li> <li> Hot flashes </li> <li> Breast tenderness </li> <li> Test change:  liver function tests </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a>, difficulty breathing </li> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a> (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> Black stools or stools that look like tar </li> <li> Severe <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a> </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n'),
(100200500128004, 'Gemcitabine', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Gemcitabine</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=41213" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Gemcitabine Hydrochloride</a><br />(NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Gemcitabine Hydrochloride</a><br />(MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.gemzar.com" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Gemzar&#174;</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name:  Gemcitabine (Gem-Site-o-Bean)<br />Trade name:  Gemzar&#174; (Gem-zar)<br />Other:  None</p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Gemcitabine is used to treat pancreatic, breast, ovarian, and non-small cell lung cancer. </p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug.  It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body.  Gemcitabine is in the "anti-metabolite" (ANT-I-met-TAB-o-light) group. </p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Gemcitabine is given intravenously (IV). </p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by this drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  Side effects almost always go away after treatment.<br /><br />Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.<br /><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood counts (increased risk for infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>, or bleeding) </li> <li> Flu-like symptoms (muscle pain, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a>, headache, chills, or feeling tired) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">Fever</a>  (within 6-12 hours of first dose) </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_006">Lack of appetite</a>  </li> <li> Skin <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a> </li> <li> Test changes: liver function tests and blood or protein in the urine </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Sore mouth</a>  or throat </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">Weakness</a>  </li> <li> Hair thinning </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_072">Disturbed sleep</a>  </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a>  (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> Black stools or stools that look like tar </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Mouth sores</a>  </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul></p><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n');
