(100200500129004, 'Goserelin', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Goserelin</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=40224" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Goserelin</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a601002.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Goserelin</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic Name:  Goserelin Accetate<br />Trade Name:  Zoladex&#174;<br />Other names:  None </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Zoladex may be used to treat advanced prostate cancer and breast cancer. </p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug works by inhibiting the production of testosterone.  Initially, the drug may cause you to have an increase in your testosterone level.  As a result, your symptoms may get worse for the first few weeks of treatment.  For example, some patients may experience a temporary increase in bone pain.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Zoladex is given through an injection under the skin (subcutaneous, SubQ).  It is injected into the belly (abdomen) every 28 days.  Before you receive this drug, the nurse will numb the injection site with Xylocaine.</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Hot flashes </li> <li> Breast tenderness </li> <li> Impotence </li> <li> Sluggishness </li> <li> Lower urinary tract symptoms (such as frequency and burning) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_066">Sexual dysfunction</a> (lack of interest, unable to have or maintain an erection, vaginal dryness) </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">Pain</a> (bone) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">Nausea</a>, vomiting </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">Fatigue</a> </li> <li> Skin <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a> </li> <li> Headache </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_015">Depression</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_066">Sexual dysfunction</a> (vaginal dryness) </li> <li> Breast swelling </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Chest pain, heart beats fast </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a>, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">weakness</a> </li> <li> Numbness or tingling in arms or legs </li> <li> Swelling (feet, ankles) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">Pain</a>, redness, or swelling in an arm or leg but not in the other </li> <li> Difficulty urinating </li> <li> Changes in mood or memory </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n'),
(100200500130004, 'Idarubicin', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Idarubicin</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=39753" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Idarubicin</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a691004.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Idarubicin</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Idarubicin (eye-da-ROO-bi-cin)<br />Trade names: Idamycin&#174;, Idamycin PFS&#174;<br />Other names: 4-DMDR, IDA </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Idarubicin is may be used to treat different kinds of leukemias.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug. It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells. There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs. Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body. Idarubicin is in the "anti-neoplastic" group.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Idarubicin is given intravenously (IV). It is a red. This drug can be very irritating to the skin. Immediately tell a nurse if you feel any <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">pain</a> or a burning sensation in your hand, arm, or IV site. </p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">Fatigue</a>  </li> <li> Urine may appear red from the color of the drug (This generally disappears within12-24 hours after treatment.) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_033">Hair loss</a>  </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Mouth sores</a>  </li> <li> Heart toxicity (Long-term use of this drug can weaken heart muscles. The total dose you receive is watched closely.) </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a>  (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a>  </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> or sleepiness </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a>  and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Dizziness, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">weakness</a>, headache, or confusion </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->'),
(100200500131004, 'Ifosfamide', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Ifosfamide</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=40024" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Ifosfamide</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a695023.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Ifosfamide</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Ifosfamide (eye-FOSS-fa-mide)<br />Trade names: Ifex&#174;, Cyfos&#174;, Ifosfamidum&#174;<br />Other names: Ifosfamide, Isophosphamide </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Ifosfamide may be used to treat germ cell testicular cancer, bone and soft tissue sarcomas, non- Hodgkin\'s lymphoma, Hodgkin\'s disease, non-small cell and small cell lung cancer, bladder cancer, head and neck cancer, and cervical cancer.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug.  It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body.  Ifosfamide is in the "alkylating agent" (L-ka-Late-ing Agent) group. Alkylating agents damage the DNA of a cell and cancer cells are more sensitive to this type of DNA damage.  </p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Ifosfamide is given intravenously (IV).  It is a clear solution.  This drug takes about 1-2 hours to infuse.</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_006">Lack of appetite</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a>  </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Skin changes (itching or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a>) </li> <li> Dizziness, headache, or confusion </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">Weakness</a>  </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a>  (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a>  and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Dizziness, headache, or confusion </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a>, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">weakness</a> or sleepiness </li> <li> Loss of balance </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> Black stools or stools that look like tar </li> <li> Severe <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a> </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->'),
(100200500132004, 'Imatinib', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Imatinib</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=37862" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Imatinib</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a606018.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Imatinib</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Imatinib (eye-MAT-eh-nib)<br />Trade name: Gleevec&#174;<br />Other names: Imatinib Mesylate, STI-571 </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Imatinib may be used to treat certain types of leukemia and cancers that have a specific abnormality called the Philadelphia chromosome. </p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug kills cells that have the Philadelphia chromosome and prevents further abnormal cells from forming.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Imatinib is taken as a pill by mouth. This drug is taken daily. It is kept at room temperature.</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">Fatigue</a>  </li> <li> Skin change (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a>) </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Headache </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">Pain</a> (joint or belly) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_006">Lack of appetite</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a>  </li> <li> Muscle aches </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Black, tarry, or blooding stools (Call your doctor immediately! This is an emergency!) </li> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a>  (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> Severe <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a> (call your doctor or nurse) </li> <li> Eyelid Swelling (call your doctor or nurse) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a>  </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> or sleepiness </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a>  and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Dizziness, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">weakness</a>, headache, or confusion </li> <li> Strange or unusual bruising or bleeding </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n'),
(100200500133004, 'Interferon alfa', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Interferon alfa</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a690006.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Interferon Alfa-2a and Alfa-2b Injection</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name:  Interferon alfa (IN-ter-FEAR-on)<br />Trade name:  Intron&#174;, Roferon-A&#174; <br />Other names:  IFN-alpha</p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Interferon alfa may be used to treat melanoma, kidney (renal cell), multiple myeloma, and some kinds of leukemia. </p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a "biological response" or immunotherapy (EM-UN-oh-THERE-a-pee) drug.  It is called that because it helps the body\'s immune system "wipe out" or kill rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  </p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Interferon alfa may be given by injection under the skin (subcutaneous, SubQ), into the muscle (intramuscular, IM), or intravenously (IV).</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all of the side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help prevent or lessen side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away.<br /><br />Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.<br /><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> Flu-like symptoms (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a>, chills, aches, pains, headache, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_006">lack of appetite</a>) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_033">Hair loss</a> </li> <li> Test changes:  calcium and glucose </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a> </li> <li> Low blood pressure </li> <li> Redness at injection site </li> <li> Skin changes (dry, itching, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a>) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_024">Dry mouth</a>, sore throat or mouth, taste change, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">cough</a> </li> <li> Feeling sad or depressed, anxious (nervous) </li> <li> Dizzy or confusion </li> <li> Unable to sleep </li> <li> Numbness or tingling of hands or feet </li> <li> Swelling of feet and ankles </li> <li> Taste change in mouth (For example, some people say it tastes like metal.) </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_021">Anxiety</a>, change in mood, or confusion </li> <li> Unable to sleep </li> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a> (more than 4 episodes in 24 hours) </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> Black stools or stools that look like tar </li> <li> Persistent <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> </li> <li> Swelling of feet </li> <li> Sudden weight gain </li></ul></p><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n'),
(100200500134004, 'Irinotecan', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Irinotecan</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=41714" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Irinotecan</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a608043.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Irinotecan</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Irinotecan (eye-rye-no-TEE-can)<br />Trade name: Camptosar&#174;<br />Other names: Camptothecin-11, CPT-11 </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Irinotecan is may be used to treat colon or rectal cancer.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug. It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells. There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs. Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body. Irinotecan is in the "plant alkaloid" (Plant L-ka-Loid) group. It is a topoisomerase type I inhibitors. Drugs in this group work by interfering with cancer cell enzymes, which damage and kill it. </p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Irinotecan is given intravenously (IV) through either a vein or central line. It takes about 90 minutes to infuse. DO NOT use Compazine within 24 hours of taking this chemotherapy.</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> Low red blood cells or platelets </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a> or  abdominal (belly) cramping </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">Weakness</a>, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">Fever</a>, chills </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_033">Hair loss</a> </li> <li> Test change:  elevations of blood sugar (Check frequently if you have diabetes.) </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Mouth sores</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_009">Constipation</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_072">Disturbed sleep</a> </li> <li> Skin change (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a>) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">Pain</a> (gas in the belly) </li> <li> Swelling of feet and ankles </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Allergic Reactions (Possible signs:  sweating, flushing, belly cramping, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">diarrhea</a>. Tell your nurse if you are having these side effects.) </li> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a> and abdominal (belly) cramping </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a> and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Dizziness, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">weakness</a>, headache, or confusion </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> or sleepiness </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><p>NOTE:  <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a> is common and can be severe. Begin taking Loperamide (a prescription that will be given to you) at the first sign of poorly formed stools, loose stools, or an increase in the number of stools (i.e., 1-2 stools above normal in a single day.) Take 4 mg (2 tablets) of Loperamide at the first sign of <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">diarrhea</a>. Then take 2 mg (1 tablet) every 2 hours around-the-clock until you are free of symptoms for at least 12 hours. Drink plenty of fluids to prevent dehydration -- at least 8 glasses each day. Notify your doctor\'s nurse if you have any of these problems or abdominal cramping. DO NOT take any laxatives or stool softeners without consulting the doctor.</p><br /><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Have used Compazine (Procholorperazine). You should not use Compazine (Procholorperazine) within 24 hours after taking this chemotherapy. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n'),
(100200500135004, 'Leucovorin', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Leucovorin</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=42584" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Leucovorin</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a682336.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Leucovorin</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Leucovorin (loo-koe-VOR-in)<br />Trade name: Wellcovorin&#174;<br />Other names: Calcium Leucovorin, Citrovorum Factor, Folinic Acid, 5-formyl tetrahydrofolate</p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Leucovorin is not a chemotherapy drug.  It is may be used with Fluorouracil to treat colon and rectal cancer, head and neck cancer, esophageal, and other cancers of the gastrointestinal tract. You may also receive this as a "rescue" medicine beginning 24 hours after receiving Methotrexate. </p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug may be used to prevent harmful effects of chemotherapy drugs. Leucovorin or folic acid is a vitamin that rescues normal cells from the toxic effects of Methotrexate.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Leucovorin is may be taken by mouth as a pill or given intravenously (IV). </p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a>  </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Skin changes (itching or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a>) </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a>  (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a>  and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Dizziness, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">weakness</a>, headache, or confusion </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> or sleepiness </li> <li> Loss of balance </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> Black stools or stools that look like tar </li> <li> Severe <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a> </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n'),
(100200500136004, 'Levamisole', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Levamisole</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=39058" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Levamisole</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Levamisole<br />\r\nTrade name: Ergamisol&#174;<br /> \r\nOther names: None </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Levamisole may be used to treat colon cancer.  It is sometimes used to treat head and neck cancer and melanoma.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>Levamisole is not a chemotherapy drug.  It is used with 5-fluorouracil to help the chemotherapy work better.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Levamisole is taken by mouth as a pill.</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">Weakness</a>, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">Fever</a>, chills, tremor, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_021">anxiety</a> </li> <li> Skin change (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a>) </li> <li> Taste change in mouth (For example, some people say it tastes like metal.) </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a> and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Dizziness, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">weakness</a>, headache, or confusion </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> or sleepiness </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n'),
(100200500137004, 'Lomustine', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Lomustine</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=43065" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Lomustine</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a682207.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Lomustine</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Lomustine (loh-MUS-teen)<br />Trade name: CeeNU&#174;<br />Other names: CCNU </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Lomustine may be used to treat brain tumors, Hodgkin\'s disease, non-Hodgkin\'s lymphoma, melanoma, lung cancer, and colon cancer. </p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug.  It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body.  Lomustine is in the "alkylating agent" (L-ka-Late-ing Agent) group.  Alkylating agents damage the DNA of a cell and cancer cells are more sensitive to this type of DNA damage. </p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Lomustine is taken by mouth as a capsule.  It comes in both a blue or green capsule.  Taking this capsule on an empty stomach may help to reduce side effects. </p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> Loss of appetite </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">Weakness</a>, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">Fatigue</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">Fever</a>, chills, tremor, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_021">anxiety</a> </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Mouth sores</a> </li> <li> Loss of fertility (This drug may affect ability get pregnant or father a child.) </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a>, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Mouth sores</a> </li> <li> Dizziness, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">weakness</a>, headache, or confusion </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> or sleepiness </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n'),
(100200500138004, 'Mercaptopurine', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Mercaptopurine</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=43436" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Mercaptopurine</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a682653.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Mercaptopurine</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Mercaptopurine (mer-kap-toe-PYOOR-een)<br />Trade names: Purinethol&#174;, Mercaptopurinum&#174;<br />Other names: 6-Mercaptopurine, 6-MP </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Mercaptopurine is may be used to treat leukemia. </p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug. It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells. There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs. Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body. Mercaptopurine is in the "anti-metabolite" (ANT-I-met-TAB-o-light) group.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Mercaptopurine is taken as a pill by mouth. It is a white pill. </p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_006">Lack of appetite</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">Weakness</a>, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">Fever</a>, chills </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Mouth sores</a> </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Mouth sores</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a> </li> <li> Skin changes (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a>, itching, dryness, or darkening) </li> <li> Loss of fertility (This drug may affect ability get pregnant or father a child.) </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a> (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a>, sore throat </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">Pain</a> (belly, joint, or when urinating) </li> <li> Dizziness, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">weakness</a>, headache, or confusion </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> or sleepiness </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> Black stools or stools that look like tar </li> <li> Swelling (feet or legs) </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking Allopurinol (Zyloprim). Allopurinol interferes with the elimination of Mercaptopurine in the body. Tell your doctor if you are taking this drug so that the dose of Mercaptopurine can be adjusted. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n');
