(100200500139004, 'Methotrexate', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Methotrexate</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=41719" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Methotrexate</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a682019.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Methotrexate</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Levamisole<br />\r\nTrade name: Ergamisol&#174;<br /> \r\nOther names: None </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Levamisole may be used to treat colon cancer.  It is sometimes used to treat head and neck cancer and melanoma.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>Levamisole is not a chemotherapy drug.  It is used with 5-fluorouracil to help the chemotherapy work better.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Levamisole is taken by mouth as a pill.</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">Weakness</a>, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">Fever</a>, chills, tremor, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_021">anxiety</a> </li> <li> Skin change (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a>) </li> <li> Taste change in mouth (For example, some people say it tastes like metal.) </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a> and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Dizziness, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">weakness</a>, headache, or confusion </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> or sleepiness </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n'),
(100200500140004, 'Mitomycin', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Mitomycin</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=42674" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Mitomycin</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a682415.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Mitomycin</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Mitomycin (mye-toe-MYE-sin)<br />Trade names: Mitozytrex&#174;, Mutamycin&#174;<br />Other names: Mitomycin-C, MTC, Mutamycin </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Mitomycin may be used to treat adenocarcinoma of the stomach or pancreas.  It can also be prescribed for treatment of anal bladder, breast, cervical, colorectal, head and neck, and non-small cell lung cancer.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug.  It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body.  Mitomycin is in the "anti-tumor antibiotic" group. </p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Mitomycin is given intravenously (IV).  This drug could be very irritating to the skin if any leaked out from the vein.  If you feel any burning or notice a change in sensation along your arm while the drug is infusing, immediately notify a nurse.</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">Weakness</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">Fatigue</a> </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> Loss of appetite </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_033">Hair loss</a> </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> or sleepiness </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> Dizziness, confusion </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a>, sore throat </li> <li> Skin changes (itching or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a>) </li> <li> Difficulty urinating </li> <li> Swelling (feet or ankles) </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n'),
(100200500141004, 'Oxaliplatin', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Oxaliplatin</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=42374" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Oxaliplatin</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a607035.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Oxaliplatin</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Oxaliplatin (ox-a-ee-PLA-tin)<br />Trade name:  Eloxatin&#174;<br />Other names: None </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Oxaliplatin may be used to treat colon or rectal cancer.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug. It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells. There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs. Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body. Oxaliplatin is in the "alkylating agent" (L-ka-Late-ing Agent) group. Alkylating agents damage the DNA of a cell and cancer cells are more sensitive to this type of DNA damage. </p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Oxaliplatin is given intravenously (IV) as a rapid infusion. </p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a> </li> <li> Numbness or tingling in hands or feet (It is important to report your symptoms to your doctor. These side effects may be controlled by slightly lowering the dose of the drug.) </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Difficulty breathing or swallowing </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Mouth sores</a> or ulcers </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> or sleepiness </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a> and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Dizziness, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">weakness</a>, headache, or confusion </li> <li> Loss of balance </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_021">Anxiety</a> </li> <li> Redness of the face </li> <li> Severe <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a> or itching </li> <li> Laryngeal spasm (difficulty swallowing) </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><p>NOTE:  If you feel like you are having difficulty swallowing, numbness, or tingling, it may be cold related. Avoiding cold food and drinks may help. If a side effect is cold related, it will either happen during the treatment or within hours after treatment. It is important to let the doctor know if you experience this side effect.</p><br /><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n'),
(100200500142004, 'Paclitaxel', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Paclitaxel</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=39762" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Paclitaxel</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a698035.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Paclitaxel</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Paclitaxel (PAK-li-tax-el)<br />Trade names: Taxol&#174;, Onxol&#174;<br />Other names: None </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Paclitaxel may be used to treat breast cancer, lung cancer, ovarian cancer, bladder cancer, prostate cancer, melanoma, esophageal, and Kaposi\'s sarcoma.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug. It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells. There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs. Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body. Paclitaxel is in the "plant alkaloid" (Plant L-ka-Loid) group. It is a topoisomerase type I inhibitors. Drugs in this group work by interfering with cancer cell enzymes, which damage and kill it.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Paclitaxel can be given as in injection or intravenously (IV).</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">Fatigue</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_009">Constipation</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Mouth sores</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_033">Hair loss</a>  </li> <li> Swelling (feet, ankles, or hands </li> <li> Sudden weight gain) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">Pain</a> (muscle or bone) </li> <li> Nail changes (Finger and toenails may change color or become soft and tender.) </li> <li> Numbness or tingling in hands or feet </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Heart toxicity (EKG\'s will be used to check your heart rate.) </li> <li> Test change:  liver function test </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a>  (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Mouth sores</a>  </li> <li> Black stools or stools that look like tar </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> or sleepiness </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a>  and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Dizziness, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">weakness</a>, headache, or confusion </li> <li> Loss of balance </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->'),
(100200500143004, 'Pamidronate', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Pamidronate</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=39149" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Pamidronate</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a601163.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Pamidronate</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Pamidronate (pa-mi-DROE-nate)<br />Trade name: Aredia&#174;<br />Other names: ADP Sodium, Pamidronate Disodium </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Pamidronate is not a chemotherapy drug.  It used along with chemotherapy to treat symptoms of cancer such as high levels of calcium in the blood and bone metastasis.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a bisphosphonate.  It is given to help slow the bone destroying activity in patients with breast cancer or myeloma that has affected the bones. </p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Pamidronate is given intravenously (IV). It takes 1-2 hours to infuse.  This drug could be very irritating to the skin if any leaked out from the vein.  Immediately notify the nurse giving you the drug if you feel any redness, burning, swelling, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">pain</a> at your IV site. </p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">Pain</a> (joint, muscle, bone) </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> Loss of appetite </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_009">Constipation</a> </li> <li> Abdomen <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">pain</a> (belly <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">pain</a>) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">Fatigue</a>, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">weakness</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">Fever</a>, chills </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Aches or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">pain</a> (bone, joint, or muscle) </li> <li> Headache </li> <li> Test change:  magnesium </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a> and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Dizziness, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">weakness</a>, headache, or confusion </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> or sleepiness </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n'),
(100200500144004, 'Pemetrexed', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Pemetrexed</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=42328" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Pemetrexed Disodium</a><br />(NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a607043.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Pemetrexed Injection</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.alimta.com" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Alimta&#174;</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name:  Pemetrexed (Pem-A-trex-ed)<br />\r\nTrade name:  Alimta&#174; (A-LIM-ta)<br />Other:  None</p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Pemetrexed may be is used to treat non-small cell lung cancer and malignant mesothelioma.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug.  It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body.  Pemetrexed is in the "anti-metabolite" (ANT-I-met-TAB-o-light) group. </p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Pemetrexed is given intravenously (IV). </p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by this drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  Side effects almost always go away after treatment.<br /><br />Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.<br /><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low white blood cell count (increased risk for infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>) </li> <li> Low red blood cell count (increased risk for <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_006">Lack of appetite</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">Fatigue</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_009">Constipation</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a>, hard to breathe, or wheezing </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2> <ul> <li> Low platelet count (increased risk for bleeding) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Sore mouth</a> or throat </li> <li> Flu-like symptoms (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a>, chills, aches and <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">pain</a>s) </li> <li> Numb or tingling hands or feet </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_015">Depression</a> (feeling sad) </li> <li> Skin change (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a>) </li> <li> Test change: creatinine </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> Black stools or stools that look like tar </li> <li> Blood in urine  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">Pain</a> and burning when urinating </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_015">Depression</a> that interferes with your ability to carry out daily activities </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul></p><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies.  </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n'),
(100200500145004, 'Sargramostim', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Sargramostim</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=40566" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Sargramostim</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a693005.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Sargramostim</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name:  Sargramostim (sar-GRAM-oh-stim)<br />Trade name:  Leukine&#174;<br />Other:  GM-CSF, Granulocyte-Macrophage Colony Stimulating Factor</p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Sargramostim is not used to treat cancer. It is used to help decrease the risk of infection. </p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is speeds up the recovery of the white blood cells (WBC) after chemotherapy.</p><p>If you are taking Sargramostim at home, keep it in the refrigerator. Do not freeze it. Write the date on the bottle when you open it. After opening, the bottle can be kept in the refrigerator for 20 days. Throw it away after 20 days, even if there is still medicine left in the bottle.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Sargramostim may be given intravenously (IV) or injection under the skin (subcutaneous, SubQ). Blood tests are done to check your response.</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by this drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. Side effects almost always go away after treatment. </p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a>  </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">Fatigue</a>  or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">weakness</a> </li> <li> Swelling or redness at injection site </li> <li> Heart beats fast </li> <li> Lightheadedness or flushing </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_033">Hair loss</a>  </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">Pain</a> (bone, muscle, joint) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">Fever</a>  </li> <li> Headache, generalized aches and pains </li> <li> Swelling in your hands and feet </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a>  (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n'),
(100200500146004, 'Tamoxifen', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Tamoxifen</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=42901" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Tamoxifen</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a682414.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Tamoxifen</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic:  Tamoxifen<br />Trade:  Nolvadex&#174;<br />Other names:  Tamoxifeni Citras </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Tamoxifen may be used to treat breast cancer. It may also be prescribed for treatment of ovarian cancer.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is an anti-estrogen that prevents or slows down breast cancer growth. Most doctors believe it prevents breast cancer cells from getting the estrogen they need to grow.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Tamoxifen is taken by mouth as a pill.</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Vaginal spotting </li> <li> Menstrual irregularities </li> <li> Headaches or dizziness </li> <li> Leg cramps </li> <li> Temporary "FLARE" of breast cancer symptoms </li> <li> Hot Flashes </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Chest Pains </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Pain, swelling, or redness in an arm or leg </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a> and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Chest <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">pain</a> </li> <li> Pain, redness, or swelling in an arm or leg but not in the other </li> <li> Changes in breasts </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_015">Depression</a> </li> <li> Blurred vision </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n'),
(100200500147004, 'Thioguanine', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Thioguanine</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=43669" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Thioguanine</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a682099.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Thioguanine</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Thioguanine (thye-oh-GWAH-neen)<br />Trade name: Thioguanine Tabloid&#174;<br />Other names: 6-TG, TG, 6-Thioguanine, 2-Amino-6-Mercaptopurine</p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Thioguanine may be used to treat leukemia.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug.  It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body.  Thioguanine is in the "anti-metabolite" (ANT-I-met-TAB-o-light) group.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Thioguanine is taken by mouth as a pill.  The pill is pale yellow in color.  It is usually suggested that this drug be taken between meals.  This will help your body completely absorb it.  Your doctor will give you specific instructions in how to take this drug.</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> Loss of appetite </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">Weakness</a> </li> <li> Headache </li> <li> Skin change (darkening) </li> <li> Test change:  liver function tests </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Mouth sores</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">Fatigue</a> </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a> (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> Black stools or stools that look like tar </li> <li> Difficulty urinating (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">pain</a> or red) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">Pain</a> (belly, joints) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a>, sore throat </li> <li> Yellow skin or eyes </li> <li> Dizziness, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">weakness</a>, headache, or confusion </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> or sleepiness </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> Swelling (feet, legs) </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n'),
(100200500148004, 'Topotecan', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Topotecan</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=41185" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Topotecan</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a697006.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Topotecan</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Topotecan (toe-poe-TEE-kan)<br />Trade name: Hycamtin&#174;<br />Other names: None </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Topotecan may be used to treat ovarian cancer and small cell lung cancer.  It is also used in combination with other medications to treat cervical cancer. </p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug.  It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Topotecan is in the "plant alkaloid" (Plant L-ka-Loid) group.  It is a topoisomerase type I inhibitors.  Drugs in this group work by interfering with cancer cell enzymes, which damage and kill it. </p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Topotecan is given intravenously (IV). It is a clear solution. </p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a> </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a>, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Skin changes (itching or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a>) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_009">Constipation</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">Fatigue</a> or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">weakness</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">Fever</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">Pain</a> (belly, back, or bone) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_006">Lack of appetite</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Mouth sores</a> </li> <li> Headache </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_033">Hair loss</a> </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a> (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a> and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Dizziness, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">weakness</a>, headache, or confusion </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> or sleepiness </li> <li> Loss of balance </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> Black stools or stools that look like tar </li> <li> Severe <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_060">rash</a> </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n');
