(100200500149004, 'Vincristine', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Vincristine</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=42251" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Vincristine</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a682822.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Vincristine</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name:  Vincristine (vin-KRIS-teen)<br />Trade name:  Oncovin&#174;, Vincasar&#174;<br />Other names:  LCR, VCR, Vincristine Sulfate </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Vincristine is used to treat many cancers. </p><br /> <a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug. It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells. There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs. Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body. Vincristine is in the "alkylating agent" (L-ka-Late-ing Agent) group. Alkylating agents damage the DNA of a cell and cancer cells are more sensitive to this type of DNA damage. </p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Vincristine is given intravenously (IV). </p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by this drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. Side effects almost always go away after treatment.  </p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2>\r\n<ul> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_033">Hair loss</a> </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_006">Lack of appetite</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Mouth sores</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">Weakness</a> </li> <li> Weight loss </li> <li> Numbness or tingling in the hands and feet </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_009">Constipation</a> </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Heart problems (fast or irregular heartbeats) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_039">Mouth sores</a> </li> <li> Severe stomach <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">pain</a> </li> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a> (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> Black stools or stools that look like tar </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_009">Constipation</a> </li> <li> Unable to urinate </li> <li> Strange bleeding or bruising </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n'),
(100200500150004, 'Vindesine', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Vindesine</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=39732" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Vindesine</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Vindesine <br />Trade name: Eldisine&#174;<br />Other names: Vindesine Sulfate, Desacetyl Vinblastine Amide </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Vindesine may be used to treat lung cancer and leukemia.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug. It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells. There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs. Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body. Vindesine is in the "antineoplastic agent" group.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Vindesine is given intravenously (IV) as a short infusion. Immediately tell a nurse if you feel any <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">pain</a> or a burning sensation along the vein or at the IV site. </p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">Fatigue</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_033">Hair loss</a> </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Numbness or tingling in hands or feet </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">Pain</a> (jaw) </li> <li> Cramping (belly) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_009">Constipation</a> </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> or sleepiness </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a> and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Dizziness, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">weakness</a>, headache, or confusion </li> <li> Strange or unusual bruising or bleeding </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n'),
(100200500151004, 'Vinorelbine', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Vinorelbine</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=40449" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Vinorelbine</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a695013.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Vinorelbine</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Vinorelbine (vi-NOR-el-been)<br />Trade name: Navelbine&#174;<br />Other names: Vinorelbine Tartrate</p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Vinorelbine may be used to treat non-small cell lung cancer. It may also be prescribed for treatment of breast cancer, ovarian cancer, or Hodgkin\'s disease.</p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug. It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells. There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs. Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body. Oxaliplatin is in the "alkylating agent" (L-ka-Late-ing Agent) group. Alkylating agents damage the DNA of a cell and cancer cells are more sensitive to this type of DNA damage. </p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Vinorelbine is given intravenously (IV) as a rapid infusion. Immediately tell a nurse if you feel any <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">pain</a> or a burning sensation along the vein or at the IV site. </p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">Fatigue</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_033">Hair loss</a> </li> <li> Numbness or tingling in hands or feet </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">Pain</a> (jaw) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">Weakness</a> </li> <li> Cramping </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_009">Constipation</a> </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a> (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> Severe <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_009">constipation</a> </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">Shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a> or sleepiness </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a> and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Dizziness, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">weakness</a>, headache, or confusion </li> <li> Strange or unusual bruising or bleeding </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n'),
(100200500152004, 'Zoledronic acid', '<!-- *************** START DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n<h1>Zoledronic acid</h1>\r\n\r\n<div id="rightcolumn">\r\n<div id="resources">\r\n\r\n<h3>More information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/Templates/drugdictionary.aspx?CdrID=42507" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Zoledronic acid</a> (NCI Drug Dictionary)</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a605023.html" onclick="popblank(\'\');" target="blank">Zoledronic acid</a> (MedlinePlus)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id="symptomtext"><ul>\r\n\r\n<li><a href=#1>What are the other names for this drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#2>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#3>How does this drug work?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#4>How is this drug given?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#5>What side effects can be caused by drug?</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=#6>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</a></li>\r\n</ul><br><a name="1"></a><h1>What are the other names for this drug?</h1><p>Generic name: Zoledronic acid (ZOE-le-dron-ik-AS-id)<br />Trade names: Zometa&#174;, Reclast&#174;<br />Other names: None </p><br /><a name="2"></a><h1>What types of cancers is this drug used to treat?</h1><p>Zometa is not a chemotherapy drug.  It is used as a support medication to treat high blood calcium levels and bone diseases in cancer patients. </p><br /><a name="3"></a><h1>How does this drug work?</h1><p>This drug is a bisphosphonate.  It is given to slow the bone destroying activity of bone metastasis and to strengthen bones.</p><br /><a name="4"></a><h1>How is this drug given?</h1><p>Zometa is given intravenously (IV). It takes 15-30 minutes to infuse.  Before you receive this drug, your doctor may have some lab work done to check your kidney function and/or calcium.  Your doctor may have you take a calcium supplement of 500 mg and a multi-vitamin with 400 IU of Vitamin D per day.  Try to drink extra water the day before, the day of, and the day after your infusion.</p><br /><a name="5"></a><h1>What side effects can be caused by drug?</h1><p>You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away.</p><p>Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away.</p><br /><h2>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_045">neutropenia</a>, or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_003">anemia</a>) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">Fever</a>, chills, aches, and <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_051">pain</a> (bone, joint, or muscle) </li> <li> Redness and swelling at the injection site </li> <li> Test changes:  magnesium, phosphorus, and calcium </li></ul><h2>LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Feeling sick (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_042">nausea</a>) </li> <li> Vomiting </li></ul><h2>SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS</h2><ul> <li> Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_018">Diarrhea</a> (more than 4 times in 24 hours) </li> <li> <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_012">Cough</a> and/or <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_069">shortness of breath</a> </li> <li> Dizziness, headache, or confusion </li> <li> Extreme <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_027">fatigue</a>, <a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_075">weakness</a>, or sleepiness </li> <li> Signs of infection (<a href="index.php?nav=menu&seq=_003_001_030">fever</a> of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills) </li></ul><a name="6"></a><h1>What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug?</h1><p>Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:</p><ul> <li> Have any allergies. </li> <li> Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products. </li> <li> Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing. </li></ul>\r\n<a href="#top">Return to top</a></div><br/>\r\n\r\n<!-- *************** STOP DOCUMENT CONTENT HERE *************** -->\r\n'),
(1003001006000001, 'What is lack of appetite?', '<p><span class="item_title">What is lack of appetite?</span><br/>You have lack of appetite when you do not feel hungry, even though you have not eaten as much as usual.</p>'),
(1003001006000002, 'How do people describe lack of appetite?', '<p><span class="item_title">When you have lack of appetite...</span><br/>...you do not feel like eating much, maybe not at all. You may also feel full faster than usual or feel a bad taste in your mouth.</p>'),
(1003001006000003, 'What causes lack of appetite?', '<p><span class="item_title">What causes lack of appetite?</span><br/>You may have lack of appetite as a result of your cancer or your cancer treatment. Also related to lack of appetite are nausea/vomiting, pain, and fatigue.</p>'),
(1003001006100000, 'Lack of Appetite-Manage', '<p><span class="item_title">What can I do about my lack of appetite?</span></p><p>First, how bad is your lack of appetite? Read these statements and click on the ONE that best describes your lack of appetite today:</p>'),
(1003001006200001, 'How can I talk to my doctor about my lack of appetite?', '<p><span class="item_title">How can I talk to my doctor about my lack of appetite?</span><br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Tell your doctor when you started losing your appetite and how it has gotten worse.</li>\n<li>Explain how your lack of appetite is affecting your quality of life.</li>\n<li>If you cannot eat, tell your doctor for how many days, and how much weight you believe you have lost.</li>\n<li>Your doctor will also want to hear if you are having other symptoms: dizziness, mental confusion, nausea or vomiting, diarrhea, constipation, depression, anxiety, or severe weakness to the point that you can hardly get out of bed.</li>\n<li>If you have not had any fluids (water or other) for a day or longer, you must also tell your doctor.</li>\n</ul>'),
(1003001006200002, 'What questions can I ask my doctor?', '<p><span class="item_title">What questions can I ask my doctor?<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>How can I change my diet so that I will feel like eating again?</li>\n<li>How much food should I have each day?</li>\n<li>Why do I have a bad taste in my mouth? How much longer will I still have it?</li>\n<li>I am losing weight. What is the solution? What are my options?</li>\n</ul>'),
(1003001006300001, 'More_Information', '<p><span class="item_title">National Cancer Institute: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/nutrition/Patient" target="_blank">Nutrition PDQ</a><br/><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/nutrition/Patient" target="_blank">www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/nutrition/Patient</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">National Cancer Institute: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/eatinghints" target="_blank">Eating Hints</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/eatinghints" target="_blank">www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/eatinghints (a book about cancer nutrition)</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">American Cancer Society: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.org/treatment/survivorshipduringandaftertreatment/nutritionforpeoplewithcancer/nutritionforthepersonwithcancer/index" target="_blank">Nutrition for the Person with Cancer During Treatment</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.org/treatment/survivorshipduringandaftertreatment/nutritionforpeoplewithcancer/nutritionforthepersonwithcancer/index" target="_blank">www.cancer.org/treatment/survivorshipduringandaftertreatment/nutritionforpeoplewithcancer/nutritionforthepersonwithcancer/index</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">American Cancer Society: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.org/treatment/survivorshipduringandaftertreatment/nutritionforpeoplewithcancer/nutritionforthepersonwithcancer/nutrition-during-treatment-poor-appetite" target="_blank">Changes in Appetite</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.org/treatment/survivorshipduringandaftertreatment/nutritionforpeoplewithcancer/nutritionforthepersonwithcancer/nutrition-during-treatment-poor-appetite" target="_blank">www.cancer.org/treatment/survivorshipduringandaftertreatment/nutritionforpeoplewithcancer/nutritionforthepersonwithcancer/nutrition-during-treatment-poor-appetite</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">American Cancer Society: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.org/cancer/news/features/eating-when-you-have-no-appetite" target="_blank">Eating When You Have No Appetite</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.org/cancer/news/features/eating-when-you-have-no-appetite" target="_blank">www.cancer.org/cancer/news/features/eating-when-you-have-no-appetite</a></span></p>'),
(1003001009001001, 'What is constipation?', '<p><span class="item_title">What is constipation?</span><br/>You are constipated when your bowel movements are rare, incomplete, or painful or when you have had no bowel movement for three days.</p>'),
(1003001009001002, 'When you are constipated', '<p><span class="item_title">\nWhen you are constipated...</span><br/>...you may feel bloated or have a sense of fullness in the rectal area.</p>'),
(1003001009001003, 'What causes constipation?', '<p><span class="item_title">What causes constipation?</span><br/>Constipation may be the result of the cancer itself or of the pain medication you are taking. Other causes include stress, fever, or changes in your diet. You may also get constipated if you do little physical activity or do not drink enough fluids.</p>'),
(1003001009100000, 'constipation-Manage', '<p><span class="item_title">What can I do about my constipation?</span></p><p><i>General management goals and strategies</i></p><p>First, how bad is your constipation? Read these statements and click on the ONE that best describes your constipation today:</p>'),
(1003001009200001, 'How can I talk to my doctor about my constipation?', '<p><span class="item_title">How can I talk to my doctor about my constipation?</span><br/></p>\n\n<p>Report to your doctor if any of these apply to you:<br/></p><ul>\n<li>No bowel movement for 3 or more days</li>\n<li>No bowel movement within 24 hours of taking a laxative</li>\n<li>No eating for 2 or more days</li>\n<li>Very hard, small, bloody, or black stools; painful bowel movements or severe abdominal pain</li>\n<li>Vomiting or bloating with the constipation for over 24 hours</li>\n<li>A greater need to urinate than usual - or the opposite: urinating less frequently</li>\n<li>Back pain</li>\n<li>Hemorrhoids or torn skin around the rectum</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Have your symptom log at hand with the following information:<br/></p><ul>\n<li>Your normal bowel movements, including a history of any past problems you have had with constipation</li>\n<li>The date when your constipation started</li>\n<li>All foods and fluids you have taken in the last couple of days</li>\n<li>All medications that you have taken in the last 3 days, including any over-the-counter medications that you have tried for your constipation</li>\n</ul>'),
(1003001009200002, 'What questions can I ask my doctor?', '<p><span class="item_title">What questions can I ask my doctor?<br/></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What is causing my constipation? Is it my pain medications or my chemotherapy?</li>\r\n<li>What type of physical activity can I do to help?</li>\r\n<li>Should I take fiber supplements?</li>\r\n<li>Is it safe to take over-the-counter products? Which ones do you recommend?</li>\r\n<li>Are there any other medications that can help?</li>\r\n</ul>'),
(1003001009300001, 'More_Information', '<p><span class="item_title">National Cancer Institute: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/gastrointestinalcomplications/Patient" target="_blank">Gastrointestinal Complications</a><br/><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/gastrointestinalcomplications/Patient" target="_blank">www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/gastrointestinalcomplications/Patient</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">National Cancer Institute: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/nutrition/Patient/Page5#Section_341" target="_blank">Nutrition PDQ - Constipation</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/nutrition/Patient/Page5#Section_341" target="_blank">www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/nutrition/Patient/Page5#Section_341</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">National Cancer Institute: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/eatinghints/page4#constipation" target="_blank">Eating Hints - Constipation</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/eatinghints/page4#constipation" target="_blank">www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/eatinghints/page4#constipation</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">American Cancer Society: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.org/treatment/survivorshipduringandaftertreatment/nutritionforpeoplewithcancer/nutritionforthepersonwithcancer/nutrition-during-treatment-constipation" target="_blank">Nutrition for the Person with Cancer During Treatment - Constipation</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.org/treatment/survivorshipduringandaftertreatment/nutritionforpeoplewithcancer/nutritionforthepersonwithcancer/nutrition-during-treatment-constipation" target="_blank">www.cancer.org/treatment/survivorshipduringandaftertreatment/nutritionforpeoplewithcancer/nutritionforthepersonwithcancer/nutrition-during-treatment-constipation</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">University of California Davis Cancer Center: </span><a href="http://www.ucdmc.ucdavis.edu/CANCER/pedresource/pedres_docs/FoodDiary.pdf" target="_blank">Food Diary Form</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.ucdmc.ucdavis.edu/CANCER/pedresource/pedres_docs/FoodDiary.pdf" target="_blank">www.ucdmc.ucdavis.edu/CANCER/pedresource/pedres_docs/FoodDiary.pdf</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">Cancer.net: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.net/all-about-cancer/treating-cancer/managing-side-effects/constipation" target="_blank">Constipation</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.net/all-about-cancer/treating-cancer/managing-side-effects/constipation" target="_blank">www.cancer.net/all-about-cancer/treating-cancer/managing-side-effects/constipation</a></span></p>'),
(1003001015001001, 'What is depression?', '<p><span class="item_title">What is depression?</span><br/>Depression is sadness that is more intense than normal, that greatly affects your daily life, and that won\'t go away.<br/><br/>\nIf you are depressed, you are not alone. Depression occurs in about 25% of people with cancer. It can cause great distress, to the point of making it difficult for you to follow your treatment schedule. You may have a crying spell for no apparent reason. You may eat too much or not enough, or sleep too much or too little. You may feel worthless, helpless, or hopeless. The good news is depression can be treated.\n</p>'),
(1003001015001002, 'What causes depression?', '<p><span class="item_title">What causes depression?</span><br/>You may have depression as a result of a specific event, such as your cancer diagnosis or the death of a loved one. Depression is sometimes the result of changes in your body chemistry.  It can come from the medications you are taking or from being tired. You have cancer, after all, and you are in treatment; both the cancer and the treatment are exhausting you. If your depression doesn\'t last long, you can usually cope on your own. But if your feelings of depression persist, you probably need to be treated with medication or counseling.</p>'),
(1003001015100000, 'depression-Manage', '<p><span class="item_title">What can I do about my depression?</span></p><p><i>General management goals and strategies.</i></p><p>First, how bad is your depression? Read these statements and click on the ONE that best describes your depression today:</p>'),
(1003001015200001, 'How can I talk to my family and friends', '<p><span class="item_title">How can I talk to my family and friends about my depression? How can they help?</span><br/></p>\n<p><ul>\n<li>Try to describe your depression and how it affects you. Be open and honest with those you love.</li>\n<li>Ask your family and friends for ideas to help you deal with your depression.</li>\n<li>Ask them to stay with you. Sometimes just having someone there with you is enough.</li>\n<li>Ask them to help you with your daily needs, or with situations or tasks that you feel are stressful.</li>\n<li>Share enjoyable activities together.</li>\n</ul></p>'),
(1003001015200002, 'How can I talk to my doctor about my depression?', '<p><span class="item_title">How can I talk to my doctor about my depression?<br/></p>\n <p>Report to your doctor if any of these apply to you:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>I feel extremely sad every day for most of the day.</li>\n<li>I have very little interest or pleasure in my usual activities.</li>\n<li>I am quickly losing or gaining a lot of weight.</li>\n<li>I feel very hungry all the time or not hungry at all.</li>\n<li>I cannot get to sleep, or I wake much earlier than usual, or I am sleepy all the time.</li>\n<li>I feel agitated or slowed-down every day.</li>\n<li>I am exhausted every day.</li>\n<li>I feel worthless or guilty most of the time.</li>\n<li>I cannot concentrate or make decisions.</li>\n<li>I have thoughts of hurting myself.</li>\n</ul>'),
(1003001015200003, 'What questions can I ask my doctor?', '<p><span class="item_title">What questions can I ask my doctor?<br/></p>\n \n<ul>\n<li>How can I tell whether I\'m just sad or actually have depression? How will you determine if I am depressed and need help?</li>\n<li>What causes my depression? Is it the cancer or the treatment? If so, how long does it usually last? How can I control it?</li>\n<li>If I treat my depression, will it interfere with my cancer treatment?</li>\n<li>How should I change my diet to help control my depression?</li>\n<li>Is there any counseling or support groups for people with depression that you can refer me to?</li>\n<li>What medications are okay for me to take?</li>\n<li>When do you want me to contact you if my depression gets worse?</li>\n</ul>'),
(1003001015300001, 'More_Information', '<p><span class="item_title">National Institutes of Medicine and Health:</span><a href="http://www.nimh.nih.gov/health/publications/depression-and-cancer/index.shtml" target="_blank"> Depression and Cancer </a><br/><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.nimh.nih.gov/health/publications/depression-and-cancer/index.shtml" target="_blank">www.nimh.nih.gov/health/publications/depression-and-cancer/index.shtml</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">MedlinePlus:</span><a href="https://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/depression.html" target="_blank"> Depression </a><br/><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="https://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/depression.html" target="_blank">www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/depression.html link</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">Mayo Clinic:</span><a href="http://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/depression/in-depth/depression-and-exercise/ART-20046495?p=1" target="_blank"> Depression and Anxiety: Exercise eases symptoms </a><br/><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/depression/in-depth/depression-and-exercise/ART-20046495?p=1" target="_blank">www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/depression/in-depth/depression-and-exercise/ART-20046495?p=1</a></span></p>'),
(1003001018001001, 'What is diarrhea?', '<p><span class="item_title">What is diarrhea?</span><br/>You have diarrhea when you have three or more loose or watery bowel movements per day.</p>'),
(1003001018001002, 'When you have diarrhea', '<p><span class="item_title">When you have diarrhea...</span><br/>...you have an urgent need to have a bowel movement and usually cannot control it. You may also have abdominal pain with cramping, bloating, or nausea. The area around your anus may be irritated and sore.</p>'),
(1003001018001003, 'What causes diarrhea?', '<p><span class="item_title">What causes diarrhea?</span><br/>The cause may be either the cancer or the cancer treatment, especially chemotherapy or radiation. You may have diarrhea immediately after your treatment or up to two weeks after treatment. Antibiotics or laxatives can also cause diarrhea.</p>'),
(1003001018100000, 'diarrhea-Manage', '<p><span class="item_title">What can I do about my diarrhea?</span></p><p><i>General management goals and strategies.</i></p><p>First, how bad is your diarrhea? Read these statements and click on the ONE that best describes your diarrhea today:</p>'),
(1003001018200001, 'How can I talk to my doctor about my diarrhea?', '<p><span class="item_title">How can I talk to my doctor about my diarrhea?</span><br/></p>\n<p>Report to your doctor if any of these apply to you:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Diarrhea for 3 or more days</li>\n<li>Temperature above 101&#176;F (38.3&#176;C) for 2 or more hours</li>\n<li>Bloody or black stools</li>\n<li>Torn, sore, or tender skin around the anus</li>\n<li>No eating for more than 24 hours; excessive thirst</li>\n<li>Feeling tired, dizzy, or weak.</li>\n<li>Urinating less often than usual; dark urine</li>\n<li>Severe abdominal cramps or pain with diarrhea</li>\n<li>Heart palpitations (a racing heart when you are at rest)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Have your symptom log at hand with the following information:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Your normal bowel movements, including a history of any past problems you have had with diarrhea</li>\n<li>The date when your diarrhea started</li>\n<li>Color, consistency, and number of bowel movements in the last 24 hours</li>\n<li>All foods and fluids you have taken in the last couple of days</li>\n<li>All medications that you have taken in the last 3 days, including any over-the-counter medications that you have tried for your constipation</li>\n<li>If you are being treated with radiation therapy to the pelvis, abdomen, or rectum</li>\n<li>Weight loss</li>\n</ul>'),
(1003001018200002, 'What questions can I ask my doctor?', '<p><span class="item_title">What questions can I ask my doctor?<br/></p>\n \n<ul>\r\n<li>What causes my diarrhea? Is it the chemotherapy or my radiation? If so, how long does it usually last? How can I control it? </li>\r\n<li>How should I change my diet to help control my diarrhea?</li>\r\n<li>What medications are okay for me to take?</li>\r\n<li>When do you want me to contact you if I develop diarrhea?</li>\r\n</ul>'),
(1003001018300001, 'More_Information', '<p><span class="item_title">National Cancer Institute: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/gastrointestinalcomplications/Patient/page5" target="_blank">Gastrointestinal Complications-Diarrhea</a><br/><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/gastrointestinalcomplications/Patient/page5" target="_blank">www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/gastrointestinalcomplications/Patient/page5</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">National Cancer Institute: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/nutrition/Patient/page5#Keypoint45" target="_blank">Nutrition PDQ-Diarrhea</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/nutrition/Patient/page5#Keypoint45" target="_blank">www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/nutrition/Patient/page5#Keypoint45</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">National Cancer Institute: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/radiation-side-effects/diarrhea.pdf" target="_blank">What to do When You Have Loose Stools</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/radiation-side-effects/diarrhea.pdf" target="_blank">www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/radiation-side-effects/diarrhea.pdf</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">American Cancer Society: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/physicalsideeffects/dealingwithsymptomsathome/caring-for-the-patient-with-cancer-at-home-diarrhea" target="_blank">Entry on Diarrhea</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/physicalsideeffects/dealingwithsymptomsathome/caring-for-the-patient-with-cancer-at-home-diarrhea" target="_blank">www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/physicalsideeffects/dealingwithsymptomsathome/caring-for-the-patient-with-cancer-at-home-diarrhea</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">Mayo Clinic: </span><a href="http://www.mayoclinic.com/health/diarrhea/CA00040" target="_blank">Diarrhea: Cancer Related Causes and How to Cope</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.mayoclinic.com/health/diarrhea/CA00040" target="_blank">www.mayoclinic.com/health/diarrhea/CA00040</a></span></p>'),
(1003001021001001, 'What is anxiety?', '<p><span class="item_title">What is anxiety?</span><br/>Anxiety is a vague feeling of uneasiness. restlessness, uncertainty, or fear because you expect bad news or harm.</p>'),
(1003001021001002, 'When you have anxiety', '<p><span class="item_title">When you have anxiety...</span><br/>...you may tremble or sweat, your heart may beat faster or you may breathe more rapidly than usual. You may also feel shaky, or have difficulty relaxing or falling asleep.</p>'),
(1003001021001003, 'What causes anxiety?', '<p><span class="item_title">What causes anxiety?</span><br/>People with cancer who have had surgery, chemotherapy, or radiation may get anxious more easily than others. Anxiety and fear are common and normal when you are coping with cancer or with the treatment of cancer. Other symptoms that you are having trouble controlling, such as pain or nausea, can make you anxious.</p>'),
(1003001021100000, 'anxiety-Manage', '<p><span class="item_title">What can I do about my anxiety?</span></p><p><i>General management goals and strategies.</i></p><p>First, how bad is your anxiety? Read these statements and click on the ONE that best describes your anxiety today:</p>'),
(1003001021200001, 'How can I talk to my family and friends about my anxiety? How can they help?', '<p><span class="item_title">How can I talk to my family and friends about my anxiety? How can they help?</span><br/></p>\n<p><ul>\n<li>Try to describe your anxiety and how it affects you (racing thoughts, lump in your throat, heart pounding in your chest, nausea, shortness of breath, feeling dizzy or scared). Be open and honest with those you love.</li>\n<li>Ask your family and friends for ideas to help you deal with your anxiety.</li>\n<li>Ask them to stay with you. Sometimes just having someone there with you is enough.</li>\n<li>Ask them to help you with your daily needs, or with situations or tasks that you feel are stressful.</li>\n<li>Share enjoyable activities together.</li>\n</ul>\n</p>'),
(1003001021200002, 'How can I talk to my doctor about my anxiety?', '<p><span class="item_title">How can I talk to my doctor about my anxiety?<br/></p>\n<p>Report to your doctor if any of these apply to you:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>I feel anxious or agitated frequently.</li>\n<li>I am fearful much of the time or all the time.</li>\n<li>I have shortness of breath lasting for a period of time.</li>\n<li>I feel very hungry all the time or not hungry at all.</li>\n<li>I cannot get to sleep, or I wake much earlier than usual, or I am sleepy all the time.</li>\n<li>I have a racing heart and excessive sweating.</li>\n<li>I have no relief after trying relaxation techniques.</li>\n</ul>'),
(1003001021200003, 'What questions can I ask my doctor?', '<p><span class="item_title">What questions can I ask my doctor?<br/></p>\n \n<ul>\n<li>How can I tell whether I\'m suffering from anxiety? How will you determine if I have anxiety and need help?</li>\n<li>What causes my anxiety? Is it the cancer or the treatment? If so, how long does it usually last? How can I control it?</li>\n<li>If I treat my anxiety, will it interfere with my cancer treatment?</li>\n<li>Is there any counseling or support groups for people with anxiety that you can refer me to?</li>\n<li>What medications are okay for me to take?</li>\n<li>When do you want me to contact you if my anxiety gets worse?</li>\n</ul>'),
(1003001021300001, 'More_Information', '<p><span class="item_title">National Cancer Institute:</span><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/about-cancer/coping/feelings/anxiety-distress-pdq" target="_blank"> Adjustment to Cancer: Anxiety and Distress (PDQ&reg;) </a><br/><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.gov/about-cancer/coping/feelings/anxiety-distress-pdq" target="_blank">www.cancer.gov/about-cancer/coping/feelings/anxiety-distress-pdq</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">MedlinePlus:</span><a href="https://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/anxiety.html" target="_blank"> Anxiety</a><br/><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="https://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/anxiety.html" target="_blank">www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/anxiety.html</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">Mayo Clinic:</span><a href="http://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/depression/in-depth/depression-and-exercise/ART-20046495?p=1" target="_blank"> Depression and Anxiety: Exercise eases symptoms </a><br/><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/depression/in-depth/depression-and-exercise/ART-20046495?p=1" target="_blank">www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/depression/in-depth/depression-and-exercise/ART-20046495?p=1</a></span></p>'),
(1003001027001001, 'What is fatigue?', '<p><span class="item_title">What is fatigue?</span><br/>You are fatigued when you have an overwhelming sense of being tired that makes it hard for you to do physical or mental work, even when you seem to have had enough sleep (usually 7-8 hours).</p>'),
(1003001027001002, 'When you are fatigued', '<p><span class="item_title">When you are fatigued...</span><br/>...you feel tired, weak, slow, or unable to concentrate. You may also feel sad, irritable, or frustrated. Your arms and legs may feel unusually heavy.</p>'),
(1003001027001003, 'What causes fatigue?', '<p><span class="item_title">What causes fatigue?</span><br/>Fatigue may be the result of the cancer itself or of stress, depression, or anxiety. Other causes include anemia (low red-blood cell count) and infection.</br/><br/>\r\n\r\nFatigue is the most common side effect of cancer treatment. You will be fatigued during and after your treatment, and the feeling often lasts for months after treatment ends.  It should always be reported to your physician.</p>'),
(1003001027100000, 'What can I do about my fatigue?', '<p><span class="item_title">What can I do about my fatigue?</span></p><p><i>General management goals and strategies.</i></p><p>First, how bad is your fatigue? Read these statements and click on the ONE that best describes your fatigue today:</p>'),
(1003001027200001, 'How should I talk to my doctor about my fatigue?', '<p><span class="item_title">How should I talk to my doctor about my fatigue?</span><br/></p>\r\n<p>Take your fatigue log with you. Explain when your fatigue started, how it has progressed, what makes it better or worse, and how it affects your daily activities.</p>\r\n<p>Report to your doctor if any of these apply to you:<br/></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>You have a temperature above 101&#176;F (38.3&#176;C) for more than two hours.</li>\r\n<li>You cannot get out of bed or walk to the bathroom for 24 hours.</li>\r\n<li>You cannot think clearly, cannot concentrate, or cannot even watch TV, read, or talk.</li>\r\n<li>You cannot do any important daily activities.</li>\r\n<li>You feel very weak or exhausted for two or more days.</li>\r\n<li>You are dizzy or lose balance.</li>\r\n<li>You have trouble breathing when you do your regular activities for 24 hours.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Discuss with your doctor the factors commonly associated with fatigue that can be managed: anemia, infection, sleep, nutritional problems, emotional distress/depression, pain, and other illnesses or medications.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ask your doctor if it is possible that you might be depressed. Antidepressants can improve your mood, energy levels, and outlook on life, but they are not always indicated. Counseling may also help with depression or anxiety.</p>'),
(1003001027200002, 'What questions can I ask my doctor?', '<p><span class="item_title">What questions can I ask my doctor?<br/></p><ul>\r\n<li>What is causing my fatigue? Is it my cancer treatment? How long will my fatigue last after I am done with treatment?</li>\r\n<li>How can I manage my fatigue?</li>\r\n<li>Do I need to change my diet? Do I need any supplements?</li>\r\n<li>Should I get a physical therapist to help me develop an exercise plan?</li>\r\n<li>What relaxation techniques do you recommend?</li>\r\n<li>Are there any medications that can help with my fatigue?</li>\r\n</ul>');
INSERT INTO `texthtml` (`html_id`, `text`, `html`) VALUES
(1003001027300001, 'More_Information', '<p><span class="item_title">National Cancer Institute: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/radiation-side-effects/fatigue.pdf" target="_blank">What To Do When You Feel Weak or Tired (Fatigue)</a><br/><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/radiation-side-effects/fatigue.pdf" target="_blank">www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/radiation-side-effects/fatigue.pdf</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">National Cancer Institute: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/fatigue/Patient" target="_blank">Fatigue PDQ</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/fatigue/Patient" target="_blank">www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/fatigue/Patient</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">National Cancer Institute: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/fatigue/Patient/page4" target="_blank">Fatigue PDQ Section on Treatments for Fatigue</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/fatigue/Patient/page4" target="_blank">www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/fatigue/Patient/page4</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">American Cancer Society: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/physicalsideeffects/fatigue/feeling-tired-vs-cancer-related-fatigue" target="_blank">Feeling Tired vs. Cancer Related Fatigue</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/physicalsideeffects/fatigue/feeling-tired-vs-cancer-related-fatigue" target="_blank">www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/physicalsideeffects/fatigue/feeling-tired-vs-cancer-related-fatigue</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">American Cancer Society: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/physicalsideeffects/fatigue/seven-ways-to-manage-cancer-related-fatigue" target="_blank">7 Ways to Manage Cancer Related Fatigue</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/physicalsideeffects/fatigue/seven-ways-to-manage-cancer-related-fatigue" target="_blank">www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/physicalsideeffects/fatigue/seven-ways-to-manage-cancer-related-fatigue</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n'),
(1003001039001001, 'What are mouth sores?', '<p><span class="item_title">What are mouth sores?</span><br/>Mouth sores occur when the lining of the mouth, tongue, and throat becomes irritated, swollen or painful. You may have open sores (called "ulcers").</p>'),
(1003001039001002, 'When you have mouth sores', '<p><span class="item_title">When you have mouth sores...</span><br/>...your mouth may feel uncomfortably warm, may tingle or be sore. Your mouth may feel unusually dry and you may have a raw feeling in your throat.</p>'),
(1003001039001003, 'What causes mouth sores?', '<p><span class="item_title">What causes mouth sores?</span><br/>Half of cancer patients on chemotherapy and most patients who have radiation to the head or neck will have mouth discomfort as a side effect of treatment. This is how you may expect mouth sores to develop relative to your chemotherapy:<br/><p>\n<ul>\n<li>3-5 days after starting treatment: warm mouth; tingling/soreness</li>\n<li>1-2 weeks after starting treatment: first sores</li>\n<li>1-2 weeks after finishing treatment: sores begin to heal</li>\n<li>3+ weeks after finishing treatment: sores and pain have disappeared</li>\n</ul>'),
(1003001039100000, 'What can I do about my mouth sores?', '<p><span class="item_title">What can I do about my mouth sores?</span></p><p><i>General management goals and strategies:</i></p>\n\n<p>First, how bad are your mouth sores? Read these statements and click on the ONE that best describes your mouth sores today:</p>'),
(1003001039200001, 'How should I talk to my doctor about my mouth sores?', '<p><span class="item_title">How should I talk to my doctor about my mouth sores?</span><br/></p>\r\n<p>Tell your doctor...<br/></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>...if you have sores or new red/white patches in your mouth or on your tongue.</li>\r\n<li>...if you have not been able to eat any food for 24 hours.</li>\r\n<li>...if you have lost 5 or more pounds in one week.</li>\r\n<li>...if you have signs of infection (especially pus) on your tongue</li>\r\n<li>...if you have a temperature above 101&#176;F (38.3&#176;C).</li>\r\n</ul>'),
(1003001039200002, 'What questions can I ask my doctor?', '<p><span class="item_title">What questions can I ask my doctor?<br/></p>\n \n<ul>\r\n<li>What causes my mouth sores? Is it my cancer treatment?</li>\r\n<li>How should I manage my daily mouth care?</li>\r\n<li>Should I consult with a dietitian to help me choose foods?</li>\r\n<li>What medications can I use for pain? How often should I use them?</li>\r\n</ul>'),
(1003001039300001, 'More_Information', '<p><span class="item_title">National Cancer Institute: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/oralcomplications/Patient" target="_blank">Oral Complications of Chemotherapy and Head/Neck Radiation PDQ</a><br/><span id="more_info_url">\n<a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/oralcomplications/Patient" target="_blank">www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/oralcomplications/Patient</a></span></p>\n\n<p><span class="item_title">National Cancer Institute: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/radiation-side-effects/mouthandthroat.pdf" target="_blank">What To Do When Your Mouth or Throat Hurts</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\n<a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/radiation-side-effects/mouthandthroat.pdf" target="_blank">www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/radiation-side-effects/mouthandthroat.pdf</a></span></p>\n\n<p><span class="item_title">American Cancer Society: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.org/treatment/survivorshipduringandaftertreatment/nutritionforpeoplewithcancer/nutritionforthepersonwithcancer/nutrition-during-treatment-mouth-throat-pain-or-sores" target="_blank">Mouth or Throat Pain or Sores</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\n<a href="http://www.cancer.org/treatment/survivorshipduringandaftertreatment/nutritionforpeoplewithcancer/nutritionforthepersonwithcancer/nutrition-during-treatment-mouth-throat-pain-or-sores" target="_blank">www.cancer.org/treatment/survivorshipduringandaftertreatment/nutritionforpeoplewithcancer/nutritionforthepersonwithcancer/nutrition-during-treatment-mouth-throat-pain-or-sores</a></span></p>\n\n<p><span class="item_title">American Cancer Society: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.org/acs/groups/content/@editorial/documents/document/acspc-031609.pdf" target="_blank">Getting Help for Mouth Sores</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\n<a href="http://www.cancer.org/acs/groups/content/@editorial/documents/document/acspc-031609.pdf" target="_blank">www.cancer.org/acs/groups/content/@editorial/documents/document/acspc-031609.pdf</a></span></p>\n\n<p><span class="item_title">Mayo Clinic: </span><a href="http://www.mayoclinic.com/health/mouth-sores/CA00054" target="_blank">Mouth Sores Caused by Cancer: How to Cope</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\n<a href="http://www.mayoclinic.com/health/mouth-sores/CA00054" target="_blank">www.mayoclinic.com/health/mouth-sores/CA00054</a></span></p>\n\n<p><span class="item_title">Indiana University School of Dentistry: </span><a href="http://www.iusd.iupui.edu/OHCCP/" target="_blank">Oral Health Care for Cancer Patients</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\n<a href="http://www.iusd.iupui.edu/OHCCP/" target="_blank">www.iusd.iupui.edu/OHCCP/</a></span></p>\n'),
(1003001042001001, 'What is nausea?', '<p><span class="item_title">What is nausea?</span><br/>Nausea is an unpleasant feeling in the back of your throat and in your stomach that can lead to vomiting. </p>'),
(1003001042001002, 'When you have nausea', '<p><span class="item_title">When you have nausea...</span><br/>...you feel queasy or sick to your stomach. It may feel like heartburn, or as though you have butterflies in your stomach. You may have an unpleasant reaction to food or smells. There may even be a bitter or acidic taste in your mouth.</p>'),
(1003001042001003, 'What causes nausea?', '<p><span class="item_title">What causes nausea?</span><br/>Nausea is caused by your cancer treatment or by the cancer itself.</p>'),
(1003001042100000, 'What can I do about my nausea?', '<p><span class="item_title">What can I do about my nausea?</span></p><p><i>General management goals and strategies</i></p><p>First, how bad is your nausea? Read these statements and click on the ONE that best describes your nausea today:</p>'),
(1003001042200001, 'How should I talk to my doctor about my nausea?', '<p><span class="item_title">How should I talk to my doctor about my nausea?</span><br/></p>\r\n<p>Report all of the following:<br/></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>A temperature above 101&#176;F (38.3&#176;C) for 2 hours or longer</li>\r\n<li>Three or more vomiting episodes per hour for more than 6 hours</li>\r\n<li>Vomiting episodes several times a day for 2 or more days</li>\r\n<li>Blood in your vomit or projectile vomiting (vomiting that ejects stomach contents with great force)</li>\r\n<li>Weight loss of 2 or more pounds in a day</li>\r\n<li>No eating for 24 hours</li>\r\n<li>Inability to keep fluids down for 12 hours (with or without the use of anti-nausea medicines)</li>\r\n<li>Shortness of breath at rest</li>\r\n<li>Abdominal pain or bloating with nausea</li>\r\n<li>Cold and clammy skin</li>\r\n<li>Dizziness/confusion</li>\r\n<li>Dark yellow urine or very little urine (signs of dehydration)</li>\r\n</ul>'),
(1003001042200002, 'What questions can I ask my doctor?', '<p><span class="item_title">What questions can I ask my doctor?<br/></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What medications can I take before my chemotherapy that will prevent nausea or vomiting?</li>\r\n<li>Which of my chemotherapy medications are likely to give me nausea or vomiting?</li>\r\n<li>What will my anti-nausea medication schedule be after treatment?</li>\r\n<li>What should I eat before and after treatment? If I am staying at the hospital overnight, should I bring any food with me?</li>\r\n<li>If my anti-nausea medications do not work, who should I contact for additional help?</li>\r\n<li>What relaxation techniques would you recommend for me?</li>\r\n</ul>'),
(1003001042300001, 'More_Information', '<p><span class="item_title">National Cancer Institute: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/nausea/Patient" target="_blank">Nausea and Vomiting PDQ</a><br/><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/nausea/Patient" target="_blank">www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/nausea/Patient</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">National Cancer Institute: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/radiation-side-effects/nausea.pdf" target="_blank">What to Do about Feeling Sick to Your Stomach and Throwing Up (Nausea and Vomiting)</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/radiation-side-effects/nausea.pdf" target="_blank">www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/radiation-side-effects/nausea.pdf</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">American Cancer Society: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/physicalsideeffects/nauseaandvomiting/nauseaandvomiting/index" target="_blank">Nausea and Vomiting</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/physicalsideeffects/nauseaandvomiting/nauseaandvomiting/index" target="_blank">www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/physicalsideeffects/nauseaandvomiting/nauseaandvomiting/index</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">American Cancer Society: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.org/acs/groups/content/@editorial/documents/document/acspc-031610.pdf" target="_blank">Getting Help for Nausea and Vomiting</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.org/acs/groups/content/@editorial/documents/document/acspc-031610.pdf" target="_blank">www.cancer.org/acs/groups/content/@editorial/documents/document/acspc-031610.pdf</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">CancerConnect.com: </span><a href="http://news.cancerconnect.com/nausea-and-vomiting-information-center/" target="_blank">Nausea and Vomiting Center</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://news.cancerconnect.com/nausea-and-vomiting-information-center/" target="_blank">news.cancerconnect.com/nausea-and-vomiting-information-center/</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n'),
(1003001048001001, 'What are numbness and tingling?', '<p><span class="item_title">What are numbness and tingling?</span><br/>When you experience numbness or tingling it means there is swelling or damage to your nerve fibers. It is a partial loss of sensation in the hands and feet beginning at the fingers and toes.</p>'),
(1003001048001002, 'When you have numbness and tingling', '<p><span class="item_title">When you have numbness and tingling...</span><br/>...you feel discomfort similar to pins and needles or burning. You are less sensitive to changes in temperature, touch, pain, or vibration. You may lose balance or drop things, have difficulty walking or picking up objects, writing, buttoning clothing, or brushing your teeth. You may feel weak, stiff, or tight in the arms or legs. You may also have blurred vision, jaw pain, or hearing loss/ringing or buzzing in the ears.</p>'),
(1003001048001003, 'What causes numbness and tingling?', '<p><span class="item_title">What causes numbness and tingling?</span><br/>Numbness and tingling are a result of your chemotherapy. It may develop suddenly after your treatment or build up gradually. Usually it is more intense right after a treatment and gets better just before the next one. It tends to be at its worst 3 to 5 months after your last treatment. You are at the greatest risk to experience numbness and tingling if you also have diabetes, alcoholism, or severe malnutrition.</p>\n\n<p>Some of the most common chemotherapy drugs that cause numbness and tingling are:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Vincristine (Oncovin&#174;)</li>\n<li>Vindesine (Eldisine&#174;)</li>\n<li>Vinorelbine (Navelbine&#174;)</li>\n<li>Vinblastine (Velban&#174;)</li>\n<li>Platinol (Cisplatin&#174;)</li>\n<li>Paraplatin (Carboplatin&#174;)</li>\n<li>Eloxatin (Oxaliplatin&#174;)</li>\n<li>Paclitaxel (Taxol&#174;)</li>\n<li>Docetaxel (Taxotere&#174;)</li>\n<li>Bortezomib (Velcade&#174;)</li>\n<li>Thalidomide</li>\n<li>Procarbazine (Matulane&#174;)</li>\n<li>Cytarabine (ARA-C&#174;)</li>\n<li>Vespide (Etoposide&#174;, vp-16)</li>\n<li>Alfa-interferon</li>\n</ul>'),
(1003001048100000, 'What can I do about my numbness and tingling?', '<p><span class="item_title">What can I do about my numbness and tingling?</span></p><p> How bad is your numbness and tingling? Read these statements and click on the ONE that best describes your numbness and tingling today:</p>'),
(1003001048200001, 'How can I talk to my doctor about my numbness and tingling?', '<p><span class="item_title">How can I talk to my doctor about my numbness and tingling?</span><br/></p>\r\n<p>Always report<br/></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Paralysis, pain, numbness, prickling, tingling, weakness, or burning in your skin that makes it difficult to perform your daily activities. (Be sure to mention if the symptoms occur in your hands, arms, or legs.)</li>\r\n<li>Changes in your sense of touch in your hands, fingers, feet, toes, or mouth that make it difficult to feel or pick up objects</li>\r\n<li>Difficulty swallowing, breathing, drinking, or chewing</li>\r\n<li>Difficulty urinating or constipation</li>\r\n<li>Blurred vision or ringing/buzzing in your ears</li>\r\n<li>Stumbling, losing your balance, or falling from numbness in your feet</li>\r\n<li>Inability to drive because your hands or feet are numb</li>\r\n<li>Need for special equipment</li>\r\n</ul>'),
(1003001048200002, 'What questions can I ask my doctor?', '<p><span class="item_title">What questions can I ask my doctor?<br/></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What causes my numbness and tingling? Is it the chemotherapy?</li>\r\n<li>Am I at risk for developing numbness and tingling? How can I prevent it?</li>\r\n<li>Will the numbness and tingling disappear after treatment?</li>\r\n<li>Am I taking any medications that could make my numbness and tingling worse?</li>\r\n<li>Can I keep on driving? Do I need a disabled parking permit?</li>\r\n<li>Would physical therapy or occupational therapy help me?</li>\r\n<li>Should I try acupuncture to manage my pain?</li>\r\n</ul>'),
(1003001048300001, 'More_Information', '<p><span class="item_title">National Cancer Institute: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/chemo-side-effects/nerve.pdf" target="_blank">Nerve Changes</a><br/><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/chemo-side-effects/nerve.pdf" target="_blank">www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/chemo-side-effects/nerve.pdf</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">American Cancer Society: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/treatmenttypes/chemotherapy/understandingchemotherapyaguideforpatientsandfamilies/understanding-chemotherapy-more-side-effects-nerve-and-muscle-problems" target="_blank">Nerve and Muscle Problems</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/treatmenttypes/chemotherapy/understandingchemotherapyaguideforpatientsandfamilies/understanding-chemotherapy-more-side-effects-nerve-and-muscle-problems" target="_blank">www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/treatmenttypes/chemotherapy/understandingchemotherapyaguideforpatientsandfamilies/understanding-chemotherapy-more-side-effects-nerve-and-muscle-problems</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">American Cancer Society: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/physicalsideeffects/chemotherapyeffects/peripheralneuropathy/peripheral-neuropathy-caused-by-chemotherapy-toc" target="_blank">Peripheral Neuropathy Caused by Chemotherapy</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/physicalsideeffects/chemotherapyeffects/peripheralneuropathy/peripheral-neuropathy-caused-by-chemotherapy-toc" target="_blank">www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/physicalsideeffects/chemotherapyeffects/peripheralneuropathy/peripheral-neuropathy-caused-by-chemotherapy-toc</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">CancerConnect.com: </span><a href="http://news.cancerconnect.com/numbness-and-tingling-peripheral-neuropathy/" target="_blank">Numbness and Tingling</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://news.cancerconnect.com/numbness-and-tingling-peripheral-neuropathy/" target="_blank">news.cancerconnect.com/numbness-and-tingling-peripheral-neuropathy/</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n'),
(1003001051001001, 'What is pain?', '<p><span class="item_title">What is pain?</span><br/>You have pain when you have an unpleasant, uncomfortable feeling. Pain means there is possible or actual damage to part of your body. </p>'),
(1003001051001002, 'When you have pain', '<p><span class="item_title">When you have pain...</span><br/>...the aching is usually concentrated in one area of your body, but it can also be vague and generalized. It can come on suddenly or gradually, and it can be sharp and intense, tingling or numbing. It can also be described as burning.</p>'),
(1003001051001003, 'What causes pain?', '<p><span class="item_title">What causes pain?</span><br/>The cause of your pain may be the cancer growing and pressing into nerves or tissue in the aching area. It can also be the result of your cancer treatment or of tissue damage during surgery.</p>'),
(1003001051100000, 'What can I do about my pain?', '<p><span class="item_title">What can I do about my pain?</span></p><p><i>General management goals and strategies</i></p>\n<p>First, how bad is your pain? Read these statements and click on the ONE that best describes your pain today:</p>'),
(1003001051200001, 'How should I talk to my doctor about my pain?', '<p><span class="item_title">How should I talk to my doctor about my pain?</span><br/></p>\r\n<p>Tell your doctor:<br/></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Where the pain is located, how long it lasts, and how long it takes for your pain medication to work</li>\r\n<li>If your current pain medication is not working or if it has unbearable side effects, such as constipation or diarrhea</li>\r\n<li>If you cannot take anything by mouth, including the pain medication</li>\r\n<li>If your pain has changed since the last visit to your doctor</li>\r\n<li>If you have a cough or fever higher than 101&#176;F (38.3&#176;C) for more than 24 hours</li>\r\n<li>If you have fatigue, nausea, or bloating for more than 2 days</li>\r\n<li>If you pain is getting worse even when you are following your pain medication schedule</li>\r\n<li>If you are confused or becoming disoriented</li>\r\n</ul>'),
(1003001051200002, 'What questions can I ask my doctor?', '<p><span class="item_title">What questions can I ask my doctor?<br/></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What is causing my pain?</li>\r\n<li>How much medication should I take, and how often?</li>\r\n<li>How long does it take for the medication to start working?</li>\r\n<li>What are the side effects of my pain medication? Can I prevent them?</li>\r\n<li>Is it safe to drink alcoholic beverages, drive, or operate machinery after I have taken my pain medication?</li>\r\n<li>If my pain medication is not working, can I take more? If the dose can be increased, by how much? Should I increase the dose or the frequency? Should I call you before I make any changes to my medication schedule?</li>\r\n<li>Can I get help managing my pain through a support group? Is there any available counseling?</li>\r\n</ul>'),
(1003001051300001, 'More_Information', '<p><span class="item_title">National Cancer Institute: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/paincontrol" target="_blank"> Pain Control: Support for People with Cancer </a><br/><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/paincontrol" target="_blank">www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/paincontrol</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">National Cancer Institute: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/pain/Patient/page1" target="_blank"> Pain </a><br><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/pain/Patient/page1" target="_blank">www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/pain/Patient/page1</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">American Cancer Institute: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.org/treatment/supportprogramsservices/onlinecommunities/participateinacancereducationclass/icancopeonline/relievingcancerpain" target="_blank">Webinar on Relieving Cancer Pain</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.org/treatment/supportprogramsservices/onlinecommunities/participateinacancereducationclass/icancopeonline/relievingcancerpain" target="_blank">www.cancer.org/treatment/supportprogramsservices/onlinecommunities/participateinacancereducationclass/icancopeonline/relievingcancerpain</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">American Cancer Institute: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.org/acs/groups/content/@editorial/documents/document/acspc-033203.pdf" target="_blank">Daily Pain Diary</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.org/acs/groups/content/@editorial/documents/document/acspc-033203.pdf" target="_blank">www.cancer.org/acs/groups/content/@editorial/documents/document/acspc-033203.pdf</a></span></p>'),
(1003001060001001, 'What is a rash?', '<p><span class="item_title">What is a rash?</span><br/>A rash is a change in the appearance or the texture of your skin. It may affect all of your skin or just one part of your body.</p>'),
(1003001060001002, 'When you have a rash', '<p><span class="item_title">\nWhen you have a rash...</span><br/>...your skin may become red and feel hot or itchy. It may also be dry or cracked, with bumps that look like acne, or blisters that can drain clear fluid. If the redness is covered in a brown crust and oozes fluid, it probably means it is infected. You may also have intense itching and may feel the need to scratch.</p>'),
(1003001060001003, 'What causes a rash?', '<p><span class="item_title">What causes a rash?</span><br/>Many chemotherapy drugs cause rashes and skin changes during treatment or within the first 36 hours after treatment. This may be an acute allergic reaction causing hives, flushing, and itching. It is very important that you let your healthcare provider know <b>immediately</b> if you experience this type of rash. However, a rash normally does not require you to stop your treatment and usually clears up within 1-2 months after treatment is completed.'),
(1003001060100000, 'Rash - Manage', '<p><span class="item_title">What can I do about my rash?</span></p><p>It is <b>very important</b> that you contact your doctor if your rash becomes bumpy and looks like acne. This rash is <b>NOT</b> acne. Do not treat it with acne medication.</p>\n\n<p><b>How bad is your rash?</b> Read these statements and select the ONE that best describes your rash today:</p>'),
(1003001060200001, 'How can I talk to my doctor about my rash?', '<p><span class="item_title">How can I talk to my doctor about my rash?</span><br/></p>\r\n<p>You must report:<br></p>\r\n<ul><li>A temperature above 101&#176;F (38.3&#176;C) for two or more hours (Don\'t drink any hot or cold drinks 15 minutes before you take your temperature.)</li>\r\n<li>A rash that does not go away in two weeks</li>\r\n<li>A rash that becomes infected, including any pus or other fluids oozing from the rash</li>\r\n<li>A rash that affects the lining of your mouth or your nose and that makes it difficult to eat, talk, or sleep</li>\r\n<li>Blisters</li>\r\n<li>Cracking or peeling fingernails</li>\r\n<li>Severe itching</li>\r\n<li>Hives, flushing, or difficulty breathing. (If you have any of these, call your doctor IMMEDIATELY.)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><b>ALWAYS</b> call your doctor if your rash gets worse or the medication prescribed is not working after two or more weeks.</p>'),
(1003001060200002, 'What questions can I ask my doctor?', '<p><span class="item_title">What questions can I ask my doctor?<br/></p>\r\n \r\n<ul><li>Do I need to take any medications before my treatment to reduce my risk of getting a rash?</li>\r\n<li>Should I stop taking my chemotherapy if I develop a rash?</li>\r\n<li>Does my chemotherapy cause my rash? If so, when will my rash go away?</li>\r\n<li>Can I wear makeup if I develop a rash?</li>\r\n<li>Would a special oatmeal bath reduce itching?</li>\r\n</ul>'),
(1003001060300001, 'More Information', '<p><span class="item_title">National Cancer Institute: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/radiation-side-effects/skin.pdf" target="_blank">What to do about Mild Skin Changes</a><br/><span id="more_info_url">\n<a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/radiation-side-effects/skin.pdf" target="_blank">www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/radiation-side-effects/skin.pdf</a></span></p>\n\n<p><span class="item_title">National Cancer Institute: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/pruritus/Patient\n" target="_blank">Pruritus (itching)</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\n<a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/pruritus/Patient\n" target="_blank">www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/pruritus/Patient\n</a></span></p>\n\n<p><span class="item_title">American Cancer Society: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.org/acs/groups/content/@editorial/documents/document/acspc-031629.pdf" target="_blank">Getting Help for Skin Changes</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\n<a href="http://www.cancer.org/acs/groups/content/@editorial/documents/document/acspc-031629.pdf" target="_blank">www.cancer.org/acs/groups/content/@editorial/documents/document/acspc-031629.pdf</a></span></p>\n\n<p><span class="item_title">Oncolink: </span><a href="http://oncolink.org/coping/article.cfm?c=5&s=75&ss=186&id=991" target="_blank">Nail and Skin Care</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\n<a href="http://oncolink.org/coping/article.cfm?c=5&s=75&ss=186&id=991" target="_blank">oncolink.org/coping/article.cfm?c=5&s=75&ss=186&id=991</a></span></p>\n\n<p><span class="item_title">National Comprehensive Cancer Network: </span><a href="http://www.nccn.org/patients/resources/life_with_cancer/managing_symptoms/skin_rashes.aspx" target="_blank">Skin Rashes in Cancer Treatment</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\n<a href="http://www.nccn.org/patients/resources/life_with_cancer/managing_symptoms/skin_rashes.aspx" target="_blank">www.nccn.org/patients/resources/life_with_cancer/managing_symptoms/skin_rashes.aspx</a></span></p>'),
(1003001069001001, 'What is shortness of breath?', '<p><span class="item_title">What is shortness of breath?</span><br/>You are short of breath when you have difficulty breathing or trouble catching your breath.</p>'),
(1003001069001002, 'When you have shortness of breath ', '<p><span class="item_title">When you have shortness of breath...</span><br/>...you need to work hard to breathe. You feel "air hungry" or suffocated.</p>'),
(1003001069001003, 'What causes shortness of breath?', '<p><span class="item_title">What causes shortness of breath?</span><br/>Shortness of breath has many possible causes: anemia, fluid in the lungs, infection, fatigue, pneumonia, pain, obesity, stress, or anxiety. You may also be short of breath after surgery, or as a side effect of chemotherapy or radiation therapy.</p>'),
(1003001069100000, 'What can I do about my shortness of breath?', '<p><span class="item_title">What can I do about my shortness of breath?</span></p><p>How bad is your shortness of breath? Read these statements and click on the ONE that best describes your shortness of breath today:</p>'),
(1003001069200001, 'How can I talk to my doctor about my shortness of breath?', '<p><span class="item_title">How can I talk to my doctor about my shortness of breath?</span><br/></p><p>Always report<br/></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The time of day and the circumstances in which you are short of breath. Does it happen after daily activity or at rest? How long does it last? (Always call your doctor if it lasts more than 24 hours.)</li>\r\n<li>Painful breathing, wheezing, flared nostrils, straining of the neck muscles, or chest pain</li>\r\n<li>Thick yellow/green or bloody phlegm</li>\r\n<li>Cold, clammy skin</li>\r\n<li>Night sweats</li>\r\n<li>Reduced activity (such as walking), increased pulse rate at rest, or a rapid, pounding heart</li>\r\n<li>Swelling of the ankles or calves of your legs</li>\r\n<li>Inability to get out of bed for two or more days</li>\r\n<li>A temperature above 101&#176;F (38.3&#176;C) for two or more hours</li>\r\n</ul>'),
(1003001069200002, 'What questions can I ask my doctor?', '<p><span class="item_title">What questions can I ask my doctor?<br/></p><ul>\r\n<li>What causes my shortness of breath? Is it my cancer treatment?</li>\r\n<li>What can be done to make it better? Should I take medication?</li>\r\n<li>Where can I learn relaxation techniques?</li>\r\n</ul>'),
(1003001069300001, 'More_Information', '<p><span class="item_title">National Cancer Institute: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/about-cancer/treatment/side-effects/cardiopulmonary-pdq#section/_143" target="_blank">National Cancer Institute: Dyspnea During Advanced Cancer </a><br/><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.gov/about-cancer/treatment/side-effects/cardiopulmonary-pdq#section/_143" target="_blank">www.cancer.gov/about-cancer/treatment/side-effects/cardiopulmonary-pdq#section/_143</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">American Cancer Society: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/physicalsideeffects/dealingwithsymptomsathome/caring-for-the-patient-with-cancer-at-home-shortness-of-breath" target="_blank">Shortness of Breath</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/physicalsideeffects/dealingwithsymptomsathome/caring-for-the-patient-with-cancer-at-home-shortness-of-breath" target="_blank">www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/physicalsideeffects/dealingwithsymptomsathome/caring-for-the-patient-with-cancer-at-home-shortness-of-breath</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">American Cancer Society: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.org/Treatment/TreatmentsandSideEffects/ComplementaryandAlternativeMedicine/complementaryandalternativemethodsandcancer/index" target="_blank"> More information on complementary and alternative medicine </a><br><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.org/Treatment/TreatmentsandSideEffects/ComplementaryandAlternativeMedicine/complementaryandalternativemethodsandcancer/index" target="_blank">www.cancer.org/Treatment/TreatmentsandSideEffects/ComplementaryandAlternativeMedicine/complementaryandalternativemethodsandcancer/index</a></span></p>'),
(1003001072001001, 'What is a sleeping problem?', '<p><span class="item_title">What is a sleeping problem?</span><br/>You have a sleeping problem if you have difficulty falling asleep, staying asleep, or getting enough sleep.</p>'),
(1003001072001002, 'When you have a sleeping problem', '<p><span class="item_title">When you have a sleeping problem...</span><br/>...you wake up several times during the night and have trouble going back to sleep, or you wake up feeling tired or too early in the morning. You may also be generally irritable or have problems with memory or concentration.</p>'),
(1003001072001003, 'What causes sleeping problems?', '<p><span class="item_title">What causes sleeping problems?</span><br/>Your chemotherapy drugs and other medications may be the cause of your sleeping problems. You may also have trouble sleeping if you are anxious or depressed about the cancer itself or the treatment. Pain, diarrhea, nausea, or vomiting can also interfere with sleep.</p>'),
(1003001072100000, 'What can I do about my sleeping problems?', '<p><span class="item_title">What can I do about my sleeping problems?</span></p><p><i>General management goals and strategies</i></p><p>First, how bad is your sleeping problem? Read these statements and click on the ONE that best describes your problem today:</p>'),
(1003001072200001, 'How should I talk to my doctor about my sleeping problems?', '<p><span class="item_title">How should I talk to my doctor about my sleeping problems?</span><br/>\r\n</p><p>Bring your sleep diary with you to discuss your problem with the doctor. Always report:<br/></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Waking up frequently during the night or difficulty falling back asleep after waking for 3 or more weeks</li>\r\n<li>Sleeping problems caused by sadness for 2 or more weeks</li>\r\n<li>Inability to do your daily activities</li>\r\n<li>Pain or fatigue that you cannot control</li>\r\n<li>Nightmares</li>\r\n<li>Shortness of breath</li>\r\n<li>Weakness, dizziness, or fainting</li>\r\n</ul>'),
(1003001072200002, 'What questions can I ask my doctor?', '<p><span class="item_title">What questions can I ask my doctor?<br/></p><ul>\r\n<li>Should I take medication for my sleeping problem? Are herbal supplements a good option?</li>\r\n<li>Will my sleep improve after my cancer treatment?</li>\r\n<li>What type and amount of physical activity is safe for me to do?</li>\r\n<li>Where can I learn more about relaxation techniques?</li>\r\n<li>Should I see a sleep specialist?</li>\r\n</ul>'),
(1003001072300001, 'More_Information', '<p><span class="item_title">National Cancer Institute: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/sleepdisorders/Patient" target="_blank">Sleep Disorders</a><br/><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/sleepdisorders/Patient" target="_blank">www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/sleepdisorders/Patient</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">American Cancer Society: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/physicalsideeffects/dealingwithsymptomsathome/caring-for-the-patient-with-cancer-at-home-sleep-problems" target="_blank">Sleep Problems</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/physicalsideeffects/dealingwithsymptomsathome/caring-for-the-patient-with-cancer-at-home-sleep-problems" target="_blank">www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/physicalsideeffects/dealingwithsymptomsathome/caring-for-the-patient-with-cancer-at-home-sleep-problems</a></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class="item_title">American Cancer Society: </span><a href="http://www.cancer.org/acs/groups/content/@editorial/documents/document/acspc-031631.pdf" target="_blank">Getting Help for Sleep Problems</a><br><span id="more_info_url">\r\n<a href="http://www.cancer.org/acs/groups/content/@editorial/documents/document/acspc-031631.pdf" target="_blank">www.cancer.org/acs/groups/content/@editorial/documents/document/acspc-031631.pdf</a></span></p>\r\n'),
(1003001006100000000, 'Lack of Appetite No Trouble', '<div id="tc0" onclick="$(\'#tcrb0\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');report(\'0\',\'TC_NoProblem Appetite\');"><input id="tcrb0" type="radio" name="tc" value="0"/><label> I don\'t have lack of appetite.</label></div>'),
(1003001006100000001, 'Lack of Appetite - TC1', '<div id="tc1" onclick="$(\'#tcrb1\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'mild_tab\',\'tab_item_mild\');report(\'2\',\'TC_Mild Appetite\');"><input id="tcrb1" type="radio" name="tc" value="1"/><label> I am less hungry than usual, but I have not changed my eating habits.</label></div>'),
(1003001006100000002, 'Lack of Appetite - TC2', '<div id="tc2" onclick="$(\'#tcrb2\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'moderate_tab\',\'tab_item_moderate\');report(\'5\',\'TC_Moderate Appetite\');"><input id="tcrb2" type="radio" name="tc" value="2"/><label> I am eating less, but I haven\'t lost weight.</label></div>'),
(1003001006100000003, 'Lack of Appetite - TC3', '<div id="tc3" onclick="$(\'#tcrb3\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'severe_tab\',\'tab_item_severe\');report(\'8\',\'TC_Severe Appetite\');"><input id="tcrb3" type="radio" name="tc" value="3"/><label> I am taking very little food or fluids and I have lost more than 10 percent of my usual weight.</label></div>'),
(1003001006100001001, 'Lack of Appetite - Mild', '<p><b>Your lack of appetite is <span id="text_mild">MILD</span></b></p>\n<p>Here are some management tips for you:</p><p>Useful activities:<br/></p><ul>\n<li>Use a log to keep a record of what you eat and drink and any medication that you are taking.</li>\n<li>Treat constipation or diarrhea as soon as possible. Both of them can affect your appetite.</li>\n<li>Doing mild physical activity such as walking for 30 minutes before a meal can make you feel hungrier.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Nutrition:<br/></p><ul>\n<li>Try having 5 or 6 smaller meals or healthy snacks throughout the day instead of 3 meals a day.</li>\n<li>Choose high-protein foods such as eggs, whole milk, cheese, meats, and peanut butter.</li>\n<li>Drink 8 glasses of water or other non-caffeinated drinks every day (a total of about half a gallon).</li>\n</ul>'),
(1003001006100001002, 'Lack of Appetite - Moderate', '<p><b>Your lack of appetite is <span id="text_moderate">MODERATE</span></b></p>\n<p>Besides following the recommendations for MILD lack of appetite, you should also consider these tips:<br/></p>\n<p>Add details to your food log:<br/></p><ul>\n<li>When is your appetite poor? When is it good?</li>\n<li>Have you had nausea? Have you vomited?</li>\n<li>Have you had constipation or diarrhea?</li>\n<li>What is your weight? Jump on the scales once a week at the same time each day.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Nutrition:<br/></p><ul>\n<li>Eat calorie-rich foods such as milk shakes or liquid supplements between meals.</li>\n<li>Try using seasonings and spices on foods that you now find unpleasant. Basil, ginger, and rosemary can add flavor to meat, fish, or poultry.</li>\n<li>Sauces and gravies make swallowing easier.</li>\n<li>Try high-calorie supplements (Boost&#8482; or Ensure&#8482;) on their own or mixed with fruit or ice-cream. They can be filling, so try to eat your meal before taking them. Many people find it easier to sip them cold through a straw.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Medication:<br/></p><ul>\n<li>Take your prescribed anti-nausea medication 30-60 minutes before eating.</li>\n<li>Ask your doctor if it would help to take Megace&#174;, a hormone that improves your appetite.</li>\n<li>Other medications that your doctor may prescribe are corticosteroids, such as Dexamethasone, Methylprednisolone, or Prednisolone.</li>\n</ul>'),
(1003001006100001003, 'Lack of Appetite - Severe', '<p><b>Your lack of appetite is <span id="text_severe">SEVERE</span></b></p>\n<p>You are probably unable to manage your lack of appetite on your own. You should call your doctor and seek help.</p>\n<p>Read about <a href="index.php?seq=_003_001_006_200">how to talk to your doctor about your lack of appetite</a>.</p>'),
(1003001009100000000, 'Symptom No Trouble', '<div id="tc0" onclick="$(\'#tcrb0\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');report(\'0\',\'TC_NoProblem Constipation\');"><input id="tcrb0" type="radio" name="tc" value="0"/><label> I don\'t have constipation.</label></div>'),
(1003001009100000001, 'Symptom - TC1', '<div id="tc1" onclick="$(\'#tcrb1\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'mild_tab\',\'tab_item_mild\');report(\'2\',\'TC_Mild Constipation\');"><input id="tcrb1" type="radio" name="tc" value="1"/><label> Sometimes I am constipated and need to use stool softeners, laxatives, enemas or special foods to help move my bowels.</label></div>'),
(1003001009100000002, 'Symptom - TC2', '<div id="tc2" onclick="$(\'#tcrb2\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'moderate_tab\',\'tab_item_moderate\');report(\'5\',\'TC_Moderate Constipation\');"><input id="tcrb2" type="radio" name="tc" value="2"/><label> I am constipated most of the time and cannot have a bowel movement without regular use of laxatives or enemas.</label></div>'),
(1003001009100000003, 'Symptom - TC3', '<div id="tc3" onclick="$(\'#tcrb3\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'severe_tab\',\'tab_item_severe\');report(\'8\',\'TC_Severe Constipation\');"><input id="tcrb3" type="radio" name="tc" value="3"/><label> My constipation is so bad that I have not had a bowel movement in at least three days and I have a lot of stomach pain.</label></div>'),
(1003001009100001001, 'constipation - Mild', '<p><b>Your constipation is <span id="text_mild">MILD</span></b></p>\n<p>Here are management tips for you:</p>\n\n<p>Use a log to keep a record of what and how much you eat and drink, and any medication that you are taking.</p>\n\n<p>Nutrition:<br/></p><ul>\n<li>Eat 3 to 5 times a day. Drink 8 glasses of water or other non-caffeinated drinks a day (a total of about half a gallon). Avoid caffeine (colas, coffee, tea, energy drinks).</li>\n<li>Drink herbal tea, lemon water, or prune juice after meals.</li>\n<li>Eat foods high in fiber: well-washed raw vegetables, raisin bran, whole grain cereal, raisins, prunes, dates, and nuts.</li>\n<li>Add legumes to your meals: alfalfa, beans, soy beans, or peas.</li>\n<li>Avoid low-fiber foods: cheeses, meats, and processed foods.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Activities:<br/></p><ul>\n<li>Do mild physical activity (like walking) for at least 15 minutes every day.</li>\n<li>If you cannot walk, try moving your legs and torso (rotate, lift, or bend) for 15 minutes at least twice a day.</li>\n<li>When your body signals the need for a bowel movement, take action. Sit upright and take your time; do not strain or push. Have a quiet, comfortable bathroom environment.</li>\n</ul>'),
(1003001009100001002, 'constipation - Moderate', '<p><b>Your constipation is <span id="text_moderate">MODERATE</span></b></p>\n<p>Besides following the recommendations for MILD constipation, you should also consider these tips::<br/></p>\n\n<p>Activities:<br/></p><ul>\n<li>Use a log to keep a record of bowel movements, bloating, gas, or abdominal pain. Always make a note of the date and time, and write a description of your stool if possible. This will help your doctor evaluate your case and give you recommendations.</li>\n<li>Have a daily bathroom routine that includes privacy.</li>\n<li>Report any history of past bowel problems or abdominal surgeries.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Nutrition:<br/></p><ul>\n<li>Add fiber to your diet in the form of bran or wheat germ. Start with two teaspoons per day and gradually increase to two tablespoons per day. Always have your fiber with water.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Medication:<br/></p><ul>\n<li>Ask your doctor for a stool softener or a laxative. You can usually buy these over the counter, but your doctor will tell you which one is best and most likely to work for you.</li>\n<li>Do NOT use enemas or suppositories without talking to your doctor first.</li>\n</ul>'),
(1003001009100001003, 'constipation - Severe', '<p><b>Your constipation is <span id="text_severe">SEVERE</span></b></p>\n<p>You are probably unable to manage your constipation on your own. You should call your doctor and seek help.</p>\n<p>Do NOT use enemas or suppositories without talking to your doctor first. Read about <a href="index.php?seq=_003_001_009_200">how to talk to your doctor about your constipation</a>.</p>'),
(1003001015100000000, 'Depression No Trouble', '<div id="tc0" onclick="$(\'#tcrb0\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');report(\'0\',\'TC_NoProblem Depression\');"><input id="tcrb0" type="radio" name="tc" value="0"/><label>I don\'t feel depressed.</label></div>'),
(1003001015100000001, 'Depression - TC1', '<div id="tc1" onclick="$(\'#tcrb1\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'mild_tab\',\'tab_item_mild\');report(\'2\',\'TC_Mild Depression\');"><input id="tcrb1" type="radio" name="tc" value="1"/><label> I feel somewhat depressed, and it is starting to affect my daily life.</label></div>'),
(1003001015100000002, 'Depression - TC2', '<div id="tc2" onclick="$(\'#tcrb2\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'moderate_tab\',\'tab_item_moderate\');report(\'5\',\'TC_Moderate Depression\');"><input id="tcrb2" type="radio" name="tc" value="2"/><label>  I feel depressed much of the time, and it is making it difficult for me to get things done.</label></div>'),
(1003001015100000003, 'Depression - TC3', '<div id="tc3" onclick="$(\'#tcrb3\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'severe_tab\',\'tab_item_severe\');report(\'8\',\'TC_Severe Depression\');"><input id="tcrb3" type="radio" name="tc" value="3"/><label> I feel depressed all the time, and I\'m having thoughts of hurting myself.</label></div>'),
(1003001015100001001, 'Depression - Mild', '<p><b>Your depression is <span id="text_mild">MILD</span></b></p>\n<p>Here are some tips you may find helpful:</p>\n<ul> \n<li><b><u>Don\'t take naps</u></b> during the day so you can get enough sleep at night.</li> \n<li><b><u>Go outdoors and walk</u></b> in gardens and parks. Bring your dog, a friend, your partner, or family along.</li> \n<li><b><u>Exercise regularly:</u></b> Walk 20 minutes 3 to 5 times a week, for instance. Exercise improves your mood and your well-being.</li> \n<li>Alcohol can make you more depressed. <b><u>Try and avoid alcohol.</u></b></li> \n<li>Keep your strength up: <b><u>Eat nutritious foods.</u></b> Ask to see a dietician if you are having problems eating.</li> \n<li><b><u>Try meditation, massage, and relaxation exercises.</u></b> Music can help, too.</li> \n<li><b><u>Relax with other people. Find fun things to do</u></b> -- dance, cook, paint.</li> \n<li><b><u>Join a support group.</u></b> If you are depressed, don\'t go through it alone.</li> \n<li>Make a list of all the medications you are taking and show it to your healthcare providers. They may stop or change some medications. Only a healthcare provider should make changes to your medications. <u>Do not stop taking any of your medications without a healthcare provider\'s okay.</u></li> \n<li>Talk to your healthcare providers about counseling or taking medication for your depression.</li> \n<li>If your providers prescribe medication for your depression, <b><u>take your depression medication as directed.</u></b></li> \n</ul>\n');
INSERT INTO `texthtml` (`html_id`, `text`, `html`) VALUES
(1003001015100001002, 'Depression - Moderate', '<p><b>Your depression is <span id="text_moderate">MODERATE</span></b></p>\n<p>Here are some tips you may find helpful:</p>\n<ul> \n<li><b><u>Don\'t take naps</u></b> during the day so you can get enough sleep at night.</li> \n<li><b><u>Go outdoors and walk</u></b> in gardens and parks. Bring your dog, a friend, your partner, or family along.</li> \n<li><b><u>Exercise regularly:</u></b> Walk 20 minutes 3 to 5 times a week, for instance. Exercise improves your mood and your well-being.</li> \n<li>Alcohol can make you more depressed. <b><u>Try and avoid alcohol.</u></b></li> \n<li>Keep your strength up: <b><u>Eat nutritious foods.</u></b> Ask to see a dietician if you are having problems eating.</li> \n<li><b><u>Try meditation, massage, and relaxation exercises.</u></b> Music can help, too.</li> \n<li><b><u>Relax with other people. Find fun things to do</u></b> -- dance, cook, paint.</li> \n<li><b><u>Join a support group.</u></b> If you are depressed, don\'t go through it alone.</li> \n<li>Make a list of all the medications you are taking and show it to your healthcare providers. They may stop or change some medications. Only a healthcare provider should make changes to your medications. <u>Do not stop taking any of your medications without a healthcare provider\'s okay.</u></li> \n<li>Talk to your healthcare providers about counseling or taking medication for your depression.</li> \n<li>If your providers prescribe medication for your depression, <b><u>take your depression medication as directed.</u></b></li> \n</ul>\n'),
(1003001015100001003, 'Depression - Severe', '<p><b>Your depression is <span id="text_severe">SEVERE</span></b></p>\n<p>You are probably unable to manage your depression on your own. You should call your doctor and seek help.</p>\n<p>Read about <a href="index.php?seq=_003_001_015_200">how to talk to your doctor about your depression</a>.</p>'),
(1003001018100000000, 'Diarrhea No Trouble', '<div id="tc0" onclick="$(\'#tcrb0\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');report(\'0\',\'TC_NoProblem Diarrhea\');"><input id="tcrb0" type="radio" name="tc" value="0"/><label> I don\'t have diarrhea.</label></div>'),
(1003001018100000001, 'Diarrhea - TC1', '<div id="tc1" onclick="$(\'#tcrb1\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'mild_tab\',\'tab_item_mild\');report(\'2\',\'TC_Mild Diarrhea\');"><input id="tcrb1" type="radio" name="tc" value="1"/><label>  I am having between 1 and 3 more bowel movements than usual each day.</label></div>'),
(1003001018100000002, 'Diarrhea - TC2', '<div id="tc2" onclick="$(\'#tcrb2\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'moderate_tab\',\'tab_item_moderate\');report(\'5\',\'TC_Moderate Diarrhea\');"><input id="tcrb2" type="radio" name="tc" value="2"/><label> I am having between 4 and 6 more bowel movements than usual each day.</label></div>'),
(1003001018100000003, 'Diarrhea - TC3', '<div id="tc3" onclick="$(\'#tcrb3\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'severe_tab\',\'tab_item_severe\');report(\'8\',\'TC_Severe Diarrhea\');"><input id="tcrb3" type="radio" name="tc" value="3"/><label> I am having at least 7 more bowel movements than usual each day and I can\'t take care of myself.</label></div>'),
(1003001018100001001, 'diarrhea - Mild', '<p><b>Your diarrhea is <span id="text_mild">MILD</span></b></p>\n<p>Here are some management tips:</p>\n<p>Nutrition:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Try eating small, frequent meals (5 to 6 meals per day). Drink 8 glasses of water or other non-caffeinated beverages per day (a total of about half a gallon). Do not take caffeine (colas, coffee, black teas, or energy drinks).</li>\n<li>These foods will help: bananas, white rice, oats, applesauce, smooth peanut butter, white toast, plain pasta, eggs, cooked carrots, baked potatoes, chicken, and turkey.</li>\n<li>These fluids will help: soup, nonfat broth, orange juice, or sports drinks like Gatorade&#174;. You can also try diluted fruit juice (half juice, half water).</li>\n<li>Do not eat food that is high in fiber: cereals in general, raw fruits and green vegetables, or legumes.</li>\n<li>Do not eat fatty, spicy, or fried foods.</li>\n<li>Do not eat rich desserts.</li>\n<li>Avoid milk products (including ice cream and sour cream).</li>\n<li>Do not eat nuts or dried fruits.</li>\n<li>Do not eat sugar-free candy or sugar-free gum.</li>\n<li>Drink fluids at room temperature. Avoid hot liquids.</li>\n<li>Drink more fluids between meals and less with meals.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Self-care:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Clean the anus with unscented baby oil or baby wipes to prevent pain and soreness.</li>\n<li>Use baby wipes instead of toilet paper, and wipe gently.</li>\n</ul>'),
(1003001018100001002, 'diarrhea - Moderate', '<p><b>Your diarrhea is <span id="text_moderate">MODERATE</span></b></p>\n<p>Besides following the recommendations for MILD diarrhea, you should also consider these tips:<br/></p>\n<p>Useful activities:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Use a log to keep a record of bowel movements, bloating, gas, or abdominal pain. Include the number of bowel movements you have per day. Always make a note of the date and time, and write a description of your stool if possible. What size is it? What color? Do you notice any blood?</li>\n<li>Record any cramping or gas pains. This log will help you to talk to your doctor.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Self-care:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Take warm baths or sitz baths 3 or 4 times a day (a sitz is a tub in which one bathes in a sitting posture). Sit in the warm water for about 10 minutes.</li>\n<li>Use a thick, protective lotion like Desitin&#174; or A&D&#174; ointment on your anus after each bowel movement. <b>CAUTION:</b> If you are receiving radiation treatment to the abdomen, pelvis, or rectal area, talk to your doctor or nurse before using any creams or ointments.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Medication:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Imodium&#174; AD, Kaopectate&#174;, Pepto-Bismol&#174;, or Maalox&#174; antidiarrheal caplets (loperamide) can help. These are all over-the-counter, but <b>always consult with your doctor</b> before taking any medications. Your doctor will prescribe a different medication if over-the-counter products do not work for you.</li>\n</ul>'),
(1003001018100001003, 'diarrhea - Severe', '<p><b>Your diarrhea is <span id="text_severe">SEVERE</span></b></p>\n<p>You are probably unable to manage your diarrhea on your own. You should call your doctor and seek help.</p>\n<p>Read about <a href="index.php?seq=_003_001_018_200">how to talk to your doctor about your diarrhea</a>.</p>'),
(1003001021100000000, 'Anxiety No Trouble', '<div id="tc0" onclick="$(\'#tcrb0\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');report(\'0\',\'TC_NoProblem Anxiety\');"><input id="tcrb0" type="radio" name="tc" value="0"/><label>I don\'t feel anxious.</label></div>'),
(1003001021100000001, 'Anxiety - TC1', '<div id="tc1" onclick="$(\'#tcrb1\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'mild_tab\',\'tab_item_mild\');report(\'2\',\'TC_Mild Anxiety\');"><input id="tcrb1" type="radio" name="tc" value="1"/><label> I feel somewhat anxious, and it is starting to affect my daily life.</label></div>'),
(1003001021100000002, 'Anxiety - TC2', '<div id="tc2" onclick="$(\'#tcrb2\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'moderate_tab\',\'tab_item_moderate\');report(\'5\',\'TC_Moderate Anxiety\');"><input id="tcrb2" type="radio" name="tc" value="2"/><label>  I feel anxious much of the time, and it is making it difficult for me to get things done.</label></div>'),
(1003001021100000003, 'Anxiety - TC3', '<div id="tc3" onclick="$(\'#tcrb3\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'severe_tab\',\'tab_item_severe\');report(\'8\',\'TC_Severe Anxiety\');"><input id="tcrb3" type="radio" name="tc" value="3"/><label> I feel anxious all the time, and I\'m having thoughts of hurting myself.</label></div>'),
(1003001021100001001, 'Anxiety - Mild', '<p><b>Your anxiety is <span id="text_mild">MILD</span></b></p>\nHere are some tips you may find helpful:</p>\n<ul> \n<li>Try to identify what "triggers" your anxiety, and list any strategies that have helped in the past.</li> \n<li>Try doing some exercise, such as walking or yoga. It can help bring calm as it reduces tension.</li> \n<li>Limit your caffeine intake by decreasing your intake of coffee, soda pop, tea, and chocolate. </li> \n<li>Increase enjoyable activities such as listening to your favorite music. </li> \n<li>Be around others as much as possible, if this is relaxing.</li> \n<li>Use prayer or other types of spiritual support, such as meditation.</li> \n<li>Ask your doctor for a counseling referral if these tips are not helpful.</li> \n<li>Try keeping a journal of your life and experiences with cancer; it might reduce your anxiety.</li> \n</ul>\n'),
(1003001021100001002, 'Anxiety - Moderate', '<p><b>Your anxiety is <span id="text_moderate">MODERATE</span></b></p>\n<p>Besides following the recommendations for MILD anxiety, you should also consider these tips:<br/></p>\n<ul> \n<li><b><u>You may need medications to help control your anxiety.</u></b>  If medications are needed, they should fit your situation, taking into account your treatment and other medical conditions.</li>\n<li>Only your doctor can prescribe medications; talk to your doctor. </li> \n</ul>\n'),
(1003001021100001003, 'Anxiety - Severe', '<p><b>Your anxiety is <span id="text_severe">SEVERE</span></b></p>\r\n<p>You are probably unable to manage your anxiety on your own. You should call your doctor and seek help.</p>\r\n<p>Read about <a href="index.php?seq=_003_001_021_200">how to talk to your doctor about your anxiety</a>.</p>'),
(1003001027100000000, 'Fatigue No Trouble', '<div id="tc0" onclick="$(\'#tcrb0\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');report(\'0\',\'TC_NoProblem Fatigue\');"><input id="tcrb0" type="radio" name="tc" value="0"/><label> I don\'t have trouble with fatigue.</label></div>'),
(1003001027100000001, 'Fatigue - TC1', '<div id="tc1" onclick="$(\'#tcrb1\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'mild_tab\',\'tab_item_mild\');report(\'2\',\'TC_Mild Fatigue\');"><input id="tcrb1" type="radio" name="tc" value="1"/><label> I am a little more tired than usual but I am able to do my normal activities.</label></div>'),
(1003001027100000002, 'Fatigue - TC2', '<div id="tc2" onclick="$(\'#tcrb2\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'moderate_tab\',\'tab_item_moderate\');report(\'5\',\'TC_Moderate Fatigue\');"><input id="tcrb2" type="radio" name="tc" value="2"/><label> I am more tired than usual and have some trouble with normal activities.</label></div>'),
(1003001027100000003, 'Fatigue - TC3', '<div id="tc3" onclick="$(\'#tcrb3\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'severe_tab\',\'tab_item_severe\');report(\'8\',\'TC_Severe Fatigue\');"><input id="tcrb3" type="radio" name="tc" value="3"/><label> I am so tired that I have trouble taking care of myself.</label></div>'),
(1003001027100001001, 'fatigue - Mild', '<p><b>Your fatigue is <span id="text_mild">MILD</span></b></p>\n<p>Here are some management tips for you:</p>\n\n<p>Keep track of your fatigue:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Create a fatigue log. Keep a record of the pattern of your fatigue: dates, times, and level of fatigue.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Save your energy:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Plan rest periods during the day. Schedule nap and rest times. Naps of 20 minutes at a time can really help, especially in the late morning or early afternoon - but avoid evening naps.</li>\n<li>Use your bed for sleeping only. Do not lie in bed reading, watching television, or surfing the Internet. Avoid long periods of bed rest.</li>\n<li>There should be no background noise (music or television) while you are sleeping.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Set priorities:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Plan to do important activities around times when you usually have the most energy. This is early in the day for most people.</li>\n<li>Ask for help with tasks that you do not need to do yourself.</li>\n<li>Some activities have to be done; others are not strictly necessary. Focus on necessary tasks.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Nutrition:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Eat a diet of fresh fruits and vegetables, low-fat milk products, and lean meat, fish, or chicken. Ask your doctor to help with your diet.</li>\n<li>Do not eat foods that are high in fat.</li>\n<li>Eat healthy snacks between meals (fruit, cereal bars, or mixed nuts) to maintain your energy.</li>\n<li>Drink 8 glasses of water or other non-caffeinated drinks daily (a total of about half a gallon). Avoid caffeine (colas, coffee, black tea, energy drinks) as far as possible.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Physical activity:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Plan to do some kind of mild physical activity for at least 30 minutes a day. Always warm up and cool down for 5 minutes. If this is too much, begin with shorter periods and try to work up to 30 minutes a day.</li>\n<li>Do activities that you enjoy. These activities help to deal with fatigue:\n	<ul>\n	<li>Walk. Start with short distances. Increase your distance every month.</li>\n	<li>Ride a bike. Use a regular or a stationary bike.</li>\n	<li>Do strength training. Use weights or resistance bands. Ask your doctor for advice on how to do this activity or to recommend a specialist to help you with this.</li>\n	<li>Do flexibility training. Include stretching with warm-ups and cool-downs. Again, ask your doctor\'s advice in this.</li>\n	<li>Consider doing yoga or mind/body exercises like Qigong (breathing exercises) or Tai Chi.</li>\n	<li>Do sitting exercises that include moving your joints and lifting light weights. These are especially helpful if you feel that you cannot handle a great deal of physical activity.</li>\n	<li>If you can, simply spend time outside. You can do gardening or yard work, talk to your neighbors, watch your children, or walk in the park.</li>\n	</ul>\n</li>\n\n<li><b>Be cautious...</b>\n	<ul>\n	<li>...if you have severe anemia (low red-blood cell count). Do not do any physical activity until your anemia improves.</li>\n	<li>...if you have a weakened immune system (low white blood cell count or a fever). Do not go to public gyms or other public areas until your white blood cell count is safe and you have not had a fever for at least 24 hours.</li>\n	<li>...if you are receiving radiation. Avoid swimming pools: chlorine irritates the skin, especially in the area of your body that is being treated with radiation.</li>\n	</ul>\n</li>\n\n<p>Keep your mind away from your fatigue. You can use a variety of distractions: music, nature, or television, even for background noise. Learn relaxation therapy, art, or music therapy. Develop a routine before going to bed and follow it every night.</p>'),
(1003001027100001002, 'fatigue - Moderate', '<p><b>Your fatigue is <span id="text_moderate">MODERATE</span></b></p>\n<p>Besides following the recommendations for MILD fatigue, you should also consider these tips:</p>\n<p>Keep a more detailed log. Write down<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Your current level of fatigue</li>\n<li>When your fatigue first started, and how it has gotten worse since then</li>\n<li>What makes your fatigue better or worse, and how it increases or decreases in relation to the treatment for your cancer</li>\n<li>How your fatigue is affecting your daily activities: your work, your sleeping, and your eating patterns</li>\n<li>Join a support group. They will share your experience and concerns, and they can provide suggestions and reassurance in a safe environment.</li>\n</ul> '),
(1003001027100001003, 'fatigue - Severe', '<p><b>Your fatigue is <span id="text_severe">SEVERE</span></b></p>\n<p>You are probably unable to manage your fatigue on your own. You should call your doctor and seek help.</p>\n<p>Read about <a href="index.php?seq=_003_001_027_200">how to talk to your doctor about your fatigue</a>.</p>'),
(1003001039100000000, 'Mouth Sores No Trouble', '<div id="tc0" onclick="$(\'#tcrb0\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');report(\'0\',\'TC_NoProblem MouthSores\');"><input id="tcrb0" type="radio" name="tc" value="0"/><label> I don\'t have mouth sores.</label></div>'),
(1003001039100000001, 'Mouth Sores - TC1', '<div id="tc1" onclick="$(\'#tcrb1\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'mild_tab\',\'tab_item_mild\');report(\'2\',\'TC_Mild MouthSores\');"><input id="tcrb1" type="radio" name="tc" value="1"/><label>  I have mouth sores but haven\'t had to change my diet.</label></div>'),
(1003001039100000002, 'Mouth Sores - TC2', '<div id="tc2" onclick="$(\'#tcrb2\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'moderate_tab\',\'tab_item_moderate\');report(\'5\',\'TC_Moderate MouthSores\');"><input id="tcrb2" type="radio" name="tc" value="2"/><label> I am able to eat and swallow but my diet has changed because of my mouth sores.</label></div>'),
(1003001039100000003, 'Mouth Sores - TC3', '<div id="tc3" onclick="$(\'#tcrb3\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'severe_tab\',\'tab_item_severe\');report(\'8\',\'TC_Severe MouthSores\');"><input id="tcrb3" type="radio" name="tc" value="3"/><label> I cannot eat or swallow enough food and liquids because of my mouth sores, and I have lost more than 10 percent of my usual weight.</label></div>'),
(1003001039100001001, 'mouth sores - Mild', '<p><b>Your mouth sores are <span id="text_mild">MILD</span></b></p>\n<p>Here are some management tips for you:</p>\n\n<p>Taking care of your mouth:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Visit your dentist and have your teeth cleaned. Take care of cavities, gum disease or poorly fitting dentures. These practices keep mouth sores from getting worse.</li>\n<li>Before starting chemotherapy, ask your dentist to show you the best way to brush and floss your teeth. Use a very soft sponge or an oral sponge. Brush all tooth surfaces for at least 90 seconds.</li>\n<li>Brush your gums and tongue to reduce the risk of fungal infection.</li>\n<li>Brush your teeth after every meal and at bedtime. Use nonabrasive toothpaste without whiteners, which may cause irritation. Avoid flavors, such as mint.</li>\n<li>Floss gently everyday with unwaxed dental floss. Stop flossing if you experience any bleeding or have low blood cell counts.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Useful activities:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Get a new toothbrush every week. Do not use electric toothbrushes.</li>\n<li>Do not use mouth rinse products that contain alcohol or glycerin.</li>\n<li>Do not use liquid medications that contain alcohol, such as cough syrup.</li>\n<li>Use lip balm, Chapstick&#174;, or petroleum jelly if your lips become dry.</li>\n<li>Use a water-based mouth moisturizer (e.g. Biotene&#174; Oral Lubricant) to help keep your mouth moist.</li>\n<li>Ask your dentist about a daily fluoride rinse or gel to prevent tooth decay.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If you wear dentures:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>If you are receiving radiation treatment to the head or the neck, ask your doctor if it is safe to wear your dentures.</li>\n<li>Clean your dentures after every meal. Do not wear your dentures overnight.</li>\n<li>If your dentures do not fit properly, repair them or replace them.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Nutrition:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Drink 8 glasses of water or other non-caffeinated drinks daily (a total of about half a gallon).</li>\n<li>Avoid food that is very hot or spicy. Also avoid food with sharp edges such as crackers or potato chips.</li>\n<li>Avoid alcohol and tobacco.</li>\n<li>Eat popsicles or suck on ice cubes for moisture. Suck on non-irritating hard candy (sugar-free is best) and chew sugarless gum.</li>\n<li>Eat small, frequent meals.</li>\n<li>Add soft, soothing foods to your diet such as ice cream, shakes, baby foods, mashed potatoes, scrambled eggs, cottage cheese, custards, puddings, or gelatin. Also, use sauces or gravies to make foods easier to chew or swallow.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Medication:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Ask your doctor if you can take Tylenol&#174; or Ibuprofen for pain relief.</li>\n<li>If you have a dry mouth, try artificial saliva such as Oral Balance&#174;, Moist Plus&#174;, or Salivant&#174;. You can buy these without a prescription.</li>\n</ul>'),
(1003001039100001002, 'mouth sores - Moderate', '<p><b>Your mouth sores are <span id="text_moderate">MODERATE</span></b></p>\n<p>Besides following the recommendations for MILD mouth sores, you should also consider these tips:<br/></p>\n<p>Taking care of your mouth:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Rinse your mouth every two hours during the day and again if you wake up during the night. Mix your own mouth solution:</li>\n<li>1/2 teaspoon salt</li>\n<li>2 teaspoons baking soda</li>\n<li>4 cups water</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Shake or stir the solution and keep it for regular use. If you make more than a one-day supply, store the rest in your refrigerator in a tightly-sealed container.<br/></p>\n<p>Nutrition:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Cut down on salty food, tomatoes, and citrus (oranges, grapefruit, tangerines, and lemons).</li>\n<li>Grind up or puree food in a blender.</li>\n<li>If you are having trouble passing solid food, have liquid supplements instead: Carnation Instant Breakfast&#174;, Ensure&#174;, or Boost&#174;.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Medication:<br/></p>\n<p>Here are a few medications that will help:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Try pain-relieving over-the-counter medications like Orajel&#174;, Anbesol&#174;, Zilactin-b&#174;, or Orabase&#174;.</li>\n<li>Try Gelclair&#174;, a prescription medication to help soothe the pain, or Caphosol&#174;, a prescription mouth rinse that lubricates the mouth and throat.</li>\n<li>Your doctor may prescribe a combination mouthwash with a local anesthetic.</li>\n<li>Chemotherapy and radiation weaken the immune system. Ask your doctor if there is a specific medication that can help fight infections.</li>\n</ul>'),
(1003001039100001003, 'mouth sores  - Severe', '<p><b>Your mouth sores are <span id="text_severe">SEVERE</span></b></p>\n<p>You are probably unable to manage your mouth sores on your own. You should call your doctor and seek help.</p>\n<p>Read about <a href="index.php?seq=_003_001_039_200">how to talk to the doctor about your mouth sores</a>.</p>'),
(1003001042100000000, 'Nausea No Trouble', '<div id="tc0" onclick="$(\'#tcrb0\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');report(\'0\',\'TC_NoProblem Nausea\');"><input id="tcrb0" type="radio" name="tc" value="0"/><label> I don\'t have nausea.</label></div>'),
(1003001042100000001, 'Nausea - TC1', '<div id="tc1" onclick="$(\'#tcrb1\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'mild_tab\',\'tab_item_mild\');report(\'2\',\'TC_Mild Nausea\');"><input id="tcrb1" type="radio" name="tc" value="1"/><label> I have vomited once in 24 hours.</label></div>'),
(1003001042100000002, 'Nausea - TC2', '<div id="tc2" onclick="$(\'#tcrb2\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'moderate_tab\',\'tab_item_moderate\');report(\'5\',\'TC_Moderate Nausea\');"><input id="tcrb2" type="radio" name="tc" value="2"/><label> I have vomited between 2 and 5 times in 24 hours.</label></div>'),
(1003001042100000003, 'Nausea - TC3', '<div id="tc3" onclick="$(\'#tcrb3\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'severe_tab\',\'tab_item_severe\');report(\'8\',\'TC_Severe Nausea\');"><input id="tcrb3" type="radio" name="tc" value="3"/><label> I have vomited 6 or more times in 24 hours and I am feeling light-headed.</label></div>'),
(1003001042100001001, 'nausea - Mild', '<p><b>Your nausea is <span id="text_mild">MILD</span></b></p>\n<p>Here are some management tips for you:<br/></p>\n<p>Useful activities:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Try to move as little as possible when you feel nauseous. Always keep your head elevated. Rest in a chair after eating, and get plenty of rest in general.</li>\n<li>The aftertaste of food can add to your nausea. Brush your teeth after meals and use mouthwashes that do not contain alcohol to improve the taste in your mouth.</li>\n<li>You should try and be as comfortable as possible. For example, wear loose-fitting clothes. Play your favorite music; it will soothe and provide distraction. Make sure there is fresh air around the house by turning on a fan or keeping a window open.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Nutrition:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Drink 8 glasses of water per day (a total of about half a gallon). Wait for at least 2 hours after a vomiting episode before taking any fluids. Sip slowly.</li>\n<li>Ginger products tend to calm the stomach - for example, ginger ale or ginger tea.</li>\n<li>Do not force yourself to eat. Focus on eating slowly instead.</li>\n<li>Many people find that they have an easier time eating early in the day. Make the most of this time by having a healthy breakfast.</li>\n<li>Do not eat large meals. Five or six small, frequent meals during the day work best.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Here are a number of recommended foods:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Cool or cold foods are sometimes more appealing than hot foods. Try Jell-O, cottage or ricotta cheese, pudding, sherbet, popsicles, cold sandwiches, and pasta or potato salad.</li>\n<li>Try to eat dry or bland food such as crackers, bagels, toast, cereal, yogurt, cookies, ice, pretzels, and skinless cooked chicken.</li>\n<li>Gum or hard candy can also help.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Avoid<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Heavy, spicy, fried, or fatty foods</li>\n<li>Very sweet or very salty foods</li>\n<li>Gas-producing vegetables (broccoli, cauliflower, cucumbers, green peppers, Brussels sprouts, sauerkraut)</li>\n<li>Acidic foods (salsa, tomatoes, vinegar, citrus fruits, and citrus fruit juices)</li>\n<li>Alcoholic beverages</li>\n<li>Food aromas and other strong odors</li>\n</ul>'),
(1003001042100001002, 'nausea - Moderate', '<p><b>Your nausea is <span id="text_moderate">MODERATE</span></b></p>\r\n<p>Besides following the recommendations for MILD nausea, you should also consider these tips:<br/></p>\r\n<p>Try therapies and techniques that can help, such as acupuncture, acupressure, guided imagery, hypnosis, music therapy, muscle relaxation, or counseling, support, and structured educational interventions.<br/></p>\r\n<p>Medication:<br/></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>If your doctor prescribes anti-nausea medication, take it 30-60 minutes before your oral chemotherapy.</li>\r\n<li>Take your anti-nausea medication before meals to help keep your food down.</li>\r\n<li>Here are some examples of common anti-nausea medications:\r\n	<ul>\r\n	<li>Ondansetron (Zofran&#174;): prevents nausea before it begins</li>\r\n	<li>Aprepitant (Emend&#174;): stops nausea/vomiting after a first episode</li>\r\n	<li>Dexamethasone: usually combined with Ondansetron for a more powerful effect</li>\r\n	</ul></li>\r\n</ul>'),
(1003001042100001003, 'nausea - Severe', '<p><b>Your nausea is <span id="text_severe">SEVERE</span></b></p>\n<p>You are probably unable to manage your nausea on your own. You should call your doctor and seek help.</p>\n<p>Read about <a href="index.php?seq=_003_001_042_200">how to talk to your doctor about your nausea</a>.</p>'),
(1003001048100000000, 'Numbness No Trouble', '<div id="tc0" onclick="$(\'#tcrb0\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');report(\'0\',\'TC_NoProblem Numbness\');"><input id="tcrb0" type="radio" name="tc" value="0"/><label> I don\'t have numbness or tingling.</label></div>'),
(1003001048100000001, 'Numbness - TC1', '<div id="tc1" onclick="$(\'#tcrb1\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'mild_tab\',\'tab_item_mild\');report(\'2\',\'TC_Mild Numbness\');"><input id="tcrb1" type="radio" name="tc" value="1"/><label> I have a little numbness and tingling but it hasn\'t kept me from doing things.</label></div>'),
(1003001048100000002, 'Numbness - TC2', '<div id="tc2" onclick="$(\'#tcrb2\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'moderate_tab\',\'tab_item_moderate\');report(\'5\',\'TC_Moderate Numbness\');"><input id="tcrb2" type="radio" name="tc" value="2"/><label> I have some numbness and tingling that keeps me from doing some things, but I can take care of myself.</label></div>'),
(1003001048100000003, 'Numbness - TC3', '<div id="tc3" onclick="$(\'#tcrb3\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'severe_tab\',\'tab_item_severe\');report(\'8\',\'TC_Severe Numbness\');"><input id="tcrb3" type="radio" name="tc" value="3"/><label> I have significant numbness and tingling that keeps me from doing most things.</label></div>'),
(1003001048100001001, 'numbness and tingling - Mild', '<p><b>Your numbness and tingling is <span id="text_mild">MILD</span></b></p>\n<p>Here are some management tips for you:</p>\n<p>Environmental safety:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>You need to make every effort to avoid falls. Pay close attention when you walk; slow down and concentrate on your movements. Wear sturdy shoes; do not wear slippers or running shoes with thick soles. Avoid wet or slippery floors, and put a rubber mat on the floor of the bathroom, tub, and shower.</li>\n<li>Always turn on the lights before you enter a room, no matter how familiar you are with it. Keep rooms bright enough so that you can see all the areas where you need to walk or do other activities. Keep a night light in your room and along the path you walk if you get up during the night.</li>\n<li>Arrange your furniture so that you have a clear pathway. Remove clutter or unnecessary rugs from the floor to prevent falls.</li>\n<li>Use soap dispensers instead of soap bars that can easily slip out of your hands. If you are having trouble feeling changes in temperature, use a non-breakable water thermometer to check your bath or dishwater temperature before you bathe or wash dishes to make sure that the water is no hotter than 100&#176;F (43.3&#176;C). Also, wear rubber gloves to prevent damage when washing the dishes or doing other housework and gardening.</li>\n<li>Avoid sudden chilling. Do not reach into a refrigerator or freezer. Avoid air conditioning in the summer, drinking ice cold drinks, eating ice cream or other cold foods, and cold showers.</li>\n<li>Pay special attention when trimming your toenails; you may not feel small cuts on your toes. Check your skin daily for burns and cuts: carefully inspect your arms, legs, fingers, and toes.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Useful activities:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>You should continue to do physical activity as usual, especially walking and swimming.</li>\n<li>If you have pain, massage the affected area or try deep breathing and relaxation.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Nutrition:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Drink 8 glasses of water daily (a total of about half a gallon).</li>\n<li>Avoid very cold beverages, chewing ice, or using straws.</li>\n<li>Eat a high fiber diet with fruits, vegetables, and whole grains.</li>\n</ul>'),
(1003001048100001002, 'numbness and tingling - Moderate', '<p><b>Your numbness and tingling is <span id="text_moderate">MODERATE</span></b></p>\n<p>Besides following the recommendations for MILD numbness and tingling above, you should also consider these tips:</p>\n<p>Environmental safety:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Install tub or shower handgrips.</li>\n<li>Use a cane or a walker if you feel week or unsteady when walking.</li>\n<li>Wear gloves or a scarf when opening the refrigerator or going into an air-conditioned room.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Useful activities:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>If you decide to have a manicure or a pedicure, ask your doctor to recommend a professional.</li>\n</ul>'),
(1003001048100001003, 'numbness and tingling - Severe', '<p><b>Your numbness and tingling is <span id="text_severe">SEVERE</span></b></p>\n<p>You are probably unable to manage your numbness/tingling on your own. You should call your doctor and seek help.</p><p>Read about <a href="index.php?seq=_003_001_048_200">how to talk to your doctor about your numbness and tingling</a>.</p>'),
(1003001051100000000, 'Pain No Trouble', '<div id="tc0" onclick="$(\'#tcrb0\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');report(\'0\',\'TC_NoProblem Pain\');"><input id="tcrb0" type="radio" name="tc" value="0"/><label> I don\'t have pain.</label></div>'),
(1003001051100000001, 'Pain - TC1', '<div id="tc1" onclick="$(\'#tcrb1\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'mild_tab\',\'tab_item_mild\');report(\'2\',\'TC_Mild Pain\');"><input id="tcrb1" type="radio" name="tc" value="1"/><label> I have some pain but it doesn\'t keep me from doing my normal activities.</label></div>'),
(1003001051100000002, 'Pain - TC2', '<div id="tc2" onclick="$(\'#tcrb2\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'moderate_tab\',\'tab_item_moderate\');report(\'5\',\'TC_Moderate Pain\');"><input id="tcrb2" type="radio" name="tc" value="2"/><label> My pain keeps me from doing some things, but I can take care of myself.</label></div>'),
(1003001051100000003, 'Pain - TC3', '<div id="tc3" onclick="$(\'#tcrb3\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'severe_tab\',\'tab_item_severe\');report(\'8\',\'TC_Severe Pain\');"><input id="tcrb3" type="radio" name="tc" value="3"/><label> My pain is so bad that I can\'t take care of myself.</label></div>'),
(1003001051100001001, 'pain - Mild', '<p><b>Your pain is <span id="text_mild">MILD</span></b></p>\n<p>Here are some management tips for you:</p>\n<p>Useful activities:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Apply heat or cold on the area of pain. Always wrap your heating pad or ice pack in a towel to protect your skin.</li>\n<li>Use pillows to keep pressure off the area of pain.</li>\n<li>Practice deep breathing exercises and relaxation techniques.</li>\n<li>Perform mild exercise, especially swimming or walking.</li>\n<li>Get a massage.</li>\n<li>Try to distract yourself by watching TV or listening to music.</li>\n<li>Keep a pain log to bring with you to the doctor. Note details about<ul>\n	<li>How long the pain lasts</li>\n	<li>What seems to make it worse</li>\n	<li>What helps to relieve the pain (heat, ice, or medication)</li>\n	<li>If you are taking medication, how long it takes for the pain to go away</li>\n	</ul></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Over-the-counter Medication:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Try a common pain reliever, such as aspirin, Tylenol&#174;, Advil&#174;, Ibuprofen&#174;, or Motrin&#174;. Take these precautions:\n	<ul>\n	<li>Do not wait until your pain is severe to take your medication. Take your pain medication exactly as prescribed.</li>\n	<li>Do not crush or break your pain pills unless you check with your doctor.</li>\n	<li>Pain medication can make you dizzy, drowsy, or sleepy. Do not drive or operate any equipment until you are sure what effects the medication has on you.</li>\n	</ul></li>\n<li>Keep at least a one-week supply of pain medication on hand. Call your doctor in good time to refill your prescription.</li>\n<li>Pain medication should not be stopped suddenly; it needs to be decreased little by little. Talk to your doctor about how to decrease the dose if you think you no longer need pain medication.</li>\n</ul>'),
(1003001051100001002, 'pain - Moderate', '<p><b>Your pain is <span id="text_moderate">MODERATE</span></b></p>\n<p>Besides following the recommendations for MILD pain, you should also consider these tips:<br/></p>\n<p>Many people believe they can become addicted to pain medication. Do not be afraid. This problem is very rare in cancer patients. Here are a few pain medications that your doctor may prescribe:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Codeine</li>\n<li>Oxycodone/OxyContin</li>\n<li>Hydrocodone</li>\n<li>Morphine</li>\n<li>Hydromorphone/Dilaudid</li>\n<li>Methadone</li>\n<li>Fentanyl</li>\n<li>Certain steroids, antidepressants, and anti-seizure medications</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Your doctor may also recommend one or more of these therapies:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Acupuncture</li>\n<li>Physical therapy</li>\n<li>Occupational therapy</li>\n<li>Transcutaneous Electrical Nerve Stimulation (TENS). This involves applying gentle electric current to the skin to relieve pain.</li>\n<li>Counseling or support groups</li>\n</ul>'),
(1003001051100001003, 'pain - Severe', '<p><b>Your pain is <span id="text_severe">SEVERE</span></b></p>\n<p>You are probably unable to manage your pain on your own. You should call your doctor and seek help.</p>\n<p>Read about <a href="index.php?seq=_003_001_051_200">how to talk to your doctor about your pain</a>.</p>'),
(1003001060100000000, 'Rash - No Trouble', '<div id="tc0" onclick="$(\'#tcrb0\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');report(\'0\',\'TC_NoProblem Rash\');"><input id="tcrb0" type="radio" name="tc" value="0"/><label> I don\'t have a rash.</label></div>'),
(1003001060100000001, 'Rash - TC1', '<div id="tc1" onclick="$(\'#tcrb1\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'mild_tab\',\'tab_item_mild\');report(\'2\',\'TC_Mild Rash\');"><input id="tcrb1" type="radio" name="tc" value="1"/><label> I have a red rash, but it doesn\'t itch or hurt. (Mild)</label></div>'),
(1003001060100000002, 'Rash - TC2', '<div id="tc2" onclick="$(\'#tcrb2\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'moderate_tab\',\'tab_item_moderate\');report(\'5\',\'TC_Moderate Rash\');"><input id="tcrb2" type="radio" name="tc" value="2"/><label> My red rash covers less than half my body and itches or hurts with some peeling. (Moderate)</label></div>'),
(1003001060100000003, 'Rash - TC3', '<div id="tc3" onclick="$(\'#tcrb3\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'severe_tab\',\'tab_item_severe\');report(\'8\',\'TC_Severe Rash\');"><input id="tcrb3" type="radio" name="tc" value="3"/><label> My red rash covers more than half my body and itches or hurts with blisters, peeling, and lots of oozing fluids. (Severe)</label></div>'),
(1003001060100001001, 'Rash - Mild', '<p><b>Your rash is <span id="text_mild">MILD</span></b></p>\n<p>Here are some management tips for you:</p>\n<p>Skin and nail care:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Use a mild moisturizing soap without perfumes. Examples include Dove&#174;, Ivory&#174; Skin Cleansing Liquid Gel, Cetaphil&#174;, Neutrogena&#174;, and Aveeno&#174;. You can also use baby shampoos and body washes. Always check the label to make sure the soap you are buying is perfume free.</li>\n<li>Do not use lotions, creams, shampoos, soaps, or aftershaves that contain alcohol, or dyes. Moisturize your skin, especially at your finger and toenails, with dye and alcohol-free lotions such as Eucerin&#174; Cream, Cetaphil&#174; Cream, Udder&#174; Cream, Zim\'s&#174; Crack Cr&#233;me, Aquaphor&#174; Ointment, Vanicream&#174;, Neutrogena&#174;, or Vaseline&#174; Intensive Care. Treat itchy skin with these lotions as well.</li>\n<li>Your skin will tend to be dry; take quick, warm showers instead of long, hot baths. When you wash and dry your skin, pat the area gently with a clean, soft towel or a washcloth, and never rub. Apply creams or lotions after your bath, while your skin is still moist.</li>\n<li>Do not expose your skin to extreme temperatures. Do not use ice packs, heating pads, or electric blankets.</li>\n<li>Keep your nails clean and cut short.</li>\n<li>Dust your body with cornstarch, especially in the folds of your skin behind your knees and under your arms or breasts.</li>\n<li>Shave less often. Do not shave at all if your skin is sore.</li>\n<li>Wear strong gloves to avoid skin contact with harsh chemicals when cleaning. Wear light cotton gloves when gardening or doing outdoor work. Put on rubber or latex gloves before washing dishes.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Sun care:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Stay out of the sun as much as possible.</li>\n<li>Wear sunscreen (SPF 30 or greater) every day, even on cloudy days.</li>\n<li>In addition to using sunscreen, wear a hat, a long-sleeved shirt, and pants for greater protection from the sun.</li>\n<li>Do not use tanning beds.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Clothing:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Wear loose-fitting, soft cotton clothing.</li>\n<li>Do not wash your clothes with perfumed laundry detergent. Wash those clothes that come in direct contact with your skin in mild Deft&#174; or Tide&#174; hypoallergenic detergents. Always read the label to make sure you are buying the correct type of detergent.</li>\n<li>If elastic bands from underclothing rub painfully on the rash, use one of the moisturizing lotions listed under "skin care," and cover with a nonstick gauze pad, such as Telfa&#174;.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Nutrition:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Drink eight glasses of water or other non-caffeinated drinks daily (a total of about half a gallon).</li>\n<li>Avoid caffeine (colas, coffee, black tea, energy drinks), as caffeine causes dehydration.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Medication:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>If your itching is mild and localized, use a topical antihistamine cream like Benadryl&#174;.</li>\n<li>If your itching is severe, use an oral antihistamine drug such as Benadryl&#174;, Claritin&#174;, or Allegra&#174;.</li>\n<li>If your rash hurts, your doctor may prescribe oral pain medications.</li>\n</ul>'),
(1003001060100001002, 'Rash - Moderate', '<p><b>Your rash is <span id="text_moderate">MODERATE</span></b></p>\r\n<p>Besides following the recommendations for MILD rash above, you should also consider these tips:<br/></p>\r\n<p>Record any details about the characteristics of your rash in a diary. Write down:<br/></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>when the rash first started and how it has got worse since it first began</li>\r\n<li>what makes it better and what does not seem to work</li>\r\n<li>how the rash gets worse or better in relation to your cancer treatment</li>\r\n<li>any current prescriptions or over-the-counter medications you are taking</li>\r\n<li>your drug allergies, including any reactions you have ever had to medications</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Skin and nail care:<br/></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Oatmeal lotions or sesame oil may help.</li>\r\n<li>For inflammation around your fingernails, soak your fingertips for 5 minutes once a day in a solution of white vinegar diluted 1:10 (one part vinegar, 10 parts tap water).</li>\r\n<li>Use Band-Aid&#174; brand Liquid Bandage, Bag&#174; Balm, and Zim\'s&#174; Crack Cream for cracks and fissures in the skin around the nails.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Medication:</p>\r\n<p>Ask your doctor what kind of medication is right for you. The doctor may prescribe one or more of the following medications:<br/></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Topical gels to decrease pain, such as RadiaPlex and Cool Magic Gel Sheets (best kept cool in the refrigerator)</li>\r\n<li>Topical antibiotic creams, such as Clindamycin and Erythromycin</li>\r\n<li>Steroids taken in pill form, such as Prednisone</li>\r\n<li>Antibiotics (if the rash shows signs of infection) in pill form, such as Tetracycline, Minocycline, Doxycycline, Trimethoprim, or Sulfamethoxazole</li>\r\n<li>Topical ammonium lactate lotions for itching, such as LacHydrin&#174; or Am-Hyrdin&#174; </li>\r\n</ul>'),
(1003001060100001003, 'Rash - Severe', '<p><b>Your rash is <span id="text_severe">SEVERE</span></b></p>\n<p>You are probably unable to manage your rash on your own. You should call your doctor and seek help.</p>\n<p>Read about <a href="index.php?seq=_003_001_060_200">how to talk to your doctor about your rash</a>.</p>'),
(1003001069100000000, 'Breath No Trouble', '<div id="tc0" onclick="$(\'#tcrb0\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');report(\'0\',\'TC_NoProblem Breath\');"><input id="tcrb0" type="radio" name="tc" value="0"/><label> I don\'t have shortness of breath.</label></div>'),
(1003001069100000001, 'Breath - TC1', '<div id="tc1" onclick="$(\'#tcrb1\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'mild_tab\',\'tab_item_mild\');report(\'2\',\'TC_Mild Breath\');"><input id="tcrb1" type="radio" name="tc" value="1"/><label> I get short of breath with activity but can walk up one flight of stairs without stopping.</label></div>'),
(1003001069100000002, 'Breath - TC2', '<div id="tc2" onclick="$(\'#tcrb2\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'moderate_tab\',\'tab_item_moderate\');report(\'5\',\'TC_Moderate Breath\');"><input id="tcrb2" type="radio" name="tc" value="2"/><label> I get short of breath with activity and I can\'t walk up one flight of stairs without stopping.</label></div>'),
(1003001069100000003, 'Breath - TC3', '<div id="tc3" onclick="$(\'#tcrb3\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'severe_tab\',\'tab_item_severe\');report(\'8\',\'TC_Severe Breath\');"><input id="tcrb3" type="radio" name="tc" value="3"/><label> I get short of breath at rest.</label></div>'),
(1003001069100001001, 'breath - Mild', '<p><b>Your shortness of breath is <span id="text_mild">MILD</span></b></p>\n<p>Here are some management tips for you:</p>\n<p>Useful activities:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>When you are short of breath, try opening a window or turning on a fan.</li>\n<li>Do not lie flat on your back. Sit upright (to at least a 45&#176; angle) and prop your head up with pillows. Apply a cool washcloth on your cheeks or forehead. If you are standing, lean forward with your forearms resting on a table or on your knees.</li>\n<li>On a regular basis, meditate or talk to someone to reduce stress and anxiety. Do mild physical activity, if you can. Do not smoke, and avoid being around those who smoke. Wear loose-fitting clothing that is easy to put on. Avoid warm temperatures, unpleasant odors, or fumes.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Deep-breathing technique:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Remain calm. Breathe in through your nose for a count of two. Purse your lips as though you are going to blow out a match or candle, and breathe out through pursed lips for a count of four. Repeat these steps until your shortness of breath is relieved.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Energy conservation:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Plan your day\'s activities carefully. Do important activities early in the day. Do not do unnecessary activities; save energy. </li>\n<li>Shower, shave, brush your teeth, or comb your hair while sitting down.</li>\n<li>Pace yourself during activities, and take multiple rest periods. Take your time when climbing stairs, and match your breaths to the steps you take. Take the elevator when possible.</li>\n<li>Wear slip-on shoes and move slowly.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Nutrition:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Drink 8 glasses of water every day (a total of about half a gallon).</li>\n<li>Eat five to six small meals per day rather than three large meals.</li>\n<li>Plan meals that are easy to make, such as salads or cooked legumes.</li>\n<li>Avoid foods that are difficult to chew.</li>\n</ul>'),
(1003001069100001002, 'shortness of breath - Moderate', '<p><b>Your shortness of breath is <span id="text_moderate">MODERATE</span></b></p>\n<p>Besides following the recommendations for MILD shortness of breath, you should also consider these tips:<br/></p>\n<p>Useful activities:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Do not bend over to pick things up from the floor; use special reaching devices.</li>\n<li>Use a wheelchair as needed.</li>\n<li>Use oxygen as prescribed by your doctor.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Nutrition:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Consider food services such as Meals on Wheels so you will not have to prepare the food yourself.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Medication:<br/></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Take medications for your shortness of breath as prescribed by your doctor.</li>\n</ul>'),
(1003001069100001003, 'shortness of breath - Severe', '<p><b>Your shortness of breath is <span id="text_severe">SEVERE</span></b></p>\n<p>You are probably unable to manage your shortness of breath on your own. You should call your doctor and seek help.</p>\n<p>Read about <a href="index.php?seq=_003_001_069_200">how to talk to your doctor about your shortness of breath</a>.</p>'),
(1003001072100000000, 'Sleep No Trouble', '<div id="tc0" onclick="$(\'#tcrb0\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');report(\'0\',\'TC_NoTrouble Sleep\');"><input id="tcrb0" type="radio" name="tc" value="0"/><label> I don\'t have sleeping problems.</label></div>'),
(1003001072100000001, 'Sleep - TC1', '<div id="tc1" onclick="$(\'#tcrb1\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'mild_tab\',\'tab_item_mild\');report(\'2\',\'TC_Mild Sleep\');"><input id="tcrb1" type="radio" name="tc" value="1"/><label> I sometimes have trouble sleeping, but it doesn\'t keep me from doing my normal activities.</label></div>'),
(1003001072100000002, 'Sleep - TC2', '<div id="tc2" onclick="$(\'#tcrb2\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'moderate_tab\',\'tab_item_moderate\');report(\'5\',\'TC_Moderate Sleep\');"><input id="tcrb2" type="radio" name="tc" value="2"/><label> I am having trouble sleeping and it keeps me from doing some things, but I can do most of my normal activities.</label></div>'),
(1003001072100000003, 'Sleep - TC3', '<div id="tc3" onclick="$(\'#tcrb3\').attr(\'checked\',\'checked\');set_symptom_tab(\'severe_tab\',\'tab_item_severe\');report(\'8\',\'TC_Severe Sleep\');"><input id="tcrb3" type="radio" name="tc" value="3"/><label> I have a lot of trouble sleeping, and it\'s keeping me from doing many of my normal activities.</label></div>');
INSERT INTO `texthtml` (`html_id`, `text`, `html`) VALUES
(1003001072100001001, 'sleeping problem - Mild', '<p><b>Your sleeping problem is <span id="text_mild">MILD</span></b></p>\n<p>Here are some management tips for you:</p>\n<p>Useful activities:</br></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Develop a sleeping routine. Try taking a warm bath an hour before bedtime. Go to bed and awake at the same time every day. If you take a nap during the day, make sure you do before 3:00PM, and do not sleep for more than 30 minutes.</li>\n<li>Make sure you are comfortable. If you are experiencing pain from your cancer or your treatment, try to deal with the pain by bedtime. Avoid watching television in the bedroom, as well as eating or reading in bed. Keep your bedroom temperature constant. Replace old mattresses and pillows. Go to another room when you cannot fall asleep in your bedroom.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Physical activity:</br></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Do some mild physical activity at least 3 hours before bedtime: Take a walk around the block, do some household chores, work in the garden, play with your children, or practice yoga.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Nutrition:</br></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Eat a high-protein snack two hours before bedtime. If you are hungry at bedtime, eat a small healthy snack with warm milk.</li>\n<li>Do not have coffee, colas, black tea, or energy drinks after noontime.</li>\n<li>Do not drink alcohol.</li>\n<li>Do not have any fluids before bedtime.</li>\n<li>Do not eat large meals in the evening.</li>\n<li>Do not eat rich, spicy, or sugary foods in the evening. </li>\n<li>Do not smoke. Nicotine is a stimulant.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Use distractions:</br></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Try mood music (nature sounds, ocean waves, etc.) to filter out noises, especially at bedtime.</li>\n<li>Practice meditation or deep breathing techniques.</li>\n</ul>'),
(1003001072100001002, 'sleeping problem - Moderate', '<p><b>Your sleeping problem is <span id="text_moderate">MODERATE</span></b></p>\n<p>Besides following the recommendations for MILD sleeping problems, you should also consider these tips:</p>\n<p>Keep a sleep diary. Record:</br></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The times when you fall asleep and wake up, including nap times</li>\n<li>When your sleeping problem started, and if it has gotten worse</li>\n<li>What seems to make your sleeping problem better or worse</li>\n<li>How your sleeping problem is affecting your daily activities</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Medication:</br></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Common medications for sleep are hypnotics, benzodiazepines, antihistamines, and antidepressants. Follow the directions of your prescribed sleep medication very carefully.</li>\n<li>Make sure your doctor has a current list of all the prescriptions, over-the-counter medications, vitamins, minerals, and herbal remedies that you are taking.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Complementary therapies:</br></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Common therapies for sleeping problems are expressive therapy, expressive writing, massage therapy, muscle relaxation, mindfulness-based stress reduction (MBSR), and yoga.</li>\n<li>You can try joining a support group. These groups can provide emotional support for any concerns or worries you may have about your sleeping problems, or about your diagnosis or treatment in general.</li>\n</ul>'),
(1003001072100001003, 'sleeping problem - Severe', '<p><b>Your sleeping problem is <span id="text_severe">SEVERE</span></b></p>\n<p>You are probably unable to manage your sleeping problem on your own. You should call your doctor and seek help.</p>\n<p>Read about <a href="index.php?seq=_003_001_072_200">how to talk to your doctor about your sleeping problems</a>.</p>'),
