(100100104, 'Welcome', 'Welcome to The Burdette Cancer Portal Information, Resources, and Tools for People Dealing With Cancer. We know that thinking about cancer can be worrisome. The good news is that today there are more than 10 million cancer survivors. We are fortunate for scientific advances in the prevention, detection, and treatment of cancer, but so much information and research can be hard to understand. We have designed this Web site to help answer your questions about cancer whether you or a family member have just been diagnosed with cancer or you want to learn about how to reduce your chance of getting cancer. \nThis site is a collaboration between the Indiana University Melvin and Bren Simon Cancer Center, Walther Cancer Foundation, and the Indiana University schools of nursing, informatics, and medicine. ...more  '),
(100100204, 'About the Portal', 'About The Portal Dr. Harold Burdette The late Dr. Harold Burdette devoted his life to the practice of medicine with a special focus on cancer. He began a collaboration with Dr. Joseph Walther in 1948 when they joined forces to start the Memorial Clinic, which was located in Indianapolis. He was appointed to the board of directors of the Walther Cancer Institute (now known as the Walther Cancer Foundation) in 1990 and established the Burdette-Kunkel endowment for direct support of research contributing to a greater understanding of how patients and their families respond to the physical and emotional effects of cancer and its treatment. His practice of medicine and support of behavioral research was a direct result of a core belief that a patient\'s environment, behaviors, and family play a major role in health outcomes. Dr. Burdette\'s support of oncology research was also based on his belief that prevention and early detection are the cornerstones in our fight against cancer morbidity and mortality. The majority of research now taking place in the Cancer Control and Prevention Program of the Indiana University Melvin and Bren Simon Cancer Center was directly supported through endowment funds from the Mary Margaret Walther research program of the Walther Cancer Institute in Indianapolis. Dr. Burdette was the major leader and board supporter of developing and sustaining this important effort.\n The Burdette Cancer Portal is a site dedicated to providing information and education about cancer to everyone, and especially to those impacted by cancer, either as a cancer patient, a caregiver for a cancer patient, or a loved one of a cancer patient. Much of the inspiration for the Burdette Cancer Portal has come from the Mary Margaret Walther Program for Cancer Care Research of the IU School of Nursing.  The Program is formed around behavioral research in the following areas: Prevention and early detection of cancer Management of symptoms and side effects of cancer treatment at diagnosis Long-term survivorship issues Problems patients and families face with advanced cancer Scientists and researchers connected to the Walther Program formed the Behavioral Cooperative Oncology Group (BCOG)/Center for Symptom Management.  The BCOG group fosters collaboration among researchers and health care practitioners in the Midwest region.  BCOG\'s work in the field of symptom management research is the basis for much of the information you will find in the symptom management section of this site. The Burdette Cancer Portal is an effort to take the findings of the BCOG group and provide a platform to foster development and translation of symptom management research to cancer patients and their families.  It is hoped that the information provided by the portal will be accessible to as many people as possible, and that the the ways people find and use the information will provide useful insights into how best to make on-line resources available for cancer patients, caregivers, survivors, and families. This site is a collaboration between the  Indiana University Melvin and Bren Simon Cancer Center Walther Cancer Foundation , and the Indiana University  School of Nursing School of Medicine , and the  School of Informatics and Computing '),
(100100404, 'Interventions', 'IU Cancer Research Interventions Research interventions conducted by the IU School of Nursing, in collaboration with the IU Simon Cancer Center, the Walther Cancer Foundation, the Mary Margaret Walther Program for Cancer Care Research, and the Behavioral Cooperative Oncology Group (BCOG)/Center for Symptom Management, have emphasized cancer prevention, cancer screening, symptom management practices, and cancer patient caregiver support. "Health Matters", Increasing Colorectal and Breast Cancer Screening in Women The  Increasing Colorectal and Breast Cancer Screening in Women study provides a website for study participants that presents information about breast and colorectal cancer screening in an informative video talk show format.  The program is interactive, with the video program pausing from time to time to allow participants to respond to questions posed by the talk show host. The program and the questions are designed to help women assess their risk for breast and colorectal cancers, and to encourage them to get cancer screenings. Mammograms Save Lives: Decide Today Mammograms Save Lives: Decide Today  is a program that explores the importance of getting regularly checked for breast cancer.  The program highlights how several different women have found ways to get regular mammograms. The program is provided on an interactive DVD, playable on a television or a computer, with opportunities for viewers to provide input to questions, and video material tailored for the viewer\'s responses. Pathways For Caring  Pathways For Caring is a research intervention designed to connect cancer patients undergoing chemotherapy with their caregivers.  Pairs of patients and caregivers were recruited for the study and asked to complete an 8-week program of symptom reporting for patients, and caregiver concern reporting for caregivers.  The program also involved information for both the patient and caregiver, as well as evaluation questionnaires to assess the usefulness of the information presented each week. Help For Cancer Caregivers Help For Cancer Caregivers  is a publicly available website, based on the caregiver resources developed for Pathways For Caring.  Caregivers provide information about their concerns, and information is provided for their priority interests.  The project is a collaboration between IU School of Nursing, IU School of Informatics, CancerCare.org, and Caregiver Action Network.  Funding was provided by Wellpoint Foundation.\n Escape From Nicotinia Escape From Nicotinia is a video game project designed to prevent smoking for young girls.  Done in the style of a graphic novel, the game uses a story line that follows a young girl who must make choices to avoid being trapped in Nicotinia, a dreary city with ash-tray architecture, and creepy characters who think they are "cool". '),
(100100904, 'Contact', 'Contact Us Please send us your comments or questions by typing them into the space below: Topic:  \n    $("#note_form").submit(function( event ){   \n        event.preventDefault();\n        $.post("php/portal_contact.php",$("#note_form").serialize(),function(data)  \n             {\n                $("#note_panel").remove();\n		$("body").append(" ");\n                $("#contact_feedback").html(data);\n             },\n             "text"\n         );\n       }\n     );\n \n		 '),
(100190004, 'Privacy Notice', 'Privacy Notice Our mission is to help cancer patients, caregivers, family, and friends who visit this web site with information, resources, and tools.  We do not collect, process, store, or share personal information about you. We do store the information you provide while using the various tools available on the site.  This provides the functionality for the tools, and also provides us with research data.   We also collect and store data about the usage of the web site.  This allows us to understand how the site is used, and which features are the most valuable to our users. We ask that you avoid using any identifiable information (i.e., actual name, e-mail address, birth date, phone number, etc.) in your username, or in the other data that you might provide on the website so that no personal information will collected or stored. '),
(100200104, 'Cancer basics', 'Cancer Basics Click on the Play button to view this video. \n	if (AC_FL_RunContent == 0) {\n		alert("This page requires AC_RunActiveContent.js.");\n	} else {\n		AC_FL_RunContent(\n			\'codebase\', \'http://download.macromedia.com/pub/shockwave/cabs/flash/swflash.cab#version=9,0,0,0\',\n			\'width\', \'250\',\n			\'height\', \'188\',\n			\'src\', \'what_is_cancer\',\n			\'quality\', \'high\',\n			\'pluginspage\', \'http://www.macromedia.com/go/getflashplayer\',\n			\'align\', \'middle\',\n			\'play\', \'true\',\n			\'loop\', \'true\',\n			\'scale\', \'showall\',\n			\'wmode\', \'window\',\n			\'devicefont\', \'false\',\n			\'id\', \'what_is_cancer\',\n			\'bgcolor\', \'#000000\',\n			\'name\', \'what_is_cancer\',\n			\'menu\', \'true\',\n			\'allowFullScreen\', \'false\',\n			\'allowScriptAccess\',\'sameDomain\',\n			\'movie\', \'what_is_cancer\',\n			\'salign\', \'\'\n			); //end AC code\n	}\n Courtesy of Matt Williamson and Albert William,  IUPUI School of Informatics  More information Learning about Cancer  (Cancer.Net)  Cancer - General Information (American Cancer Society) Cancer  (Medlineplus)  What You Need To Know About Cancer (National Cancer Institute) Your body is made up of trillions of cells.  The life cycle of each of your cells is controlled by its genes.  Cancer is caused by changes (or mutations) in a cell\'s genes.  Researchers have learned that mutations in genes can be caused by  risk factors , such as lifestyle or the environment.   It is common for cancers to be named for the part of the body or type of cell where they began.  Cancers normally start out small and in one part of the body.  The cancer cells can break away (or metastasize) from the first (or primary) site of  diagnosis .  The metastasized cancer cells can enter the bloodstream, spreading to other areas of the body and form new tumors.  The new tumors and primary tumor have the same name because they are made of the same kind of abnormal cells.  The best time to find (or detect) and diagnose cancer is in the early stage of its growth.  Learn about cancer\'s  early warning signs .  Not all cancers have early warning signs.  Regularly check your body for any changes.  If you are concerned, schedule an appointment with your doctor.  Having regular check-ups and screenings help your doctor to monitor any irregular changes in your body.  If you are diagnosed with cancer, the treatment will depend on the type and stage of the cancer. You and your care team will decide what the best comprehensive  treatment  plan is for you.  '),
(100200204, 'Types of Cancer', 'Types of Cancer \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n More information A to Z List of Cancers (National Cancer Institute) Cancer Types  (Cancer.Net)  \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n By category \r\n\r\n Blood Cancers and Disorders Bone and Soft Tissue Cancers Brain and Spinal Tumors  Breast Cancer Chest Cavity Cancers Childhood Cancers Endocrine Cancers Female Reproductive Cancers Head and Neck Cancers Skin Cancer Stomach and Intestinal Cancers Testis Cancer Urinary Tract and Male Reproductive Cancers \r\n\r\n Alphabetical order \r\n\r\n &nbsp;   &nbsp;   &nbsp;  \r\n&nbsp; D &nbsp;   &nbsp;   \r\n&nbsp;   &nbsp;   &nbsp; I \r\n&nbsp; J &nbsp;   &nbsp;   \r\n&nbsp;   &nbsp;   &nbsp;  \r\n&nbsp;   &nbsp; Q &nbsp;   \r\n&nbsp;   &nbsp;   &nbsp;  \r\n&nbsp;   &nbsp;   &nbsp; X &nbsp; Y &nbsp; Z &nbsp; \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n AIDS-related Kaposi\'s Sarcoma  (National Cancer Institute) AIDS-related Lymphomas  (National Cancer Institute) Adrenocortical Carcinoma  (National Cancer Institute) Anal Cancer  (National Cancer Institute) Appendix Cancer  (National Cancer Institute) \r\n\r\n Bile Duct Cancer  (National Cancer Institute) Bladder Cancer  (National Cancer Institute) Blood Cancers and Disorders Bone Cancer  (National Cancer Institute) Bone and Soft Tissue Cancers Brain Tumors  (National Cancer Institute) Brain and Spinal Tumors Breast Cancer \r\n\r\n Cervical Cancer  (National Cancer Institute) Chest Cavity Cancers Childhood Cancers Colon and Rectal Cancer  (National Cancer Institute) \r\n\r\n Endocrine Cancers Endometrial Cancer  (National Cancer Institute) Esophageal Cancer  (National Cancer Institute) Ewing Family of Tumors  (National Cancer Institute) Extrahepatic Bile Duct Cancer  (National Cancer Institute) Extracranial Germ Cell Tumor (Childhood)  (National Cancer Institute) Extragonadal Germ Cell Tumor  (National Cancer Institute) \r\n\r\n Fallopian Tube Cancer  (OncoLink&#174;) Female Reproductive Cancers \r\n\r\n Gallbladder Cancer  (National Cancer Institu