(100200500204, 'Decisions', 'Making Treatment Decisions \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n More information Making Treatment Decisions (American Cancer Society) Treatment Decisions Tools (American Cancer Society) \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n To help you decide which treatment is best for you, ask your doctors some questions.  You may find it helpful to write down questions before your appointment, take notes during your conversation, and have a family member or caregiver go with you.  Below is a list of questions to help you get started:  \r\n\r\n \r\n   What is my diagnosis?  \r\n   Is there any evidence the cancer has spread? What is the stage of the disease?  \r\n   What are my treatment choices? Which do you recommend for me? Why?  \r\n   What new treatments are being studied? Would a clinical trial be appropriate for me?  \r\n   What are the expected benefits of each kind of treatment?  \r\n   What are the risks and possible side effects of each treatment?  \r\n   Is infertility a side effect of cancer treatment? Can anything be done about it?  \r\n   What can I do to prepare for treatment?  \r\n   How often will I have treatments?  \r\n   How long will treatment last?  \r\n   Will I have to change my normal activities? If so, for how long?  \r\n   What is the treatment likely to cost?  \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n '),
(100200500304, 'Side Effects', 'Managing Side Effects More information Symptom Management Nutrition for the Person with Cancer  (American Cancer Society) Managing Eating Problems During Treatment  (National Cancer Institute) Managing Eating Problems Caused by Chemotherapy  (Chemocare.com) Once you select a treatment plan and begin your treatment, you may start to have side effects.  Side effects and their severities will vary from person to person.  Often, side effects happen because healthy cells are affected by the therapy used to kill the cancer cells.  Hair loss, nausea and vomiting, infertility and a deceased ability to fight infection are common side effects.  Possible side effects should be among your considerations when selecting a treatment plan.  '),
(100200500404, 'Clinical Trials', 'Clinical Trials What is a clinical trial? Why are clinical trials important? Should I participate in a clinical trial? Where can I get more informaiton? What is a clinical trial? Scientists all over the world conduct research studies known as clinical trials.  At the IU Simon Cancer Center, more than one hundred scientists and doctors, nurses, psychologists, social workers, and technologists are working to advance cancer care through clinical trials.  Standard therapy does not help all cancer patients.  That is why researchers at the IU Simon Cancer Center continue their search for new treatments and, hopefully, new cures.  Why are clinical trials important? Clinical trials are an important treatment option for people with cancer to consider.  A cancer clinical trial is a research study in which people help doctors, nurses, psychologists, and social workers, find ways to improve cancer care.  These cancer research studies try to answer scientific questions and find better ways to prevent, diagnose, or treat cancer.  They also try to find ways to the improve quality of life of cancer survivors.  It is important that men and women of all ages and backgrounds take part in clinical trials. Each trial has eligibility criteria (or rules) about who can and cannot be in the study. Talk to your doctor to see if you may be an option for you.   Should I participate in a clinical trial? Only you can make the final decision about whether or not to take part in a clinical trial. Before you make your decision, you should:  Learn as much as you can about your disease.  See the  National Cancer Institute\'s A to Z List of Cancers  for cancer information or the  Types of Cancer  section of this website for more cancer-specific resources. Find out about trials that are available to you.  You can view the  current clinical trials at the IU Simon Cancer Center  or a comprehensive list of trials throughout the United States at the  NCI\'s Search for Clinical Trials Ask your doctor about the benefits, risks, and steps taken to protect people who take part in clinical trials.  All trials have both benefits and risks to the patient.  Talk about this information and how you feel about it with your doctor and/or nurse, family members, and friends.  They can help you decide what is right for you.  Where can I get more information? Clinical Trials  (Cancer.Net) Clinical Trials  (American Cancer Society)  Clinical Trials  (National Cancer Institute)  Clinical Trials: Questions and Answers  (National Cancer Institute)  Search IU Clinical Trials  (Indiana University Office of Clinical Research)  Should I Take Part in a Clinical Trial?  (National Cancer Institute)  Participating in a Trial: Questions to Ask Your Doctor  (National Cancer Institute)  Protecting Participants in Clinical Trials  (National Cancer Institute)  Search for Trial  (Coalition of Cancer Cooperative Groups)  Cancer Trials and Locations  (Hoosier Oncology Group)  '),
(100300100604, 'Lack of Appetite', 'Lack of Appetite What is lack of appetite? How do people describe lack of appetite? What causes lack of appetite? What can I do about lack of appetite? What can family members and friends do to help me with my lack of appetite? How can I talk with my family members and friends about my lack of appetite? What should I report to my healthcare provider about my lack of appetite?  What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about my lack of appetite?  Where can I get more information? References Supportive evidence-based practice What is lack of appetite? A lack of or decreased appetite is when a person does not feeling hungry, even though they have not eaten enough to meet their basic caloric needs. If not treated and managed, it can lead to a more serious condition. Increasing your appetite, you can improve both your quality of life and ability to tolerate cancer treatments.  How do people describe lack of appetite? Lack of appetite can be described as not having the desire to eat.  Often, people with cancer or those undergoing cancer treatment report that they have no appetite, feel full quicker than usual, or both. What causes lack of appetite? Cancer itself can affect your appetite, food digestion, and energy level.  Many people report that their senses of taste and smell change because of their treatment. These changes can decrease appetite.  Some have experienced changes in appetite because of nausea, vomiting, or uncontrolled pain and fatigue.  Other factors that can contribute to appetite loss include medications, anxiety, depression or sadness, lack of sleep, difficulty swallowing, constipation, or diarrhea.  What can I do about lack of appetite? Not eating well can keep you from getting the nutrients that you need.  Here are some tips you might find helpful: ACTIVITY  Assess your nutritional status by keeping a log of the food that you eat.  Write down all of the food that you ate in a 24 hour period.   Freeze food in meal size portions.   Give food a chance.  Even though you have trouble eating now, you may find a time when eating is enjoyable.   Weigh yourself at the same time every day.   Stock up on favorite foods.   Keep a supply of foods that can be eaten during times of illness, such as popsicles, broths, or lemon-lime soda.   Do not eat your favorite foods on the day of your treatments or when you feel nauseated.  Your body may learn to associate these foods with nausea.   Eat foods that are cold or room temperature if food odors bother you.   Do not try to lose weight while being treated for cancer, unless directed by your healthcare provider to do so.   Do light exercises for 30 minutes before mealtime may help you to feel hungrier.  Examples of light exercises are walking around the block or around the house.  COMMUNICATION  Ask your nurse, dietician, or doctor to help you assess your nutritional status before and during your treatment.  DIET  Try new foods.  Tastes can change.  Different foods may be a pleasant addition to your menu.   Using sauces and gravies can make swallowing easier.   Drink 8 (8oz.) glasses of water or other non-caffeinated drinks every day.  Avoid caffeine (i.e. colas, coffee) when possible.  Caffeine can cause dehydration.   Eat calorie-rich foods such as malts, shakes, and omelets.   Try eating 5-6 smaller meals or snacks throughout the day.   Avoid carbonated beverages, they can make you feel full but do not add nutrition.   Get approval from your oncologist to try Boost or Ensure. These high-calorie supplements can also be mixed with fruit or ice cream to make a shake.  Supplements can be filling, so try to eat your meal before taking them.  NOTE:  Supplements can stay on your tongue and mouth.  Many find it helpful to sip through a straw and drink them cold.   Suck on hard candy if you have a metallic taste in your mouth.   Eat meats, fruits and vegetables in small portions throughout the day.  Avoid milk if its upsets your stomach.   Eat protein everyday (tuna fish, chicken, peanut butter, and cheese).   Treat constipation and diarrhea.  Both of them can affect your appetite. Use seasonings on foods that you are finding unpleasant.  Basil, oregano and rosemary can make meat, fish or poultry more flavorful.  MEDICATION  Take a daily vitamin supplement.   Take your prescribed anti-nausea medications 30-60 minutes before eating.   Ask your doctor if an appetite stimulant like Megace (a hormone that improves appetite and can help you increase your calorie intake) would be good for you.  INFORMATION FOR CAREGIVERS  Do not try to push your family member into eating or drinking.   Provide encouragement and support without being overwhelming.   Keep snacks and utensils within easy reach.   Plan on small, frequent meals.   Encourage fluids if your family member cannot eat. Many fluids are nutritious and contain calories. Your family member may not drink much at a time.  Even when sipped, juices and other fluids can be beneficial.   Be prepared for changing tastes. They may changes day-to-day.  Favorite foods may not taste good some days.   Have high-energy foods available.  What can family members and friends do to help me with my lack of appetite? Ask family members and friends to:  Keep foods around that require little or no preparation time.  Examples of easy to prepare foods include: cheese, eggs, pudding, peanut butter, or tuna fish.   Help with grocery shopping and cooking.   Make mealtime pleasant. This may include fresh flowers on the table or pleasant music while eating.  How can I talk with my family members and friends about my lack of appetite? Here are some ideas that may help you talk to family members and friends:  Tell your family members and friends how the lack of appetite is affecting your daily activities and emotions.   Ask your family members and friends for suggestions that might help.   Make suggestions about your food preferences.  What should I report to my healthcare provider about my lack of appetite? If you experience any of the following symptoms, report them to your healthcare provider:  Several days (3-5) of eating poorly.   Decreased amount of urine.   Dark colored urine.   Fever greater than 100.4 degrees Farenheit (38.0 C) for over 24 hours.   Dizziness.   Mental confusion.   Uncontrolled nausea or vomiting.   Inability to tolerate fluids for over 24 hours.   Loss of 5 pounds in a week or more than 2 pounds in 24 hours.   Nothing to eat or drink for 24 hours.   Constipation (no bowel movement for 2 days).   Pain.   Depression and/or anxiety.  What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about my lack of appetite? If you are experiencing a lack of appetite, you should discuss the following with your healthcare provider at your next appointment:  Can you help me find ways to improve my diet, even though I lack an appetite?   How many calories should I consume each day?   How long will I continue to experience strange tastes in my mouth? What is causing this?   I am losing weight steadily. How can we approach and reverse this problem? What are my options?  Where can I get more information? For more information, contact the people or organizations at the numbers or websites listed below:  Contact your healthcare provider.   National Cancer Institute: 1-800-4-CANCER or  http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo/  Click on coping with cancer. Find and click on nutrition in cancer patients.   American Cancer Society: 1-800-ACS-2345 or  http://www.cancer.org  Click patients, family & friends, then coping with treatment.   Family Care Research Program:  http://www.cancercare.msu.edu  National Coalition For Cancer Survivorship:  http://canceradvocacy.org  Click on Resource Guide then Side effects.   Oncology Nursing Society:  http://www.cancersymptoms.org References  Cunningham, R.S. (2003). The anorexia-cachexia syndrome. In C.H. Yarbro, M.H. Frogge, & M. Goodman (Eds.), Cancer Symptom Management, 3rd Ed. (pp. 137-167). Boston: Jones And Bartlett.   National Cancer Institute (n.d.).  National Cancer Institute. Retrieved from   http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo/  University Of Pennsylvania Oncolink (2008). OncoLink: The web\'s first cancer resource.  Retrieved from:  http://www.oncolink.upenn.edu  Wickham, R., Rewaldt, M., Kefer, C., Shott, S., Abbas, K., Glynn-Tucker, E., Et Al. (1999). Taste changes experienced by patients receiving chemotherapy. Oncology Nursing Forum, 26, 697-706.  Supportive evidence-based practice  Laviano, A., Meguid, M.M., Inui, A., Muscaritoli, M., & Rossi-Fanelli, F. (2005). Therapy insight: cancer anorexia-cachexia syndrome-when all you can eat is yourself. Nature Clinical Practice Oncology, 2 (3), 158-165.   Mcgrath, P. (2002). Reflections on nutritional issues associated with cancer therapy. Cancer Practice, 10 (2), 94-101.  Return to top This information was developed in collaboration with Michigan State University and the Behavioral Cooperative Oncology Group. ');
