(100300103904, 'Mouth Sores', 'Mouth Sores \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n What are Mouth Sores? How do people describe mouth sores? What causes mouth sores? What can I do about mouth sores? What can family members and friends do to help me with my mouth sores? How can I talk to my family and friends about my mouth sores? What should I report to my healthcare provider about my mouth sores? What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about my mouth sores? Where can I get more information? References Supportive evidence-based practice What are mouth sores? Mucositis is when the mucus lining of the mouth and tongue and throat become reddened, swollen and painful. Open sores called ulcers can develop. About half of cancer patients on chemotherapy and almost all who have radiation to the head or neck will experience mouth discomfort as a side effect of treatment. The discomfort can range from mild to severe. Mild discomfort is a change in the way the mouth feels. It is easily treated and quick to heal. Moderate discomfort is considered to be redness and open sores in the mouth. Severe mucositis involves many sores in the mouth, bleeding, and severe pain. None of these discomfort levels are pleasant. Each can cause other problems including difficulty swallowing, talking, eating, and infection. There are preventive steps and treatment that you can do to minimize this uncomfortable side effect.  It is very important that any discomfort in your mouth is reported to your doctor or nurse immediately. Early reporting is the best way to decrease the severity and prevent further complications. Mucositis can delay your cancer treatment or limit the dose of your therapy. How do people describe mouth sores? After about three to five days of chemotherapy and/or radiation therapy, the lining of the mouth may feel a little warm. There may be some tingling or minor soreness. Within one to two weeks of starting your treatment, sores may begin to appear. A week or two after your treatment is finished the sores begin to heal.  Usually after the third week out of treatment, the ulcers and pain will have disappeared.  There are a number of warning signs that commonly describe mucositis, including:  Burning or tingling feeling inside the mouth.   Inside of the mouth looks red, shiny, and swollen.   Red, inflamed patches. These may include white spots.   Raw feeling in the throat.   Unusual mouth dryness.   Open sores or ulcers in the mouth or under the tongue.   Thick secretions or saliva.   Blood in the mouth or saliva.   Pain in the mouth.  What causes mouth sores? Chemotherapy and radiation therapy work on rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  They also attack other cells in the body, including those forming the lining of the mouth and throat. As mouth cells die from the treatment, open sores can develop.  Gradually, normal cells in the mouth start to grow again and the sores heal.  Individual risk factors for developing mouth sores include:   Advanced age.   Poor nutritional status.   Poor oral hygiene.   Poor fitting dentures.   Tobacco use (cigarettes, cigars, or pipes).   Drink alcohol beverages (beer, wine, or liquor).  Treatment related risk factors include:  Drug dosage.   Treatment schedule.   Receiving radiation therapy.  A large number of chemotherapy drugs can cause mouth sores. It is most commonly reported with:  5- fluoroucil (5-FU)   Cisplatin&#174;   Etoposide&#174;   Methotrexate&#174;   Cytarabine&#174;   Bleomycin&#174;   Cyclophosphamide&#174;   Dactinomycin&#174;   Paclitaxel&#174;   High doses of chemotherapy  What can I do about mouth sores? Proper mouth care on a frequent, daily basis plays an important role in oral health during cancer therapy. You may not be able to prevent all problems, but it will decrease the severity of the problems, especially with certain chemotherapy treatments and/or radiation therapy. ACTIVITY  Schedule a complete dental examination before you begin your chemotherapy and/or radiation treatment.  Inform your dentist that you will be undergoing cancer treatment.   Take care of your mouth and keep it clean.  That means careful brushing and flossing based on discussion with your doctor and/or dentist.   Use the softest bristle brush available or an oral sponge.  (Rinsing the bristles in hot water can even make them softer).   Brush your teeth after every meal and at bedtime using nonabrasive toothpaste with no strong whiteners, which may cause irritation. Brush all tooth surfaces for at least 90 seconds.   Brush your tongue as well as teeth and gums to help reduce the risk of fungal infections.   Change your toothbrush frequently --every week or so.   Do not use special appliances, such as water piks and electric toothbrushes. They may further irritate sensitive mouth tissue and gums.   Floss gently everyday with unwaxed dental floss.  Stop flossing if you experience any bleeding or low blood counts.   Clean dentures after every meal.  If possible, avoid wearing dentures overnight while asleep.   Make sure your dentures fit properly. Repair or replace them if they do not fit well.  Poor fitting dentures can rub and cause additional pain in a tender mouth.   Avoid using mouth rinse products that have glycerin or alcohol as they can cause dying in your mouth.   Rinse mouth frequently (every 2 hours while awake & when awake during the night).  Mouth solution:   1/2 teaspoon salt 2 teaspoons baking soda 4 cups (1 quart) of plain water Shake or stir the solution.  Keep it with you for regular use.  If you make more than a one-day supply, keep the remainder in the refrigerator. COMMUNICATION  Check with your healthcare provider to make sure it is safe to wear your dentures if you are receiving radiation treatments to the head and neck area.   Talk to your healthcare provider if you need additional suggestions or continue to lose weight during your treatment.  Many practices have dieticians available for advice.   Ask your doctor if you can take Tylenol&#174; or ibuprofen&#174; for pain relief.   Ask your healthcare provider if there is a specific medication that can help fight infections.  Chemotherapy and radiation can weaken the immune system.  Bacteria that live in the mouth can cause infections in mouth sores.  DIET  Drink at least 8-10 glasses of non-carbonated liquids each day.   Suck on non-irritating hard candy (sugar-free is best). Chewing gum may help.   Eat popsicles or suck ice cubes for moisture.   Avoid very hot food.  If your mouth is tender, try eating most of your food warm or at room temperature.   Avoid highly seasoned food, which can aggravate mouth soreness.   Avoid alcohol and tobacco.  Both irritate an already-sore mouth and throat.   Restrict the amount of citrus fruit, tomatoes, and salty food in your diet. They can be uncomfortable for some people with mouth sores.   Grind up or puree food in a blender. Foods with shape edges, such as chips and cracker, may be irritating.   Use sauces or gravies to make foods easier for you to swallow and chew.   Small, frequent meals may also be easier for you to eat.   Drink liquid supplements to maintain your calorie intake. Examples of supplements are  Carnation&#174; Instant Breakfast&#174;, Ensure&#174;, and Boost&#174;.   Choose to eat soft and soothing foods. Examples include: ice cream, milkshakes, baby foods, mashed potatoes, scrambled eggs, cottage cheese, custards, puddings, and gelatin.  MEDICATION  Try artificial saliva, such as Oral Balance&#174;, Moist Plus&#174;, and Salivant&#174;. This can be purchased at a drugstore without a prescription.   Keep your lips moist with lip balm, Chapstick&#174;, or petroleum jelly.   Use a water-based mouth moisturizer to help keep the mouth moist. An example of a moisturizer is Biotene&#174; Oral Lubricant.)   Do not use liquid medications containing alcohol, such as cough medications. They may irritate the mouth.   Take stronger drugs for severe pain. Pain causes stress, depression, and fatigue. Opiates are a class of strong drugs, one of which is morphine, that provide effective pain relief. It is very important to talk to your doctor or nurse if your pain is not being controlled. Many opiates are also available in liquids and patches if you are not able to swallow pills.   Treat discomfort/pain:   Use topical or local agents such as Orajel&#174;, Anbesol&#174;, Zilactin-b&#174;, or Orabase&#174;, which are available in the drugstore. A combination mouthwash with a local anesthetic can be prescribed from your healthcare provider. Take 2 teaspoons every 2-4 hours or prior to meals to alleviate mild discomfort. Gelclair&#174; is a prescription medication available to sooth the oral pain from sores. Ask your doctor if you can take Tylenol&#174; or ibuprofen&#174; for pain relief.  Severe pain:   Do not resist taking stronger drugs for severe pain. Pain causes stress, depression, and fatigue. Opiates&#174;, a class of drug that includes morphine, are used for pain relief. It is very important to talk to your healthcare provider if your pain is not being controlled. Many opiates are also available in liquids and patches if you are not able to swallow pills.  Fight infections:   Chemotherapy and radiation can weaken the immune system.  Bacteria that live in the mouth can cause infections in mouth sores. Your healthcare provider may order specific medications to help fight infections. What can family members and friends do to help me with my mouth sores? Ask family members and friends to:   Prepare meals high in protein to promote healing.   Remind you to perform mouth care after meals and at bedtime.   Prepare bland, soft foods that will be more tolerable.   Help buy or prepare mouth care solutions, toothpaste and lip balm.  How can I talk to my family and friends about my mouth sores? Here are some ideas that may help you talk to family members and friends:  Be open with your family members about how you feel having mouth sores.   Ask them for ideas on how to deal with your mouth sores.   Tell your family members how your mouth sores are affecting your emotions.   Ask your family members how your mouth sores are affecting them.  What should I report to my healthcare provider about my mouth sores? If you experience any of the following symptoms, report them to your healthcare provider:  New red or white patches your mouth or tongue.   New sores in your mouth or tongue.   Weight loss of more than 5 pounds in one week.   Inability to eat any food for 24 hours.   Pain that is not relieved.   Bleeding from gums or mouth sores.   Pain with swallowing or sore throat that interferes with eating, drinking, or sleeping.   Fever.   Pain or signs of infection (tongue heavily coated).  What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about my mouth sores? If you are experiencing mouth sores, you should discuss the following with your healthcare provider at your next appointment:  Is it likely that my cancer treatment will cause mouth sores?   Specifically, how should I manage my mouth care on a daily basis?   Is there a dietician available to help guide me in choosing appropriate foods?   Will the mouth sores interfere with the schedule of my cancer treatment?   What medications can I use for pain and how often should I use them?   What are the warning signs of infection, and what should I do if my mouth becomes infected?  Where can I get more information? For more information, contact the people or organizations at the numbers or websites listed below:  Contact your family dentist.   Contact your healthcare provider.   National Cancer Institute: 1-800-4-CANCER or  http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo  Click on coping with cancer.   American Cancer Society: 1-800-ACS-2345 or  http://cancer.org  Family Care Research Program:  http://www.cancercare.msu.edu  National Coalition For Cancer Survivorship:  http://canceradvocacy.org  Click on learn then side effects.   Chemocare:  http://chemocare.com  Click on managing side effects.   Oncology Nursing Society: 1-866-257-4ONS or  http://www.cancersymptoms.org References  Cawley, M., M. & Benson, L., M. (2005). Current trends In managing oral mucositis. Clinical Journal Of Oncology Nursing, 9 (5), Pp. 584-592.   Davidson, D. (2006). Oral mucositis. Clinical Journal Of Oncology Nursing, 10 (2), pp. 283-284.   Multiple association of supportive care in oncology. Summary of evidenced-based guidelines for care of patients with oral and gastrointestinal mucositis. Retreived From The Internet From  http://www.masc.org  On December 18, 2006.   Peterson, D., E. (2006). New strategies for management of oral mucositis in cancer patients. The Journal Of Supportive Oncology, (4) 2 Suppl. 1, Pp. 9-13.   Posner, M.R. & Haddad, R.I. (2007). Novel agents for the treatment of mucositis. A Supplement to: The Journal of Supportive Oncology, 5(9), 33-39.   Rajesh, V., L., & Peterson, D., E. (2006). Treatment of mucositis, including new medications. The Cancer Journal, 12 (5), Pp. 348-354.   Shish, A., Miaskowski, D., Dodd, M., J., Stotts, N., A., & Mcphail, L., (2002). A research review of the current treatments for radiation-induced oral mucositis in patients with head and neck cancer. Oncology Nursing Forum, 29 (7), Pp. 1063-80.   Sonis, S., T., Elting, L., S., Keefe, D., Peterson, D., E., Schubert, M., & Hauer-Jensen, M., Et Al. (2004). Perspectives on cancer therapy-induced mucosal injury. Cancer, 100 (9) Suppl. Pp.1995-2011.   Zitella, L., J., Friese, C., R., Hauser, J., Gobel, B., Woolery, M., & O\'leary, C. (2006). Putting evidence into practice: prevention of infection. Clinical Journal Of Oncology Nursing, 10 (6), Pp. 739-745.  Supportive evidence-based practice  Harris, D.J., Eilers, J., Harriman, A., Cashavelly, B.J., Maxwell, C. (2008). Putting evidence into practice: Evidence-based interventions for the management of oral mucositis. Clinical Journal of Oncology Nursing, 12(1), 141-152.   Rubenstien, E. B., Peterson, D. D., Schubert, M., Keefe, D., Mcguire, D., Et Al. (2004