(100300106004, 'Rash', 'Rash What is rash? How do people describe rash? What causes a rash? What can I do about rash? What can family and friends do to help with my rash? How can I talk with my family members and friends about my rash? Drugs that may be prescribed by your healthcare provider What should I report to my healthcare provider about my rash? What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about my rash? Where can I get more information? References Supportive evidence-based practice What is a rash? A rash is any change in the skin that alters its appearance or texture. It may affect all of the skin or be localized to one part of the body. Rashes can irritate the skin by causing it to itch, change colors, become warm, bumpy, dry, crack or blister. Swelling and pain can also occur. If you are receiving chemotherapy it is important to let your healthcare provider know when you develop a rash. It will be important for you to describe the appearance of the rash, where it is located, when it first appeared, and any symptoms you are experiencing. How do people describe rash? Rash is a general term for a skin reaction. There are many terms used to describe what the rash looks like such as:  Erythematous - Redness.   Macular - Small, distinct, flat areas.   Papular - Small raised lesions.   Macular-Papular - Usually bright red in color. The skin may feel hot, burning, or itchy.   Hives (uticaria) - Round, raised, itchy, or red blotches, which may be pale in the center and red around the outside.   Follicular eruptions - Tiny sacs on the skin surface from which hair grows.  These eruptions look very similar to acne. Some doctors call it an acne-like rash. Follicular eruptions are raised and can be filled with pus have a yellow drainage.   Itching (or pruitis) - A peculiar tingling or uneasy irritation of the skin that causes a desire to scratch the affected area. Itching may be over the whole body (generalized), or only in a particular location (localized).   Flushing - A temporary redness of the face and neck caused by swelling of the blood vessels.   Blistering - Round raised areas of fluid under the upper layer of the skin, which can weep or drain clear fluid.   Honey yellow crusting - Yellowish-brown crust over the red eruptions with oozing of fluid from lesions may indicate a bacterial infection.  What causes a rash? It is very important that you understand the side effects of your chemotherapy treatment. Many chemotherapy drugs can cause rashes and skin changes. Some of the skin reactions can develop immediately during treatment or within the first 36 hours after receiving your treatment. This is an acute allergic or hypersensitivity reaction causing hives, flushing and itching. It is very important that you let your healthcare provider know immediately if you experience this type of rash. This is your body\'s protective immune response to a foreign substance that has entered the body, such as chemotherapy. This is not a common reaction, but is more common with certain chemotherapy drugs, such as, Paclitaxel, Bleomycin, L-Asparaginase, Docetaxel, Cisplatin, Carbotaxol and Monoclonal Antibodies.  Ask your healthcare provider if your chemotherapy might cause a reaction Allergic drug rashes can also be delayed developing within days or weeks after your treatment.  This type of skin rash usually develops on the back of the body. The arms and legs are often involved however, the face is not usually affected. This rash is usually bright red in color, and the skin will feel hot and burning. It is very important to let your healthcare provider know all the medications that you are currently taking and whether you have any medication allergies or history of allergic reactions. There are many new chemotherapy drugs that are associated with rashes. Scientists have developed numerous new drugs that appear to be effective treatments for many different kinds of cancer. Known as  targeted treatments , these drugs are designed to prevent cancer cells from getting nourished, growing, dividing, and possibly spreading.  Targeted treatments are different than chemotherapy.  Unlike chemotherapy, which can harm healthy cells as it kills cancer cells, targeted treatments focus on blocking cancer cell growth and killing cancer cells.  Treatments may be given in combination with chemotherapy or alone as a single treatment. In particular, one type of targeted treatment blocks the epidermal growth factor receptors (EGFRs), which can cause rashes and dry skin.  These rashes are not an allergic response.  They are a side effect from the drug itself.  EGFR - blocking drugs that commonly cause a rash include Cetuximab (Erbitux&#174;), Erlotinib (Tarceva&#174;), Gefitinib (Iressa&#174;) and Panitumumab (Vectibix&#174;).  Another type of targeted treatment blocks the development of blood vessels that feed tumors.  It is called vascular endothelial growth factors receptors (VEGFRs).  VEGF - blocking drugs include Sorafenib (Nexavar&#174;) and Sunitinib (Sutent&#174;). These rashes usually appear within 1-3 weeks of treatment. The rash is characterized by an acne-like rash with pustules.  Generally, they first appear on the face, particularly around the nose or on the cheeks.  However, the rash may also appear on the back, arms and legs. The severity of the rash may come and go during your treatment. Typically the rash clears up within 1-2 months after your treatment is completed. The rash normally does not require you to stop your treatment. Some studies have suggested that the rash may actually be a positive sign that your body is responding to the drug.  It is very important that you notify your healthcare provider if this rash develops.  This rash is NOT acne.  Do not treat it with acne medication What can I do about rash? Here are some tips you might find helpful: ACTIVITY  Wear loose soft cotton clothing.   Use a mild moisturizing soap without perfumes when bathing.  Examples of mild moisturizing soaps are Dove&#174;, Ivory&#174; Skin Cleansing Liquid Gel, Cetaphil&#174;, Neutrogena&#174; and Aveeno&#174;.   Pat skin gently after washing the area with a clean soft towel or washcloth.   Avoid exposing your skin to temperature extremes.  Try not to use hot lamps, ice packs, heating pads and electric blankets.   Treat dry skin with emollient lotions, such as: Eucerin&#174; Cream, Cetaphil&#174; Cream, Bag&#174; Balm, Udder&#174; Cream, Zim\'s&#174; Crack Cream, Aquaphor&#174; ointment, Vanicream&#174;, Neutrogena&#174;, or Vaseline&#174; Intensive Care (dye free & alcohol free).   Treat itchy skin with the emollient lotions listed above and Aveeno&#174; Baths, Sarna&#174; Ultra Cream, Regenecare&#174; Gel, Gold Bond&#174; Powder and Sweet cream.   Strong gloves will help avoid skin contact with friction and harsh chemicals, which can further damage your skin.  Wear light cotton gloves when gardening or doing outdoor work.  Put on rubber or latex gloves before washing dishes.   Use Band-Aid&#174; brand Liquid Bandage, Bag&#174; Balm, and Zim\'s&#174; Crack Cream for cracks and fissures.   For inflammation around your fingernails try soaking your fingertips in a solution of white vinegar diluted 1:10 in tap water for 5 minutes a day.   Wash your clothes and other fabrics that come in direct contact with your skin in mild hypoallergenic detergents.  Deft and Tide make a hypoallergenic laundry soap.  Read the label to be sure that buy the correct type.   Avoid tanning beds.   Wear sunscreen everyday, even on cloudy days.  Your sensitivity to the sun has increased.  Wearing long sleeves and long pants can help but you still need to wear sunscreen.  A new ingredient called Helioplex keeps a sunscreen from breaking down.  Helioplex is gentle on sensitive skin and can be found in several Neutrogena sunscreens, including Neutrogena Ultra Sheer Dry Tough Sunblock SPF 55.   Wear a hat.   DO NOT treat the rash with acne medication such as Clearasil&#174;, Oxy&#174;, Benzoyl&#174; Peroxide&#174;, or Stridex&#174;.   Makeup is safe to use, but avoid makeup products that contain many ingredients.   Avoid lotions, creams and soaps that contain alcohol, perfumes, or dyes.  These ingredients may increase dryness and can cause further skin irritation.  COMMUNICATION  Call your healthcare provider immediately if a new rash appears before your next appointment.  DIET  Drink 8 (8oz.) glasses of water or other non-caffeinated drinks every day.  Avoid caffeine (i.e. colas, coffee) when possible.  Caffeine can cause dehydration.  MEDICATION  Ask your healthcare provider if a topical or oral medication is right for you. They may be able to prescribe one.  What can family and friends do to help with my rash? Ask family and friends to:  Help select proper lotions for dryness and itching.   Help remind you to wear sunscreen when outside.   Help apply medications and lotions to skin if necessary.   Assist you with chores around the house.   Help bathing to keep skin clean.   Help by letting your healthcare provider know if rashes or itching occur.  How can I talk with my family members and friends about my rash? Here are some ideas that may help you talk to family members and friends:  Describe how having a rash makes you feel.   Ask your family member how your rash is affecting them.   Ask family members for support or suggestion to help cope with the rash.   Tell family members what feels good and helps with the rash.   Try describing how the itching or rash may interfere with your usual activities.  Drugs that may be prescribed by your healthcare provider  Topical steroid creams are currently not recommended.   Topical antibiotics creams may include:   Clindamycin Erythromycin  Antibiotics taken by mouth in pill form may include:   Tetracyline Minocylcline Doxycycline  Mild, localized itching may benefit from a topical antihistamine cream like Benadryl&#174;. Oral antihistamine drugs, such as, Benadryl&#174;, Claritin&#174;, or Allegra&#174; are all available over the counter and can be helpful for severe itching.  If the rash hurts, pain medications may be prescribed.  What should I report to my healthcare provider about my rash? If you experience any of the following symptoms, report them to your healthcare provider:  Report all rashes even if they are not causing you discomfort. Not all rashes require treatment.   Any new fever reading above 100.9 (38.3), or a temperature higher than 100.4 F (38.0 C) that lasts for more than an hour. Make sure that when you take your temperature you have not had any hot drinks within the last 10-15 minutes.   Increase warmth or redness to the skin area.   Any drainage or pus from the rash.   A rash that will not go away or becomes infected.   Any blisters that formed.   Cracking or peeling fingernails.   Dry nagging cough.   Severe or unmanageable itching.   Hives, flushing and difficulty breathing. Seek help immediately and notify your healthcare provider.   If your rash worsens or if the medications prescribed by your healthcare provider are not working.  What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about my rash? If you are experiencing a rash, you should discuss the following with your healthcare provider at your next appointment:  Am I at risk for developing an allergic reaction or rash with my treatment?   Do I need to take any medications prior to my treatment to reduce my risk of reaction?   Do I stop taking my chemotherapy if I develop at rash?   Can I wear make-up if I develop a rash?  Where can I get more information? For more information, contact the people or organizations at the numbers or websites listed below:  Call your healthcare provider.   American Cancer Society: 1-800-ACS-2345 or  http://www.cancer.org  Click on patients, family & friends, then coping with treatment.   National Cancer Institute: 1-800-4-CANCER or  http://www.cancer.gov  Click on coping with cancer.   Family Care Research Program:  http://cancercare.msu.edu  Chemo Care:  http://www.chemocare.com    Click on managing side effects.   Cancer Care http://CancerCare.org  or 1-800-813-HOPE (4673).  References  Esper, P., Gale, D. & Muehlbauer, P. (2007).  What kind of rash is it? Deciphering the dermatologic toxicities or biologic and targeted therapies. Clinical Journal of Oncology Nursing, 11(5) 659-666.   Lacouture, M.E. (2007) Tips to help with EGFR Targeted therapy. The Oncologist. AlphaMed Press.   Lynch, T.J., Kim, E.S., Garey, J., West, D.P., Lacouture, M.E. (2007). Epidermal growth factor receptor inhibitor- Associated cutaneous toxicities: An evolving paradigm in clinical management. The Oncologist,12, 610-621.   Oestreicher, P. (2007). Mangage Skin Toxicities Associated with Targeted Therapies. ONS connect, 22(11):20-21.   Oishi, K. (2008). Clinical approaches to minimize rash associated with EGFR inhibitors. Oncology Nursing Forum, 35(1): 103-111.   Sipples, R. (2006). Common side effects of Anti-EGF therapy: Acneform Rash. Seminars in Oncology Nursing, 22(1), 28-34.   Viele, C., S. (2005). Keys to unlock cancer: Targeted therapy. Oncology Nursing Forum, 23(5), 935-940.   Perez-Soler, R., Delord, J., Halpern, A., Kelly, K., Krueger, J. & Sureda, B. et al. (2005). HER1/EGFR Inhibitor-associated rash: Future directions for management and investigation outcomes from the HER/EGFR inhibitor rash management forum. The Oncologist, 10, 345-356.   Family Care Research Program, Michigan State University. Retrieved September 21, 2006 from  http://www.cancercare.msu.edu  National Cancer Institute. Retrieved September 21, 2006 from  http://www.cancer.gov  Hamilton, S. Care during chemotherapy and beyond: Skin reactions & Allergic reaction and chemotherapy. Retrieved September 21, 2006 from Http://chemocare.com/managing/skin_reactions.asp, Http://www.chemocare.com/managing/allergic_reactions_and_chemotherapy.asp.   Herberst, R., Fox, L., Viele, C., & Messner, C. Managing rash and other skin reactions to targeted treatments. Retrieved October 26, 2006 from  http://cancercare.org  Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia. Retrieved September 21, 2006 from  http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rash  Fox, L. (2006). Pathology and management of dermatologic toxicities associated with anti-EGFR Therapy. Oncology, 20(5) suppl. 26-33.  Supportive evidence-based practice  Lenz, H. (2006). Anti-EGFR mechanism of action: Antitumor effect and underlying cause of adverse events. Oncology, 20(5) suppl. 5-13.   Write, L. (2006). Maculopapular skin rashes associated with high-dose chemotherapy: Prevalence and risk factors. Oncology Nursing Forum, 33(6), 1095-1103.  Return to top This information was developed in collaboration with Michigan State University and the Behavioral Cooperative Oncology Group. '),
(100300106904, 'Breath', 'Shortness of Breath \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n What is shortness of breath? How do people describe shortness of breath? What causes shortness of breath? What can I do about shortness of breath? What can my family members and friends do to help me with my shortness of breath? How can I talk with my family members and friends about my shortness of breath? What should I report to my healthcare provider about my shortness of breath? What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about shortness of breath?  Where can I get more information? References What is shortness of breath? Dyspnea or shortness of breath is difficulty breathing or trouble catching your breath. Shortness of breath or difficulty breathing sometimes occurs when the body is not getting enough oxygen.  How do people describe shortness of breath? Some people describe it as a feeling of working very hard to breathe.  Others describe it as "air hunger" or a feeling of suffocation.  When people are short of breath, they are unable to do their usual activities. They tire more easily. Shortness of breath can make it difficult to talk, eat meals, or sleep at night. What causes shortness of breath? People with cancer may experience shortness of breath because of: chronic lung disorders, fatigue, pneumonia, pain, immobility, malnutrition, obesity, stress, or anxiety. Shortness of breath can also result from surgery, anemia, side effects of chemotherapy or radiation therapy, tumors or fluid in the lungs.  These problems prevent the lungs from breathing in enough air and delivering oxygen to the bloodstream. What can I do about shortness of breath? Here are some tips you might find helpful: ACTIVITY  Plan your day to do important or fun activities first.   Limit unnecessary activity.   Do not lie flat on your back.  Prop your head up while in bed.  Pillows can be helpful.  Some people find it helpful to lie on their stomach.   Use oxygen as prescribed by your doctor.   Sit upright and lean forward with your forearms on a table, another piece of furniture, or your knees.   Try breathing techniques when having difficulty breathing.  One technique is to:   Breathe through your nose for a count of 2. Purse your lips, like you are going to blow out a match or candle. Breathe out through pursed lips for a count of 4. Repeat these steps until shortness of breath is relieved.  Do not smoke and avoid being around people who smoke.   Wear loose and easy to put on clothes.   Take part in activities such as board games, listening to music, watching TV, or reading.   Perform daily grooming activities (showering, shaving, brushing teeth, combing hair) while sitting down.   Take rest period during activities.  Pace your activities to provide rest periods.   Apply a cool washcloth on cheeks.   Try opening a window or turning on a fan.   Avoid warm temperatures, unpleasant odors and fumes.   Use a wheelchair as needed.   Wear slip on shoes.  Pull socks and shoes on while sitting.   Use special devices to pick up items on the floor or ground.   Move slowly and breathe deeply.   Remain physically active.  Do mild gently exercises, as tolerated.   Take your time when climbing stairs.  Match your breaths to the steps you take.  COMMUNICATION  Ask your healthcare provider about services, such as Meals on Wheels.  DIET  Eat 6 small meals a day rather than 3 large ones.   Be sure to keep up your fluid level up by drinking 8 glasses of water per day (8oz. each).  This is important if you are breathing through your mouth.   Avoid foods that are difficult to chew.   Use frozen-foods.  These meals are easy to make and take less energy to prepare.   Buy ready-made meals.  Many are nourishing and tasty.  MEDICATION  Take medications as prescribed that decrease shortness of breath.  PSYCHOLOGICAL  Remain calm and try to stay relaxed.   Do relaxation exercises to help improve your breathing.   Try to decrease your stress levels.  What can my family members and friends do to help me with my shortness of breath? Ask family and friends to:   Help with cleaning, grocery shopping and cooking.   Assist with relaxation techniques and keeping the environment calm.   Participate in activities to distract you, such as doing puzzles, visiting, and watching movies.   Join a support group with you.   Open a window or turn on a fan.   Coach you through breathing exercises, such as pursed lip breathing.   Remind you to take your scheduled medications.   Help prop you up in bed with pillows.  How can I talk with my family members and friends about my shortness of breath? Here are some ideas that may help you talk to family members and friends:  Try to describe how the shortness of breath affects your emotions and mood.  Remember you are the expert.   Ask for suggestions that might help relieve your shortness of breath.   Try describing how the shortness of breath may interfere with your usual activities and may make you tired.  What should I report to my healthcare provider about my shortness of breath? If you experience any of the following symptoms, report them to your healthcare provider:  Pain with breathing, chest pain, wheezing.   Cold, clammy skin.   Night sweats.   Thick, yellow, green or bloody phlegm (saliva mixed with mucus that was coughed up from the respiratory tract).   Flared nostrils during breathing -- straining of neck muscles during breathing.   An increased pulse rate.   Pounding heart in the chest.   Unable to get out of bed for 24 hours.   Swelling in your ankles or calves.  \r\n\r\n It is important to note if the shortness of breath occurs after activity, or when you are resting. Tell your healthcare provider when the shortness of breath occurs.  \r\n\r\n What things should I discuss with my healthcare provider about shortness of breath? If you are experiencing shortness of breath, you should discuss the following with your healthcare provider at your next appointment:  Will my cancer treatments make my shortness of breath worse?   What is causing my shortness of breath?   What can be done to relieve my shortness of breath?   Where can I learn relaxation techniques to improve my breathing?   Should I take medication to improve my breathing?  Where can I get more information? For more information, contact the people or organizations at the numbers or websites listed below:  Contact your healthcare provider.   National Cancer Institute: 1-800-4-CANCER or  http://www.cancer.gov/cancerinfo  Click on coping with cancer.   American Cancer Society: 1-800-ACS-2345 or  http://cancer.org  Family Care Research Program:  http://www.cancercare.msu.edu  Oncology Nursing Society: 1-866-257-4ONS or  http://www.cancersymptoms.org  Click on patient than cope with cancer then managing side effects.   National Coalition for Cancer Survivorship:  http://canceradvocacy.org  Click on Resource Guide then side effects.   CancerHelp&#174;:  http://cancerhelp.org References  American Cancer Society at (2008).  Shortness of breath. Retrieved from:  http://www.cancer.org  Trustees of the University of Pennsylvania (2008).  Cancer Center\'s Oncolink. Retrieved  from:  http://www.oncolink.com  Hood, L.E. & Harwood, K.V. (2003). Dyspnea. In C.H. Yarbro, M.H. Frogge, & M. Goodman (Eds.), Cancer symptom management, 3rd Ed. (Pp. 29-46). Boston: Jones And Bartlett.   American Society of Clinical Oncology (2008). Cancer. Net: Making a world of difference in cancer care.  Retrieved from:  http://www.plwc.org  Oncology Nursing Society (2006). Cancer Symptoms. Org. Retrieved from:  http://www.cancersymptoms.org  Fabbro, E., Dalal, S., & Bruera, E. (2006). Symptom control in palliative care, part III: Dyspnea and delirium. Journal of Palliative Medicine, 9(2), 422-436.   Cancer Care (n.d.). It\'s Time to Focus on Lung Cancer. Retrieved from:  http://www.lungcancer.org Return to top \r\n\r\n This information was developed in collaboration with Michigan State University and the Behavioral Cooperative Oncology Group. \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n '