(100200500101004, 'Aldesleukin', 'Aldesleukin \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n More information Aldesleukin  (NCI Drug Dictionary) Aldesleukin  (MedlinePlus) \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n What are the other names for this drug? What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? How does this drug work? How is this drug given? What side effects can be caused by drug? What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? What are the other names for this drug? Generic name: Aldesleukin (al-des-LOO-kin) \r\nTrade name: Proleukin&#174; \r\nOther names: IL-2, Interleukin-2, r- serHuIL  What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? Aldesleukin is used to treat kidney cancer (renal cell cancer), melanoma, and skin cancer. How does this drug work? This drug is a type of cancer treatment known as "immunotherapy". In immunotherapy, the drug is given to make the body\'s immune system work better to fight cancer. Interluekin-2 may be given in your IV, or you may receive it as an injection under the skin. You or a family member may learn to give the injections, or they may be given in the doctor\'s office. How is this drug given? Aldesleukin may be given by injection under the skin (subcutaneous, SubQ) or intravenously (IV). If you are given this drug by injection, you may notice some hard bumps under your skin. Do not get the injection at the same site. Rotate the injection sites often. It may be helpful to put an ice pack on the injection site. Do this before and after the shot.  What side effects can be caused by drug? You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away. Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away. COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  \r\n\r\n  Feeling sick ( nausea  Vomiting  Diarrhea Fatigue Fever , chill   Skin change ( rash \r\n\r\n LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Chest pain, heart beats fast   Low blood pressure   Lung congestion   Swelling (feet, ankles, or other places)  \r\n\r\n SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS  Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Diarrhea  (more than 4 times in 24 hours)   Severe  rash  Extreme  fatigue  or sleepiness  Cough  and/or  shortness of breath  Dizziness,  weakness , headache, or confusion   Signs of infection ( fever  of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills  \r\n\r\n What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.   Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing.  Return to top \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n '),
(100200500102004, 'Aminoglutethimide', 'Aminoglutethimide \r\n\r\n What are the other names for this drug? What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? How does this drug work? How is this drug given? What side effects can be caused by drug? What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? What are the other names for this drug? Generic:  Aminoglutethimide (ah-mee-no-gloo-TEH-tha-mide) Trade:  Cytadren&#174;, Elipten Other names:  None  What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? Aminoglutethimide may be used to treat breast cancer and metastatic prostate cancer.  How does this drug work? This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug.  It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body.  Aminoglutethimide is in the "adrenal steroid inhibitor" group.  How is this drug given? Aminoglutethimide is taken by mouth as a pill.  What side effects can be caused by drug? You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away. Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away. COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from  neutropenia , or  anemia  Feeling sick ( nausea  Vomiting   Loss of appetite   Swelling (especially of the lower extremities)  Weakness Shortness of breath  Blurred vision   Skin change ( rash Hair loss \r\n\r\n LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS Mouth sores  Dizziness, confusion  SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS  Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Diarrhea   (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Cough   and/or  shortness of breath  Headache or confusion   Extreme  fatigue  or sleepiness   Blurred vision   Loss of balance   Strange bleeding or bruising   Black stools or stools that look like tar   Severe  rash  Signs of infection ( fever  of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills)  \r\n\r\n What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.   Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing.  Return to top \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n '),
(100200500103004, 'Bevacizumab', 'Bevacizumab \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n More information Bevacizumab  (NCI Drug Dictionary) Bevacizumab Injection  (MedlinePlus) \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n What are the other names for this drug? What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? How does this drug work? How is this drug given? What side effects can be caused by drug? What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? What are the other names for this drug? Generic name: Bevacizumab (be-va-SIZ-yoo-mab) Trade name: Avastin&#174; Other names: None  \r\n\r\n What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? Bevacizumab is not a chemotherapy drug. It may be used to treat colon or rectal cancer, breast cancer, and non-small cell lung cancer. \r\n\r\n How does this drug work? This is a monoclonal antibody directed specifically against vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF). The drug blocks the tumor\'s ability to create new blood vessels from which to get nourishment to live. This causes cell death due to lack of oxygen and nutrients. \r\n\r\n How is this drug given? Bevacizumab is given intravenously (IV). It takes about 90 minutes to give the first infusion. If your body handles the infusion well, the second infusion will be given to you in about 60 minutes. If your body handles that infusion well, the remaining infusion will be given to you in about 30 minutes.  \r\n\r\n What side effects can be caused by drug? You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away. Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away. \r\n\r\n COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from  neutropenia , or  anemia  Feeling sick ( nausea  Vomiting  Fatigue weakness Diarrhea Hair loss Rash  or peeling skin   Headache, dizziness  Pain  Nose bleeds   High blood pressure  \r\n\r\n LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS Mouth sores Fever , chills, muscle aches   Watery eyes, stuffy nose   Heart rate changes (slow or fast)   Skin irritation at IV site   Liver or kidney damage  Constipation  Blood in urine   Bleeding, blot clots   Test change:  protein in the urine  \r\n\r\n SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS  Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Shortness of breath  Extreme  fatigue  or sleepiness  Cough  and/or  shortness of breath  Dizziness,  weakness , headache, or confusion   Strange or unusual bruising or bleeding   Signs of infection ( fever  of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills)  \r\n\r\n What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.   Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing.  Return to top \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n '),
(100200500104004, 'Bleomycin', 'Bleomycin \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n More information Bleomycin  (NCI Drug Dictionary) Bleomycin  (MedlinePlus) \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n What are the other names for this drug? What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? How does this drug work? How is this drug given? What side effects can be caused by drug? What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? What are the other names for this drug? Generic name: Bleomycin (blee-oh-MYE-sin) Trade name: Blenoxane&#174; Other names: Bleomycin Sulfate What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? Bleomycin may be used to treat Hodgkin\'s and non-Hodgkin\'s lymphoma, squamous cell cancers, melanoma, sarcoma, and testicular cancer. It may also be used to treat pleural effusion. How does this drug work? This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug. It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells. There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs. Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body. Bleomycin is in the "anti-tumor antibiotics" group.  How is this drug given? Bleomycin is given intravenously (IV). It is often used with other drugs because it does not decrease bone marrow functioning. This drug can be prepared in a syringe, bag, or bottle. It takes only a few minutes to give. Tell your nurse if you are having trouble breathing, short of breath, dizziness, confusion, chest tightness, numbness, or itching. What side effects can be caused by drug? You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away. Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away. COMMON SIDE EFFECTS Fever , chills (Some patients experience  fever  and chills 6-8 hours after treatment. Tylenol taken before treatment may minimize or prevents this effect.  Fever  experienced on the day of treatment does not require the attention of a doctor.)   Vomiting   Feeling sick ( nausea  Swelling of fingers or hands   Skin changes (darkening, redness,  rash  over hands and elbows)   Nails thicken  Hair loss LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS Mouth sores  Lung toxicity (This is related to age, dose, and radiation therapy. The dose you receive is watched closely. Chest x-rays and a physical exam can be used to check your lungs.)  SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS  Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Diarrhea  (more than 4 times in 24 hours)   Strange bleeding or bruising   Black stools or stools that look like tar  Mouth sores Shortness of breath Cough  and/or  shortness of breath  Signs of infection ( fever  of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills)  What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.   Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing.  Return to top \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n '),
(100200500105004, 'Busulfan', 'Busulfan More information Busulfan  (NCI Drug Dictionary) Busulfan  (MedlinePlus) What are the other names for this drug? What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? How does this drug work? How is this drug given? What side effects can be caused by drug? What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? What are the other names for this drug? Generic name:  Busulfan  (byoo-SUL-fan) Trade name:  Busulfex&#174;, Myleran&#174; Other names:  None What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? Busulfan may be used to treat some kinds of leukemias and blood disorders. It can also be used in bone marrow transplantation.  How does this drug work? This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug.  It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body.  Busulfan is in the "alkylating agent" (L-ka-Late-ing Agent) group.  Alkylating agents damage the DNA of a cell and cancer cells are more sensitive to this type of DNA damage.  How is this drug given? Busulfan may be taken by mouth as a pill or given intravenously (IV).  What side effects can be caused by drug? You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away. Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away. COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from  neutropenia , or  anemia  Feeling sick ( nausea  Vomiting  Lack of appetite Diarrhea Sore mouth   or throat  LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Discoloration of the skin (especially in hands and nails)   Skin changes (itching or  rash  Itching  SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS  Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Diarrhea   (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Cough   and/or  shortness of breath  Yellow eyes   Extra fluid in belly (ascites), which may cause you belly to feel very full or distended   Sudden weight loss   Dizziness,  weakness , headache, or confusion   Extreme  fatigue  or sleepiness   Loss of balance   Seizures   Strange bleeding or bruising   Black stools or stools that look like tar   Signs of infection (  of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills)  What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.   Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing.  Return to top '),
(100200500106004, 'Camptothecin-11', 'Camptothecin-11 \r\n\r\n What are the other names for this drug? What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? How does this drug work? How is this drug given? What side effects can be caused by drug? What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? What are the other names for this drug? Generic name:  Camptothecin-11 (kamp-toe-THE-kin),CPT-11 Trade name:  Camptosar&#174;,Irinotecan&#174; Other names:  None  What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? Camptothecin-11 may be used to treat colon and rectal cancer. How does this drug work? This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug. It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells. There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs. Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body. Camptothecin-11 is in the "alkylating agent" (L-ka-Late-ing Agent) group. Alkylating agents damage the DNA of a cell and cancer cells are more sensitive to this type of DNA damage.  How is this drug given? CPT-11 is given intravenously (IV). Treatments are usually about 90 minutes long. NOTE:  Do not take prochlorperazine (Compazine&#174;) within 24 hours of getting Camptothecin-11.  What side effects can be caused by drug? You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away. Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away. COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from  neutropenia , or  anemia  Feeling sick ( nausea  Vomiting  Hair loss Lack of appetite Fever  Test change:  increase of blood sugar  (Check frequently if you have diabetes.)  LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Allergic Reactions (Possible signs:  sweating or flushing of face during treatment. Tell your nurse if you are having these side effects.)  Constipation  Chills  Mouth sores  Skin change ( rash  Headache   Unable to sleep   Swelling of feet and ankles  SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS  Allergic Reactions (Possible signs:   diarrhea  or belly cramping. Tell your nurse if you are having these side effects. Do not take any laxatives or stool softeners without talking to your doctor or nurse.)   Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Cough   and/or  shortness of breath  Dizziness,  weakness , headache, or confusion   Extreme  fatigue  Strange bleeding or bruising   Dark colored urine (may be a sign of dehydration)   Signs of infection ( fever  of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills)  What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.   Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing.  Return to top \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n '),
(100200500107004, 'Capecitabine', 'Capecitabine \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n More information Capecitabine  (NCI Drug Dictionary) Capecitabine  (MedlinePlus) Xeloda&#174; \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n What are the other names for this drug? What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? How does this drug work? How is this drug given? What side effects can be caused by drug? What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? What are the other names for this drug? Generic name:  Capecitabine (Cap-Site-o-Bean) Trade name: Xeloda&#174; (ZA-low-duh) Other: None What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? Capecitabine may be used to treat colon, rectal, and breast cancer. How does this drug work? This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug. It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body.  Capecitabine is in the "anti-metabolite" (ANT-I-met-TAB-o-light) group. How is this drug given? Capecitabine is taken by mouth as a pill.  Take this drug exactly as your doctor tells you to take it.  Usually, this drug is taken in twice a day, in the morning and in the evening.  Take the drug after food (within 30 minutes of a meal) and with water.  If you miss a dose, do not double the next dose.  Continue your regular dosing schedule and check with your doctor. What side effects can be caused by drug? You may have none, some, or all of the side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away. Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away. COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Low red blood cell count (increased risk for  anemia Fatigue Diarrhea   or  constipation  Hand-foot syndrome (Skin on hands and feet may turn red, peel, or be painful.)   Feeling sick ( nausea  Vomiting  Lack of appetite  Test change:  increased bilirubin  LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Low white blood cell count (increased risk of infection resulting from  neutropenia  Low platelet count (increased risk of bleeding)  Sore mouth   or throat   Skin changes (dry or itching)   Fingernail color may become darker  Pain  (stomach, chest, back, joint, or muscles)   Hair thinning  Disturbed sleep SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS  Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Diarrhea   (more than 4 times in 24 hours)   Strange bleeding or bruising   Black stools or stools that look like tar   Painful  mouth sores  Signs of infection ( fever  of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills)  What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.   Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing.  Return to top \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n '),
(100200500108004, 'Carboplatin', 'Carboplatin \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n More information Carboplatin  (NCI Drug Dictionary) Carboplatin  (MedlinePlus) \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n What are the other names for this drug? What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? How does this drug work? How is this drug given? What side effects can be caused by drug? What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? What are the other names for this drug? Generic name:  Carboplatin   (car-BO-plat-tin) Trade name:  Paraplatin&#174; Other names:  None What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? Carboplatin is used to treat many cancers. How does this drug work? This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug.  It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body.  Carboplatin is in the "alkylating agent" (L-ka-Late-ing Agent) group. How is this drug given? Carboplatin may be given intravenously (IV) or into the belly (abdomen) by special injection. What side effects can be caused by drug? You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away. Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away. COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Low blood cell counts (increased risk for infection resulting from  neutropenia anemia , or bleeding)   Feeling sick ( nausea  Vomiting   Taste change in the mouth  Hair loss Weakness  Taste change in the mouth   Test change: magnesium  LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Burning feeling at the injection site  Pain  (belly)  Diarrhea   or  constipation Sore mouth   or throat   Numbness or tingling in finger tips   Difficulty walking   Test changes:  sodium, potassium, calcium, and liver function tests  SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS  Dizziness, loss of balance, or confusion   Excessive sleepiness   Seizures   Hearing loss   Muscle cramps or twitches   Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Diarrhea   (more than 4 times in 24 hours)   Painful  mouth sores  Strange bleeding or bruising   Black stools or stools that look like tar  Cough   and/or  shortness of breath  Signs of infection ( fever  of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills)  What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.    Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing.  Return to top \r\n\r\n '),
(100200500109004, 'Carmustine', 'Carmustine \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n More information Carmustine  (NCI Drug Dictionary) Carmustine  (MedlinePlus) \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n What are the other names for this drug? What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? How does this drug work? How is this drug given? What side effects can be caused by drug? What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? What are the other names for this drug? Generic name: Carmustine (kar-MUS-teen) Trade names:  BiCNU&#174;, Becenum&#174;, Carmubris&#174; Other names: BCNU  What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? Carmustine may be used to treat brain tumors, multiple myeloma, Hodgkin\'s disease, non-Hodgkin\'s lymphomas, melanoma, lung cancer, and colon cancer. How does this drug work? This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug.  It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body.  Carmustine is in the "alkylating agent" (L-ka-Late-ing Agent) group.  Alkylating agents damage the DNA of a cell and cancer cells are more sensitive to this type of DNA damage.  How is this drug given? Carmustine is given intravenously (IV).  It takes about 30 minutes to 1 hour to infuse.  This drug could be very irritating to the skin if any leaked out from the vein.  If you feel any burning or notice a change in sensation along your arm while the drug is infusing, immediately notify a nurse. What side effects can be caused by drug? You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away. Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away. COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from  neutropenia , or  anemia  Feeling sick ( nausea  Vomiting   Loss of appetite   Headache  Shortness of breath Weakness LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Lung toxicity (The dose you receive is watched closely.  Chest x-rays and a physical exam can be used to check your lungs.)   Blurred vision, redness   Dizziness, loss of balance   Test change:  liver function tests  SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS  Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Cough   and/or  shortness of breath  Dizziness,  weakness , headache, or confusion   Extreme  fatigue  or sleepiness   Strange bleeding or bruising   Blurred vision   Yellow skin or eyes   Signs of infection ( fever  of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills)  What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.   Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing.  Return to top \r\n\r\n '),
(100200500110004, 'Cetuximab', 'Cetuximab \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n More information Cetuximab  (NCI Drug Dictionary) Cetuximab Injection  (MedlinePlus) \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n What are the other names for this drug? What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? How does this drug work? How is this drug given? What side effects can be caused by drug? What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? What are the other names for this drug? Generic name: Cetuximab (se-TUX-i-mab) Trade name: Erbitux&#174; Other names: C225  What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? Cetuximab may be used to treat colorectal cancer and squamous cell carcinoma of the head and neck. How does this drug work? Cetuximab is a recombinant monoclonal antibody that binds specifically to the epidermal growth factor receptor (EGFR) on both normal and tumor cells. Binding of Cetuximab to the EGFR results in decreased cell growth and causes cell death. How is this drug given? Before getting the infusion, you will be given Benadryl to help decrease the chance of a reaction to Cetuximab. Cetuximab is given intravenously (IV). It is a clear solution. It takes about 2 hours for the first infusion. The remaining infusions will take about 1 hour to complete. Immediately tell a nurse if you feel any  pain or a burning sensation along the vein or at the IV site. Also, tell your nurse if you are having trouble breathing, short of breath, dizziness, confusion, chest tightness, numbness, or itching. To make sure that you do not have any side effects from Eribtix, your nurse will monitor you for about 1 hour after the infusion.  What side effects can be caused by drug? You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away. Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away. COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Skin change ( rash ; looks like acne, appears mainly on face, upper chest, and back)  Fatigue Diarrhea  Feeling sick ( nausea  Vomiting  Constipation LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Lung injury (Less than half of 1% of people have experienced this effect. You will be watched closely throughout your treatment.)  SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS  Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Shortness of breath Cough   and/or  shortness of breath  Signs of infection ( fever  of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills)  What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.   Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing.  Return to top \r\n\r\n '),
