(100200500116004, 'Daunorubicin', 'Daunorubicin \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n More information Daunorubicin  (NCI Drug Dictionary) Daunorubicin  (MedlinePlus) \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n What are the other names for this drug? What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? How does this drug work? How is this drug given? What side effects can be caused by drug? What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? What are the other names for this drug? Generic name: Daunorubicin (daw-noe-ROO-bi-sin) Trade names: Cerubidine&#174;, DaunoXome&#174; Other names: Daunorubicin Hydrochloride, Daunomycin, Rubidomycin Hydrochloride What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? Daunorubicin may be used to treat different kinds of leukemias. How does this drug work? This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug. It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells. There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs. Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body. Daunorubicin is in the "antitumor antibiotics" group. How is this drug given? Daunorubicin is given intravenously (IV) through either a vein or central line. It is red. Immediately tell a nurse if you feel a burning sensation along the vein or at the IV site. Also, tell your nurse if you are having trouble breathing, short of breath, dizziness, confusion, chest tightness, numbness, or itching. What side effects can be caused by drug? You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away. Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away. COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from  neutropenia , or  anemia  Feeling sick ( nausea  Vomiting  Fatigue Hair loss  Urine may appear red, pink, or orange from the color of the drug (This generally goes away within 24 hours after treatment.)   Numbness or tingling in hands or feet  Pain  (jaw)  Weakness  Cramping  Constipation LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS Mouth sores Cough shortness of breath Pain  (belly)  Lack of appetite Fever , chills, or aches   Numbness or tingling in hands or feet   Heart toxicity (Long-term use of this drug can weaken heart muscles. The total dose you receive is watched closely.)  SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS  Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Diarrhea  (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Mouth sores  Heart beats fast  Shortness of breath  Extreme  fatigue  or sleepiness  Cough  and/or  shortness of breath  Dizziness,  weakness , headache, or confusion   Strange or unusual bruising or bleeding   Signs of infection ( fever  of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills)  What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.   Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing.  Return to top \r\n\r\n ');
