(100200500117004, 'Docetaxel', 'Docetaxel \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n More information Docetaxel  (NCI Drug Dictionary) Docetaxel  (MedlinePlus) \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n What are the other names for this drug? What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? How does this drug work? How is this drug given? What side effects can be caused by drug? What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? What are the other names for this drug? Generic name: Docetaxel (doe-se-TAKS-sel) Trade name: Taxotere&#174; Other names: None  What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? Docetaxel may be used to treat breast cancer, non-small cell lung cancer, metastatic prostate cancer, stomach cancer, and head and neck cancer. How does this drug work? This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug. It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells. There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs. Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body. Docetaxel is in the "plant alkaloid" (Plant L-ka-Loid) group. It is a topoisomerase type I inhibitors. Drugs in this group work by interfering with cancer cell enzymes, which damage and kill it. How is this drug given? Docetaxel may be given intravenously (IV) through either a vein or a central line. It takes about 60 minutes to infuse. Immediately notify a nurse if you feel a warm sensation, tightness in the chest, or itching during the infusion. Any of these signs could mean there is a possible allergic reaction to the drug. What side effects can be caused by drug? You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away. Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away. COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from  neutropenia , or  anemia  Feeling sick ( nausea  Vomiting  Diarrhea Shortness of breath Fatigue  Swelling (feet, ankles, or hands)   Sudden weight gain  Hair loss Pain  (You may experience muscle, joint, or bone  pain  for a few days following each infusion. If you do, tell your doctor or nurse. They will suggest ways to make you more comfortable.)   Nail changes (Finger and toenails may color or become soft and tender.   Numbness or tingling in hands or feet  LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Vomiting   Test change:  liver function test  SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS  Allergic reactions (Reactions are rare. Tell the nurse immediately if you feel a warm sensation, tightness in the chest, or itching during treatment.)   Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Diarrhea   (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Mouth sores Shortness of breath  Strange bleeding or bruising   Black stools or stools that look like tar   Swelling   Sudden weight gain   Extreme  fatigue  or sleepiness   Dizziness,  weakness , headache, or confusion   Loss of balance   Signs of infection ( fever  of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills)  What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.   Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing.  Return to top \r\n\r\n '),
(100200500118004, 'Doxorubicin', 'Doxorubicin \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n More information Doxorubicin  (MedlinePlus) \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n What are the other names for this drug? What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? How does this drug work? How is this drug given? What side effects can be caused by drug? What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? What are the other names for this drug? Generic name: Doxorubicin (dox-oh-ROO-bi-sin) Trade names:  Doxil&#174;, Adriamycin&#174;, Adriamycin PFS&#174;, Adriamycin RDF&#174;, Rubex&#174; Other names: Hydroxydaunomycin, Hydroxydoxorubicin, Liposomal doxorubicin What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? Doxorubicin may be used to treat many different types of cancers including:  breast, ovarian, prostate, testis, bladder, and head and neck. How does this drug work? This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug. It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells. There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs. Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body. Doxorubicin is in the "antitumor antibiotics" group. How is this drug given? Doxorubicin is given intravenously (IV). It is red. Immediately tell a nurse if you feel any  pain or a burning sensation along the vein or at the IV site. Also, tell your nurse if you are having trouble breathing, short of breath, dizziness, confusion, chest tightness, numbness, or itching. What side effects can be caused by this drug? You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away. Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away. COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from  neutropenia , or  anemia  Feeling sick ( nausea  Vomiting  Fatigue Hair loss  Urine may appear red from the color of the drug (This generally goes away within 12-24 hours after treatment.)  LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS Mouth sores  Heart toxicity (Long-term use of this drug can weaken heart muscles. The total dose you receive is watched closely.)  SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS  Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Shortness of breath  Extreme  fatigue  or sleepiness  Cough   and/or  shortness of breath  Dizziness,  weakness , headache, or confusion   Strange or unusual bruising or bleeding   Signs of infection ( fever  of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills)  What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.   Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing.  Return to top \r\n\r\n '),
