(100200500120004, 'Edrecolomab', 'Edrecolomab \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n More information Edrecolomab  (NCI Drug Dictionary) \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n What are the other names for this drug? What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? How does this drug work? How is this drug given? What side effects can be caused by drug? What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? What are the other names for this drug? Generic Name:  Monoclonal antibody 17-1A Trade Name: Panorex Other names:  MOAB 17-1A  What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? Edrecolomab may be used to treat colon cancer and breast cancer. How does this drug work? This drug is a monoclonal antibody (protein). It is capable of binding to an antigen (a specific part of a cell). Edrecolomab adheres to antigens on the surface of tumor cells, which helps the body recognize the tumor cells as foreign and destroy them.  How is this drug given? Edrecolomab is given intravenously (IV). What side effects can be caused by drug? You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away. Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away. COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Feeling sick ( nausea  Vomiting  Fever , chills   Abdominal (belly)  pain  Loss of appetite  SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS  Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Diarrhea  (more than 4 times in 24 hours)   Signs of infection ( fever  of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills)  What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.   Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to t