(100200500122004, 'Estramustine', 'Estramustine \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n More information Estramustine  (NCI Drug Dictionary) Estramustine  (MedlinePlus) \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n What are the other names for this drug? What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? How does this drug work? How is this drug given? What side effects can be caused by drug? What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? What are the other names for this drug? Generic name: Estramustine (es-tra-MUS-teen) Trade name: Emcyt&#174; Other names: Estramustine Phosphate Sodium  What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? Estramustine may be used to treat progressive prostate cancer. How does this drug work? This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body.  Estramustine is in the "antimicrotubule agent" group.  The way that Estramustine works is not completely understood.  It seems to interfere with the growth of cancer cells, which are eventually destroyed.  How is this drug given? Estramustine is taken by mouth as a capsule.  Do not take Estramustine within one hour before or two hours after meals.  Milk, milk products, calcium rich foods, and drugs must not be taken with Estramustine. What side effects can be caused by drug? You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away. Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away. COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from  neutropenia , or  anemia  Feeling sick ( nausea  Vomiting  Loss of appetite  Swelling (especially of the lower extremities)  Weakness , dizziness  Sexual dysfunction  (unable to have or maintain an erection)  LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Phlebitis (irritation of the vein)  SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS  Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Diarrhea  (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Cough  and/or  shortness of breath  Headache or confusion   Extreme  fatigue  or sleepiness   Loss of balance   Strange bleeding or bruising   Black stools or stools that look like tar   Severe  rash  Signs of infection ( fever  of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills)  What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.   Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child.  Return to top \r\n\r\n '),
