(100200500126004, '5-Fluorouracil', '5-Fluorouracil \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n More information Fluorouracil  (NCI Drug Dictionary) Fluorouracil  (MedlinePlus) \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n What are the other names for this drug? What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? How does this drug work? How is this drug given? What side effects can be caused by drug? What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? What are the other names for this drug? Generic name:  Fluorouracil (FLURE-oh-YOU\'RE-a-sill) Trade name:  Adrucil&#174;,\r\nAdrucil&#174;, Carac&#174;, Efudex&#174;, Fluoroplex&#174; Other names:  5-FU What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? 5-Fluorouracil may be used to treat colon, rectal, head and neck, breast, and ovarian cancer.  It can also be used to treat basal cell cancer of the skin.  How does this drug work? This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug.  It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body.  5-Fluorouracil is in the "anti-metabolite" (ANT-I-met-TAB-o-light) group. How is this drug given? 5-Fluorouracil may be taken by mouth as a pill, applied to the skin as a cream, or given intravenously (IV). What side effects can be caused by this drug? You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  Side effects almost always go away after treatment. Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away. COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Low blood counts (increased risk for infection resulting from  neutropenia anemia , or bleeding)  Diarrhea  Feeling sick ( nausea  Vomiting  Sore mouth   or throat  Lack of appetite  Watery eyes, bright light bothers the eyes (photophobia or light sensitivity)   Taste change in mouth (For example, some people say it tastes like metal.  LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Skin change (dry)   Hair thinning   Finger nail color may become darker   Hand-foot syndrome (Skin on hands and feet may turn red, peel, or be painful.)  SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS  Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Diarrhea   (more than 4 times in 24 hours)   Strange bleeding or bruising   Black stools or stools that look like tar   Extreme  fatigue  Painful  mouth sores  Signs of infection ( fever  of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills)  What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.   Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing.  Return to top \r\n\r\n '),
(100200500127004, 'Flutamide', 'Flutamide \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n More information Flutamide  (NCI Drug Dictionary) \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n What are the other names for this drug? What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? How does this drug work? How is this drug given? What side effects can be caused by drug? What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? What are the other names for this drug? Generic name: Flutamide (FLOO-ta-mide) Trade name: Eulexin&#174; Other names: None  What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? Flutamide may be used to treat prostate cancer. How does this drug work? This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug.  It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body.  Flutamide is in the "anti-androgen" group. The adrenal glands produce a small amount of male hormones (androgens).  Flutamide blocks the androgens from feeding the cancerous prostate cells.  It is usually given in combination with Lupron. How is this drug given? Flutamide is taken by mouth as a pill. What side effects can be caused by drug? You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away. Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away. COMMON SIDE EFFECTS Diarrhea  Impotence   Hot flashes   Breast tenderness   Test change:  liver function tests  LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Feeling sick ( nausea  Vomiting  SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS Shortness of breath , difficulty breathing   Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Diarrhea  (more than 4 times in 24 hours)   Black stools or stools that look like tar   Severe  rash  Signs of infection ( fever  of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills)  What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.   Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child.  Return to top \r\n\r\n '),
