air thinning  Disturbed sleep SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS  Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Diarrhea   (more than 4 times in 24 hours)   Strange bleeding or bruising   Black stools or stools that look like tar  Mouth sores  Signs of infection ( fever  of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills)  What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.   Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing.  Return to top \r\n\r\n '),
(100200500129004, 'Goserelin', 'Goserelin \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n More information Goserelin  (NCI Drug Dictionary) Goserelin  (MedlinePlus) \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n What are the other names for this drug? What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? How does this drug work? How is this drug given? What side effects can be caused by drug? What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? What are the other names for this drug? Generic Name:  Goserelin Accetate Trade Name:  Zoladex&#174; Other names:  None  What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? Zoladex may be used to treat advanced prostate cancer and breast cancer.  How does this drug work? This drug works by inhibiting the production of testosterone.  Initially, the drug may cause you to have an increase in your testosterone level.  As a result, your symptoms may get worse for the first few weeks of treatment.  For example, some patients may experience a temporary increase in bone pain. How is this drug given? Zoladex is given through an injection under the skin (subcutaneous, SubQ).  It is injected into the belly (abdomen) every 28 days.  Before you receive this drug, the nurse will numb the injection site with Xylocaine. What side effects can be caused by drug? You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away. Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away. COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Hot flashes   Breast tenderness   Impotence   Sluggishness   Lower urinary tract symptoms (such as frequency and burning)  Sexual dysfunction  (lack of interest, unable to have or maintain an erection, vaginal dryness)  LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS Pain  (bone)  Nausea , vomiting  Fatigue  Skin  rash  Headache  Depression Sexual dysfunction  (vaginal dryness)   Breast swelling  SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS  Chest pain, heart beats fast  Shortness of breath  Extreme  fatigue weakness  Numbness or tingling in arms or legs   Swelling (feet, ankles)  Pain , redness, or swelling in an arm or leg but not in the other   Difficulty urinating   Changes in mood or memory   Signs of infection ( fever  of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills)  What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.   Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing.  Return to top \r\n\r\n '),
(100200500130004, 'Idarubicin', 'Idarubicin \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n More information Idarubicin  (NCI Drug Dictionary) Idarubicin  (MedlinePlus) \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n What are the other names for this drug? What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? How does this drug work? How is this drug given? What side effects can be caused by drug? What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? What are the other names for this drug? Generic name: Idarubicin (eye-da-ROO-bi-cin) Trade names: Idamycin&#174;, Idamycin PFS&#174; Other names: 4-DMDR, IDA  What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? Idarubicin is may be used to treat different kinds of leukemias. How does this drug work? This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug. It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells. There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs. Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body. Idarubicin is in the "anti-neoplastic" group. How is this drug given? Idarubicin is given intravenously (IV). It is a red. This drug can be very irritating to the skin. Immediately tell a nurse if you feel any  pain  or a burning sensation in your hand, arm, or IV site.  What side effects can be caused by drug? You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away. Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away. COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from  neutropenia , or  anemia  Feeling sick ( nausea  Vomiting  Diarrhea Fatigue  Urine may appear red from the color of the drug (This generally disappears within12-24 hours after treatment.)  Hair loss LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS Mouth sores  Heart toxicity (Long-term use of this drug can weaken heart muscles. The total dose you receive is watched closely.)  SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS  Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Diarrhea   (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Shortness of breath  Extreme  fatigue  or sleepiness  Cough   and/or  shortness of breath  Dizziness,  weakness , headache, or confusion   Signs of infection ( fever  of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills)  What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.   Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing.  Return to top \r\n\r\n '),
(100200500131004, 'Ifosfamide', 'Ifosfamide \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n More information Ifosfamide  (NCI Drug Dictionary) Ifosfamide  (MedlinePlus) \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n What are the other names for this drug? What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? How does this drug work? How is this drug given? What side effects can be caused by drug? What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? What are the other names for this drug? Generic name: Ifosfamide (eye-FOSS-fa-mide) Trade names: Ifex&#174;, Cyfos&#174;, Ifosfamidum&#174; Other names: Ifosfamide, Isophosphamide  What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? Ifosfamide may be used to treat germ cell testicular cancer, bone and soft tissue sarcomas, non- Hodgkin\'s lymphoma, Hodgkin\'s disease, non-small cell and small cell lung cancer, bladder cancer, head and neck cancer, and cervical cancer. How does this drug work? This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug.  It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body.  Ifosfamide is in the "alkylating agent" (L-ka-Late-ing Agent) group. Alkylating agents damage the DNA of a cell and cancer cells are more sensitive to this type of DNA damage.   How is this drug given? Ifosfamide is given intravenously (IV).  It is a clear solution.  This drug takes about 1-2 hours to infuse. What side effects can be caused by drug? You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away. Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away. COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from  neutropenia , or  anemia  Feeling sick ( nausea  Vomiting  Lack of appetite Diarrhea LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Skin changes (itching or  rash  Dizziness, headache, or confusion  Weakness SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS  Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Diarrhea   (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Cough   and/or  shortness of breath  Dizziness, headache, or confusion   Extreme  fatigue weakness  or sleepiness   Loss of balance   Strange bleeding or bruising   Black stools or stools that look like tar   Severe  rash  Signs of infection ( fever  of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills)  What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.   Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing.  Return to top \r\n\r\n '),
(100200500132004, 'Imatinib', 'Imatinib \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n More information Imatinib  (NCI Drug Dictionary) Imatinib  (MedlinePlus) \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n What are the other names for this drug? What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? How does this drug work? How is this drug given? What side effects can be caused by drug? What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? What are the other names for this drug? Generic name: Imatinib (eye-MAT-eh-nib) Trade name: Gleevec&#174; Other names: Imatinib Mesylate, STI-571  What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? Imatinib may be used to treat certain types of leukemia and cancers that have a specific abnormality called the Philadelphia chromosome.  How does this drug work? This drug kills cells that have the Philadelphia chromosome and prevents further abnormal cells from forming. How is this drug given? Imatinib is taken as a pill by mouth. This drug is taken daily. It is kept at room temperature. What side effects can be caused by drug? You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away. Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away. COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from  neutropenia , or  anemia  Feeling sick ( nausea  Vomiting  Diarrhea Fatigue  Skin change ( rash LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Headache  Pain  (joint or belly)  Lack of appetite Shortness of breath  Muscle aches  SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS  Black, tarry, or blooding stools (Call your doctor immediately! This is an emergency!)   Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Diarrhea   (more than 4 times in 24 hours)   Severe  rash  (call your doctor or nurse)   Eyelid Swelling (call your doctor or nurse)  Shortness of breath  Extreme  fatigue  or sleepiness  Cough   and/or  shortness of breath  Dizziness,  weakness , headache, or confusion   Strange or unusual bruising or bleeding   Signs of infection ( fever  of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills)  What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.   Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing.  Return to top \r\n\r\n ');
