(100200500133004, 'Interferon alfa', 'Interferon alfa \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n More information Interferon Alfa-2a and Alfa-2b Injection  (MedlinePlus) \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n What are the other names for this drug? What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? How does this drug work? How is this drug given? What side effects can be caused by drug? What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? What are the other names for this drug? Generic name:  Interferon alfa (IN-ter-FEAR-on) Trade name:  Intron&#174;, Roferon-A&#174;  Other names:  IFN-alpha What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? Interferon alfa may be used to treat melanoma, kidney (renal cell), multiple myeloma, and some kinds of leukemia.  How does this drug work? This drug is a "biological response" or immunotherapy (EM-UN-oh-THERE-a-pee) drug.  It is called that because it helps the body\'s immune system "wipe out" or kill rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.   How is this drug given? Interferon alfa may be given by injection under the skin (subcutaneous, SubQ), into the muscle (intramuscular, IM), or intravenously (IV). What side effects can be caused by drug? You may have none, some, or all of the side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help prevent or lessen side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away. Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away. COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from  neutropenia , or  anemia  Flu-like symptoms ( fever , chills, aches, pains, headache, or  lack of appetite Hair loss  Test changes:  calcium and glucose  LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Feeling sick ( nausea  Vomiting  Diarrhea  Low blood pressure   Redness at injection site   Skin changes (dry, itching, or  rash Dry mouth , sore throat or mouth, taste change, or  cough  Feeling sad or depressed, anxious (nervous)   Dizzy or confusion   Unable to sleep   Numbness or tingling of hands or feet   Swelling of feet and ankles   Taste change in mouth (For example, some people say it tastes like metal.)  SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS Anxiety , change in mood, or confusion   Unable to sleep   Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Diarrhea  (more than 4 episodes in 24 hours)   Strange bleeding or bruising   Black stools or stools that look like tar   Persistent  fever  Swelling of feet   Sudden weight gain  What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.   Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing.  Return to top \r\n\r\n '),
(100200500134004, 'Irinotecan', 'Irinotecan \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n More information Irinotecan  (NCI Drug Dictionary) Irinotecan  (MedlinePlus) \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n What are the other names for this drug? What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? How does this drug work? How is this drug given? What side effects can be caused by drug? What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? What are the other names for this drug? Generic name: Irinotecan (eye-rye-no-TEE-can) Trade name: Camptosar&#174; Other names: Camptothecin-11, CPT-11  What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? Irinotecan is may be used to treat colon or rectal cancer. How does this drug work? This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug. It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells. There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs. Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body. Irinotecan is in the "plant alkaloid" (Plant L-ka-Loid) group. It is a topoisomerase type I inhibitors. Drugs in this group work by interfering with cancer cell enzymes, which damage and kill it.  How is this drug given? Irinotecan is given intravenously (IV) through either a vein or central line. It takes about 90 minutes to infuse. DO NOT use Compazine within 24 hours of taking this chemotherapy. What side effects can be caused by drug? You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away. Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away. COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from  neutropenia , or  anemia  Low red blood cells or platelets   Feeling sick ( nausea  Vomiting  Diarrhea  or  abdominal (belly) cramping  Shortness of breath Weakness fatigue Fever , chills  Hair loss  Test change:  elevations of blood sugar (Check frequently if you have diabetes.)  LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS Mouth sores Cough Constipation Disturbed sleep  Skin change ( rash Pain  (gas in the belly)   Swelling of feet and ankles  SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS  Allergic Reactions (Possible signs:  sweating, flushing, belly cramping, or  diarrhea . Tell your nurse if you are having these side effects.)   Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Diarrhea  and abdominal (belly) cramping  Cough  and/or  shortness of breath  Dizziness,  weakness , headache, or confusion   Extreme  fatigue  or sleepiness   Strange bleeding or bruising   Signs of infection ( fever  of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills)  NOTE:   Diarrhea  is common and can be severe. Begin taking Loperamide (a prescription that will be given to you) at the first sign of poorly formed stools, loose stools, or an increase in the number of stools (i.e., 1-2 stools above normal in a single day.) Take 4 mg (2 tablets) of Loperamide at the first sign of  diarrhea . Then take 2 mg (1 tablet) every 2 hours around-the-clock until you are free of symptoms for at least 12 hours. Drink plenty of fluids to prevent dehydration -- at least 8 glasses each day. Notify your doctor\'s nurse if you have any of these problems or abdominal cramping. DO NOT take any laxatives or stool softeners without consulting the doctor. What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.   Have used Compazine (Procholorperazine). You should not use Compazine (Procholorperazine) within 24 hours after taking this chemotherapy.   Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing.  Return to top \r\n\r\n '),
(100200500135004, 'Leucovorin', 'Leucovorin \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n More information Leucovorin  (NCI Drug Dictionary) Leucovorin  (MedlinePlus) \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n What are the other names for this drug? What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? How does this drug work? How is this drug given? What side effects can be caused by drug? What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? What are the other names for this drug? Generic name: Leucovorin (loo-koe-VOR-in) Trade name: Wellcovorin&#174; Other names: Calcium Leucovorin, Citrovorum Factor, Folinic Acid, 5-formyl tetrahydrofolate What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? Leucovorin is not a chemotherapy drug.  It is may be used with Fluorouracil to treat colon and rectal cancer, head and neck cancer, esophageal, and other cancers of the gastrointestinal tract. You may also receive this as a "rescue" medicine beginning 24 hours after receiving Methotrexate.  How does this drug work? This drug may be used to prevent harmful effects of chemotherapy drugs. Leucovorin or folic acid is a vitamin that rescues normal cells from the toxic effects of Methotrexate. How is this drug given? Leucovorin is may be taken by mouth as a pill or given intravenously (IV).  What side effects can be caused by drug? You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away. Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away. COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from  neutropenia , or  anemia  Feeling sick ( nausea  Vomiting  Diarrhea LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Skin changes (itching or  rash SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS  Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Diarrhea   (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Cough   and/or  shortness of breath  Dizziness,  weakness , headache, or confusion   Extreme  fatigue  or sleepiness   Loss of balance   Strange bleeding or bruising   Black stools or stools that look like tar   Severe  rash  Signs of infection ( fever  of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills)  What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.   Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing.  Return to top \r\n\r\n '),
