n  (bone, joint, or muscle)   Headache   Test change:  magnesium  SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS  Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Cough  and/or  shortness of breath  Dizziness,  weakness , headache, or confusion   Extreme  fatigue  or sleepiness   Strange bleeding or bruising   Signs of infection ( fever  of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills)  What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.   Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing.  Return to top \r\n\r\n '),
(100200500144004, 'Pemetrexed', 'Pemetrexed \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n More information Pemetrexed Disodium (NCI Drug Dictionary) Pemetrexed Injection  (MedlinePlus) Alimta&#174; \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n What are the other names for this drug? What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? How does this drug work? How is this drug given? What side effects can be caused by drug? What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? What are the other names for this drug? Generic name:  Pemetrexed (Pem-A-trex-ed) \r\nTrade name:  Alimta&#174; (A-LIM-ta) Other:  None What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? Pemetrexed may be is used to treat non-small cell lung cancer and malignant mesothelioma. How does this drug work? This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug.  It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body.  Pemetrexed is in the "anti-metabolite" (ANT-I-met-TAB-o-light) group.  How is this drug given? Pemetrexed is given intravenously (IV).  What side effects can be caused by this drug? You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  Side effects almost always go away after treatment. Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away. COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Low white blood cell count (increased risk for infection resulting from  neutropenia  Low red blood cell count (increased risk for  anemia  Feeling sick ( nausea  Vomiting  Lack of appetite Fatigue Constipation Shortness of breath , hard to breathe, or wheezing  LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Low platelet count (increased risk for bleeding)  Sore mouth  or throat   Flu-like symptoms ( fever , chills, aches and  pain  Numb or tingling hands or feet  Depression  (feeling sad)   Skin change ( rash  Test change: creatinine  SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS  Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours)   Strange bleeding or bruising   Black stools or stools that look like tar   Blood in urine   Pain  and burning when urinating   Extreme  fatigue Depression  that interferes with your ability to carry out daily activities   Signs of infection ( fever  of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills)  What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.    Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing.  Return to top \r\n\r\n '),
(100200500145004, 'Sargramostim', 'Sargramostim \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n More information Sargramostim  (NCI Drug Dictionary) Sargramostim  (MedlinePlus) \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n What are the other names for this drug? What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? How does this drug work? How is this drug given? What side effects can be caused by drug? What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? What are the other names for this drug? Generic name:  Sargramostim (sar-GRAM-oh-stim) Trade name:  Leukine&#174; Other:  GM-CSF, Granulocyte-Macrophage Colony Stimulating Factor What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? Sargramostim is not used to treat cancer. It is used to help decrease the risk of infection.  How does this drug work? This drug is speeds up the recovery of the white blood cells (WBC) after chemotherapy. If you are taking Sargramostim at home, keep it in the refrigerator. Do not freeze it. Write the date on the bottle when you open it. After opening, the bottle can be kept in the refrigerator for 20 days. Throw it away after 20 days, even if there is still medicine left in the bottle. How is this drug given? Sargramostim may be given intravenously (IV) or injection under the skin (subcutaneous, SubQ). Blood tests are done to check your response. What side effects can be caused by this drug? You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. Side effects almost always go away after treatment.  Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away. COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Feeling sick ( nausea  Vomiting  Diarrhea Fatigue   or  weakness  Swelling or redness at injection site   Heart beats fast   Lightheadedness or flushing  Hair loss LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS Pain  (bone, muscle, joint)  Fever  Headache, generalized aches and pains   Swelling in your hands and feet  SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS  Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Diarrhea   (more than 4 times in 24 hours)   Extreme  fatigue  Signs of infection ( fever  of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills)  What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.   Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing.  Return to top \r\n\r\n '),
(100200500146004, 'Tamoxifen', 'Tamoxifen \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n More information Tamoxifen  (NCI Drug Dictionary) Tamoxifen  (MedlinePlus) \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n What are the other names for this drug? What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? How does this drug work? How is this drug given? What side effects can be caused by drug? What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? What are the other names for this drug? Generic:  Tamoxifen Trade:  Nolvadex&#174; Other names:  Tamoxifeni Citras  What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? Tamoxifen may be used to treat breast cancer. It may also be prescribed for treatment of ovarian cancer. How does this drug work? This drug is an anti-estrogen that prevents or slows down breast cancer growth. Most doctors believe it prevents breast cancer cells from getting the estrogen they need to grow. How is this drug given? Tamoxifen is taken by mouth as a pill. What side effects can be caused by drug? You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away. Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away. COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Vaginal spotting   Menstrual irregularities   Headaches or dizziness   Leg cramps   Temporary "FLARE" of breast cancer symptoms   Hot Flashes  LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Chest Pains  Shortness of breath  Pain, swelling, or redness in an arm or leg  SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS Cough  and/or  shortness of breath  Chest  pain  Pain, redness, or swelling in an arm or leg but not in the other   Changes in breasts  Depression  Blurred vision   Strange bleeding or bruising  What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.   Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing.  Return to top \r\n\r\n '),
(100200500147004, 'Thioguanine', 'Thioguanine \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n More information Thioguanine  (NCI Drug Dictionary) Thioguanine  (MedlinePlus) \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n What are the other names for this drug? What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? How does this drug work? How is this drug given? What side effects can be caused by drug? What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? What are the other names for this drug? Generic name: Thioguanine (thye-oh-GWAH-neen) Trade name: Thioguanine Tabloid&#174; Other names: 6-TG, TG, 6-Thioguanine, 2-Amino-6-Mercaptopurine What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? Thioguanine may be used to treat leukemia. How does this drug work? This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug.  It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body.  Thioguanine is in the "anti-metabolite" (ANT-I-met-TAB-o-light) group. How is this drug given? Thioguanine is taken by mouth as a pill.  The pill is pale yellow in color.  It is usually suggested that this drug be taken between meals.  This will help your body completely absorb it.  Your doctor will give you specific instructions in how to take this drug. What side effects can be caused by drug? You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away. Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away. COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from  neutropenia , or  anemia  Feeling sick ( nausea  Vomiting   Loss of appetite  Shortness of breath Weakness  Headache   Skin change (darkening)   Test change:  liver function tests  LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS Mouth sores Fatigue SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS Shortness of breath  Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Diarrhea  (more than 4 times in 24 hours)   Black stools or stools that look like tar   Difficulty urinating ( pain  or red)  Pain  (belly, joints)  Cough , sore throat   Yellow skin or eyes   Dizziness,  weakness , headache, or confusion   Extreme  fatigue  or sleepiness   Strange bleeding or bruising   Swelling (feet, legs)   Signs of infection ( fever  of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills)  What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.   Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing.  Return to top \r\n\r\n '),
(100200500148004, 'Topotecan', 'Topotecan \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n More information Topotecan  (NCI Drug Dictionary) Topotecan  (MedlinePlus) \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n What are the other names for this drug? What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? How does this drug work? How is this drug given? What side effects can be caused by drug? What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? What are the other names for this drug? Generic name: Topotecan (toe-poe-TEE-kan) Trade name: Hycamtin&#174; Other names: None  What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? Topotecan may be used to treat ovarian cancer and small cell lung cancer.  It is also used in combination with other medications to treat cervical cancer.  How does this drug work? This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug.  It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells.  There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs.  Topotecan is in the "plant alkaloid" (Plant L-ka-Loid) group.  It is a topoisomerase type I inhibitors.  Drugs in this group work by interfering with cancer cell enzymes, which damage and kill it.  How is this drug given? Topotecan is given intravenously (IV). It is a clear solution.  What side effects can be caused by drug? You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away. Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away. COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from  neutropenia , or  anemia  Feeling sick ( nausea  Vomiting  Diarrhea LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS Cough shortness of breath  Skin changes (itching or  rash Constipation Fatigue  or  weakness Fever Pain  (belly, back, or bone)  Lack of appetite Mouth sores  Headache  Hair loss SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS  Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Diarrhea  (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Cough  and/or  shortness of breath  Dizziness,  weakness , headache, or confusion   Extreme  fatigue  or sleepiness   Loss of balance   Strange bleeding or bruising   Black stools or stools that look like tar   Severe  rash  Signs of infection ( fever  of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills)  What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.   Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing.  Return to top \r\n\r\n '),
(100200500149004, 'Vincristine', 'Vincristine \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n More information Vincristine  (NCI Drug Dictionary) Vincristine  (MedlinePlus) \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n What are the other names for this drug? What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? How does this drug work? How is this drug given? What side effects can be caused by drug? What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? What are the other names for this drug? Generic name:  Vincristine (vin-KRIS-teen) Trade name:  Oncovin&#174;, Vincasar&#174; Other names:  LCR, VCR, Vincristine Sulfate  What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? Vincristine is used to treat many cancers.  How does this drug work? This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug. It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells. There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs. Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body. Vincristine is in the "alkylating agent" (L-ka-Late-ing Agent) group. Alkylating agents damage the DNA of a cell and cancer cells are more sensitive to this type of DNA damage.  How is this drug given? Vincristine is given intravenously (IV).  What side effects can be caused by this drug? You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. Side effects almost always go away after treatment.   Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away. COMMON SIDE EFFECTS Hair loss LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from  neutropenia , or  anemia  Feeling sick ( nausea  Vomiting  Diarrhea Lack of appetite Mouth sores Weakness  Weight loss   Numbness or tingling in the hands and feet  Constipation SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS  Heart problems (fast or irregular heartbeats)  Mouth sores  Severe stomach  pain  Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Diarrhea  (more than 4 times in 24 hours)   Black stools or stools that look like tar  Constipation  Unable to urinate   Strange bleeding or bruising   Signs of infection ( fever  of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills)  What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.   Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing.  Return to top \r\n\r\n ');
