(100200500150004, 'Vindesine', 'Vindesine \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n More information Vindesine  (NCI Drug Dictionary) \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n What are the other names for this drug? What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? How does this drug work? How is this drug given? What side effects can be caused by drug? What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? What are the other names for this drug? Generic name: Vindesine  Trade name: Eldisine&#174; Other names: Vindesine Sulfate, Desacetyl Vinblastine Amide  What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? Vindesine may be used to treat lung cancer and leukemia. How does this drug work? This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug. It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells. There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs. Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body. Vindesine is in the "antineoplastic agent" group. How is this drug given? Vindesine is given intravenously (IV) as a short infusion. Immediately tell a nurse if you feel any  pain  or a burning sensation along the vein or at the IV site.  What side effects can be caused by drug? You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away. Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away. COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from  neutropenia , or  anemia  Feeling sick ( nausea  Vomiting  Fatigue Hair loss LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Numbness or tingling in hands or feet  Pain  (jaw)   Cramping (belly)  Constipation SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS  Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Shortness of breath  Extreme  fatigue  or sleepiness  Cough  and/or  shortness of breath  Dizziness,  weakness , headache, or confusion   Strange or unusual bruising or bleeding   Signs of infection ( fever  of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills)  What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.   Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing.  Return to top \r\n\r\n '),
(100200500151004, 'Vinorelbine', 'Vinorelbine \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n More information Vinorelbine  (NCI Drug Dictionary) Vinorelbine  (MedlinePlus) \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n What are the other names for this drug? What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? How does this drug work? How is this drug given? What side effects can be caused by drug? What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? What are the other names for this drug? Generic name: Vinorelbine (vi-NOR-el-been) Trade name: Navelbine&#174; Other names: Vinorelbine Tartrate What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? Vinorelbine may be used to treat non-small cell lung cancer. It may also be prescribed for treatment of breast cancer, ovarian cancer, or Hodgkin\'s disease. How does this drug work? This drug is a chemotherapy (KEEM-o-TH-AIR-a-pee) drug. It "wipes out" or kills rapidly dividing cells, such as cancer cells. There are many kinds of chemotherapy drugs. Doctors divide these drugs into different groups based on how they affect cells in the body. Oxaliplatin is in the "alkylating agent" (L-ka-Late-ing Agent) group. Alkylating agents damage the DNA of a cell and cancer cells are more sensitive to this type of DNA damage.  How is this drug given? Vinorelbine is given intravenously (IV) as a rapid infusion. Immediately tell a nurse if you feel any  pain  or a burning sensation along the vein or at the IV site.  What side effects can be caused by drug? You may have none, some, or all side effects listed. Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here. There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects. After treatment, side effects almost always go away. Some side effects are more serious than others. Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away. COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from  neutropenia , or  anemia  Feeling sick ( nausea  Vomiting  Fatigue Hair loss  Numbness or tingling in hands or feet  Pain  (jaw)  Weakness  Cramping  Constipation SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS  Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Diarrhea  (more than 4 times in 24 hours)   Severe  constipation Shortness of breath  Extreme  fatigue  or sleepiness  Cough  and/or  shortness of breath  Dizziness,  weakness , headache, or confusion   Strange or unusual bruising or bleeding   Signs of infection ( fever  of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills)  What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.   Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing.  Return to top \r\n\r\n '),
(100200500152004, 'Zoledronic acid', 'Zoledronic acid \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n More information Zoledronic acid  (NCI Drug Dictionary) Zoledronic acid  (MedlinePlus) \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n What are the other names for this drug? What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? How does this drug work? How is this drug given? What side effects can be caused by drug? What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? What are the other names for this drug? Generic name: Zoledronic acid (ZOE-le-dron-ik-AS-id) Trade names: Zometa&#174;, Reclast&#174; Other names: None  What types of cancers is this drug used to treat? Zometa is not a chemotherapy drug.  It is used as a support medication to treat high blood calcium levels and bone diseases in cancer patients.  How does this drug work? This drug is a bisphosphonate.  It is given to slow the bone destroying activity of bone metastasis and to strengthen bones. How is this drug given? Zometa is given intravenously (IV). It takes 15-30 minutes to infuse.  Before you receive this drug, your doctor may have some lab work done to check your kidney function and/or calcium.  Your doctor may have you take a calcium supplement of 500 mg and a multi-vitamin with 400 IU of Vitamin D per day.  Try to drink extra water the day before, the day of, and the day after your infusion. What side effects can be caused by drug? You may have none, some, or all side effects listed.  Or, you may have side effects that are not listed here.  There are many ways to help lessen or prevent side effects.  After treatment, side effects almost always go away. Some side effects are more serious than others.  Your doctor or nurse will tell you what side effects they need to know about right away. COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Low blood cell counts (increased risk of bleeding, infection resulting from  neutropenia , or  anemia Fever , chills, aches, and  pain  (bone, joint, or muscle)   Redness and swelling at the injection site   Test changes:  magnesium, phosphorus, and calcium  LESS COMMON SIDE EFFECTS  Feeling sick ( nausea  Vomiting  SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS  Vomiting (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Diarrhea  (more than 4 times in 24 hours)  Cough  and/or  shortness of breath  Dizziness, headache, or confusion   Extreme  fatigue weakness , or sleepiness   Signs of infection ( fever  of 101.0 degrees Farenheit or higher, chills)  What should I tell my doctor before taking this drug? Before taking this drug, make sure to tell your doctor if you:  Have any allergies.   Are taking any other drugs, such as over-the-counter drugs, vitamins, or herbal products.   Are thinking about having a child or have a partner that could become pregnant. This drug may be unsafe to the pregnancy. Ask your doctor about when it might be safe to have a child. Women choosing to breastfeed should talk to their doctor before nursing.  Return to top \r\n\r\n '),
(1003001006000001, 'What is lack of appetite?', 'What is lack of appetite? You have lack of appetite when you do not feel hungry, even though you have not eaten as much as usual. '),
(1003001006000002, 'How do people describe lack of appetite?', 'When you have lack of appetite... ...you do not feel like eating much, maybe not at all. You may also feel full faster than usual or feel a bad taste in your mouth. '),
(1003001006000003, 'What causes lack of appetite?', 'What causes lack of appetite? You may have lack of appetite as a result of your cancer or your cancer treatment. Also related to lack of appetite are nausea/vomiting, pain, and fatigue. '),
(1003001006100000, 'Lack of Appetite-Manage', 'What can I do about my lack of appetite? First, how bad is your lack of appetite? Read these statements and click on the ONE that best describes your lack of appetite today: '),
(1003001006200001, 'How can I talk to my doctor about my lack of appetite?', 'How can I talk to my doctor about my lack of appetite? Tell your doctor when you started losing your appetite and how it has gotten worse. Explain how your lack of appetite is affecting your quality of life. If you cannot eat, tell your doctor for how many days, and how much weight you believe you have lost. Your doctor will also want to hear if you are having other symptoms: dizziness, mental confusion, nausea or vomiting, diarrhea, constipation, depression, anxiety, or severe weakness to the point that you can hardly get out of bed. If you have not had any fluids (water or other) for a day or longer, you must also tell your doctor. '),
(1003001006200002, 'What questions can I ask my doctor?', 'What questions can I ask my doctor? How can I change my diet so that I will feel like eating again? How much food should I have each day? Why do I have a bad taste in my mouth? How much longer will I still have it? I am losing weight. What is the solution? What are my options? '),
(1003001006300001, 'More_Information', 'National Cancer Institute:  Nutrition PDQ www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/nutrition/Patient \r\n\r\n National Cancer Institute:  Eating Hints www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/eatinghints (a book about cancer nutrition) \r\n\r\n American Cancer Society:  Nutrition for the Person with Cancer During Treatment www.cancer.org/treatment/survivorshipduringandaftertreatment/nutritionforpeoplewithcancer/nutritionforthepersonwithcancer/index \r\n\r\n American Cancer Society:  Changes in Appetite www.cancer.org/treatment/survivorshipduringandaftertreatment/nutritionforpeoplewithcancer/nutritionforthepersonwithcancer/nutrition-during-treatment-poor-appetite \r\n\r\n American Cancer Society:  Eating When You Have No Appetite www.cancer.org/cancer/news/features/eating-when-you-have-no-appetite '),
(1003001009001001, 'What is constipation?', 'What is constipation? You are constipated when your bowel movements are rare, incomplete, or painful or when you have had no bowel movement for three days. '),
(1003001009001002, 'When you are constipated', '\nWhen you are constipated... ...you may feel bloated or have a sense of fullness in the rectal area. '),
(1003001009001003, 'What causes constipation?', 'What causes constipation? Constipation may be the result of the cancer itself or of the pain medication you are taking. Other causes include stress, fever, or changes in your diet. You may also get constipated if you do little physical activity or do not drink enough fluids. '),
(1003001009100000, 'constipation-Manage', 'What can I do about my constipation? General management goals and strategies First, how bad is your constipation? Read these statements and click on the ONE that best describes your constipation today: '),
(1003001009200001, 'How can I talk to my doctor about my constipation?', 'How can I talk to my doctor about my constipation? Report to your doctor if any of these apply to you: No bowel movement for 3 or more days No bowel movement within 24 hours of taking a laxative No eating for 2 or more days Very hard, small, bloody, or black stools; painful bowel movements or severe abdominal pain Vomiting or bloating with the constipation for over 24 hours A greater need to urinate than usual - or the opposite: urinating less frequently Back pain Hemorrhoids or torn skin around the rectum Have your symptom log at hand with the following information: Your normal bowel movements, including a history of any past problems you have had with constipation The date when your constipation started All foods and fluids you have taken in the last couple of days All medications that you have taken in the last 3 days, including any over-the-counter medications that you have tried for your constipation '),
(1003001009200002, 'What questions can I ask my doctor?', 'What questions can I ask my doctor? What is causing my constipation? Is it my pain medications or my chemotherapy? What type of physical activity can I do to help? Should I take fiber supplements? Is it safe to take over-the-counter products? Which ones do you recommend? Are there any other medications that can help? '),
(1003001009300001, 'More_Information', 'National Cancer Institute:  Gastrointestinal Complications www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/gastrointestinalcomplications/Patient \r\n\r\n\r\n National Cancer Institute:  Nutrition PDQ - Constipation www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/nutrition/Patient/Page5#Section_341 \r\n\r\n National Cancer Institute:  Eating Hints - Constipation www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/eatinghints/page4#constipation \r\n\r\n American Cancer Society:  Nutrition for the Person with Cancer During Treatment - Constipation www.cancer.org/treatment/survivorshipduringandaftertreatment/nutritionforpeoplewithcancer/nutritionforthepersonwithcancer/nutrition-during-treatment-constipation \r\n\r\n University of California Davis Cancer Center:  Food Diary Form www.ucdmc.ucdavis.edu/CANCER/pedresource/pedres_docs/FoodDiary.pdf \r\n\r\n Cancer.net:  Constipation www.cancer.net/all-about-cancer/treating-cancer/managing-side-effects/constipation '),
(1003001018001001, 'What is diarrhea?', 'What is diarrhea? You have diarrhea when you have three or more loose or watery bowel movements per day. '),
(1003001018001002, 'When you have diarrhea', 'When you have diarrhea... ...you have an urgent need to have a bowel movement and usually cannot control it. You may also have abdominal pain with cramping, bloating, or nausea. The area around your anus may be irritated and sore. '),
(1003001018001003, 'What causes diarrhea?', 'What causes diarrhea? The cause may be either the cancer or the cancer treatment, especially chemotherapy or radiation. You may have diarrhea immediately after your treatment or up to two weeks after treatment. Antibiotics or laxatives can also cause diarrhea. '),
(1003001018100000, 'diarrhea-Manage', 'What can I do about my diarrhea? General management goals and strategies. First, how bad is your diarrhea? Read these statements and click on the ONE that best describes your diarrhea today: '),
(1003001018200001, 'How can I talk to my doctor about my diarrhea?', 'How can I talk to my doctor about my diarrhea? Report to your doctor if any of these apply to you: Diarrhea for 3 or more days Temperature above 101&#176;F (38.3&#176;C) for 2 or more hours Bloody or black stools Torn, sore, or tender skin around the anus No eating for more than 24 hours; excessive thirst Feeling tired, dizzy, or weak. Urinating less often than usual; dark urine Severe abdominal cramps or pain with diarrhea Heart palpitations (a racing heart when you are at rest) Have your symptom log at hand with the following information: Your normal bowel movements, including a history of any past problems you have had with diarrhea The date when your diarrhea started Color, consistency, and number of bowel movements in the last 24 hours All foods and fluids you have taken in the last couple of days All medications that you have taken in the last 3 days, including any over-the-counter medications that you have tried for your constipation If you are being treated with radiation therapy to the pelvis, abdomen, or rectum Weight loss '),
(1003001018200002, 'What questions can I ask my doctor?', 'What questions can I ask my doctor? What causes my diarrhea? Is it the chemotherapy or my radiation? If so, how long does it usually last? How can I control it?  How should I change my diet to help control my diarrhea? What medications are okay for me to take? When do you want me to contact you if I develop diarrhea? '),
(1003001018300001, 'More_Information', 'National Cancer Institute:  Gastrointestinal Complications-Diarrhea www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/gastrointestinalcomplications/Patient/page5 \r\n\r\n National Cancer Institute:  Nutrition PDQ-Diarrhea www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/nutrition/Patient/page5#Keypoint45 \r\n\r\n National Cancer Institute:  What to do When You Have Loose Stools www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/radiation-side-effects/diarrhea.pdf \r\n\r\n American Cancer Society:  Entry on Diarrhea www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/physicalsideeffects/dealingwithsymptomsathome/caring-for-the-patient-with-cancer-at-home-diarrhea \r\n\r\n Mayo Clinic:  Diarrhea: Cancer Related Causes and How to Cope www.mayoclinic.com/health/diarrhea/CA00040 '),
(1003001027001001, 'What is fatigue?', 'What is fatigue? You are fatigued when you have an overwhelming sense of being tired that makes it hard for you to do physical or mental work, even when you seem to have had enough sleep (usually 7-8 hours). '),
(1003001027001002, 'When you are fatigued', 'When you are fatigued... ...you feel tired, weak, slow, or unable to concentrate. You may also feel sad, irritable, or frustrated. Your arms and legs may feel unusually heavy. '),
(1003001027001003, 'What causes fatigue?', 'What causes fatigue? Fatigue may be the result of the cancer itself or of stress, depression, or anxiety. Other causes include anemia (low red-blood cell count) and infection. \r\n\r\nFatigue is the most common side effect of cancer treatment. You will be fatigued during and after your treatment, and the feeling often lasts for months after treatment ends.  It should always be reported to your physician. '),
(1003001027100000, 'What can I do about my fatigue?', 'What can I do about my fatigue? General management goals and strategies. First, how bad is your fatigue? Read these statements and click on the ONE that best describes your fatigue today: '),
(1003001027200001, 'How should I talk to my doctor about my fatigue?', 'How should I talk to my doctor about my fatigue? Take your fatigue log with you. Explain when your fatigue started, how it has progressed, what makes it better or worse, and how it affects your daily activities. Report to your doctor if any of these apply to you: You have a temperature above 101&#176;F (38.3&#176;C) for more than two hours. You cannot get out of bed or walk to the bathroom for 24 hours. You cannot think clearly, cannot concentrate, or cannot even watch TV, read, or talk. You cannot do any important daily activities. You feel very weak or exhausted for two or more days. You are dizzy or lose balance. You have trouble breathing when you do your regular activities for 24 hours. \r\n\r\n Discuss with your doctor the factors commonly associated with fatigue that can be managed: anemia, infection, sleep, nutritional problems, emotional distress/depression, pain, and other illnesses or medications. \r\n\r\n Ask your doctor if it is possible that you might be depressed. Antidepressants can improve your mood, energy levels, and outlook on life, but they are not always indicated. Counseling may also help with depression or anxiety. '),
(1003001027200002, 'What questions can I ask my doctor?', 'What questions can I ask my doctor? What is causing my fatigue? Is it my cancer treatment? How long will my fatigue last after I am done with treatment? How can I manage my fatigue? Do I need to change my diet? Do I need any supplements? Should I get a physical therapist to help me develop an exercise plan? What relaxation techniques do you recommend? Are there any medications that can help with my fatigue? '),
(1003001027300001, 'More_Information', 'National Cancer Institute:  What To Do When You Feel Weak or Tired (Fatigue) www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/radiation-side-effects/fatigue.pdf \r\n\r\n National Cancer Institute:  Fatigue PDQ www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/fatigue/Patient \r\n\r\n National Cancer Institute:  Fatigue PDQ Section on Treatments for Fatigue www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/fatigue/Patient/page4 \r\n\r\n American Cancer Society:  Feeling Tired vs. Cancer Related Fatigue www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/physicalsideeffects/fatigue/feeling-tired-vs-cancer-related-fatigue \r\n\r\n American Cancer Society:  7 Ways to Manage Cancer Related Fatigue www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/physicalsideeffects/fatigue/seven-ways-to-manage-cancer-related-fatigue \r\n\r\n '),
(1003001039001001, 'What are mouth sores?', 'What are mouth sores? Mouth sores occur when the lining of the mouth, tongue, and throat becomes irritated, swollen or painful. You may have open sores (called "ulcers"). '),
(1003001039001002, 'When you have mouth sores', 'When you have mouth sores... ...your mouth may feel uncomfortably warm, may tingle or be sore. Your mouth may feel unusually dry and you may have a raw feeling in your throat. '),
(1003001039001003, 'What causes mouth sores?', 'What causes mouth sores? Half of cancer patients on chemotherapy and most patients who have radiation to the head or neck will have mouth discomfort as a side effect of treatment. This is how you may expect mouth sores to develop relative to your chemotherapy: 3-5 days after starting treatment: warm mouth; tingling/soreness 1-2 weeks after starting treatment: first sores 1-2 weeks after finishing treatment: sores begin to heal 3+ weeks after finishing treatment: sores and pain have disappeared '),
(1003001039100000, 'What can I do about my mouth sores?', 'What can I do about my mouth sores? General management goals and strategies: First, how bad are your mouth sores? Read these statements and click on the ONE that best describes your mouth sores today: '),
(1003001039200001, 'How should I talk to my doctor about my mouth sores?', 'How should I talk to my doctor about my mouth sores? Tell your doctor... ...if you have sores or new red/white patches in your mouth or on your tongue. ...if you have not been able to eat any food for 24 hours. ...if you have lost 5 or more pounds in one week. ...if you have signs of infection (especially pus) on your tongue ...if you have a temperature above 101&#176;F (38.3&#176;C). '),
(1003001039200002, 'What questions can I ask my doctor?', 'What questions can I ask my doctor? What causes my mouth sores? Is it my cancer treatment? How should I manage my daily mouth care? Should I consult with a dietitian to help me choose foods? What medications can I use for pain? How often should I use them? '),
(1003001039300001, 'More_Information', 'National Cancer Institute:  Oral Complications of Chemotherapy and Head/Neck Radiation PDQ www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/oralcomplications/Patient National Cancer Institute:  What To Do When Your Mouth or Throat Hurts www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/radiation-side-effects/mouthandthroat.pdf American Cancer Society:  Mouth or Throat Pain or Sores www.cancer.org/treatment/survivorshipduringandaftertreatment/nutritionforpeoplewithcancer/nutritionforthepersonwithcancer/nutrition-during-treatment-mouth-throat-pain-or-sores American Cancer Society:  Getting Help for Mouth Sores www.cancer.org/acs/groups/content/@editorial/documents/document/acspc-031609.pdf Mayo Clinic:  Mouth Sores Caused by Cancer: How to Cope www.mayoclinic.com/health/mouth-sores/CA00054 Indiana University School of Dentistry:  Oral Health Care for Cancer Patients www.iusd.iupui.edu/OHCCP/ '),
(1003001042001001, 'What is nausea?', 'What is nausea? Nausea is an unpleasant feeling in the back of your throat and in your stomach that can lead to vomiting.  '),
(1003001042001002, 'When you have nausea', 'When you have nausea... ...you feel queasy or sick to your stomach. It may feel like heartburn, or as though you have butterflies in your stomach. You may have an unpleasant reaction to food or smells. There may even be a bitter or acidic taste in your mouth. '),
(1003001042001003, 'What causes nausea?', 'What causes nausea? Nausea is caused by your cancer treatment or by the cancer itself. '),
(1003001042100000, 'What can I do about my nausea?', 'What can I do about my nausea? General management goals and strategies First, how bad is your nausea? Read these statements and click on the ONE that best describes your nausea today: '),
(1003001042200001, 'How should I talk to my doctor about my nausea?', 'How should I talk to my doctor about my nausea? Report all of the following: A temperature above 101&#176;F (38.3&#176;C) for 2 hours or longer Three or more vomiting episodes per hour for more than 6 hours Vomiting episodes several times a day for 2 or more days Blood in your vomit or projectile vomiting (vomiting that ejects stomach contents with great force) Weight loss of 2 or more pounds in a day No eating for 24 hours Inability to keep fluids down for 12 hours (with or without the use of anti-nausea medicines) Shortness of breath at rest Abdominal pain or bloating with nausea Cold and clammy skin Dizziness/confusion Dark yellow urine or very little urine (signs of dehydration) '),
(1003001042200002, 'What questions can I ask my doctor?', 'What questions can I ask my doctor? What medications can I take before my chemotherapy that will prevent nausea or vomiting? Which of my chemotherapy medications are likely to give me nausea or vomiting? What will my anti-nausea medication schedule be after treatment? What should I eat before and after treatment? If I am staying at the hospital overnight, should I bring any food with me? If my anti-nausea medications do not work, who should I contact for additional help? What relaxation techniques would you recommend for me? '),
(1003001042300001, 'More_Information', 'National Cancer Institute:  Nausea and Vomiting PDQ www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/nausea/Patient \r\n\r\n National Cancer Institute:  What to Do about Feeling Sick to Your Stomach and Throwing Up (Nausea and Vomiting) www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/radiation-side-effects/nausea.pdf \r\n\r\n American Cancer Society:  Nausea and Vomiting www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/physicalsideeffects/nauseaandvomiting/nauseaandvomiting/index \r\n\r\n American Cancer Society:  Getting Help for Nausea and Vomiting www.cancer.org/acs/groups/content/@editorial/documents/document/acspc-031610.pdf \r\n\r\n CancerConnect.com:  Nausea and Vomiting Center news.cancerconnect.com/nausea-and-vomiting-information-center/ \r\n\r\n '),
(1003001048001001, 'What are numbness and tingling?', 'What are numbness and tingling? When you experience numbness or tingling it means there is swelling or damage to your nerve fibers. It is a partial loss of sensation in the hands and feet beginning at the fingers and toes. '),
(1003001048001002, 'When you have numbness and tingling', 'When you have numbness and tingling... ...you feel discomfort similar to pins and needles or burning. You are less sensitive to changes in temperature, touch, pain, or vibration. You may lose balance or drop things, have difficulty walking or picking up objects, writing, buttoning clothing, or brushing your teeth. You may feel weak, stiff, or tight in the arms or legs. You may also have blurred vision, jaw pain, or hearing loss/ringing or buzzing in the ears. '),
(1003001048001003, 'What causes numbness and tingling?', 'WWhat causes numbness and tingling? Numbness and tingling are a result of your chemotherapy. It may develop suddenly after your treatment or build up gradually. Usually it is more intense right after a treatment and gets better just before the next one. It tends to be at its worst 3 to 5 months after your last treatment. You are at the greatest risk to experience numbness and tingling if you also have diabetes, alcoholism, or severe malnutrition. \r\n\r\n Some of the most common chemotherapy drugs that cause numbness and tingling are: Vincristine (Oncovin&#174;) Vindesine (Eldisine&#174;) Vinorelbine (Navelbine&#174;) Vinblastine (Velban&#174;) Platinol (Cisplatin&#174;) Paraplatin (Carboplatin&#174;) Eloxatin (Oxaliplatin&#174;) Paclitaxel (Taxol&#174;) Docetaxel (Taxotere&#174;) Bortezomib (Velcade&#174;) Thalidomide Procarbazine (Matulane&#174;) Cytarabine (ARA-C&#174;) Vespide (Etoposide&#174;, vp-16) Alfa-interferon '),
(1003001048100000, 'What can I do about my numbness and tingling?', 'What can I do about my numbness and tingling?  How bad is your numbness and tingling? Read these statements and click on the ONE that best describes your numbness and tingling today: '),
(1003001048200001, 'How can I talk to my doctor about my numbness and tingling?', 'How can I talk to my doctor about my numbness and tingling? Always report Paralysis, pain, numbness, prickling, tingling, weakness, or burning in your skin that makes it difficult to perform your daily activities. (Be sure to mention if the symptoms occur in your hands, arms, or legs.) Changes in your sense of touch in your hands, fingers, feet, toes, or mouth that make it difficult to feel or pick up objects Difficulty swallowing, breathing, drinking, or chewing Difficulty urinating or constipation Blurred vision or ringing/buzzing in your ears Stumbling, losing your balance, or falling from numbness in your feet Inability to drive because your hands or feet are numb Need for special equipment '),
(1003001048200002, 'What questions can I ask my doctor?', 'What questions can I ask my doctor? What causes my numbness and tingling? Is it the chemotherapy? Am I at risk for developing numbness and tingling? How can I prevent it? Will the numbness and tingling disappear after treatment? Am I taking any medications that could make my numbness and tingling worse? Can I keep on driving? Do I need a disabled parking permit? Would physical therapy or occupational therapy help me? Should I try acupuncture to manage my pain? '),
(1003001048300001, 'More_Information', 'National Cancer Institute:  Nerve Changes www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/chemo-side-effects/nerve.pdf \r\n\r\n American Cancer Society:  Nerve and Muscle Problems www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/treatmenttypes/chemotherapy/understandingchemotherapyaguideforpatientsandfamilies/understanding-chemotherapy-more-side-effects-nerve-and-muscle-problems \r\n\r\n\r\n American Cancer Society:  Peripheral Neuropathy Caused by Chemotherapy www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/physicalsideeffects/chemotherapyeffects/peripheralneuropathy/peripheral-neuropathy-caused-by-chemotherapy-toc \r\n\r\n CancerConnect.com:  Numbness and Tingling news.cancerconnect.com/numbness-and-tingling-peripheral-neuropathy/ \r\n\r\n '),
(1003001051001001, 'What is pain?', 'What is pain? You have pain when you have an unpleasant, uncomfortable feeling. Pain means there is possible or actual damage to part of your body.  '),
(1003001051001002, 'When you have pain', 'When you have pain... ...the aching is usually concentrated in one area of your body, but it can also be vague and generalized. It can come on suddenly or gradually, and it can be sharp and intense, tingling or numbing. It can also be described as burning. '),
(1003001051001003, 'What causes pain?', 'What causes pain? The cause of your pain may be the cancer growing and pressing into nerves or tissue in the aching area. It can also be the result of your cancer treatment or of tissue damage during surgery. '),
(1003001051100000, 'What can I do about my pain?', 'What can I do about my pain? General management goals and strategies First, how bad is your pain? Read these statements and click on the ONE that best describes your pain today: '),
(1003001051200001, 'How should I talk to my doctor about my pain?', 'How should I talk to my doctor about my pain? Tell your doctor: Where the pain is located, how long it lasts, and how long it takes for your pain medication to work If your current pain medication is not working or if it has unbearable side effects, such as constipation or diarrhea If you cannot take anything by mouth, including the pain medication If your pain has changed since the last visit to your doctor If you have a cough or fever higher than 101&#176;F (38.3&#176;C) for more than 24 hours If you have fatigue, nausea, or bloating for more than 2 days If you pain is getting worse even when you are following your pain medication schedule If you are confused or becoming disoriented '),
(1003001051200002, 'What questions can I ask my doctor?', 'What questions can I ask my doctor? What is causing my pain? How much medication should I take, and how often? How long does it take for the medication to start working? What are the side effects of my pain medication? Can I prevent them? Is it safe to drink alcoholic beverages, drive, or operate machinery after I have taken my pain medication? If my pain medication is not working, can I take more? If the dose can be increased, by how much? Should I increase the dose or the frequency? Should I call you before I make any changes to my medication schedule? Can I get help managing my pain through a support group? Is there any available counseling? '),
(1003001051300001, 'More_Information', 'National Cancer Institute:  Cancer Pain Can Be Managed www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/paincontrol National Cancer Institute:  Summary of Pain Management Techniques www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/pain/Patient/page1 American Cancer Institute:  Webinar on Relieving Cancer Pain www.cancer.org/treatment/supportprogramsservices/onlinecommunities/participateinacancereducationclass/icancopeonline/relievingcancerpain American Cancer Institute:  Daily Pain Diary www.cancer.org/acs/groups/content/@editorial/documents/document/acspc-033203.pdf '),
(1003001060001001, 'What is a rash?', 'What is a rash? A rash is a change in the appearance or the texture of your skin. It may affect all of your skin or just one part of your body. '),
(1003001060001002, 'When you have a rash', '\nWhen you have a rash... ...your skin may become red and feel hot or itchy. It may also be dry or cracked, with bumps that look like acne, or blisters that can drain clear fluid. If the redness is covered in a brown crust and oozes fluid, it probably means it is infected. You may also have intense itching and may feel the need to scratch. '),
(1003001060001003, 'What causes a rash?', 'What causes a rash? Many chemotherapy drugs cause rashes and skin changes during treatment or within the first 36 hours after treatment. This may be an acute allergic reaction causing hives, flushing, and itching. It is very important that you let your healthcare provider know  immediately  if you experience this type of rash. However, a rash normally does not require you to stop your treatment and usually clears up within 1-2 months after treatment is completed. '),
(1003001060100000, 'Rash - Manage', 'What can I do about my rash? It is  very important  that you contact your doctor if your rash becomes bumpy and looks like acne. This rash is   acne. Do not treat it with acne medication. How bad is your rash?  Read these statements and select the ONE that best describes your rash today: '),
(1003001060200001, 'How can I talk to my doctor about my rash?', 'How can I talk to my doctor about my rash? You must report: A temperature above 101&#176;F (38.3&#176;C) for two or more hours (Don\'t drink any hot or cold drinks 15 minutes before you take your temperature.) A rash that does not go away in two weeks A rash that becomes infected, including any pus or other fluids oozing from the rash A rash that affects the lining of your mouth or your nose and that makes it difficult to eat, talk, or sleep Blisters Cracking or peeling fingernails Severe itching Hives, flushing, or difficulty breathing. (If you have any of these, call your doctor IMMEDIATELY.) ALWAYS  call your doctor if your rash gets worse or the medication prescribed is not working after two or more weeks. '),
(1003001060200002, 'What questions can I ask my doctor?', 'What questions can I ask my doctor? \r\n \r\n Do I need to take any medications before my treatment to reduce my risk of getting a rash? Should I stop taking my chemotherapy if I develop a rash? Does my chemotherapy cause my rash? If so, when will my rash go away? Can I wear makeup if I develop a rash? Would a special oatmeal bath reduce itching? '),
(1003001060300001, 'More Information', 'National Cancer Institute:  What to do about Mild Skin Changes www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/coping/radiation-side-effects/skin.pdf National Cancer Institute:  Pruritus (itching) www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/pruritus/Patient\n American Cancer Society:  Getting Help for Skin Changes www.cancer.org/acs/groups/content/@editorial/documents/document/acspc-031629.pdf Oncolink:  Nail and Skin Care oncolink.org/coping/article.cfm?c=5&s=75&ss=186&id=991 National Comprehensive Cancer Network:  Skin Rashes in Cancer Treatment www.nccn.org/patients/resources/life_with_cancer/managing_symptoms/skin_rashes.aspx '),
(1003001069001001, 'What is shortness of breath?', 'What is shortness of breath? You are short of breath when you have difficulty breathing or trouble catching your breath. '),
(1003001069001002, 'When you have shortness of breath ', 'When you have shortness of breath... ...you need to work hard to breathe. You feel "air hungry" or suffocated. '),
(1003001069001003, 'What causes shortness of breath?', 'What causes shortness of breath? Shortness of breath has many possible causes: anemia, fluid in the lungs, infection, fatigue, pneumonia, pain, obesity, stress, or anxiety. You may also be short of breath after surgery, or as a side effect of chemotherapy or radiation therapy. '),
(1003001069100000, 'What can I do about my shortness of breath?', 'What can I do about my shortness of breath? How bad is your shortness of breath? Read these statements and click on the ONE that best describes your shortness of breath today: '),
(1003001069200001, 'How can I talk to my doctor about my shortness of breath?', 'How can I talk to my doctor about my shortness of breath? Always report The time of day and the circumstances in which you are short of breath. Does it happen after daily activity or at rest? How long does it last? (Always call your doctor if it lasts more than 24 hours.) Painful breathing, wheezing, flared nostrils, straining of the neck muscles, or chest pain Thick yellow/green or bloody phlegm Cold, clammy skin Night sweats Reduced activity (such as walking), increased pulse rate at rest, or a rapid, pounding heart Swelling of the ankles or calves of your legs Inability to get out of bed for two or more days A temperature above 101&#176;F (38.3&#176;C) for two or more hours '),
(1003001069200002, 'What questions can I ask my doctor?', 'What questions can I ask my doctor? What causes my shortness of breath? Is it my cancer treatment? What can be done to make it better? Should I take medication? Where can I learn relaxation techniques? '),
(1003001069300001, 'More_Information', 'National Cancer Institute:  Dyspnea (Shortness of Breath) www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/cardiopulmonary/Patient/page2 \r\n\r\n American Cancer Society:  Shortness of Breath www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/physicalsideeffects/dealingwithsymptomsathome/caring-for-the-patient-with-cancer-at-home-shortness-of-breath \r\n\r\n American Cancer Society:  Yoga www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/complementaryandalternativemedicine/mindbodyandspirit/yoga \r\n\r\n '),
(1003001072001001, 'What is a sleeping problem?', 'What is a sleeping problem? You have a sleeping problem if you have difficulty falling asleep, staying asleep, or getting enough sleep. '),
(1003001072001002, 'When you have a sleeping problem', 'When you have a sleeping problem... ...you wake up several times during the night and have trouble going back to sleep, or you wake up feeling tired or too early in the morning. You may also be generally irritable or have problems with memory or concentration. '),
(1003001072001003, 'What causes sleeping problems?', 'What causes sleeping problems? Your chemotherapy drugs and other medications may be the cause of your sleeping problems. You may also have trouble sleeping if you are anxious or depressed about the cancer itself or the treatment. Pain, diarrhea, nausea, or vomiting can also interfere with sleep. '),
(1003001072100000, 'What can I do about my sleeping problems?', 'What can I do about my sleeping problems? General management goals and strategies First, how bad is your sleeping problem? Read these statements and click on the ONE that best describes your problem today: '),
(1003001072200001, 'How should I talk to my doctor about my sleeping problems?', 'How should I talk to my doctor about my sleeping problems? Bring your sleep diary with you to discuss your problem with the doctor. Always report: Waking up frequently during the night or difficulty falling back asleep after waking for 3 or more weeks Sleeping problems caused by sadness for 2 or more weeks Inability to do your daily activities Pain or fatigue that you cannot control Nightmares Shortness of breath Weakness, dizziness, or fainting '),
(1003001072200002, 'What questions can I ask my doctor?', 'What questions can I ask my doctor? Should I take medication for my sleeping problem? Are herbal supplements a good option? Will my sleep improve after my cancer treatment? What type and amount of physical activity is safe for me to do? Where can I learn more about relaxation techniques? Should I see a sleep specialist? '),
(1003001072300001, 'More_Information', 'National Cancer Institute:  Sleep Disorders www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/supportivecare/sleepdisorders/Patient \r\n\r\n American Cancer Society:  Sleep Problems www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/physicalsideeffects/dealingwithsymptomsathome/caring-for-the-patient-with-cancer-at-home-sleep-problems \r\n\r\n American Cancer Society:  Getting Help for Sleep Problems www.cancer.org/acs/groups/content/@editorial/documents/document/acspc-031631.pdf '),
(1003001006100000000, 'Lack of Appetite No Trouble', ' I don\'t have lack of appetite. '),
(1003001006100000001, 'Lack of Appetite - TC1', ' I am less hungry than usual, but I have not changed my eating habits. '),
(1003001006100000002, 'Lack of Appetite - TC2', ' I am eating less, but I haven\'t lost weight. '),
(1003001006100000003, 'Lack of Appetite - TC3', ' I am taking very little food or fluids and I have lost more than 10 percent of my usual weight. '),
(1003001006100001001, 'Lack of Appetite - Mild', 'Your lack of appetite is  MILD Here are some management tips for you: Useful activities: Use a log to keep a record of what you eat and drink and any medication that you are taking. Treat constipation or diarrhea as soon as possible. Both of them can affect your appetite. Doing mild physical activity such as walking for 30 minutes before a meal can make you feel hungrier. Nutrition: Try having 5 or 6 smaller meals or healthy snacks throughout the day instead of 3 meals a day. Choose high-protein foods such as eggs, whole milk, cheese, meats, and peanut butter. Drink 8 glasses of water or other non-caffeinated drinks every day (a total of about half a gallon). '),
(1003001006100001002, 'Lack of Appetite - Moderate', 'Your lack of appetite is  MODERATE Besides following the recommendations for MILD lack of appetite, you should also consider these tips: Add details to your food log: When is your appetite poor? When is it good? Have you had nausea? Have you vomited? Have you had constipation or diarrhea? What is your weight? Jump on the scales once a week at the same time each day. Nutrition: Eat calorie-rich foods such as milk shakes or liquid supplements between meals. Try using seasonings and spices on foods that you now find unpleasant. Basil, ginger, and rosemary can add flavor to meat, fish, or poultry. Sauces and gravies make swallowing easier. Try high-calorie supplements (Boost&#8482; or Ensure&#8482;) on their own or mixed with fruit or ice-cream. They can be filling, so try to eat your meal before taking them. Many people find it easier to sip them cold through a straw. Medication: Take your prescribed anti-nausea medication 30-60 minutes before eating. Ask your doctor if it would help to take Megace&#174;, a hormone that improves your appetite. Other medications that your doctor may prescribe are corticosteroids, such as Dexamethasone, Methylprednisolone, or Prednisolone. '),
(1003001006100001003, 'Lack of Appetite - Severe', 'Your lack of appetite is  SEVERE You need medical attention. Call your doctor right away. Read about  how to talk to your doctor about your lack of appetite '),
(1003001009100000000, 'Symptom No Trouble', ' I don\'t have constipation. '),
(1003001009100000001, 'Symptom - TC1', ' Sometimes I am constipated and need to use stool softeners, laxatives, enemas or special foods to help move my bowels. '),
(1003001009100000002, 'Symptom - TC2', ' I am constipated most of the time and cannot have a bowel movement without regular use of laxatives or enemas. '),
(1003001009100000003, 'Symptom - TC3', ' My constipation is so bad that I have not had a bowel movement in at least three days and I have a lot of stomach pain. '),
(1003001009100001001, 'constipation - Mild', 'Your constipation is  MILD Here are management tips for you: Use a log to keep a record of what and how much you eat and drink, and any medication that you are taking. Nutrition: Eat 3 to 5 times a day. Drink 8 glasses of water or other non-caffeinated drinks a day (a total of about half a gallon). Avoid caffeine (colas, coffee, tea, energy drinks). Drink herbal tea, lemon water, or prune juice after meals. Eat foods high in fiber: well-washed raw vegetables, raisin bran, whole grain cereal, raisins, prunes, dates, and nuts. Add legumes to your meals: alfalfa, beans, soy beans, or peas. Avoid low-fiber foods: cheeses, meats, and processed foods. Activities: Do mild physical activity (like walking) for at least 15 minutes every day. If you cannot walk, try moving your legs and torso (rotate, lift, or bend) for 15 minutes at least twice a day. When your body signals the need for a bowel movement, take action. Sit upright and take your time; do not strain or push. Have a quiet, comfortable bathroom environment. '),
(1003001009100001002, 'constipation - Moderate', 'Your constipation is  MODERATE Besides following the recommendations for MILD constipation, you should also consider these tips:: Activities: Use a log to keep a record of bowel movements, bloating, gas, or abdominal pain. Always make a note of the date and time, and write a description of your stool if possible. This will help your doctor evaluate your case and give you recommendations. Have a daily bathroom routine that includes privacy. Report any history of past bowel problems or abdominal surgeries. Nutrition: Add fiber to your diet in the form of bran or wheat germ. Start with two teaspoons per day and gradually increase to two tablespoons per day. Always have your fiber with water. Medication: Ask your doctor for a stool softener or a laxative. You can usually buy these over the counter, but your doctor will tell you which one is best and most likely to work for you. Do NOT use enemas or suppositories without talking to your doctor first. '),
(1003001009100001003, 'constipation - Severe', 'Your constipation is  SEVERE You need medical attention. Call your doctor right away.\nDo NOT use enemas or suppositories without talking to your doctor first. Read about  how to talk to your doctor about your constipation '),
(1003001018100000000, 'Diarrhea No Trouble', ' I don\'t have diarrhea. '),
(1003001018100000001, 'Diarrhea - TC1', '  I am having between 1 and 3 more bowel movements than usual each day. '),
(1003001018100000002, 'Diarrhea - TC2', ' I am having between 4 and 6 more bowel movements than usual each day. '),
(1003001018100000003, 'Diarrhea - TC3', ' I am having at least 7 more bowel movements than usual each day and I can\'t take care of myself. ');
