(1003001018100001001, 'diarrhea - Mild', 'Your diarrhea is  MILD Here are some management tips: Nutrition: Try eating small, frequent meals (5 to 6 meals per day). Drink 8 glasses of water or other non-caffeinated beverages per day (a total of about half a gallon). Do not take caffeine (colas, coffee, black teas, or energy drinks). These foods will help: bananas, white rice, oats, applesauce, smooth peanut butter, white toast, plain pasta, eggs, cooked carrots, baked potatoes, chicken, and turkey. These fluids will help: soup, nonfat broth, orange juice, or sports drinks like Gatorade&#174;. You can also try diluted fruit juice (half juice, half water). Do not eat food that is high in fiber: cereals in general, raw fruits and green vegetables, or legumes. Do not eat fatty, spicy, or fried foods. Do not eat rich desserts. Avoid milk products (including ice cream and sour cream). Do not eat nuts or dried fruits. Do not eat sugar-free candy or sugar-free gum. Drink fluids at room temperature. Avoid hot liquids. Drink more fluids between meals and less with meals. Self-care: Clean the anus with unscented baby oil or baby wipes to prevent pain and soreness. Use baby wipes instead of toilet paper, and wipe gently. '),
(1003001018100001002, 'diarrhea - Moderate', 'Your diarrhea is  MODERATE Besides following the recommendations for MILD diarrhea, you should also consider these tips: Useful activities: Use a log to keep a record of bowel movements, bloating, gas, or abdominal pain. Include the number of bowel movements you have per day. Always make a note of the date and time, and write a description of your stool if possible. What size is it? What color? Do you notice any blood? Record any cramping or gas pains. This log will help you to talk to your doctor. Self-care: Take warm baths or sitz baths 3 or 4 times a day (a sitz is a tub in which one bathes in a sitting posture). Sit in the warm water for about 10 minutes. Use a thick, protective lotion like Desitin&#174; or A&D&#174; ointment on your anus after each bowel movement.  CAUTION:  If you are receiving radiation treatment to the abdomen, pelvis, or rectal area, talk to your doctor or nurse before using any creams or ointments. Medication: Imodium&#174; AD, Kaopectate&#174;, Pepto-Bismol&#174;, or Maalox&#174; antidiarrheal caplets (loperamide) can help. These are all over-the-counter, but  always consult with your doctor  before taking any medications. Your doctor will prescribe a different medication if over-the-counter products do not work for you. '),
(1003001018100001003, 'diarrhea - Severe', 'Your diarrhea is  SEVERE You need medical attention. Call your doctor right away.\nRead about  how to talk to your doctor about your diarrhea '),
(1003001027100000000, 'Fatigue No Trouble', ' I don\'t have trouble with fatigue. '),
(1003001027100000001, 'Fatigue - TC1', ' I am a little more tired than usual but I am able to do my normal activities. '),
(1003001027100000002, 'Fatigue - TC2', ' I am more tired than usual and have some trouble with normal activities. '),
(1003001027100000003, 'Fatigue - TC3', ' I am so tired that I have trouble taking care of myself. '),
(1003001027100001001, 'fatigue - Mild', 'Your fatigue is  MILD Here are some management tips for you: Keep track of your fatigue: Create a fatigue log. Keep a record of the pattern of your fatigue: dates, times, and level of fatigue. Save your energy: Plan rest periods during the day. Schedule nap and rest times. Naps of 20 minutes at a time can really help, especially in the late morning or early afternoon - but avoid evening naps. Use your bed for sleeping only. Do not lie in bed reading, watching television, or surfing the Internet. Avoid long periods of bed rest. There should be no background noise (music or television) while you are sleeping. Set priorities: Plan to do important activities around times when you usually have the most energy. This is early in the day for most people. Ask for help with tasks that you do not need to do yourself. Some activities have to be done; others are not strictly necessary. Focus on necessary tasks. Nutrition: Eat a diet of fresh fruits and vegetables, low-fat milk products, and lean meat, fish, or chicken. Ask your doctor to help with your diet. Do not eat foods that are high in fat. Eat healthy snacks between meals (fruit, cereal bars, or mixed nuts) to maintain your energy. Drink 8 glasses of water or other non-caffeinated drinks daily (a total of about half a gallon). Avoid caffeine (colas, coffee, black tea, energy drinks) as far as possible. Physical activity: Plan to do some kind of mild physical activity for at least 30 minutes a day. Always warm up and cool down for 5 minutes. If this is too much, begin with shorter periods and try to work up to 30 minutes a day. Do activities that you enjoy. These activities help to deal with fatigue:\n	 Walk. Start with short distances. Increase your distance every month. Ride a bike. Use a regular or a stationary bike. Do strength training. Use weights or resistance bands. Ask your doctor for advice on how to do this activity or to recommend a specialist to help you with this. Do flexibility training. Include stretching with warm-ups and cool-downs. Again, ask your doctor\'s advice in this. Consider doing yoga or mind/body exercises like Qigong (breathing exercises) or Tai Chi. Do sitting exercises that include moving your joints and lifting light weights. These are especially helpful if you feel that you cannot handle a great deal of physical activity. If you can, simply spend time outside. You can do gardening or yard work, talk to your neighbors, watch your children, or walk in the park. Be cautious... ...if you have severe anemia (low red-blood cell count). Do not do any physical activity until your anemia improves. ...if you have a weakened immune system (low white blood cell count or a fever). Do not go to public gyms or other public areas until your white blood cell count is safe and you have not had a fever for at least 24 hours. ...if you are receiving radiation. Avoid swimming pools: chlorine irritates the skin, especially in the area of your body that is being treated with radiation. Keep your mind away from your fatigue. You can use a variety of distractions: music, nature, or television, even for background noise. Learn relaxation therapy, art, or music therapy. Develop a routine before going to bed and follow it every night. '),
(1003001027100001002, 'fatigue - Moderate', 'Your fatigue is  MODERATE Besides following the recommendations for MILD fatigue, you should also consider these tips: Keep a more detailed log. Write down Your current level of fatigue When your fatigue first started, and how it has gotten worse since then What makes your fatigue better or worse, and how it increases or decreases in relation to the treatment for your cancer How your fatigue is affecting your daily activities: your work, your sleeping, and your eating patterns Join a support group. They will share your experience and concerns, and they can provide suggestions and reassurance in a safe environment. '),
(1003001027100001003, 'fatigue - Severe', 'Your fatigue is  SEVERE You need medical attention. Call your doctor right away.\nRead about  how to talk to your doctor about your fatigue '),
(1003001039100000000, 'Mouth Sores No Trouble', ' I don\'t have mouth sores. '),
(1003001039100000001, 'Mouth Sores - TC1', '  I have mouth sores but haven\'t had to change my diet. '),
(1003001039100000002, 'Mouth Sores - TC2', ' I am able to eat and swallow but my diet has changed because of my mouth sores. '),
(1003001039100000003, 'Mouth Sores - TC3', ' I cannot eat or swallow enough food and liquids because of my mouth sores, and I have lost more than 10 percent of my usual weight. '),
(1003001039100001001, 'mouth sores - Mild', 'Your mouth sores are  MILD Here are some management tips for you: Taking care of your mouth: Visit your dentist and have your teeth cleaned. Take care of cavities, gum disease or poorly fitting dentures. These practices keep mouth sores from getting worse. Before starting chemotherapy, ask your dentist to show you the best way to brush and floss your teeth. Use a very soft sponge or an oral sponge. Brush all tooth surfaces for at least 90 seconds. Brush your gums and tongue to reduce the risk of fungal infection. Brush your teeth after every meal and at bedtime. Use nonabrasive toothpaste without whiteners, which may cause irritation. Avoid flavors, such as mint. Floss gently everyday with unwaxed dental floss. Stop flossing if you experience any bleeding or have low blood cell counts. Useful activities: Get a new toothbrush every week. Do not use electric toothbrushes. Do not use mouth rinse products that contain alcohol or glycerin. Do not use liquid medications that contain alcohol, such as cough syrup. Use lip balm, Chapstick&#174;, or petroleum jelly if your lips become dry. Use a water-based mouth moisturizer (e.g. Biotene&#174; Oral Lubricant) to help keep your mouth moist. Ask your dentist about a daily fluoride rinse or gel to prevent tooth decay. If you wear dentures: If you are receiving radiation treatment to the head or the neck, ask your doctor if it is safe to wear your dentures. Clean your dentures after every meal. Do not wear your dentures overnight. If your dentures do not fit properly, repair them or replace them. Nutrition: Drink 8 glasses of water or other non-caffeinated drinks daily (a total of about half a gallon). Avoid food that is very hot or spicy. Also avoid food with sharp edges such as crackers or potato chips. Avoid alcohol and tobacco. Eat popsicles or suck on ice cubes for moisture. Suck on non-irritating hard candy (sugar-free is best) and chew sugarless gum. Eat small, frequent meals. Add soft, soothing foods to your diet such as ice cream, shakes, baby foods, mashed potatoes, scrambled eggs, cottage cheese, custards, puddings, or gelatin. Also, use sauces or gravies to make foods easier to chew or swallow. Medication: Ask your doctor if you can take Tylenol&#174; or Ibuprofen for pain relief. If you have a dry mouth, try artificial saliva such as Oral Balance&#174;, Moist Plus&#174;, or Salivant&#174;. You can buy these without a prescription. '),
(1003001039100001002, 'mouth sores - Moderate', 'Your mouth sores are  MODERATE Besides following the recommendations for MILD mouth sores, you should also consider these tips: Taking care of your mouth: Rinse your mouth every two hours during the day and again if you wake up during the night. Mix your own mouth solution: 1/2 teaspoon salt 2 teaspoons baking soda 4 cups water Shake or stir the solution and keep it for regular use. If you make more than a one-day supply, store the rest in your refrigerator in a tightly-sealed container. Nutrition: Cut down on salty food, tomatoes, and citrus (oranges, grapefruit, tangerines, and lemons). Grind up or puree food in a blender. If you are having trouble passing solid food, have liquid supplements instead: Carnation Instant Breakfast&#174;, Ensure&#174;, or Boost&#174;. Medication: Here are a few medications that will help: Try pain-relieving over-the-counter medications like Orajel&#174;, Anbesol&#174;, Zilactin-b&#174;, or Orabase&#174;. Try Gelclair&#174;, a prescription medication to help soothe the pain, or Caphosol&#174;, a prescription mouth rinse that lubricates the mouth and throat. Your doctor may prescribe a combination mouthwash with a local anesthetic. Chemotherapy and radiation weaken the immune system. Ask your doctor if there is a specific medication that can help fight infections. '),
(1003001039100001003, 'mouth sores  - Severe', 'Your mouth sores are  SEVERE You need medical attention. Call your doctor right away.\n Read about  how to talk to the doctor about your mouth sores '),
(1003001042100000000, 'Nausea No Trouble', ' I don\'t have nausea. '),
(1003001042100000001, 'Nausea - TC1', ' I have vomited once in 24 hours. '),
(1003001042100000002, 'Nausea - TC2', ' I have vomited between 2 and 5 times in 24 hours. '),
(1003001042100000003, 'Nausea - TC3', ' I have vomited 6 or more times in 24 hours and I am feeling light-headed. '),
(1003001042100001001, 'nausea - Mild', 'Your nausea is  MILD Here are some management tips for you: Useful activities: Try to move as little as possible when you feel nauseous. Always keep your head elevated. Rest in a chair after eating, and get plenty of rest in general. The aftertaste of food can add to your nausea. Brush your teeth after meals and use mouthwashes that do not contain alcohol to improve the taste in your mouth. You should try and be as comfortable as possible. For example, wear loose-fitting clothes. Play your favorite music; it will soothe and provide distraction. Make sure there is fresh air around the house by turning on a fan or keeping a window open. Nutrition: Drink 8 glasses of water per day (a total of about half a gallon). Wait for at least 2 hours after a vomiting episode before taking any fluids. Sip slowly. Ginger products tend to calm the stomach - for example, ginger ale or ginger tea. Do not force yourself to eat. Focus on eating slowly instead. Many people find that they have an easier time eating early in the day. Make the most of this time by having a healthy breakfast. Do not eat large meals. Five or six small, frequent meals during the day work best. Here are a number of recommended foods: Cool or cold foods are sometimes more appealing than hot foods. Try Jell-O, cottage or ricotta cheese, pudding, sherbet, popsicles, cold sandwiches, and pasta or potato salad. Try to eat dry or bland food such as crackers, bagels, toast, cereal, yogurt, cookies, ice, pretzels, and skinless cooked chicken. Gum or hard candy can also help. Avoid Heavy, spicy, fried, or fatty foods Very sweet or very salty foods Gas-producing vegetables (broccoli, cauliflower, cucumbers, green peppers, Brussels sprouts, sauerkraut) Acidic foods (salsa, tomatoes, vinegar, citrus fruits, and citrus fruit juices) Alcoholic beverages Food aromas and other strong odors '),
(1003001042100001002, 'nausea - Moderate', 'Your nausea is  MODERATE Besides following the recommendations for MILD nausea, you should also consider these tips: Try therapies and techniques that can help, such as acupuncture, acupressure, guided imagery, hypnosis, music therapy, muscle relaxation, or counseling, support, and structured educational interventions. Medication: If your doctor prescribes anti-nausea medication, take it 30-60 minutes before your oral chemotherapy. Take your anti-nausea medication before meals to help keep your food down. Here are some examples of common anti-nausea medications:\r\n	 Ondansetron (Zofran&#174;): prevents nausea before it begins Aprepitant (Emend&#174;): stops nausea/vomiting after a first episode Dexamethasone: usually combined with Ondansetron for a more powerful effect '),
(1003001042100001003, 'nausea - Severe', 'Your nausea is  SEVERE You need medical attention. Call your doctor right away.\nRead about  how to talk to your doctor about your nausea '),
(1003001048100000000, 'Numbness No Trouble', ' I don\'t have numbness or tingling. '),
(1003001048100000001, 'Numbness - TC1', ' I have a little numbness and tingling but it hasn\'t kept me from doing things. '),
(1003001048100000002, 'Numbness - TC2', ' I have some numbness and tingling that keeps me from doing some things, but I can take care of myself. '),
(1003001048100000003, 'Numbness - TC3', ' I have significant numbness and tingling that keeps me from doing most things. '),
(1003001048100001001, 'numbness and tingling - Mild', 'Your numbness and tingling is  MILD Here are some management tips for you: Environmental safety: You need to make every effort to avoid falls. Pay close attention when you walk; slow down and concentrate on your movements. Wear sturdy shoes; do not wear slippers or running shoes with thick soles. Avoid wet or slippery floors, and put a rubber mat on the floor of the bathroom, tub, and shower. Always turn on the lights before you enter a room, no matter how familiar you are with it. Keep rooms bright enough so that you can see all the areas where you need to walk or do other activities. Keep a night light in your room and along the path you walk if you get up during the night. Arrange your furniture so that you have a clear pathway. Remove clutter or unnecessary rugs from the floor to prevent falls. Use soap dispensers instead of soap bars that can easily slip out of your hands. If you are having trouble feeling changes in temperature, use a non-breakable water thermometer to check your bath or dishwater temperature before you bathe or wash dishes to make sure that the water is no hotter than 100&#176;F (43.3&#176;C). Also, wear rubber gloves to prevent damage when washing the dishes or doing other housework and gardening. Avoid sudden chilling. Do not reach into a refrigerator or freezer. Avoid air conditioning in the summer, drinking ice cold drinks, eating ice cream or other cold foods, and cold showers. Pay special attention when trimming your toenails; you may not feel small cuts on your toes. Check your skin daily for burns and cuts: carefully inspect your arms, legs, fingers, and toes. Useful activities: You should continue to do physical activity as usual, especially walking and swimming. If you have pain, massage the affected area or try deep breathing and relaxation. Nutrition: Drink 8 glasses of water daily (a total of about half a gallon). Avoid very cold beverages, chewing ice, or using straws. Eat a high fiber diet with fruits, vegetables, and whole grains. '),
(1003001048100001002, 'numbness and tingling - Moderate', 'Your numbness and tingling is  MODERATE Besides following the recommendations for MILD numbness and tingling above, you should also consider these tips: Environmental safety: Install tub or shower handgrips. Use a cane or a walker if you feel week or unsteady when walking. Wear gloves or a scarf when opening the refrigerator or going into an air-conditioned room. Useful activities: If you decide to have a manicure or a pedicure, ask your doctor to recommend a professional. '),
(1003001048100001003, 'numbness and tingling - Severe', 'Your numbness and tingling is  SEVERE You need medical attention. Contact your doctor right away. Read about  how to talk to your doctor about your numbness and tingling '),
(1003001051100000000, 'Pain No Trouble', ' I don\'t have pain. '),
(1003001051100000001, 'Pain - TC1', ' I have some pain but it doesn\'t keep me from doing my normal activities. '),
(1003001051100000002, 'Pain - TC2', ' My pain keeps me from doing some things, but I can take care of myself. '),
(1003001051100000003, 'Pain - TC3', ' My pain is so bad that I can\'t take care of myself. '),
(1003001051100001001, 'pain - Mild', 'Your pain is  MILD Here are some management tips for you: Useful activities: Apply heat or cold on the area of pain. Always wrap your heating pad or ice pack in a towel to protect your skin. Use pillows to keep pressure off the area of pain. Practice deep breathing exercises and relaxation techniques. Perform mild exercise, especially swimming or walking. Get a massage. Try to distract yourself by watching TV or listening to music. Keep a pain log to bring with you to the doctor. Note details about How long the pain lasts What seems to make it worse What helps to relieve the pain (heat, ice, or medication) If you are taking medication, how long it takes for the pain to go away Over-the-counter Medication: Try a common pain reliever, such as aspirin, Tylenol&#174;, Advil&#174;, Ibuprofen&#174;, or Motrin&#174;. Take these precautions:\n	 Do not wait until your pain is severe to take your medication. Take your pain medication exactly as prescribed. Do not crush or break your pain pills unless you check with your doctor. Pain medication can make you dizzy, drowsy, or sleepy. Do not drive or operate any equipment until you are sure what effects the medication has on you. Keep at least a one-week supply of pain medication on hand. Call your doctor in good time to refill your prescription. Pain medication should not be stopped suddenly; it needs to be decreased little by little. Talk to your doctor about how to decrease the dose if you think you no longer need pain medication. '),
(1003001051100001002, 'pain - Moderate', 'Your pain is  MODERATE Besides following the recommendations for MILD pain, you should also consider these tips: Many people believe they can become addicted to pain medication. Do not be afraid. This problem is very rare in cancer patients. Here are a few pain medications that your doctor may prescribe: Codeine Oxycodone/OxyContin Hydrocodone Morphine Hydromorphone/Dilaudid Methadone Fentanyl Certain steroids, antidepressants, and anti-seizure medications Your doctor may also recommend one or more of these therapies: Acupuncture Physical therapy Occupational therapy Transcutaneous Electrical Nerve Stimulation (TENS). This involves applying gentle electric current to the skin to relieve pain. Counseling or support groups '),
(1003001051100001003, 'pain - Severe', 'Your pain is  SEVERE You need medical attention. Call your doctor right away. Read about  how to talk to your doctor about your pain '),
(1003001060100000000, 'Rash - No Trouble', ' I don\'t have a rash. '),
(1003001060100000001, 'Rash - TC1', ' I have a red rash, but it doesn\'t itch or hurt. (Mild) '),
(1003001060100000002, 'Rash - TC2', ' My red rash covers less than half my body and itches or hurts with some peeling. (Moderate) '),
(1003001060100000003, 'Rash - TC3', ' My red rash covers more than half my body and itches or hurts with blisters, peeling, and lots of oozing fluids. (Severe) '),
(1003001060100001001, 'Rash - Mild', 'Your rash is  MILD Here are some management tips for you: Skin and nail care: Use a mild moisturizing soap without perfumes. Examples include Dove&#174;, Ivory&#174; Skin Cleansing Liquid Gel, Cetaphil&#174;, Neutrogena&#174;, and Aveeno&#174;. You can also use baby shampoos and body washes. Always check the label to make sure the soap you are buying is perfume free. Do not use lotions, creams, shampoos, soaps, or aftershaves that contain alcohol, or dyes. Moisturize your skin, especially at your finger and toenails, with dye and alcohol-free lotions such as Eucerin&#174; Cream, Cetaphil&#174; Cream, Udder&#174; Cream, Zim\'s&#174; Crack Cr&#233;me, Aquaphor&#174; Ointment, Vanicream&#174;, Neutrogena&#174;, or Vaseline&#174; Intensive Care. Treat itchy skin with these lotions as well. Your skin will tend to be dry; take quick, warm showers instead of long, hot baths. When you wash and dry your skin, pat the area gently with a clean, soft towel or a washcloth, and never rub. Apply creams or lotions after your bath, while your skin is still moist. Do not expose your skin to extreme temperatures. Do not use ice packs, heating pads, or electric blankets. Keep your nails clean and cut short. Dust your body with cornstarch, especially in the folds of your skin behind your knees and under your arms or breasts. Shave less often. Do not shave at all if your skin is sore. Wear strong gloves to avoid skin contact with harsh chemicals when cleaning. Wear light cotton gloves when gardening or doing outdoor work. Put on rubber or latex gloves before washing dishes. Sun care: Stay out of the sun as much as possible. Wear sunscreen (SPF 30 or greater) every day, even on cloudy days. In addition to using sunscreen, wear a hat, a long-sleeved shirt, and pants for greater protection from the sun. Do not use tanning beds. Clothing: Wear loose-fitting, soft cotton clothing. Do not wash your clothes with perfumed laundry detergent. Wash those clothes that come in direct contact with your skin in mild Deft&#174; or Tide&#174; hypoallergenic detergents. Always read the label to make sure you are buying the correct type of detergent. If elastic bands from underclothing rub painfully on the rash, use one of the moisturizing lotions listed under "skin care," and cover with a nonstick gauze pad, such as Telfa&#174;. Nutrition: Drink eight glasses of water or other non-caffeinated drinks daily (a total of about half a gallon). Avoid caffeine (colas, coffee, black tea, energy drinks), as caffeine causes dehydration. Medication: If your itching is mild and localized, use a topical antihistamine cream like Benadryl&#174;. If your itching is severe, use an oral antihistamine drug such as Benadryl&#174;, Claritin&#174;, or Allegra&#174;. If your rash hurts, your doctor may prescribe oral pain medications. '),
(1003001060100001002, 'Rash - Moderate', 'Your rash is  MODERATE Besides following the recommendations for MILD rash above, you should also consider these tips: Record any details about the characteristics of your rash in a diary. Write down: when the rash first started and how it has got worse since it first began what makes it better and what does not seem to work how the rash gets worse or better in relation to your cancer treatment any current prescriptions or over-the-counter medications you are taking your drug allergies, including any reactions you have ever had to medications Skin and nail care: Oatmeal lotions or sesame oil may help. For inflammation around your fingernails, soak your fingertips for 5 minutes once a day in a solution of white vinegar diluted 1:10 (one part vinegar, 10 parts tap water). Use Band-Aid&#174; brand Liquid Bandage, Bag&#174; Balm, and Zim\'s&#174; Crack Cream for cracks and fissures in the skin around the nails. Medication: Ask your doctor what kind of medication is right for you. The doctor may prescribe one or more of the following medications: Topical gels to decrease pain, such as RadiaPlex and Cool Magic Gel Sheets (best kept cool in the refrigerator) Topical antibiotic creams, such as Clindamycin and Erythromycin Steroids taken in pill form, such as Prednisone Antibiotics (if the rash shows signs of infection) in pill form, such as Tetracycline, Minocycline, Doxycycline, Trimethoprim, or Sulfamethoxazole Topical ammonium lactate lotions for itching, such as LacHydrin&#174; or Am-Hyrdin&#174;  '),
(1003001060100001003, 'Rash - Severe', 'Your rash is  SEVERE You need medical attention. Contact your doctor right away. Read about  how to talk to your doctor about your rash '),
(1003001069100000000, 'Breath No Trouble', ' I don\'t have shortness of breath. '),
(1003001069100000001, 'Breath - TC1', ' I get short of breath with activity but can walk up one flight of stairs without stopping. '),
(1003001069100000002, 'Breath - TC2', ' I get short of breath with activity and I can\'t walk up one flight of stairs without stopping. '),
(1003001069100000003, 'Breath - TC3', ' I get short of breath at rest. '),
(1003001069100001001, 'breath - Mild', 'Your shortness of breath is  MILD Here are some management tips for you: Useful activities: When you are short of breath, try opening a window or turning on a fan. Do not lie flat on your back. Sit upright (to at least a 45&#176; angle) and prop your head up with pillows. Apply a cool washcloth on your cheeks or forehead. If you are standing, lean forward with your forearms resting on a table or on your knees. On a regular basis, meditate or talk to someone to reduce stress and anxiety. Do mild physical activity, if you can. Do not smoke, and avoid being around those who smoke. Wear loose-fitting clothing that is easy to put on. Avoid warm temperatures, unpleasant odors, or fumes. Deep-breathing technique: Remain calm. Breathe in through your nose for a count of two. Purse your lips as though you are going to blow out a match or candle, and breathe out through pursed lips for a count of four. Repeat these steps until your shortness of breath is relieved. Energy conservation: Plan your day\'s activities carefully. Do important activities early in the day. Do not do unnecessary activities; save energy.  Shower, shave, brush your teeth, or comb your hair while sitting down. Pace yourself during activities, and take multiple rest periods. Take your time when climbing stairs, and match your breaths to the steps you take. Take the elevator when possible. Wear slip-on shoes and move slowly. Nutrition: Drink 8 glasses of water every day (a total of about half a gallon). Eat five to six small meals per day rather than three large meals. Plan meals that are easy to make, such as salads or cooked legumes. Avoid foods that are difficult to chew. '),
(1003001069100001002, 'shortness of breath - Moderate', 'Your shortness of breath is  MODERATE Besides following the recommendations for MILD shortness of breath, you should also consider these tips: Useful activities: Do not bend over to pick things up from the floor; use special reaching devices. Use a wheelchair as needed. Use oxygen as prescribed by your doctor. Nutrition: Consider food services such as Meals on Wheels so you will not have to prepare the food yourself. Medication: Take medications for your shortness of breath as prescribed by your doctor. '),
(1003001069100001003, 'shortness of breath - Severe', 'Your shortness of breath is  SEVERE You need medical attention. Contact your doctor right away. Read about  how to talk to your doctor about your shortness of breath '),
(1003001072100000000, 'Sleep No Trouble', ' I don\'t have sleeping problems. '),
(1003001072100000001, 'Sleep - TC1', ' I sometimes have trouble sleeping, but it doesn\'t keep me from doing my normal activities. '),
(1003001072100000002, 'Sleep - TC2', ' I am having trouble sleeping and it keeps me from doing some things, but I can do most of my normal activities. '),
(1003001072100000003, 'Sleep - TC3', ' I have a lot of trouble sleeping, and it\'s keeping me from doing many of my normal activities. '),
(1003001072100001001, 'sleeping problem - Mild', 'Your sleeping problem is  MILD Here are some management tips for you: Useful activities: Develop a sleeping routine. Try taking a warm bath an hour before bedtime. Go to bed and awake at the same time every day. If you take a nap during the day, make sure you do before 3:00PM, and do not sleep for more than 30 minutes. Make sure you are comfortable. If you are experiencing pain from your cancer or your treatment, try to deal with the pain by bedtime. Avoid watching television in the bedroom, as well as eating or reading in bed. Keep your bedroom temperature constant. Replace old mattresses and pillows. Go to another room when you cannot fall asleep in your bedroom. Physical activity: Do some mild physical activity at least 3 hours before bedtime: Take a walk around the block, do some household chores, work in the garden, play with your children, or practice yoga. Nutrition: Eat a high-protein snack two hours before bedtime. If you are hungry at bedtime, eat a small healthy snack with warm milk. Do not have coffee, colas, black tea, or energy drinks after noontime. Do not drink alcohol. Do not have any fluids before bedtime. Do not eat large meals in the evening. Do not eat rich, spicy, or sugary foods in the evening.  Do not smoke. Nicotine is a stimulant. Use distractions: Try mood music (nature sounds, ocean waves, etc.) to filter out noises, especially at bedtime. Practice meditation or deep breathing techniques. '),
(1003001072100001002, 'sleeping problem - Moderate', 'Your sleeping problem is  MODERATE Besides following the recommendations for MILD sleeping problems, you should also consider these tips: Keep a sleep diary. Record: The times when you fall asleep and wake up, including nap times When your sleeping problem started, and if it has gotten worse What seems to make your sleeping problem better or worse How your sleeping problem is affecting your daily activities Medication: Common medications for sleep are hypnotics, benzodiazepines, antihistamines, and antidepressants. Follow the directions of your prescribed sleep medication very carefully. Make sure your doctor has a current list of all the prescriptions, over-the-counter medications, vitamins, minerals, and herbal remedies that you are taking. Complementary therapies: Common therapies for sleeping problems are expressive therapy, expressive writing, massage therapy, muscle relaxation, mindfulness-based stress reduction (MBSR), and yoga. You can try joining a support group. These groups can provide emotional support for any concerns or worries you may have about your sleeping problems, or about your diagnosis or treatment in general. '),
(1003001072100001003, 'sleeping problem - Severe', 'Your sleeping problem is  SEVERE You need medical attention. Call your doctor right away. Read about  how to talk to your doctor about your sleeping problems ');
